##title
Frederick Chiluba
##doc
0 Frederick Jacob Titus Chiluba ( April 30 , 1943 – June 18 , 2011 ) was a Zambian politician who was the second President of Zambia from 1991 to 2002 .
1 Chiluba , a trade union leader , won the country 's multi - party presidential election in 1991 as the candidate of the Movement for Multi - party Democracy ( MMD ) , defeating long - time President Kenneth Kaunda .
2 He was re - elected in 1996 .
3 As he was unable to run for a third term in 2001 , former Vice President Levy Mwanawasa instead ran as the MMD candidate and succeeded him .
4 After leaving office , Chiluba was the subject of a long investigation and trial regarding alleged corruption ; he was eventually acquitted in 2009 .

##title
Front of Islamic Revolution Stability
##doc
0 Front of Islamic Revolution Stability ( , also translated Persevering Front , Endurance Front and Steadfast Front ) is an Iranian principlist political group described as " extreme end of the fundamentalist camp " and " Iran ’s most right - wing party " .
1 It was established as an electoral list for the 2012 legislative election .
2 The Front is partly made up of former ministers of Mahmoud Ahmadinejad and Mohammad Taghi Mesbah Yazdi is said to be the " spiritual leader " behind the group .
3 In 2013 , the Front supported Saeed Jalili for president after Kamran Bagheri Lankarani 's withdrawal , and released electoral list for local elections in several cities , with a landslide victory in Mashhad City Council .
4 The front declares that it stands against both “ sedition ” ( 2009 Iranian presidential election protests ) and the “ deviant current ” .
5 Rajanews website is its online mouthpiece .

##title
Will Weng
##doc
0 Will Weng ( February 25 , 1907 – May 2 , 1993 ) was an American journalist and crossword puzzle constructor who served as crossword puzzle editor for New York Times from 1969 - 1977 .
1 Born in Terre Haute , Indiana , he attended Indiana State Teachers College .
2 Weng came to New York City in 1927 .
3 He got a master 's degree from the Columbia University School of Journalism and joined the Times in 1930 as a reporter .
4 He served as a lieutenant commander in the United States Navy during World War II .
5 Weng had succeeded Margaret Farrar as crossword puzzle editor , and was himself succeeded by Eugene T. Maleska .
6 After leaving the New York Times he became the editor for a start - up crossword puzzle venue called The Crosswords Club , preparing five Sunday - size crosswords every month for distribution to subscribers .
7 Weng died of throat cancer in Manhattan .

##title
James De Alwis
##doc
0 James De Alwis ( 1823 – 1878 ) was a lawyer , writer , poet and a prominent colonial era legislator from Ceylon .
1 He was an unofficial member of the Legislative Council .
2 He is remembered for his writings that included several works on Buddhism .
3 Educated at the Colombo Academy as one of its first students , he was part of the Macaulay of Ceylon along with Frederick Nell and his brother Louis , Charles Ambrose Lorensz , John Prins , Charle Ferdinands and Dandris de Silva Gunaratna inspired by the Young England movement .
4 Qualified as a Procter , he went on to become an Advocate and served as the a District Judge and Police Magistrate .
5 During his legal practice his clients included Mudliyar Jeronis de Soysa ( father of Sir Charles Henry de Soysa ) , Arunasalam Ponnambalam Mudliyar ( father of Sir Ponnambalam Ramanathan ) and S. Edirimanasingham , Mudaliyar of the Governor ’s Gate ( grand uncle of Sir Ponnambalam Ramanathan )
6 Later he was appointed as an unofficial member of the Legislative Council of Ceylon ; however he resigned together with George Wall , Charles Ambrose Lorensz , W. Thompson , John Capper and John Eaton on 15 November 1864 on a point of principle regarding the fiscal policy of the Government and its strict disregard to respect the procedures of the Legislative Council .
7 His daughter married Felix Reginald Dias Bandaranaike I , who became a Judge of the Supreme Court of Ceylon .

##title
War between Armenia and Iberia
##doc
0 The War between Armenia and Iberia ( AD 51 ) is known chiefly through its description in Tacitus ' Annals .
1 The war took place as a delicate balance of power between the Roman and Parthian empires was in place in the Caucasus .
2 Rome was then ruled by Claudius , Parthia by Vologases I.
3 Two Iberian brothers then ruled the Caucasian kingdoms , Pharasmanes I in Iberia , Mithridates in Armenia .
4 They were both dependent on Roman support , which had installed Mithridates on the Armenian throne in 35 AD .
5 However , 15 years later , trust between the brothers had deteriorated , which Tacitus blames on the intrigues of Pharasmanes ' son Rhadamistus .
6 Fearing usurpation by Rhadamistus , his father convinced him to make war upon his uncle and claim the Armenian throne for himself .
7 The Iberians invaded with a large army and surrounded Mithridates at the fortress of Gorneas ( Garni ) , which was garrisoned by the Romans under the command of Caelius Pollio , a prefect , and Casperius , a centurion .
8 Rhadamistus was unable to take the fortress by assault or by siege .
9 Pollio , swayed by bribery from Rhadamistus , betrayed Mithridates and induced the Roman soldiers to threaten the capitulation of the garrison .
10 Under this threat , Mithridates left the fortress in order to make peace with Rhadamistus .
11 Rhadamistus then executed Mithridates and his sons , despite a promise of non - violence , and became King of Armenia .
12 Of this usurpation , Tacitus wrote " Rhadamistus might retain his ill - gotten gains , as long as he was hated and infamous ; for this was more to Rome 's interest than for him to have succeeded with glory " .
13 However , faced with this upset of the regional balance and fearing that Armenia and Iberia would unite as a single powerful kingdom in the hands of Rhadamistus , Tiridates entered Armenia with Parthian support in 53 AD .
14 After 2 years of war , the Armenian nobility revolted and replaced Rhadamistus with the Arsacid prince Tiridates .
15 This was unacceptable to Rome , and started the Roman – Parthian War of 58–63 .

##title
Patriot Hills Base Camp
##doc
0 Patriot Hills Base Camp ( ) was the only private seasonally occupied camp in Antarctica .
1 It was located in the Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains , next to the Patriot Hills that give it its name .
2 The camp was run by the private company Adventure Network International ( now Antarctic Logistics & Expeditions LLC , known as ALE ) ,
3 a company that provides expedition support and tours to the interior of Antarctica .
4 It was constructed in 1987 and used during the summer months of November to January .
5 Patriot Hills was for many adventurers and explorers a stop on the way from Chile 's Punta Arenas into the interior of Antarctica .
6 The flight time from Punta Arenas is about 4.5 hours .
7 As of November 2010 ALE has moved operations .
8 Union Glacier Camp is the new base of operations and Union Glacier Blue - Ice Runway SCGC is the new runway .
9 Patriot Hills is being retained as a backup runway .
10 In the summer months the temperature rises to −15   ° C .
11 The temperature in the winter months is estimated to be about −40   ° C , but no one has yet overwintered in the Ellsworth Mountains .

##title
Vätsäri Wilderness Area
##doc
0 The Vätsäri Wilderness Area ( , ) is located along the northeastern shore of Lake Inari in Inari , northern Finland , stretching all the way to the Finland – Norway border .
1 The landscape is dominated by taiga forests of Scots pine , bog and bodies of water .
2 The northeastern part rises as a treeless fell ridge .
3 Vätsäri is one of twelve wilderness areas in Lapland and covers an area of .
4 The wilderness has one marked trail and a few cabins .
5 The reserve is under the management of Metsähallitus ( Administration of Forests ) and was established with the other wilderness reserves in 1991 .
6 It is part of Pasvik – Inari Trilateral Park along with Øvre Pasvik National Park and Øvre Pasvik Landscape Protection Area in Norway , and the joint Norwegian – Russian Pasvik Nature Reserve .
7 The area has a short growing season , cold winters , little precipitation and poor soil quality created by the gneiss bedrock .
8 Lake Inari has been affected by acid rain and loss of fish from the Paatsjoki River Hydroelectric Plants .
9 The reserve is an important habitat of the brown bear and also has a large moose population ; reindeer husbandry is practiced by the Samis .
10 Whitefish and vendace are the most common species of fish , the latter being an introduced species .

##title
Scimitar oryx
##doc
0 The scimitar oryx or scimitar - horned oryx ( Oryx dammah ) , also known as the Sahara oryx , is a species of Oryx once widespread across North Africa which went extinct in the wild in 2000 .
1 It has a long taxonomic history since its scientific description in 1816 by Lorenz Oken , who named it Oryx algazel .
2 This antelope stands a little more than at the shoulder .
3 The males weigh and the females weigh .
4 The coat is white with a red - brown chest and black markings on the forehead and down the length of the nose .
5 The calves are born with a yellow coat without distinguishing marks ; their coats change to adult coloration at 3–12 months old .
6 The scimitar oryx formed herds of mixed sexes of up to 70 members , usually guided by the bulls .
7 They inhabited semideserts and deserts and were adapted to live in the extreme heat , with their efficient cooling mechanism and very low requirement of water .
8 Scimitar oryx feed on foliage , grasses , succulent plants and plant parts during the night or early morning .
9 Births peak between March and October .
10 After a gestation of eight to nine months , one calf is born .
11 Soon after , the female has a postpartum estrus .
12 The scimitar oryx was once widespread across northern Africa .
13 Its decline began as a result of climate change during the neolithic period , and later it was hunted extensively for its horns .
14 Today , it is bred in captivity in special reserves in Tunisia , Morocco and Senegal and on private exotic animal ranches in the Texas Hill Country .
15 In 2016 a reintroduction program was launched and currently a small herd has been successfully reintroduced in Chad .
16 The scimitar oryx was domesticated in Ancient Egypt and is believed to have been used as food and sacrificed as offerings to gods .
17 Wealthy people in Ancient Rome also bred them .
18 The use of their valuable hides began in the Middle Ages .
19 The unicorn myth may have originated from sightings of a scimitar oryx with a broken horn .
20 The scimitar oryx was the emblem of the ancient Egyptian Oryx nome and today is the animal symbol of the Sahara Conservation Fund .
##labels

##title
Baunilha e chocolate
##doc
0 " Baunilha e chocolate " ( " Vanilla and chocolate " ) was the Portuguese entry in the Eurovision Song Contest 1995 , performed in Portuguese by Tó Cruz .
1 The song is inspired by urban music and features Cruz singing to his " sweetheart with white skin " while musing on their interracial relationship ( Cruz is black ) .
2 He suggests that this could only have been made possible via the intrepid maritime history of their country , and sings about the spices and cultural knowledge that were brought back to Portugal as a result of this history .
3 The song was performed sixteenth on the night , following the United Kingdom 's Love City Groove with " Love City Groove " and preceding Cyprus ' Alexandros Panayi with " Sti Fotia " .
4 At the close of voting , it had received 5 points , placing 21st in a field of 23 .
5 It was succeeded as Portuguese representative at the 1996 contest by Lúcia Moniz with " O meu coração não tem cor " .

##title
La prima notte di quiete
##doc
0 La prima notte di quiete , released in USA as Indian Summer ( from the phrase Der Nachsommer , an insignia of Goethe ) is a 1972 Italian and French drama film directed by Valerio Zurlini .
1 It is starred and produced by Alain Delon .
2 In France and Germany it runs less than the Italian cut .
3 It is known and available on DVD in France as Le Professeur ( The Professor ) and in Germany as Oktober in Rimini ( October in Rimini ) .
4 It tells the story of a gifted but restless young man who can not live up to the high traditions of his family and survives in obscurity , taking casual teaching jobs and living in a loveless partnership with a depressed woman .
5 His aimless existence reaches a crisis point when he falls for one of his pupils , a beautiful but badly damaged girl .

##title
Młociny metro station
##doc
0 Młociny is a Warsaw Metro station serving as a northern terminus to Line M1 .
1 It is situated within Warsaw administrative boundaries and ZTM ticketing zone 1 , in the dzielnica of Bielany , in a close proximity to Warsaw 's ArcelorMittal steelworks .
2 The station opened on 25 October 2008 and is the final northern extension of Line M1 .
3 The area beyond the station has been remodelled into a major public transportation junction after Młociny opened .
4 It is served by trams and both urban and suburban buses .
5 Although there are no plans to extend Line M1 further , the station is built in such way that it will be possible to do so if need be .
6 The trains are turned back at sidings behind Młociny .
7 Terminating trains arrive at eastern side platform , whereas southbound trains depart from western side platform .

##title
Sara Black
##doc
0 Sara Black ( born 1978 ) is an American artist .
1 She currently teaches at Antioch College and previously taught at Northwestern University and the School of the Art Institute of Chicago .
2 Her " performances , sculpture , installation , and collaborative works evolve around an interest in how materials move through the world and the shifting designation of values in American culture . "
3 She holds a BFA in sculpture and installation from the University of Chicago , a Bachelor of Arts in environmental studies and art from The Evergreen State College , and a Bachelor of Fine Arts in sculpture and painting from the University of Wisconsin – Eau Claire .
4 She was a co - founder of the art collective Material Exchange which was active in Chicago until 2010 and currently works collaboratively with artists Jillian Soto , Charlie Vinz and others .
5 Her work has been widely exhibited in several galleries including the Smart Museum of Art , the Experimental Station , the Museum of Contemporary Art , Chicago , the Betty Rymer Gallery , Gallery 400 , the Hyde Park Art Center , Portland State University , The Park Avenue Armory , New York , The Museum of Contemporary Craft , Portland , Eyebeam , New York and the DeVos Art Museum .

##title
Church of Saint Francis of Assisi (Ouro Preto)
##doc
0 The Church of Saint Francis of Assisi is a Rococo Catholic church in Ouro Preto , Brazil .
1 Its erection began in 1766 after a design by the Brazilian architect and sculptor Antônio Francisco Lisboa , otherwise known as Aleijadinho .
2 Lisboa designed both the structure of the church and the carved decorations on the interior , which were only finished towards the end of the 19th century .
3 The circular bell towers and the oculus closed by a relief were original features in religious architecture of that time in Brazil .
4 The façade has a single entrance door under a soapstone frontispiece under a relief depicting Saint Francis receiving the stigmata .
5 The interior is richly decorated with golden woodwork , statues and paintings , and the wooden ceiling displays a painting by Manuel da Costa Ataíde .
6 Due to its architecture and historical significance regarding eighteenth century gold mining , this church is classified on the UNESCO World Heritage List .

##title
Rudolf Halin
##doc
0 Rudolf Halin ( February 3 , 1934 , Uerdingen – November 14 , 2014 , Mölln ) was a German graph theorist , known for defining the ends of infinite graphs , for Halin 's grid theorem , for extending Menger 's theorem to infinite graphs , and for his early research on treewidth and tree decomposition .
1 He is also the namesake of Halin graphs , a class of planar graphs constructed from trees by adding a cycle through the leaves of the given tree ; earlier researchers had studied the subclass of cubic Halin graphs but Halin was the first to study this class of graphs in full generality .
2 Halin earned his doctorate from the University of Cologne in 1962 , under the supervision of Klaus Wagner and Karl Dörge , after which he joined the faculty of the University of Hamburg .
3 In February 1994 , a colloquium was held at the University of Hamburg in honor of Halin 's 60th birthday .

##title
Cimatti
##doc
0 Cimatti was an Italian manufacturer of bicycles , motorcycles and mopeds active between 1937 and 1984 .
1 In 1937 , the Olympic cyclist Marco Cimatti founded a small company in Bologna that originally produced bicycles .
2 In 1950 , he changed to mopeds , and in the 1960s , started producing motorcycles , including the and Sport Luxury road and Kaiman Cross racing models with four - speed gearboxes .
3 In 1972 – 77 , he introduced two models , one for motocross with a five - speed gearbox and the other for road .
4 In those years Cimatti 's son Enrico expanded the business to export motorcycles to the United States , France , Norway and Tunisia .
5 In the 1970s through early 1980s , Cimatti produced several moped lines including the City - Bike and the larger Town - Bike .
6 Cimatti used two - stroke engines bought from both Moto Morini and Moto Minarelli .
7 A recession in the early 1980s forced the company to close in 1984 .

##title
Olof Mörck
##doc
0 Olof Mörck ( born 12 December 1981 in Gothenburg , Sweden ) is the guitarist and one of the songwriters of the metal band Amaranthe , as well as guitarist of the power metal band Dragonland .
1 He is well known for his platinum blonde hair .
2 He was also a member of Nightrage between 2006 and 2011 as a guitarist .
3 Recently , he has provided two guitar solos for the album The Isolation Game by the Italian melodic death metal band Disarmonia Mundi .
4 In 2010 , My Darling Dismay released a video of a song with the same title .
5 The song is more of a rock style than his previous metal projects .
6 Mörck appears on the 2010 album The History of Saints by the North Carolina band Vanisher , performing the solo for the song " Oceans . "
7 Mörck provided a guest solo for Australian melodic death metal band Universum on the track , " Sum of the Universe , " from their 2011 release Mortuus Machina .
8 Mörck also provides a guest solo for Australian power metal band Lord on an instrumental song from their 2009 release Set in Stone .

##title
Addy Lee
##doc
0 Addy Lee a celebrities ' hair stylist , known for innovative methods with hair .
1 He left home in 1984 , at the age of 13 to pursue a childhood dream .
2 He was the youngest son of a grocery shop owner .
3 In his young mind , he had wished to work in an air - conditioned area where he did n't have to sweat and with nice clothes to wear .
4 In 1990 , at the age of 19 , he left his hometown in Penang and went to Singapore in search for that dream .
5 For 3 years , he moved from one establishment to another , gathering experience in both the creative art of hairdressing and the competencies of running a hair salon business .
6 Lee is , today a well known name in Singapore .
7 He possesses a wide portfolio of work that ranges from TV , print commercials , hairshows , seminars workshops and celebrities that includes famous local names like Michelle Chia , Joanne Peh , Quan Yi Fong , Mark Lee , Bryan Wong and more .
8 Lee has opened 9 salons in Singapore and Malaysia , and has started Monsoon Hair Academy to help others who wish to establish a career in the hairdressing industry .
9 He tried mesotherapy because he wanted a smaller waist , but it was painful , the injections left marks , and he did not see results .

##title
Lampedusa
##doc
0 Lampedusa (; ; ) is the largest island of the Italian Pelagie Islands in the Mediterranean Sea .
1 The comune of Lampedusa e Linosa is part of the Sicilian province of Agrigento which also includes the smaller islands of Linosa and Lampione .
2 It is the southernmost part of Italy and Italy 's southernmost island .
3 Tunisia , which is about away , is the closest landfall to the islands .
4 Sicily is farther at , whilst the island nation of Malta is to the east .
5 Lampedusa has an area of and a population of about 6,000 people .
6 Its main industries are fishing , agriculture , and tourism .
7 A ferry service links the island with Porto Empedocle , near Agrigento , Sicily .
8 There are also year - round flights from Lampedusa Airport to Palermo and Catania on the Sicilian mainland .
9 In the summer , there are additional services to Rome and Milan , besides many other seasonal links with the Italian mainland .
10 Since the early 2000s , the island has become a primary European entry point for migrants , mainly coming from Africa .
11 In 2013 , Rabbit Beach ( it .
12 " Spiaggia dei Conigli " ) , located in the southern part of the island , was voted the world 's best beach by travel site TripAdvisor .

##title
Radu Lecca
##doc
0 Radu D. Lecca ( February 15 , 1890 – 1980 ) was a Romanian spy , journalist , civil servant and convicted war criminal .
1 A World War I veteran who served a prison term for espionage in France during the early 1930s , he was a noted supporter of antisemitic concepts and , after 1933 , an agent of influence for Nazi Germany .
2 While becoming a double agent for Romania 's Special Intelligence Service ( SSI ) , Lecca was involved in fascist politics , gained in importance during World War II and the successive dictatorships , and eventually grew close to Conducător Ion Antonescu .
3 After 1941 , Lecca was Commissioner , later Commissioner General , tasked with solving the " Jewish Question " in Romania , sharing Romania 's responsibility for the Holocaust .
4 Advised by the special German envoys Manfred Freiherr von Killinger and Gustav Richter and acting with Antonescu 's consent , he established the Central Jewish Office ( Centrala Evreiască , CE ) through which he persecuted , exploited and extorted the Romanian Jewish community , whose existence was threatened by deportations into Transnistria .
5 The system he supervised was notoriously corrupt , with many of the funds extorted being used for the personal benefit of Lecca or his political associates .
6 Commissioner Lecca was also instrumental in negotiating the Final Solution 's application in Romania , a plan which was eventually abandoned , while considering mass emigration to Palestine in exchange for payments .
7 After the August 1944 Coup removed Antonescu and aligned Romania with the Allies , Lecca was among the high - ranking Romanian politicians arrested and transported to the Soviet Union .
8 Upon his 1946 return , Lecca was Antonescu 's co - defendant in a People 's Tribunal case , and was condemned to death .
9 His sentence was commuted into life imprisonment and later reduced by the communist regime .
10 After his release , Lecca wrote memoirs which make various controversial claims , and which minimize his and Antonescu 's participation in Holocaust - related crimes .

##title
Kerstin Thorborg
##doc
0 Kerstin Thorborg ( May 19 , 1896 - April 12 , 1970 )
1 Born in Venjan , Sweden , the contralto Kerstin Thorborg was one of the best dramatic Wagnerian singers in the two decades between 1930 and 1950 .
2 She made her debut in 1924 singing the difficult role of Ortrud in Lohengrin .
3 Eight years later , the famed conductor Bruno Walter engaged her for the Städtische Oper in Berlin and became her mentor .
4 Although a contralto , Thorborg 's upper register was so secure that she sang numerous mezzo - soprano roles , including Venus , Kundry , Fricka , Waltraute , and Magdalena .
5 She was especially known for her searingly beautiful Brangäne , which was preserved on record .
6 She also appears to wonderful advantage in the live recording of Mahler 's Das Lied von der Erde , with Charles Kullmann , under Bruno Walter , at the Vienna Musikverein in 1936 .
7 In 1938 , to escape the Nazis , she made her home in the United States , singing various roles at the Met .
8 She returned to her native Sweden in 1950 , after her retirement .
9 By all accounts , Thorborg was a magnificent actor with great stage presence .
10 In addition , she was endowed with a beautifully steady and intense tone .

##title
Rockefeller Brothers Fund
##doc
0 The Rockefeller Brothers Fund ( RBF ) is a philanthropic foundation created and run by members of the Rockefeller family .
1 It was founded in New York City in 1940 as the primary philanthropic vehicle for the five third - generation Rockefeller brothers : John D. Rockefeller III , Nelson , Laurance , Winthrop and David .
2 It is distinct from the Rockefeller Foundation .
3 The Rockefellers are an industrial , political , and banking family that made one of the world 's largest fortunes in the oil business during the late 19th and early 20th centuries .
4 The Fund 's stated mission is to " advance social change that contributes to a more just , sustainable , and peaceful world . "
5 The current president of RBF is Stephen Heintz , who was appointed to the post in 2000 .
6 Valerie Rockefeller serves as RBF 's chairwoman .
7 She succeeded Richard Rockefeller , the fifth child of David Rockefeller , who served as RBF 's chairman until 2013 .

##title
Omero Mumba
##doc
0 Omero James Mumba ( born 2 July 1989 ) is an Irish actor and singer .
1 Mumba was born in Dublin , Ireland , to Peter Mumba , a Zambian aircraft engineer and Barbara , who is Irish ; his sister , Samantha Mumba , is an actress and singer .
2 He features on the song " The Boy " , released on her first album Got ta Tell You .
3 In 2002 , aged 13 , he attempted a musical career of his own with his single " Lil ' Big Man " .
4 It peaked at number 42 in the UK Singles Chart .
5 After appearing in a 1995 episode of the television series , The Governor , Mumba was cast opposite his sister , Samantha , in the 2002 film version of H.G.
6 Wells ' The Time Machine .
7 He played Kalen , the brother of his sister 's character .
8 In 2009 , he had a minor role in the Irish film 3 Crosses .

##title
Elbląg County
##doc
0 Elbląg County ( ) is a unit of territorial administration and local government ( powiat ) in Warmian - Masurian Voivodeship , northern Poland .
1 It came into being on January 1 , 1999 , as a result of the Polish local government reforms passed in 1998 .
2 Its administrative seat is the city of Elbląg , although the city is not part of the county ( it constitutes a separate city county ) .
3 The county contains three towns : Pasłęk , east of Elbląg , Tolkmicko , north of Elbląg , and Młynary , north - east of Elbląg .
4 The county covers an area of .
5 As of 2006 its total population is 56,412 , out of which the population of Pasłęk is 12,179 , that of Tolkmicko is 2,731 , that of Młynary is 1,837 , and the rural population is 39,665 .

##title
Grand Wing Servo-Tech
##doc
0 Grand Wing Servo - Tech Co. , Ltd. or GWS is a Taiwanese manufacturer of foam radio controlled aircraft and accessories , including their own line of electric motors , servos , radio systems and gyros .
1 In the U.S. , the company is known as Grand Wing System with headquarters in City of Industry , California .
2 GWS was founded in 1993 and has quickly risen to become one of the leading manufacturers of RC products with sales in 2004 of more than US$ 12,000,000 .
3 The company designs and manufactures all of its own products in their own factories in both Taiwan and China , while mainly in China by now .
4 This allows GWS to be an original equipment manufacturer as well , with custom tooling and development available .
5 GWS USA , LLC was established in January 2004 to improve distribution of GWS products in North America .
6 The division handles sales , warranty , claims and partial repairs for the entire North American market as well .
7 GWS headquarters in Taiwan and subsidiary GWS China take care of claims for the rest of the world .

##title
Cinema Verity
##doc
0 Cinema Verity was a British independent television and film production company , founded in 1985 by Verity Lambert , the television producer , who named the company after herself and as a pun on the expression ' cinéma vérité ' .
1 The company 's first major venture was the 1988 feature film A Cry in the Dark , which was produced by Lambert herself and based on the infamous Azaria Chamberlain ' dingo baby ' case in Australia in the early 1980s .
2 Thereafter , the company was active mainly in television , producing two sitcoms for BBC1 , May to December ( 1989 – 94 ) and So Haunt Me ( 1992 – 94 ) and also co - produced the soap opera Eldorado ( 1992 – 93 ) .
3 Other work included the literary adaptation The Cazalets for BBC One in 2001 .
4 This programme was co - produced by actress Joanna Lumley , whose initial idea the adaptation had been .
5 The company was voluntarily dissolved in 2011 .

##title
Hang Tuah station
##doc
0 Hang Tuah station is an interchange station in the Pudu district of Kuala Lumpur , Malaysia , between the Ampang and Sri Petaling Lines ( formerly known as STAR ) and the KL Monorail .
1 Seamless physical and fare integration was achieved on 1 March 2012 when the " paid - up " or restricted areas of both the LRT and monorail stations , which previously operated as two separate stations , were linked up , allowing passengers to transfer without needing to buy new tickets for the first time since the monorail became operational in 2003 .
2 Located on the northwestern tip of Pudu , the station is in the vicinity of the Methodist Boys School , Victoria Institution , the former Pudu Prison , the Hang Tuah police station and the National Stadium .

##title
Betty Bowes
##doc
0 Betty Bowes ( July 30 , 1911 – September 12 , 2007 ) was an American painter .
1 Bowes , known for her semi - abstract work in acrylic , was born in Philadelphia , and studied at the Moore College of Art and the University of Pennsylvania .
2 She received a George W. Elkins European Fellowship .
3 During her career she exhibited widely , both in solo and in group exhibitions .
4 She was a member of the American Watercolor Society , the National Academy of Design , the National Society of Painters in Casein and Acrylic , the Audubon Artists , and the Knickerbocker Artists .
5 She won many awards and honors , including seventeen medals of honor from the American Watercolor Society ; her work is in the collections of the Philadelphia Museum of Art , the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts , the National Academy of Design , and the University of Southern California , among other organizations .
6 She married Thomas David Bowes in 1946 ; the couple divorced in 1981 .
7 At her death she left a bequest to the Francisvale Home for Smaller Animals in Radnor , Pennsylvania , and as a result a dog park in the town was named in her honor in 2016 .

##title
Ko Joo-yeon
##doc
0 Ko Joo - yeon ( born February 22 , 1994 ) is a South Korean actress who has gained attention in the Korean film industry for her roles in Blue Swallow ( 2005 ) and The Fox Family ( 2006 ) .
1 In 2007 she appeared in the horror film Epitaph as Asako , a young girl suffering from overbearing nightmares and aphasia , becoming so immersed in the role that she had to deal with sudden nosebleeds while on set .
2 Kyu Hyun Kim of Koreanfilm.org highlighted her performance in the film , saying , " [ The cast 's ] acting thunder is stolen by the ridiculously pretty Ko Joo - yeon , another Korean child actress who we dearly hope continues her film career . "

##title
Rufus Carter
##doc
0 Rufus Seaman Carter ( March 31 , 1866 – 1932 ) was a farmer and political figure in Nova Scotia , Canada .
1 He represented Cumberland County in the Nova Scotia House of Assembly from 1911 to 1920 as a Liberal member .
2 He was born in Cumberland County , Nova Scotia , the son of William Dobson Carter and Elizabeth Ann Reed .
3 Carter attended the military college in Fredericton , New Brunswick .
4 He went to sea for a time but returned to farming after his father 's death .
5 Carter was also involved in the lumber trade with the United States and Great Britain .
6 In 1894 , he married Ella Mabel Morris .
7 Carter served several years as a member of the municipal council .

##title
Pljeskavica
##doc
0 Pljeskavica ( , ) , a grilled dish of spiced meat patty mixture of pork , beef and lamb , is a national dish of Serbia , also popular in Bosnia and Herzegovina and Croatia .
1 It is a main course served with onions , kajmak ( milk cream ) , ajvar ( relish ) , and urnebes ( spicy cheese salad ) , either on plate with side dishes , or with lepinja ( flatbread , as a type of hamburger ) .
2 Recently , Pljeskavica has gained popularity elsewhere in Europe and is served in a few speciality fast food restaurants in Germany , Sweden , and Austria .
3 Varieties include the " Leskovac Pljeskavica " ( Leskovačka pljeskavica ) very spicy with onions , " Šar Pljeskavica " ( Šarska pljeskavica ) stuffed with kačkavalj cheese , " Hajduk Pljeskavica " ( Hajdučka pljeskavica ) of beef mixed with smoked pork meat , and " Vranje Pljeskavica " ( Vranjanska pljeskavica ) .
4 The Leskovac Pljeskavica is an official brand of Serbia .

##title
Lark Force
##doc
0 Lark Force was an Australian Army formation established in March 1941 during World War II for service in New Britain and New Ireland .
1 Under the command of Lieutenant Colonel John Scanlan , it was raised in Australia and deployed to Rabaul and Kavieng , aboard SS Katoomba , MV Neptuna and HMAT Zealandia , to defend their strategically important harbours and airfields .
2 The objective of the force , was to maintain a forward air observation line as long as possible and to make the enemy fight for this line rather than abandon it at the first threat as the force was considered too small to withstand any invasion .
3 Most of Lark Force was captured by the Imperial Japanese Army after Rabaul and Kavieng were captured in January 1942 .
4 The officers of Lark Force were transported to Japan , however the NCOs and men were unfortunately torpedoed by the USS Sturgeon while being transported aboard the Montevideo Maru .
5 Only a handful of the Japanese crew were rescued , with none of the between 1,050 and 1,053 prisoners aboard surviving as they were still locked below deck .

##title
Santa Elena de Uairén
##doc
0 Santa Elena de Uairén ( ) is a small Venezuelan city ( 29,795 inhabitants in 2006 ) in the state of Bolívar near the border with Brazil and Guyana .
1 It was Founded by Lucas Fernandez Peña in 1923 .
2 The city 's name originates from the first daughter of Lucas Fernandez Pena Elena , and Uairén by the river that crosses the city .
3 Located in the middle of La Gran Sabana ( Great Plains ) , Santa Elena is home to many travel agencies offering tours in Canaima National Park , flights over Angel Falls , and hiking tours to the famous Monte Roraima .
4 The town is notable for its influential presence of indigenous peoples ; there is even a community called Manakrü ( pronounced mah - nah - CREE ) populated entirely by indigenous people .
5 The schools in this neighborhood use both Spanish and Pemon , an indigenous language .
6 Due to its proximity to the Brazilian state of Roraima , Santa Elena sees a busy exchange between the two countries of Brazilian consumer products from Brazil and Venezuelan oil and petrol .
7 Other Brazilian cities that trade with Santa Elena de Uairen are Manaus , Santarém , Macapá , Belém .

##title
The Catholic Catechism (Hardon)
##doc
0 The Catholic Catechism is a major volume on the teachings of the Catholic Church written by John Hardon and published in 1975 .
1 It was written at the request of Pope Paul VI to counter the emergence of perceived rampant liberalism after the Second Vatican Council ( 1962 - 1965 ) .
2 The Catholic Catechism was a significant work in the sense that it essentially brought modern Vatican II Catholic teaching and faith into one book , unlike any other before , and was a precursor to the Catechism of the Catholic Church , which is the official codified teaching of the Catholic Church , written by Joseph Cardinal Ratzinger ( now Pope Benedict XVI ) and promulgated by Pope John Paul II in 1992 .
3 Hardon 's Catholic Catechism remains a standard work on Catholic orthodoxy even to this day .
4 The book is published with the nihil obstat and imprimatur .

##title
Vicente Genaro de Quesada
##doc
0 Vicente Genaro de Quesada ( 1782 Havana , Cuba – 15 August 1836 Madrid ) was a Spanish military figure .
1 He participated in the Battle of Burgos ( 1808 ) during the Peninsular War , leading the Royal Guard and Walloon Guard .
2 Forming a rearguard for the shattered Spanish lines , these troops absorbed repeated charges by General Lasalle 's French cavalry without yielding any ground .
3 He later fought in the First Carlist War on the Isabeline ( Liberal ) side , losing the Battle of Alsasua in April 1834 .
4 After the Mutiny of La Granja in August 1836 , he tried to suppress demonstrations in Madrid in support of restoring the Constitution of 1812 .
5 The next day , with the queen regent having acceded to the demands of the mutineers , he fled to the village of Hortaleza , but was captured and killed there by a crowd including members of the National Militia .

##title
Nicky Ladanowski
##doc
0 Nicky Ladanowski is an Los Angeles - based English actress and writer working in television , film and theatre .
1 She is known for various roles in an extensive film and television career including Merle Jackson in Coronation Street , Mandy Cutler in Paradise Heights and Mand in Grease Monkeys .
2 She is often known for playing beautiful and glamorous characters such as Anne - Marie in Hollyoaks and loveable characters such as nurse Sarah in Death Becomes Him and Lisa Trotter in The Sarah Jane Adventures for the BBC .
3 She is also famed for her many comedic roles in shows such as the BBC 's My Family and with Ricky Gervais in Extras as Les Dennis 's fiancé Simone Lewis .
4 Having starred in all of the UK 's medical drama 's Doctors , Holby City and Casualty she has recently been seen in two of the UK 's other primetime shows for ITV and Waterloo Road for the BBC .

##title
L'Oblat
##doc
0 L'Oblat ( The Oblate ) is the last novel by the French writer Joris - Karl Huysmans , first published in 1903 .
1 It is the final book in Huysmans ' cycle of four novels featuring the character Durtal , a thinly disguised portrait of the author himself .
2 Durtal had already appeared in Là - bas , En route and La cathédrale , which traced his ( and the author 's ) conversion to Catholicism .
3 In L'Oblat , Durtal becomes an oblate , reflecting Huysmans ' own experiences in the religious community at Ligugé .
4 Like many of Huysmans ' other novels , it has little plot .
5 The author uses the book to examine the Christian liturgy , express his opinions about the state of Catholicism in contemporary France and explore the question of suffering ( one notable passage describes the Garden of Gethsemane ) .

##title
Christian Hee Hwass
##doc
0 Christian Hee Hwass ( 1731 – 1803 ) was a Danish malacologist who is remembered for his work in conchology .
1 Although born in Denmark , Hwass did most of his important work in France .
2 He moved to Paris in 1780 , and later Auteuil ( 1794 ) .
3 In France , he collaborated with famous scientists Jean - Baptiste Lamarck ( 1744 – 1829 ) and Heinrich Christian Friedrich Schumacher ( 1757 – 1830 ) , a fellow Dane on a research trip in Paris during the 1780s .
4 Hwass is remembered for amassing a large shell collection that included numerous rare specimens .
5 Many European scientists used the collection as a reference work for their personal publications .
6 Hwass 's best - known written work was the 1792 publication of Encyclopedie Methodique .
7 Although his friend , Jean Guillaume Bruguière ( 1750 – 1798 ) , is often credited as author of the encyclopedia , the majority of the work was done by Hwass .

##title
Anne-Marguerite Petit du Noyer
##doc
0 Anne - Marguerite du Noyer ( Nîmes , 2 June 1663 — Voorburg , May 1719 ) was one of the most famous early 18th century female journalists .
1 Her reports of the negotiations leading to the Peace of Utrecht were read all over Europe and admired for the distinction with which she reported on scandal and gossip .
2 Born a Protestant she converted to Catholicism in the years of the Huguenot persecution .
3 In 1686 she married Guillaume du Noyer .
4 In 1701 she converted back to Calvinism and had to leave France in the event .
5 She first moved to Geneva , then to The Hague .
6 Among her famous visitors was Voltaire in 1713 .
7 The following is an extract of the biography published with the Letters from a Lady at Paris to a Lady at Avignon , vol .
8 1 ( London , W. Mears/ J. Browne , 1716 ) , the attack on Richard Steele makes Delarivier Manley a likely candidate as author of these lines :
9 Her works are appreciated in the same context :

##title
Tyche
##doc
0 Tyche (; from , Túkhē , meaning " luck " ; Roman equivalent : Fortuna ) was the presiding tutelary deity who governed the fortune and prosperity of a city , its destiny .
1 In Classical Greek mythology , she is the daughter of Aphrodite and Zeus or Hermes .
2 In literature , she might be given various genealogies , as a daughter of Hermes and Aphrodite , or considered as one of the Oceanids , daughters of Oceanus , and Tethys , or of Zeus .
3 She was connected with Nemesis and Agathos Daimon ( " good spirit " ) .
4 The Greek historian Polybius believed that when no cause can be discovered to events such as floods , droughts , frosts , or even in politics , then the cause of these events may be fairly attributed to Tyche .

##title
Baltimore and Ohio Railroad Martinsburg Shops
##doc
0 Baltimore and Ohio Railroad Martinsburg Shops is a historic industrial district in Martinsburg , West Virginia .
1 It is significant both for its railroading architecture by Albert Fink and John Rudolph Niernsee and for its role in the Great Railroad Strike of 1877 .
2 It consists of three contributing buildings , one of which is the oldest covered roundhouse in the United States .
3 The presence of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad Company in Martinsburg dates back to the late 1840s , when the first engine and machine shops were erected for the expanding company .
4 The shops were designated a National Historic Landmark and placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2003 .
5 They are now managed by a local authority as an event venue .

##title
Extraordinary Merry Christmas
##doc
0 " Extraordinary Merry Christmas " is the ninth episode and mid - season finale of the third season of the American musical television series Glee , and the fifty - third overall .
1 Written by Marti Noxon and directed by Matthew Morrison , the episode aired on Fox in the United States on December   13 , 2011 , and features the members of New Directions starring in a black - and - white Christmas television special that is presented within the episode itself .
2 Nine songs are performed over the course of the episode , eight of which come from the second Glee Christmas soundtrack album , .
3 The episode has the same name as an original song on that album , " Extraordinary Merry Christmas " , which was written for Glee by the show 's executive music producer Adam Anders , song producer Peer Åström , and Shelly Peiken .
4 The remaining eight songs are covers , and all nine were released as singles .
5 Reviewers generally praised the music in the episode .
6 Although reviewers were polarized in their views of the episode as a whole , the special within the episode received mostly favorable comments , though the rest of the episode was deemed light on plot .
7 Some aspects of the framing sequences were criticized , such as Rachel 's excessive demands for Christmas presents despite the fact that she is Jewish .
8 Upon its initial airing , this episode was viewed by 7.13   million American viewers and garnered a 3.0/8   Nielsen rating / share in the 18–49 demographic .
9 The total viewership was up marginally from the previous episode , " Hold On to Sixteen " .

##title
Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla
##doc
0 Don Miguel Gregorio Antonio Ignacio Hidalgo - Costilla y Gallaga Mandarte Villaseñor ; 8 May 1753   – 30 July 1811 ) , more commonly known as Don Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla or simply Miguel Hidalgo ( , was a Mexican Roman Catholic priest and a leader of the Mexican War of Independence .
1 He was a professor at the Colegio de San Nicolás Obispo in Valladolid and was ousted in 1792 .
2 He served in a church in Colima and then in Dolores , Dias .
3 After his arrival , he was shocked by the rich soil he had found .
4 He tried to help the poor by showing them how to grow olives and grapes , but in Mexico , growing these crops was discouraged or prohibited by the authorities due to Spanish imports of the items .
5 In 1810 he gave the famous speech , " The Cry of Dolores " , calling upon the people to protect the interest of their King Fernando VII ( held captive by Napoleon ) by revolting against the European - born Spaniards who had overthrown the Spanish Viceroy .
6 He marched across Mexico and gathered an army of nearly 90,000 poor farmers and Mexican civilians who attacked and killed both Spanish Peninsulares and Criollo elites , even though Hidalgo 's troops lacked training and were poorly armed .
7 These troops ran into an army of 6,000 well - trained and armed Spanish troops ; most of Hidalgo 's troops fled or were killed at the Battle of Calderón Bridge .

##title
Heeney, Colorado
##doc
0 Heeney is a census - designated place in northern Summit County , Colorado , United States .
1 The population as of the 2010 Census was 76 .
2 It is situated on the hillside along the west side of Green Mountain Reservoir , in the valley of the Blue River , between Kremmling and Silverthorne .
3 It is accessible by a county road from State Highway 9 .
4 The community consists of a cluster of vacation homes and permanent residences perched above the reservoir , which is a destination for recreational boating and fishing .
5 The businesses of the town include a liquor / bait and tackle store oriented towards sportsmen .
6 The U.S. Post Office at Silverthorne ( ZIP Code 80498 ) now serves Heeney postal addresses .
7 A post office called Heeney was established in 1939 , and remained in operation until 1960 .
8 The community has the name of Paul Heeney , a local property owner .

##title
Rachel Perry (artist)
##doc
0 Rachel Perry ( born 1962 , formerly Rachel Perry Welty ) is an American artist .
1 She is known for conceptual works using drawing , photography , video , collage , sculpture and performance , which address “ the fleeting nature of experience , the elusiveness of desire , and the persistence of objects in a throwaway culture . ” Art critic Jerry Saltz has written that her work " not only grappl[es ] with consumerism but [ she is ] just about swallowed whole by it . ” Her work also considers themes of gender identity , narcissism , privacy and information overload .
2 She has exhibited widely throughout the United States and internationally , including a solo exhibition at Yancey Richardson Gallery in 2015 , about which art critic Roberta Smith wrote , “ … obsessive delights await in this strange and beautiful show … ”
3 She lives and works in Gloucester , Massachusetts and Brooklyn , New York .

##title
Nikita Bogoslovsky
##doc
0 Nikita Vladimirovich Bogoslovsky (; May 22 , 1913 in Saint - Petersburg , Russian Empire – April 4 , 2004 in Moscow , Russia ) was a Soviet Russian composer , author of more than 200 songs , 8 symphonies ( 1940 – 1991 ) , 17 operettas and musical comedies , 58 soundtracks , and 52 scores for theater productions .
1 Bogoslovsky is best known for two Mark Bernes 's trademark songs from the Great Patriotic War film Two Fighters ( Dva boitsa , 1943 ) , " Tyomnaya noch " ( Dark Night ) and " Shalandy polnye kefali " ( Boats Full of Mullets ) .
2 Among his many honorary titles and State awards were People 's Artist of the USSR ( 1983 ) , Order of the Red Banner of Labour ( 1971 ) , and Order of the Red Star ( 1946 ) .

##title
Lumia imaging apps
##doc
0 Lumia imaging apps are imaging applications by Microsoft Mobile and formerly by Nokia for Lumia devices built on the technology of Scalado ( except for Lumia Panorama which was developed earlier by Nokia originally for Symbian and MeeGo devices ) .
1 The Lumia imaging applications were notably all branded with " Nokia " in front of their names , but after Microsoft acquired Nokia 's devices and services business the Nokia branding was superseded with " Lumia " , and often updates included nothing but name changes , but for the Lumia Camera this included a new wide range of feature additions .
2 Most of the imaging applications are developed by the Microsoft Lund division .
3 As part of the release of Windows 10 Mobile and the integration of Lumia imaging features into the Windows Camera and Microsoft Photos applications some of these applications stopped working in October 2015 .

##title
Pointr
##doc
0 Pointr is a startup company based in London specialized in indoor positioning and navigation utilising iBeacons , which are Bluetooth Low Energy devices formalised by Apple Inc. Pointr have created a GPS - like experience with true position and turn - by - turn navigation that is supported by most modern smartphones operating on both Android and iOS .
1 Analytics and messaging modules can be added on to help communicate with users and understand venue usage respectively .
2 The features are provided through a software package ( SDK ) which aims to improve user experience whilst connecting the online and offline worlds .
3 Many of the features are available without an internet connection , including sending messages between users with a form of Mesh networking , however for intelligent offers and live analytics then an internet connection is required .
4 The markets where the technology is most frequently used are retail , exhibition centres , airports and museums , but there are a number of uses in hospitals , warehouses , offices and entertainment venues as well .
5 The majority of software development is done in their office in Istanbul , with specialist modules created in London .
6 The technology is commonly used in permanent installations where the SDK is offered with a license fee model , however some installations have been temporary and hence one - off payments have been used .
##labels

iOS, Apple Inc., founded by(P112), []

##title
The Colts (vocal group)
##doc
0 The Colts : also known ( as Four Colts & a Filly ) , is an American vocal group from Bakersfield , California .
1 The group 's founding members consisted of a four - man line - up : lead singer Ruben Grundy , his brother Joe Grundy , Carl Moland .
2 In 1955 , while attending L.A. City College , in Los Angeles , New Jersey native Leroy Smith had joined the group .
3 The following year later , the Colts had added singer : Mel Williams wife , Mickey Lynn , to their lineup , and changed the group 's name to Four Colts & a Filly .
4 The Colts is best known for their version , the first recording of the popular doowop classic " Adorable . "
5 The Colts is also the first African American vocal group ever coming out of the San Joaquin Valley from Kern county .

##title
Eleazar Lipsky
##doc
0 Eleazar Lipsky ( September 6 , 1911 – February 14 , 1993 ) was a prosecutor , lawyer , novelist and playwright born in the Bronx , New York , United States .
1 He wrote the novels that formed the basis of two very successful films , Kiss of Death ( based on a 100-page manuscript ) and The People Against O'Hara ( based on his detective novel ) .
2 Other novels include Lincoln McKeever ( 1953 ) , The Devil 's Daughter ( Meredith Press , 1969 , based on the legal troubles of William Sharon ) and The Scientists ( 1959 ) , a Book - of - the - Month Club selection .
3 Lipsky , who practiced law until three weeks before his death , was an assistant district attorney for Manhattan in the 1940s and later had a diversified law practice in Manhattan and served as legal counsel to the Mystery Writers of America .
4 Lipsky was active in many Jewish organizations .

##title
Tartu
##doc
0 Tartu ( , South Estonian : Tarto ) is the second largest city of Estonia , after Estonia 's political and financial capital Tallinn .
1 Tartu is often considered the intellectual centre of the country , especially since it is home to the nation 's oldest and most renowned university , the University of Tartu .
2 The city also houses the Supreme Court of Estonia , the Ministry of Education and Research , and the new building of the Estonian National Museum , opened to the public in October 2016 .
3 It is also the birthplace of Estonian Song Festivals .
4 Situated southeast of Tallinn and 245 kilometres ( 152 miles ) northeast of Riga , Tartu lies on the Emajõgi ( " Mother river " ) , which connects the two largest lakes of Estonia .
5 The city is served by Tartu Airport .

##title
Peadar Bracken
##doc
0 Peadar Bracken ( 23 January 1887 – January 19 , 1961 ) was an Irish freedom fighter during Ireland 's War of Independence .
1 In 1914 he was elected Captain by the men of the Tullamore Company Irish Volunteers , before later being appointed Commandant of the Athlone Brigade area by Padraig Pearse .
2 Bracken , alongside his comrade Seamus Brennan are credited with firing the first ever shots in the 1916 rising in Tullamore .
3 Bracken was under order from Padraig Pearse and took command off him for the duration of the 1916 rising .
4 He commanded the critical GPO garrison outpost at O'Connell Bridge , Dublin during the Easter Rising .
5 Later on in his career , in 1920 , he was a senior officer in the Irish Republican Brotherhood branch in Tullamore , and commanding officer in chief of the Athlone Brigade .
6 Bracken died in January 19 , 1961 .

##title
Iowa Telecom
##doc
0 Iowa Telecommunications Services , Inc. , commonly known as Iowa Telecom , provided local telephone service to former GTE customers in the U.S. states of Iowa , Missouri , Illinois , and Minnesota .
1 Iowa Telecom was founded in 1999 as a partnership between Iowa Network Services and ING Barings .
2 It acquired the assets of GTE Midwest , which served Iowa following Bell Atlantic 's purchase of GTE .
3 It had 257,700 access lines and served 435 communities in Iowa .
4 In 2002 Iowa Telecom bought PC Partner Communications and Zumatel Communications .
5 On February 7 , 2008 , Iowa Telecom bought Lakedale Communications , Sherbtel Comminuations , Conntections - ETC , and SOMA , all located in Minnesota .
6 At that time it also acquired Willinet in New York .
7 On November 24 , 2009 Iowa Telecom was acquired by Windstream .
8 Its telephone directories were published by Pinnacle Publishing .

##title
Viscount Alanbrooke
##doc
0 Viscount Alanbrooke , of Brookeborough in the County of Fermanagh , was a title in the Peerage of the United Kingdom .
1 It was created on 29 January 1946 for Field Marshal Alan Brooke , 1st Baron Alanbrooke .
2 He had already been created Baron Alanbrooke , of Brookeborough in the County of Fermanagh , on 18 September 1945 , also in the Peerage of the United Kingdom .
3 Brooke was the sixth son of Sir Victor Brooke , 3rd Baronet , and the uncle of Sir Basil Brooke , 5th Bt .
4 ( created Viscount Brookeborough in 1952 ) , the Prime Minister of Northern Ireland from May 1943 until March 1963 .
5 Field Marshal Lord Alanbrooke was succeeded by his elder son , Thomas , who was unmarried and had no children .
6 The titles were then held by his half - brother , Alan Brooke 's younger son , also named Alan ( but popularly known as Victor ) .
7 The 3rd Viscount died on 10 January 2018 and the viscountcy became extinct on his death .

##title
Gei Zantzinger
##doc
0 Alfred Geist Zantzinger ( April 6 , 1936 – February 16 , 2007 ) was an American documentary filmmaker specializing in documentaries about traditional musics of the world .
1 He directed and produced films about the musics of Mozambique , Zimbabwe , Cape Verde , Lesotho , South Africa , and Brittany .
2 He was the grandson of noted Philadelphia architect Clarence C. Zantzinger .
3 He graduated from Westminster School in Connecticut and earned bachelor 's and master 's degrees in folklore and anthropology from the University of Pennsylvania .
4 Zantzinger began making films in southern Africa in 1966 , while a Ph.D. candidate in the folklore / folklife program at the University of Pennsylvania .
5 He studied film with Sol Worth at the University of Pennsylvania 's Annenberg School of Communications .
6 Zantzinger also worked as a record producer .
7 He lived in Devault , Chester County , Pennsylvania , where his production company , Constant Spring Productions , was based .
8 He died of leukemia on February 16 , 2007 , at the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania .

##title
Kusha (Ramayana)
##doc
0 Kusha or Kusa ( Sanskrit : कुश ) and his twin brother Lava were the children of Rama and Sita .
1 Their story is recounted in the Hindu epic , the Ramayana .
2 Hindu traditions claim he ruled the entire region of Kashmir , Indus River and Hindu Kush as frontier lands of India known as Hindu Kush Kshetra and founded the city of Kashmir in the valley and Kasur with Lavapuri of lava in base lands , though local lore contends Kasur was founded in 1525 by Pashtun migrants .
3 His brother Lava is traditionally believed to have founded Lavapuri ( current day city of Lahore ) .
4 The imperial line that ruled Kingdom of Benares - Kashi and the Maurya Empire , which ruled South Asia from 320 - 185 BCE , claimed descent from Kusha .
5 Kusha is said to be an Raghuvanshi Ikshvaku Suryavanshi .

##title
Pavol Sedlák
##doc
0 Pavol Sedlák ( born 21 November 1979 in Bratislava ) is a Slovak footballer , who currently plays for SK Schwadorf and also assistant manager in the Slovak giant ŠK Slovan Bratislava .
1 His former clubs were MŠK Rimavská Sobota and ŠK Slovan Bratislava .
2 He previously played for FK DAC 1904 Dunajská Streda .
3 He is a midfielder with a lot of international experience .
4 He is well known for his dribbling ability and super strong shots from medium distances .
5 Together with Samuel Slovák , he is one of the leaders inside the squad of the club .
6 He previously played for Turkish Turkcell Super League club Gaziantepspor , Çaykur Rizespor , 1 .
7 FC Brno , Dukla Banská Bystrica , FC Rimavská Sobota and Slovan Bratislava .

##title
Odessa (Bee Gees album)
##doc
0 Odessa is the sixth studio album by the Bee Gees , originally released on 30 March 1969 .
1 Regarded as the most significant of the group 's Sixties albums , it was released as a double vinyl record initially in an opulent red flocked cover with gold lettering .
2 An ambitious project , originally intended as a concept album on the loss of a fictional ship in 1899 , it created tension and disagreements in the band regarding the album 's direction ; finally , a dispute over which song to release as a single led to Robin Gibb temporarily leaving the group .
3 The album was not well received by the public or the music press on release , and led to a decline in the group 's fortunes until their disco period in the mid 1970s .
4 Released in March 1969 by Polydor Records in the UK and Atco Records in the US , it was the group 's fourth album released internationally , their sixth overall , and their only double album of original music .
5 Odessa would be the final album for the band 's original incarnation , and this was the last album to include guitarist Vince Melouney .
6 The album contains " First of May " , " Lamplight " , " Marley Purt Drive " and " Melody Fair " .
7 The album was reissued as a single - disc in 1976 when interest was revived in the Bee Gees career , since then the album has gained increasing critical acclaim ; it was reissued again in 2009 as a deluxe 3 disc set , and is included in 1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die .

##title
Louis Lombardi
##doc
0 Louis Lombardi ( born January 17 , 1968 ) is an American actor .
1 Lombardi was born in The Bronx , New York City , the son of Louis Lombardi , Sr . On television , Lombardi had a recurring role on The Sopranos as Agent Skip Lipari , and guest starred on such shows as Entourage , Heroes and .
2 He was a cast member of a 1990s revival of Fantasy Island and played Edgar Stiles on 24 .
3 He also played Stucky Fein in the short - lived television show Mob City .
4 He has had roles in films including Beer League , The Usual Suspects , Natural Born Killers , Suicide Kings , Beverly Hills Cop III , The Animal , Spider - Man 2 , 3000 Miles to Graceland , The Crew , The Hot Chick , The Spirit , Battleship , and Jersey Boys .
5 He also wrote and directed the film Dough Boys , released in 2008 .

##title
Electoral district of Frankston East
##doc
0 Electoral district of Frankston East was an electoral district of the Legislative Assembly in the Australian state of Victoria .
1 It was created in 1992 , mostly out of the old Frankston North .
2 The seat is notable for having decided the 1999 state election , which proved to be the last election in which it was contested .
3 The incumbent , Liberal - turned - independent Peter McLellan , died on election day , forcing a supplementary election a month later .
4 Neither the Coalition nor Labor had won a majority , placing the balance of power in the hands of three independents .
5 They deferred their decision until the supplementary election .
6 In the 16 October supplementary election , Labor candidate Matt Viney won on a swing of 7.7 percent , resulting in a hung parliament .
7 The independents then announced their support for Labor , making Labor leader Steve Bracks premier .

##title
Goodooga, New South Wales
##doc
0 Goodooga is a village in the Australian state of New South Wales in Brewarrina Shire on the eastern bank of the Bokhara River .
1 It is near Brewarrina and Lightning Ridge , its closest neighbour .
2 The town lies 20 kilometres south of the Queensland border .
3 Goodooga is an Aboriginal word meaning , according to some " Yam " .
4 However it has been proposed that it derives from " guduu+ga " , ' at the place of the Murray cod ' [ guduu ] , rather than " gudugaa " , a species of yam .
5 At the 2006 census , Goodooga had a population of 265 , with 81 % of the population of Aboriginal descent .
6 Goodooga 's newspaper is the Goodooga Flash .
7 Goodooga 's main sport is Rugby league , the Goodooga Magpies or the Goodooga ' Newtown ' Jets .
8 The other sports played in town are Netball , Bowls and Basketball .

##title
Delia Gallagher
##doc
0 Delia Buckley Gallagher ( born 11 March 1970 ) is an American journalist based in Rome who currently serves as the Senior Editor for Inside the Vatican magazine .
1 She formerly served as CNN ’s Faith and Values Correspondent .
2 Based in New York , Gallagher was a long time CNN Vatican Analyst , Vaticanologist , and religious journalist .
3 Prior to joining CNN full time , she lived in Rome for 7 years .
4 In Rome , she wrote a weekly column for Zenit News Agency and was a contributing editor for the magazine .
5 The History Channel Documentary , " Angels and Demons Decoded " released by A & E Television Networks profiled Gallagher commenting on Dan Brown 's bestseller book which was made into a movie .
6 Subsequently , Gallagher moderated the Angels and Demons movie press conference film debut in Rome on stage with Tom Hanks , Ron Howard and Dan Brown often speaking in Italian and English .
7 She knows Pope Benedict XVI personally and travelled extensively with John Paul II , including his last trip to Poland .
8 Upon the death of Pope John Paul II , she broadcast and commented for CNN Worldwide covering the unfolding event .

##title
Bill DeMott
##doc
0 William Charles DeMott II ( born November 10 , 1966 ) is an American retired professional wrestler and road agent .
1 He is best known for his appearances with World Championship Wrestling ( WCW ) as Hugh Morrus and World Wrestling Federation / Entertainment ( WWF / E ) under his real name .
2 DeMott also performed as Crash the Terminator in both Extreme Championship Wrestling ( ECW ) and Japan .
3 He was most recently the head trainer for WWE 's developmental system NXT until his resignation in 2015 following allegations of misconduct , which he denied .
4 Generally used as a jobber to the stars in WCW , he attained championship success during the promotion 's dying days in late 2000 and early 2001 , holding the WCW United States Heavyweight Championship twice .
5 After an unsuccessful stint as a performer in WWE , DeMott retired from in - ring competition and transitioned into the role of a trainer for the company 's Tough Enough program , on which he became known for using a rough , controversial style in handling trainees , as well as WWE 's developmental territories Deep South Wrestling , Florida Championship Wrestling , and NXT .

##title
Western Ukraine
##doc
0 Western Ukraine or West Ukraine ( ) is a geographical and historical relative term used in reference to the western territories of Ukraine .
1 It includes several actual historical regions such as Transcarpathia , Halychyna including Pokuttia , most of Volhynia , northern Bukovina as well as western Podolia .
2 Less often it includes territories of eastern Volhynia , Podolia , and small portion of northern Bessarabia ( eastern part of Chernivtsi Oblast ) .
3 Important cities are Buchach , Chernivtsi , Drohobych , Halych ( hence - Halychyna ) , Ivano - Frankivsk , Khotyn , Lutsk , Lviv , Mukacheve , Rivne , Ternopil , Uzhhorod and others .
4 Western Ukraine is not an administrative category within Ukraine .
5 It is defined mainly in the context of European history pertaining to the 20th - century wars and the ensuing period of annexations .
6 At the onset of World War II the whole territory was incorporated into the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic ( УРСР ) , following elections which are acknowledged as staged and specifically for the purpose to manufactured public consent for the transfer of land from occupied Poland to the Soviet Union as of October 22 , 1939 .
7 Its historical background makes Western Ukraine uniquely different from the rest of the country , and contributes to its distinctive character of today .

##title
Sonic the Hedgehog
##doc
0 Sonic the Hedgehog is a media franchise created and produced by Sega .
1 It is primarily a video game franchise , centering on a series of speed - based platform games .
2 Sonic , the protagonist , is an anthropomorphic blue hedgehog with supersonic speed , capable of reaching the speed of sound .
3 Typically , Sonic — usually along with some of his friends , such as Tails , Amy , and Knuckles — must stop antagonist Doctor Eggman 's plans for world domination .
4 The first game in the series , released in 1991 , was conceived by Sega 's Sonic Team division after Sega requested a mascot character .
5 Its success spawned many sequels and helped Sega become one of the leading video game companies during the 16-bit era of the early 1990s .
6 While the first Sonic games were side - scrolling platform games , later games expanded into other genres , such as Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games .
7 The series and its spin - offs had sold over 89million physical copies by March 2011 , and grossed over by 2014 .
8 As of 2018 , the series has shifted 800million units , including free - to - play mobile game downloads .
9 The franchise has also been spun out into other media , including cartoons , anime , and a comic book series recognized as the longest running based on a video game by Guinness World Records .

##title
Louis Chollet
##doc
0 Louis Chollet ( 5 April 1815 in Paris - 21 March 1851 , Paris ) was a French organist and composer for piano , choir and orchestra .
1 He was admitted to Pierre Zimmermann 's piano class at the Conservatoire de Paris aged ten in 1826 and two years later won first prize for piano .
2 In 1834 he succeeded Jean - Nicolas Marrigues as organist of the church of Saint - Thomas d’Aquin in Paris , holding it until his death and being succeeded there by Pierre - Edmond Hocmelle .
3 In 1837 he also won first - ever second prize in the Prix de Rome competition .
4 He completed his organ training under by François Benoist in 1838 , winning first prize in organ that year .

##title
Subramaniapuram
##doc
0 Subramaniapuram is a 2008 Tamil - language period drama film produced , written , and directed by M. Sasikumar .
1 The low - budget film received critical acclaim for its original script , expert direction , screenplay , editing , accurate sets and costumes to resurrect Madurai from the 1980s .
2 Sasikumar cast then relatively new actors Jai , Swathi , Ganja Karuppu and himself in pivotal roles .
3 Shot in 85 days , it became one of the biggest commercial successes of the year .
4 The movie was dubbed into Malayalam under the same name and remade in Kannada in 2012 as Prem Adda .
5 Director Anurag Kashyap had revealed twice that this movie was the inspiration for his Gangs of Wasseypur series - once in 2010 and once on the 10th anniversary of this movie .

##title
Jonathan Sayeed
##doc
0 Jonathan Sayeed ( born 20 March 1948 ) is a British politician who was a Conservative Member of Parliament in the United Kingdom from 1983 to 1992 and from 1997 to 2005 .
1 He was the only member of the Conservative front bench who consistently , openly and publicly opposed the invasion of Iraq in 2003 .
2 Even though he was reselected by the Mid Bedfordshire Conservative Association as the Conservative candidate to recontest his seat in the House of Commons shortly before the 2005 General Election , he was forced to retire by ill health .
3 He was criticised by the Committee on Standards and Privileges for being " at the least negligent , at the worst careless " in respect of a company in which he had an interest but was completely cleared of any impropriety .
4 In the investigation by Sir Thomas Legg into MPs expenses he was one of the minority of MPs who were completely cleared of any misuse of their second home allowances .

##title
TMF (UK &amp; Ireland)
##doc
0 TMF ( The Music Factory ) was a music video and entertainment channel in the United Kingdom and Ireland .
1 The channel was owned by Viacom International Media Networks and was originally a Dutch channel .
2 Formed after the two other TMF stations , which are based in mainland Europe , the channel was created to counter against EMAP 's The Hits channel ( now 4Music ) on the new free - to - air digital terrestrial television service Freeview in 2002 .
3 Upon launch , TMF 's description was " TMF is designed to replicate the rhythms of the whole family , playing the best pop videos with the biggest pop stars to become the sound track to the British family life . "
4 However , it had since broadened its content to show programmes from its sister channels MTV , VH1 , Nick Jr. and Comedy Central , so no longer relied on just music videos .
5 TMF broadcast on Freeview , Sky and Virgin Media and as well as in some Irish cable packages .
6 The channel was the most viewed music video related station in the UK , according to BARB ratings .
7 TMF had a new look on screen graphics in March 2008 to match the other British MTV channels .
8 The previous on screen graphics were used since July 2005 and the original on screen graphics were used since October 2002 .
9 The original DOG was on the top right of the screen , it has been moved to the top left of the screen since July 2005 .
10 The new look TMF still used the old pre-2007 TMF logo whereas both the Dutch and Belgian TMF channels adapted the new logo .
11 The DOG on music programmes was TMF : Music .

##title
Stars and Stripes Forever (film)
##doc
0 Stars and Stripes Forever is a 1952 American Technicolor film biography of the late-19th-/early-20th - century composer and band leader John Philip Sousa .
1 This 20th Century Fox feature was produced by Lamar Trotti , directed by Henry Koster , and stars Clifton Webb , Debra Paget , Robert Wagner , and Ruth Hussey .
2 The film 's title is taken from Sousa 's " The Stars and Stripes Forever " , which has become the best known of his military marches .
3 While the film 's storyline is loosely based on Sousa 's autobiography Marching Along , the film takes considerable liberties and dramatic license , often expanding and examining themes and passages from Sousa 's book .
4 Two examples : In the film , Private Willie Little ( Robert Wagner ) , is credited with inventing the Sousaphone and naming it after his mentor , but in reality Sousa himself designed the instrument .
5 The inspiration for the film 's title march is depicted in a scene with a voice over by Webb quoting Sousa 's actual description of its creation while he was aboard ship recovering from typhoid fever .
6 In reality , having learned of the sudden death of his band 's manager , Sousa and his wife canceled their European vacation and were returning to the U.S. by steamship when the march came to him .

##title
Queen of Mauritius
##doc
0 Elizabeth II was Queen of Mauritius from 1968 to 1992 .
1 Mauritius was a constitutional monarchy with Elizabeth as head of state .
2 The Queen was also the monarch of the United Kingdom and the other Commonwealth realms .
3 Her constitutional roles in Mauritius were delegated to a Governor - General .
4 The Parliament of the United Kingdom 's Mauritius Independence Act 1968 transformed the British Crown Colony of Mauritius into an independent sovereign state .
5 Unusually , no member of the British royal family attended the independence ceremony on the island because of security concerns .
6 Princess Alexandra was due to attend but after communal violence the British Minister of State for the Commonwealth , Lord Shepherd , advised that her visit be cancelled .
7 The Queen and her husband Prince Philip , Duke of Edinburgh , visited Mauritius for three days ( 24–26 March ) in 1972 , as part of a tour of Asia and Africa .
8 They arrived in Port Louis on the royal yacht Britannia after visiting the Seychelles .
9 They were met by a crowd of nearly a quarter of a million people , and rode through the city in an open - topped car .
10 During the visit , the Queen opened the sixth session of the third Mauritius Parliament .
11 The royal couple left Mauritius for Nairobi by air .
12 It was the first ever visit to the island by a reigning monarch .
13 Mauritius became a republic within the Commonwealth in 1992 with the President of Mauritius replacing the Queen as head of state .
14 To date , Mauritius is the most recent of the Queen 's realms to become a republic .
##labels

##title
Kungliga Hovkapellet
##doc
0 Kungliga Hovkapellet ( , The Royal Court Orchestra ) is a Swedish orchestra , originally part of the Royal Court in Sweden 's capital Stockholm .
1 Its existence was first recorded in 1526 .
2 Since 1773 it is part of the Royal Swedish Opera 's company .
3 Kungliga Hovkapellet is one of the oldest active orchestras in the world .
4 It was first recorded in the royal account books from 1526 .
5 The orchestra originally consisted of both musicians and singers .
6 It had only male members until 1727 , when Sophia Schröder and Judith Fischer were employed as vocalists ; in the 1850s , the harpist Marie Pauline Åhman became the first female instrumentalist .
7 It had a golden age under the leadership of several members of the Düben family during the 17th century .
8 In the 18th century , its directors included Johan Helmich Roman and Francesco Uttini .
9 From 1731 , public concerts were performed at Riddarhuset in Stockholm .
10 Since 1773 , when the Royal Swedish Opera was founded by Gustav III of Sweden , the Kungliga Hovkapellet has been part of the opera 's company .

##title
Asian Games
##doc
0 The Asian Games , also known as Asiad , is a continental multi - sport event held every four years among athletes from all over Asia .
1 The Games were regulated by the Asian Games Federation ( AGF ) from the first Games in New Delhi , India , until the 1978 Games .
2 Since the 1982 Games , they have been organized by the Olympic Council of Asia ( OCA ) , after the breakup of the Asian Games Federation .
3 The Games are recognized by the International Olympic Committee ( IOC ) and are described as the second largest multi - sport event after the Olympic Games .
4 In its history , nine nations have hosted the Asian Games .
5 Forty - six nations have participated in the Games , including Israel , which was excluded from the Games after their last participation in 1974 .
6 The most recent games was held in Jakarta and Palembang , Indonesia from 18 August to 2 September 2018 .
7 The next games are scheduled to Hangzhou , China between 10 and 25 September 2022 .
8 Since 2010 , host cities are contracted to manage both the Asian Games and the Asian Para Games , in which athletes with physical disabilities compete with one another .
9 The Asian Para Games are held immediately following the Asian Games .
