##title
Admission to the Union
##doc
0 The Admission to the Union Clause of the United States Constitution , oftentimes called the New States Clause , and found at Article IV , Section 3 , , authorizes the Congress to admit new states into the United States beyond the thirteen already in existence at the time the Constitution went into effect .
1 The Constitution went into effect on June 21 , 1788 , after ratification by 9 of the 13 states , and the federal government began operations under it on March 4 , 1789 .
2 Since then , 37 additional states have been admitted into the Union .
3 Each new state has been admitted on an equal footing with those already in existence .
4 Of the 37 states admitted to the Union by Congress , all but six have been established within an existing U.S. organized incorporated territory .
5 A state so created might encompass all or a portion of a territory .
6 When the people of a territory or a region thereof would make their desire for statehood known to the federal government , in most cases Congress passed an enabling act authorizing the people of that territory or region to frame a proposed state constitution as a step toward admission to the Union .
7 Although the use of an enabling act was a common historic practice , a number of states were admitted to the Union without one .
8 In many instances , an enabling act would detail the mechanism by which the territory would be admitted as a state following ratification of their constitution and election of state officers .
9 Although the use of such an act is a traditional historic practice , a number of territories have drafted constitutions for submission to Congress absent an enabling act and were subsequently admitted .
10 The broad outline for this process was established by the Land Ordinance of 1784 and the 1787 Northwest Ordinance , both of which predate the present U.S. Constitution .
11 The Admission to the Union Clause also forbids the creation of new states from parts of existing states without the consent of both the affected states and Congress .
12 The primary intent of this caveat was to give Eastern states that still had western land claims ( there were four at that time ) a veto over whether their western counties could become states .
13 This clause has served the same function since , each time a proposal to partition an existing state or states has arisen .

##title
Glandularia
##doc
0 Glandularia , common name mock vervain or mock verbena , is a genus of annual and perennial herbaceous flowering plants in the family Verbenaceae .
1 They are native to the Americas .
2 Glandularia species are closely related to the true vervains and sometimes still included with them in Verbena .
3 Horizontal chloroplast transfer occurred at least twice and possibly three times between these genera , which are otherwise too distinct to warrant unification .
4 The discovery of the signal in the chloroplast genome was announced in 2008 by researchers from the University of Washington .
5 Somehow , chloroplasts from V.   orcuttiana , swamp verbena ( V.   hastata ) or a close relative of these had admixed into the G.   bipinnatifida genome .
6 Although hybridization runs rampant in the true and mock vervains – the ancestors of the well - known garden vervain are quite obscure – it does not seem to have been the cause of the cross - species gene transfer .
7 In addition , the researchers discovered the signal of one more transfer event .
8 This had introduced chloroplasts from an ancestral member of the Verbena lineage nowadays found in South America into Glandularia .
9 Although all members of the present genus can be distinguished to have a chromosome count of five , the South American species are diploid , while polyploid hybrid Glandularia are very widespread from northern Central America northwards .
10 The second genetic introgression must have occurred before the genus spread north , as species with the Verbena - like chloroplasts are found all over the Americas .
11 Since the new chloroplast genes replaced the old ones , it may be that the possibly hybridogenic G.   bipinnatifida actually underwent horizontal chloroplast transfer twice in its evolutionary history .

##title
List of Spanish inventions and discoveries
##doc
0 The following list is composed of items , techniques and processes that were invented by or discovered by people from Spain .
1 Spain was an important center of knowledge during the medieval era .
2 While most of western and southern Europe suffered from the collapse of the Roman Empire , although declining , some regions of the former empire , Hispania ( the Iberian Peninsula ) , southern Italy , and the remainder of the Eastern Roman Empire or Byzantine Empire , did not to suffer from the full impact of the so - called Dark Ages when education collapsed with the collapse of the empire and most knowledge was lost .
3 The Islamic conquests of places such as Egypt , which was a major part of the Byzantine Empire , and other places which were centers of knowledge in earlier times , gave the Muslims access to knowledge from many cultures which they translated into Arabic and recorded in books for the use of their own educated elites , who flourished in this period , and took with them to the Hispania after it fell under Muslim control .
4 Much of this knowledge was later translated by Christian and Jewish scholars in the Christian kingdoms of the Reconquista from Arabic into Latin , and from there it spread through Europe .

##title
Association of Australian Artistes
##doc
0 The Association of Australian Artistes was established in London in 1975 by Australian expatriate James Hunt .
1 It was based at Australia House and its aims and objectives were to present new Australian plays around London 's Fringe featuring professional Australian actors then living in London .
2 The inaugural Production Coordinator was Barbara Angell and a fund - raising concert was held in the Australia House basement on Sunday , 25 January 1976 , coinciding with the Australia Day Weekend .
3 Monies raised supported the group during its lifetime .
4 Members included Ken Shorter , Darlene Johnson , Bob Hornery , Mark McManus .
5 Playwrights who were premiered in London included Steve J. Spears .
6 The Association continued for about 2 years , presenting at such as The Arts Theatre , The Gate and various pub rooms until security measures during the IRA bombing campaign inhibited audience attendances .

##title
Aramis Ayala
##doc
0 Aramis Ayala ( born February 2 , 1975 ) is the State Attorney for the Ninth Judicial Circuit Court of Florida .
1 Ayala was elected in November 2016 , and serves as the chief prosecutor .
2 Ayala was born in Saginaw , Michigan , and graduated from the University of Michigan with an undergraduate degree .
3 She then obtained her law degree from the University of Detroit .
4 Controversy arose after she announced she would not seek capital punishment in any case , causing Governor Rick Scott to reassign potential death penalty cases to another State Attorney .
5 Ayala has filed lawsuits disputing this action in the Supreme Court of Florida , and in federal court .
6 Ayala lost her Supreme Court case against Gov Rick Scott .
7 The Florida Supreme Court ruled against Ayala saying the Governor was within his power to take cases away from Ayala because of her position to abandon the death penalty .

##title
TY.O
##doc
0 TY.O is the third studio album by British record producer and recording artist Taio Cruz .
1 Taking a more electronic music sound than his previous releases , TY.O was released in December 2011 by Universal Island Records but for reasons unknown to Cruz , its British and American release were held off .
2 Instead , a year after its original release , an extended play ( EP ) version of the album titled The Fast Hits was released in the UK on 16 December 2012 .
3 TY.O features a range of top - twenty and top - thirty singles including " Hangover " ( featuring Flo Rida ) , " Troublemaker " , " There She Goes " ( sometimes featuring Pitbull ) , the limited release " World in Our Hands " and " Fast Car " which features on the Special Edition and Fast Hits versions of the album .
4 The album itself reached top - twenty in Switzerland and top - thirty in Germany , considerably less successful than Cruz 's previous albums .

##title
Historiographic metafiction
##doc
0 Historiographic metafiction is a term coined by Canadian literary theorist Linda Hutcheon in the late 1980s .
1 The term is used for works of fiction which combine the literary devices of metafiction with historical fiction .
2 Works regarded as historiographic metafiction are also distinguished by frequent allusions to other artistic , historical and literary texts ( i.e.
3 intertextuality ) in order to show the extent to which works of both literature and historiography are dependent on the history of discourse .
4 The term is closely associated with works of postmodern literature , usually novels .
5 According to Hutcheon , in " A Poetics of Postmodernism " , works of historiographic metafiction are " those well - known and popular novels which are both intensely self - reflexive and yet paradoxically also lay claim to historical events and personages " .
6 Works often described as examples of historiographical metafiction include : William Shakespeare 's Pericles , Prince of Tyre ( c.1608 ) , John Fowles ' The French Lieutenant 's Woman ( 1969 ) , E. L. Doctorow 's Ragtime ( 1975 ) , William Kennedy 's Legs ( 1975 ) , Salman Rushdie 's Midnight 's Children ( 1981 ) , A. S. Byatt 's Possession ( 1990 ) , Michael Ondaatje 's The English Patient ( 1992 ) , Thomas Pynchon 's Mason & Dixon ( 1997 ) and many others .
7 By seeking to represent both actual historical events from World War Two while , at the same time , problematizing the very notion of doing exactly that , Kurt Vonnegut 's Slaughterhouse - Five ( 1969 ) features a metafictional , " Janus - headed " perspective .
##labels
Linda Hutcheon, A Poetics of Postmodernism, notable work(P800), [5]
A Poetics of Postmodernism, Linda Hutcheon, author(P50), [5]
Pericles , Prince of Tyre ( c.1608 ), William Shakespeare, author(P50), [6]

##title
Li Jiancheng
##doc
0 Li Jiancheng (; 589 – July 2 , 626 , formally Crown Prince Yin ( , literally , " the hidden crown prince " ) , nickname Pishamen ( ; Sanskrit : Vaiśravaṇa ) , was the first crown prince of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty .
1 He was the oldest son of the founding emperor Emperor Gaozu ( Li Yuan ) and the crown prince after the founding of the dynasty in 618 .
2 Li Jiancheng was murdered by his younger brother , Li Shimin , the Prince of Qin during Xuanwu Gate indident in 626 .
3 All of Li Jiancheng 's sons were executed and excluded from imperial clan .
4 After Li Shimin took the throne , Li Jiancheng was posthumously created the Prince of Xi ( 息隐王 ) .
5 Later , he was buried with ceremonies due an imperial prince .
6 In 642 , Li Jiancheng 's crown prince title was restored as the crown Prince of Yin ( 隐太子 ) .

##title
Sunol Valley
##doc
0 Sunol Valley is located in Alameda County , California , United States .
1 The small town of Sunol lies in the valley .
2 It is largely rural , but is in proximity to the highly populated Bay Area suburbs of Fremont , Pleasanton , and Livermore .
3 Interstate 680 runs through the valley .
4 The historic Sunol Water Temple is situated in the Sunol Valley .
5 Historically steelhead have run as high as the Sunol Valley via Alameda Creek , and restoration plans are underway to restore such anadromous fish runs .
6 These restoration plans by the San Francisco Public Utilities Commission include the planned modification of a Pacific Gas and Electric pipeline that has blocked fish migration in Alameda Creek .
7 The Sunol Valley Rock Quarry is located within the Sunol Valley ; this facility has been used as the source for fill material in a considerable amount of the land development for neighboring communities .
8 In the course of excavating this quarry for such fill , chemical analysis has been conducted to ascertain the safety of such soils .
9 Resultant analyses have shown that the soil has environmentally safe characteristics as defined by low or non - detectable concentrations of 18 heavy metals and asbestos fibers .

##title
Juan Balboa Boneke
##doc
0 Juan Balboa Boneke ( 9 June 1938 – 10 March 2014 ) was an Equatorial Guinean politician and writer .
1 He was born in Rebola , Spanish Guinea and studied at the Escuela Superior de Santa Isabel and at La Escuela social de Granada .
2 He was minister under Teodoro Obiang until he dissented with the dictatorship 's policies and went into exile in Valencia , Spain .
3 Prior to his position in the Guinean government , he would live for over 15 years in Majorca ( where his daughter María Concepción , a flamenco singer best known as Concha Buika , was born ) .
4 After his exile , he settled down in Valencia with his second wife and her family .
5 Balboa Boneke died from renal problems , coupled with a three - year depression caused by the death of his wife , on 10 March 2014 in Valencia , Spain .

##title
Tudor Chirilă
##doc
0 Tudor Chirilă ( born 28 May 1974 in Bucharest ) is a Romanian actor , musician , composer , and producer .
1 He was the lead singer of the band Vama Veche , after which he founded the band Vama .
2 As an actor , he featured in both short and long movies and has played reference roles in plays of some of the most important Romanian directors .
3 In 2012 , he published his first book , " Exerciții de Echilibru " , which has united some of the writings from his personal blog .
4 In 2014 , he became a coach for The Voice Romania , alongside Loredana Groza , Smiley and Marius Moga .
5 Over the years , Chirilă has been involved in numerous social causes .
6 In 2005 , he initiated the campaign " Live pentru viață " , which had the intent to gather donations for flood victims .
7 He supported the fundraiser campaign for children with cancer called " Nu ma ignora " , which was initiated by " Salvează Vieți " Association .
8 Along with Agenția de Vise , his management and booking company , he conducted a number of projects with social and cultural impact , some of which are : " Chrilă in licee " – mentorship tour for high schools in Bucharest , " Cruciada Culturii " , " Ioan Chirilă Awards " .

##title
Osaka Bay
##doc
0 Osaka Bay ( 大阪湾 Ōsaka - wan ) is a bay in western Japan .
1 As an eastern part of the Inland Sea , it is separated from the Pacific Ocean by the Kii Channel and from the neighbor western part of the Inland Sea by the Akashi Strait .
2 Its western shore is formed by Awaji Island , and its northern and eastern shores are part of the Kansai metropolitan area .
3 Major ports on Osaka Bay include Osaka , Kobe , Nishinomiya , Sakai , Amagasaki , and Hannan .
4 A number of artificial islands have been created in Osaka Bay in past decades , including Kansai International Airport , Kobe Airport , Port Island , and Rokko Island .
5 Several islands at the south end of Osaka Bay are part of the Seto Inland Sea National Park .
6 Industries locate around Osaka Bay because there is a skilled and plentiful workforce , many port facilities , efficient linkages ( from small to medium to large firms ) .
7 There are good transport links ( including the Shinkansen ) , room for expansion ( land reclaimed from the sea ) , and a large local market ( 9 million ) .
8 In a recent economic change in Osaka Bay , older ' heavy ' industries such as Nippon Steel have declined , and ' new tech ' companies such as ICT have expanded .
9 There has been a growth in the quaternary industries — research , development , and information .
10 There has also been a development in the science parks and the building of new motorways ; this has meant the loss of the countryside .
11 The Tempozan Ferris Wheel and Osaka Aquarium Kaiyukan are both located in the Tempozan Harbor Village area of Osaka .

##title
Yandina, Solomon Islands
##doc
0 Yandina is a town on Mbanika Island in the Russell Islands , in the Central Province of Solomon Islands .
1 It is a port , and an airport ( ICAO code : AGGY , IATA code : XYA ) .
2 Yandina is the site of a copra and cocoa plantation and has basic services such as a store , post office , and rest house .
3 The Yandina police station was the scene of one of the opening events of the ethnic tensions , where a group of men raided the armoury and stole high powered weapons and ammunition .
4 The group involved became known as the Guadalcanal Revolutionary Army , and later as Isatabu Freedom Movement .
5 Yandina is the site of one of the RAMSI posts .
6 Yandina is also known as a diving destination .

##title
Penedo da Saudade
##doc
0 Penedo da Saudade is the name of an historical public garden in Coimbra , Portugal .
1 The garden have partial views of Coimbra skyline and the Coimbra City Stadium .
2 According to the legend , nothing remained the same after the death of Inês de Castro .
3 It used to be a relaxing and isolated place , where D. Pedro used to come to grieve the loss of his beloved Inês .
4 It is said that this mourning and sadness gave this place its name – Penedo da Saudade ( Rock of Nostalgia ) .
5 Many centuries later , it seemed to be the right place for the romantic encounters of students , and it was at this time that Coimbra Fado was born , challenging eternity with words they etched on the stone .
6 These words represent the feelings of many generations of Coimbra students and lovers which can be seen today in the rocks of the garden .

##title
Lisa Mona Lisa
##doc
0 " Lisa Mona Lisa " was the Austrian entry in the Eurovision Song Contest 1988 , performed in German by Wilfried .
1 The song was performed twelfth on the night , following Germany 's Maxi & Chris Garden with " Lied für einen Freund " and preceding Denmark 's Kirsten & Søren with " Ka ' du se hva ' jeg sa ' ? " .
2 At the close of voting , it had received no points , placing it last out of a field of 21 .
3 The song is a ballad in which the singer likens the object of his affection to the Mona Lisa , in that she is very mysterious but nonetheless entrancing .
4 The song was recorded in German , French and English .
5 Due to the song 's poor performance , the English version was not released .
6 It was succeeded as Austrian representative at the 1989 Contest by Thomas Forstner singing " Nur ein Lied " .

##title
Battle of Samugarh
##doc
0 Battle of Samugarh , Jang - e - Samugarh , ( May 29 , 1658 ) , was a decisive battle in the struggle for the throne during the Mughal war of succession ( 1658 – 1659 ) between the sons of the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan after the emperor 's serious illness in September 1657 .
1 The battle of Samugarh was fought between his sons Dara Shikoh ( the eldest son and heir apparent ) and his two younger brothers Aurangzeb and Murad Baksh ( third and fourth sons of the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan ) .
2 Dara Shikoh began to retreat towards Samugarh , about 10 miles ( 16   km ) east of Agra , India , south of the Yamuna River , after Aurangzeb had defeated Dara Shikoh 's forces during the Battle of Dharmat .
3 Aurangzeb and his smaller but formidable army then flanked Dara ’s fortified line along the Chambal River by finding a little - known and unguarded ford .
4 The battle was fought during northern India 's warmest season and Aurangzeb 's men were on the march for a very long while .
5 The army of Aurangzeb arrived with yellow banners and flags and fortified their position in front of the heir apparent .
6 Dara Shikoh then tried to protect his rear flank by erecting massive red tents and banners .

##title
Irish in the British Armed Forces
##doc
0 The Irish in the British Armed Forces refers to the history of Irish people serving in the British Armed Forces ( including the British Army , the Royal Navy , the Royal Air Force and other elements ) .
1 Ireland was then as part of the United Kingdom from 1800 - 1922 and during this time in particular many Irishmen fought in the British Army .
2 Different social classes joined the military for various reasons , including the Anglo - Irish officers who thoroughly identified with the British Empire , while others , typically poorer Irish Catholics did so to feed their families or seeking adventure .
3 Many Irishmen and members of the Irish diaspora in Britain and also Ulster - Scots served in both World War I and World War II as part of the British forces .
4 However , especially since the advent of Irish independence and The Troubles , the topic of enlistment in the British forces has been controversial for the Irish at home , but does still occur .
5 Since partition , Irish citizens have continued to have the right to serve in the British Army .
6 Since 2007 , when troops finally withdrew from the streets of Northern Ireland , the number of Irish citizens joining has increased , reaching its highest levels since World War II .

##title
Alexeni
##doc
0 Alexeni is a commune in Ialomița County , Romania , some 65   km north - east of Bucharest , near the town of Urziceni .
1 It is composed of a single village , Alexeni .
2 Until 2001 a Romanian Air Force military helicopters unit was located at the nearby airfield . In 2007 , as the airfield was not used by the Romanian Air Force anylonger , the former Minister of Transport Radu Berceanu suggested to use the location for Bucharest 's new low - cost flights airport(as the operational tariffs for Bucharest 's previous low - cost hub , Aurel Vlaicu Airport , were set to grow ) .
3 However , some analysts considered the project unrealistic and doomed to fail due to the poor conditions of the infrastructure in the area .
4 Eventually those plans were abandoned and all low - cost flights were moved in March 2012 at Bucharest main airport Henri Coandă International Airport .

##title
Juan Carlos Muñoz
##doc
0 Juan Carlos Muñoz ( 4 March 1919 – 22 November 2009 ) was a footballer from Argentina who played as a right winger for River Plate , from 1939 to 1950 , playing 184 games and scoring 39 goals .
1 He started playing professionally for Sportivo Dock Sud in 1938 . and he was sold in June 1939 to River Plate .
2 He was part of the team known as La Máquina ( " the machine " ) which dominated Argentine football in the 1940s , and was also a member of the Argentine national team that won three South American Championships during the same decade .
3 During his time at River Plate he won 4 titles and is considered one of their greatest ever players .
4 After a very successful time at River Plate He moved to Platense , from 1951 to 1953 , where he played in 39 games making 3 goals .
5 Muñoz played 11 times for the Argentina national team scoring two goals , he was part of the squad that won Copa América 1945 .
6 He never played in the FIFA World Cup because the best part of his career coincided with the Second World War .
7 After retiring as a player Muñoz went on to become the manager and then president of Club Atlético Platense .

##title
Law of the Cayman Islands
##doc
0 The law of the Cayman Islands is a combination of common law and statute , and is based heavily upon English law .
1 Law in the Cayman Islands tends to be a combination of the very old and the very new .
2 As a leading offshore financial centre , the Cayman Islands has extremely modern statutes dealing with company law , insolvency , banking law , trust law , insurance and other related matters .
3 However , in other areas of law , such as family law , the laws of the Cayman Islands are based upon old English statutes which can cause some difficulty in modern times .
4 Other areas of law , such as international law , are essentially regulated externally through the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in London by Order in Council .
5 A large body of the laws of the Cayman Islands consists of the common law , which continually updates itself through judicial precedent in the Territory and in other common law countries .
6 The Cayman Islands is a dependent territory of the United Kingdom .
7 Although the local legislature and courts are independent from the United Kingdom , the British Government deals with all international relations on behalf of the Territory .
8 The Cayman Islands does not have a separate vote at the United Nations .

##title
Cello Suites (Bach)
##doc
0 The six Cello Suites , BWV 1007 - 1012 , are suites for unaccompanied cello by Johann Sebastian Bach .
1 They are some of the most frequently performed and recognizable solo compositions ever written for cello .
2 Bach most likely composed them during the period 1717 – 23 , when he served as Kapellmeister in Köthen .
3 The title given on the cover of the Anna Magdalena Bach manuscript was Suites à Violoncello Solo senza Basso ( Suites for cello solo without bass ) .
4 These suites for unaccompanied cello are remarkable in that they achieve the effect of implied three- to four - voice contrapuntal and polyphonic music in a single musical line .
5 As usual in a Baroque musical suite , after the prelude which begins each suite , all the other movements are based around baroque dance types ; the cello suites are structured in six movements each : prelude , allemande , courante , sarabande , two minuets or two bourrées or two gavottes , and a final gigue .
6 The Bach cello suites are considered to be among the most profound of all classical music works .
7 Wilfrid Mellers described them in 1980 as " Monophonic music wherein a man has created a dance of God . "
8 Due to the works ' technical demands , étude - like nature , and difficulty in interpretation because of the non - annotated nature of the surviving copies , the cello suites were little known and rarely publicly performed until they were revived and recorded by Pablo Casals in the early 20th century .
9 They have since been performed and recorded by many renowned cellists and have been transcribed for numerous other instruments ; they are considered some of Bach 's greatest musical achievements .
##labels

##title
Ispendje
##doc
0 İspençe was a tax levied on non - Muslims in the Ottoman Empire .
1 İspençe was a land - tax on non - Muslims in parts of the Ottoman Empire ; its counterpart , for Muslim taxpayers , was the resm - i çift - which was set at slightly lower rate .
2 The treasury was well aware of the difference in tax takes , and the incentive to convert ; the legal reforms of Bayezid II halved some criminal penalties on nonmuslim taxpayers " so that the taxpayers shall not vanish " ; this rule was reconfimed , a century later , in 1587 .
3 In other cases , local taxes were imposed on nonmuslims specifically to encourage conversion .
4 İspençe had existed in the Balkans before the Ottoman conquest ; the Ottoman Empire typically adapted local taxes and institutions in each conquered area , leading to a patchwork of different taxes and rates .
5 The concept of İspençe , theoretically a payment in lieu of corvee labour , was derived from the Byzantine " zeugaratikion " , a land tax based on the zeugarion - the area of farmland which could be ploughed by a pair of oxen .
6 The zeugarion itself was taken up as the Ottoman " çift " , a word meaning " pair " .

##title
Muir Beach, California
##doc
0 Muir Beach is a census designated place ( CDP ) , unincorporated community , and beach that is located northwest of San Francisco in western Marin County , California , United States .
1 It is named for John Muir .
2 The population was 310 at the 2010 census .
3 The community itself flanks the northwest side of the beach .
4 Located about 2 miles ( 3   km ) from the entrance to Muir Woods National Monument , the beach is about 1000 feet ( 305 m ) long and 200 feet ( 61 m ) wide , with coarse sand and several large boulders .
5 Redwood Creek empties into the beach .
6 There is a parking lot at the beach , which is accessible via a footbridge .
7 The beach was formerly called Big Lagoon after a freshwater lagoon that was located where the parking lot is now .
8 Damage from 20th century dairy farms interfered with the flow of the creek and the lagoon .

##title
Guybrush Threepwood
##doc
0 Guybrush Ulysses Threepwood is the main protagonist of the Monkey Island series of computer adventure games by LucasArts .
1 Guybrush is voiced by actor Dominic Armato in the third , fourth and fifth games , as well as the enhanced remakes of The Secret of Monkey Island and .
2 Though a " mighty pirate " by his own account , it is a running joke throughout the games for characters to garble Guybrush Threepwood 's unusual name , either deliberately or accidentally .
3 The origin of the name " Guybrush " comes in part from Deluxe Paint , the tool used by the artists to create the character sprite .
4 Since the character had no name at this point , the file was simply called ' Guy ' .
5 When the file was saved , Steve Purcell , the artist responsible for the sprite , added ' brush ' to the filename , indicating that it was the Deluxe Paint " brush file " for the " Guy " sprite .
6 The file name was then " guybrush.bbm " , so the developers eventually just started referring to this unnamed ' Guy ' as " Guybrush " .
7 Guybrush 's surname " Threepwood " was decided upon in a company contest and is derived from P. G. Wodehouse 's family of characters including Galahad Threepwood and Freddie Threepwood ( with whom he shares similar characteristics ) .
8 " Threepwood " is also rumoured to have been the name of Dave Grossman 's RPG character .

##title
Kiirunavaara
##doc
0 Kiirunavaara ( Northern Sami : Gironvárri , Meänkieli : Kierunavaara ) is a mountain in Kiruna , Sweden that contains one of the largest and richest bodies of iron ore in the world .
1 The presence of iron in the area was known already in the mid-17th century , but at this early time communication lines to this northerly region were quite insufficient to permit any major exploitation .
2 Only with the construction of a railway , the Iron Ore Line and the ports of Narvik and Luleå at the end of the 19th century did commercial mining become a realistic proposition .
3 The Swedish mining company LKAB ( Luossavaara - Kiirunavaara Aktiebolag ) has been mining the mountain since the beginning of the 20th century .
4 The mining area around Kiruna and Malmberget and the iron port and steelworks at Luleå made Norrbotten County one of the first , and most prominent , regions of heavy industry in Sweden , and the wider region has remained at the forefront of mining and steel smelting and alloying technology .

##title
Devichandraguptam
##doc
0 Devi - Chandraguptam ( IAST : Devīcandraguptam ) or Devi - Chandragupta is an Indian Sanskrit - language political drama authored by Vishakhadatta .
1 The complete text of the play is now lost , but its portions survive in form of quotations in the later works .
2 The plot also survives in form of a Persian language story , which appears to be a adaptation of the play , and is included in the 11th century text Majmal - ut - Tawarikh .
3 In the play , king Ramagupta decides to surrender his queen Dhruvadevi ( " Devi " ) to a Shaka enemy when besieged .
4 Ramagupta 's younger brother Chandragupta enters the enemy camp disguised as the queen , and kills the enemy ruler .
5 The rest of the story is not clear from the surviving passages , but based on other historical evidence , it appears that in the last part of the play , Chandragupta dethrones Ramagupta and marries Dhruvadevi .

##title
Rio Grande de Mindanao
##doc
0 The Rio Grande de Mindanao , also known as the Mindanao River , is the second largest river system in the Philippines , located on the southern island of Mindanao .
1 It has a drainage area of , draining the majority of the central and eastern portion of the island , with a total length of approximately .
2 It is an important transportation artery on the island , used mainly in transporting agricultural products and , formerly , timber .
3 Its headwaters are in the mountains of Impasugong , Bukidnon , south of Gingoog City in Misamis Oriental , where it is called the Pulangi River .
4 Joining the Kabacan River , it becomes the Mindanao River .
5 Flowing out of the mountains , it forms the center of a broad , fertile plain in the south - central portion of the island .
6 Before its mouth in the Illana Bay , it splits into two parallel sections , the Cotabato and Tamontaka , separated by a hill .
7 Population centers along the river include Cotabato City , Datu Piang , and Midsayap .

##title
List of Chief Ministers of Madhya Pradesh
##doc
0 The Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh is the chief executive of the central Indian state of Madhya Pradesh .
1 In accordance with the Constitution of India , the governor is a state 's de jure head , but de facto executive authority rests with the chief minister .
2 Following elections to the Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly , the state 's governor usually invites the party ( or coalition ) with a majority of seats to form the government .
3 The governor appoints the chief minister , whose council of ministers are collectively responsible to the assembly .
4 Given the confidence of the assembly , the chief minister 's term is for five years and is subject to no term limits .
5 Following Madhya Pradesh 's reorganisation on 1 November 1956 , 17 people have served as its chief minister .
6 Eleven of these belonged to the Indian National Congress , including the inaugural officeholder Ravishankar Shukla .
7 The first non - Congress chief minister was Govind Narayan Singh who defected from the party and lead a Samyukta Vidhayak Dal government from 1967 to 1969 .
8 Digvijaya Singh of the Congress became the first officeholder to serve two full five - year terms .
9 He was succeeded by Uma Bharti of the Bharatiya Janata Party , Madhya Pradesh 's only woman chief minister .
10 Her party - mate Shivraj Singh Chouhan is the current incumbent and the state 's longest - serving chief minister , having held office since November 2005 .

##title
First Battle of Homs
##doc
0 The first Battle of Homs was fought on December 10 , 1260 , between the Ilkhanates of Persia and the forces of Egypt , in Syria .
1 After the historic Mamluk victory over the Ilkhanates at the Battle of Ain Jalut in September 1260 , Hulagu Khan of the Ilkhanate had the Ayyubid Sultan of Damascus and other Ayyubid princes executed in revenge , thus effectively ending the dynasty in Syria .
2 However , the defeat at Ain Jalut forced the Ilkhanate armies out of Syria and the Levant .
3 The main cities of Syria , Aleppo and Damascus were thus left open to Mamluk occupation .
4 But Homs and Hama remained in the possession of minor Ayyubid princes .
5 These princes , rather than the Mamluks of Cairo themselves , actually fought and won the First Battle of Homs .
6 Due to the open war between Hulagu and his cousin Berke of the Golden Horde during the civil war of the Mongol Empire , the Ilkhanate could only afford to send 6,000 troops back into Syria to retake control of the lands .
7 This expedition was initiated by Ilkhanate generals such as Baidu who was forced to leave Gaza when the Mamluks advanced just before the battle of Ain Jalut .
8 After quickly recapturing Aleppo , the force travelled southwards to Homs , but were decisively defeated .
9 This ended the first campaign into Syria by the Ilkhanate , though there were several later incursions , none of which ended with conquests lasting more than a year .

##title
Tullgarn Palace
##doc
0 Tullgarn Palace ( ) is a royal summer palace in the province of Södermanland , south of Stockholm , Sweden .
1 Built in the 1720s , the palace offers a mixture of rococo , Gustavian and Victorian styles .
2 The interior design is regarded as one of Sweden 's finest .
3 Tullgarn Palace is mainly associated with King Gustaf V and Queen Victoria , who spent their summers here at the end of the 19th century and beginning of the 20th century .
4 However , the palace was originally built for Duke Fredrik Adolf in the 1770s .
5 Since Tullgarn was a popular summer palace amongst Swedish royalty , the palace houses fine examples of interiors from different epochs and personal styles , such as the small drawing room , decorated in the 1790s , the breakfast room in southern German Renaissance style from the 1890s and Gustav V 's cigar room , which has remained largely untouched since his death in 1950 .

##title
Memogate (Pakistan)
##doc
0 The memogate controversy ( also Mullen memo controversy ) revolves around a memorandum ( addressed to Admiral Mike Mullen ) ostensibly seeking help of the Obama administration in the wake of the Osama bin Laden raid to avert a military takeover of the civilian government in Pakistan , as well as assisting in a civilian takeover of the government and military apparatus .
1 The memo was delivered in May 2011 ; Mansoor Ijaz wrote a Financial Times article in October 2011 bringing initial public attention to the affair .
2 The memo , which at first was questioned to even exist , was published in November , leading to the resignation of Ambassador Haqqani and the continuing Pakistani Supreme Court investigation .
3 Central actors in the plot include Pakistani - American businessman Mansoor Ijaz , who alleged that long - time friend and former Pakistan Ambassador to the United States Husain Haqqani asked him to deliver a confidential memo asking for US assistance .
4 The memo is alleged to have been drafted by Haqqani at the behest of President of Pakistan Asif Ali Zardari .
5 The memo was delivered to Mike Mullen through then National Security Advisor James L. Jones .
6 The Supreme Court of Pakistan has opened a broader inquiry into the origins , credibility and purpose of the memo .
7 On 19 April 2012 a petition was submitted in the Supreme Court to arrest former Pakistan ambassador to US Husain Haqqani through Interpol for his refusal to return to Pakistan .
8 On 12 June the supreme court commission released its findings and found that after testimony by all parties and verifying the forensic results of Ijaz 's BlackBerry conversations with Haqqani it was " incontrovertibly established " that Husain Haqqani had written the memo and was being called back to Pakistan to face likely charges of treason .

##title
The Private Life of Helen of Troy
##doc
0 The Private Life of Helen of Troy is a 1927 American silent film about Helen of Troy based on the 1925 novel of the same name by John Erskine , and adapted to screen by Gerald Duffy .
1 The film was directed by Alexander Korda and starred María Corda as Helen , Lewis Stone as Menelaus , and Ricardo Cortez as Paris .
2 Coming at the end of the silent film era , it was nominated for an Academy Award in 1929 , the year of the Awards ' inception , in the category of Best Title Writing .
3 Duffy died on 25 June 1928 , and was the first person to be posthumously nominated for an Academy Award .
4 That same year , the first " talkie " , The Jazz Singer , received an honorary award for introducing sound to film , and the category for which The Private Life of Helen of Troy was nominated was dropped by the second Academy Awards .
5 Two sections from the beginning and end , running about 27–30 minutes in total , are reportedly all that survive of The Private Life of Helen of Troy ; they are preserved by the British Film Institute .

##title
Stanisław Tymiński
##doc
0 Stanisław " Stan " Tymiński (; born January 27 , 1948 ) is a Canadian businessman of Polish origin , dealing in electronics and computers , and a sometime - politician in both Poland and Canada .
1 Although Tymiński was born in Pruszków , he was completely unknown in his native Poland until shortly before the 1990 presidential election , he emerged from the first ballot as the second strongest candidate , defeating liberal prime minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki and forcing Solidarity leader Lech Wałęsa to stand a second ballot .
2 After Wałęsa defeated him by a wide margin , Tymiński was a leader of Party X in Poland ( 1990 – 1995 ) and then returned to Canada to resume his business activities .
3 Tymiński also ran in the 2005 Polish presidential election .

##title
Souvlaki
##doc
0 Souvlaki ( Greek : ) , plural souvlakia , is a popular Greek fast food consisting of small pieces of meat and sometimes vegetables grilled on a skewer .
1 It is usually eaten straight off the skewer while still hot .
2 It can be served with pita bread , fried potatoes , lemon , and sauces , but the souvlaki itself is eaten on its own , with the side dishes eaten subsequently .
3 The meat usually used in Greece and Cyprus is pork , although chicken , beef , and lamb may also be used .
4 In other countries ( and for tourists ) , souvlaki may be made with meats such as lamb , beef , chicken , and sometimes fish .
5 The word souvlaki is a diminutive of the Medieval Greek σούβλα souvla ' skewer ' , itself borrowed from Latin subula .
6 ' Souvlaki ' is the common term in Hellenic Macedonia and other regions of northern Greece , while in southern Greece around Athens it is commonly known as ' kalamaki ' , ' reed ' .

##title
How Could Hell Be Any Worse?
##doc
0 How Could Hell Be Any Worse ?
1 is the first full - length album by American punk rock band Bad Religion , released on January 19 , 1982 by Epitaph Records .
2 Released almost a year after their self - titled EP , it was financed by a $ 3,000 loan by guitarist Brett Gurewitz 's father .
3 Its success surprised the band when it sold 10,000 copies in under a year .
4 How Could Hell Be Any Worse ?
5 was recorded over two time periods at Track Record Studios in North Hollywood , California , during October – November 1980 and again in January 1981 .
6 After the original recording sessions , drummer Jay Ziskrout left Bad Religion and was replaced by his friend and the band 's roadie Pete Finestone , who was brought in to complete the rest of the album .
7 Though not yet credited as a member of the band , future guitarist Greg Hetson , who was in Circle Jerks during this time , provided a guitar solo on " Part III " .
8 How Could Hell Be Any Worse ?
9 was also Bad Religion 's last album featuring Jay Bentley on bass for six years , until 1988 's Suffer .
10 The front cover photograph was taken by Edward Colver near the Hollywood Bowl , while the back cover featured one of Gustave Dore 's illustrations of Dante 's Divine Comedy .

##title
Elwood Buchanan
##doc
0 Elwood C. Buchanan , Sr was an American jazz trumpeter and teacher who became an early mentor of Miles Davis .
1 Buchanan was born in St Louis , Missouri on January 26 , 1907 , and was trained in music by Joseph Gustat , the principal trumpeter with the St Louis Symphony Orchestra .
2 He began his career playing in local dance bands , including Andy Kirk 's orchestra , and on the riverboats that travelled on the Mississippi River between St Louis and New Orleans .
3 During the late 1930s and early 1940s , he taught music and directed the band at Lincoln High School in East St Louis , and also visited the local elementary schools to give weekly lessons .
4 Buchanan was known for his strict and demanding teaching style , and for encouraging pupils to compete with one another .
5 Buchanan was a patient of Miles Davis 's father , who told him of his son 's interest in music .
6 Although Davis , at thirteen , was then too young to attend Buchanan 's school , Buchanan began giving him private lessons .
7 Davis joined the school band when he began attending Lincoln .
8 Although Buchanan had the band play mainly marches rather than jazz , the techniques he taught profoundly affected Davis ' jazz style .
9 In particular , Buchanan went against the times by recommending to his students that they play without vibrato , and is said to have broken Davis of the habit by rapping his knuckles with a ruler and commanding : " Stop shakin ' that note .
10 You 're going to shake enough when you get old " .
11 Buchanan also encouraged Davis to study the lean , relaxed playing of Bobby Hackett ( then little known beyond the East Coast ) and Harold Shorty Baker .
12 In this , too , Buchanan went against fashion ; the most popular trumpeter of the day was Louis Armstrong , whose hot playing style was very different from those of Hackett or Baker .
13 Davis later credited Buchanan with persuading his parents to buy him a new trumpet , rather than a violin as his mother had preferred .
14 Buchanan also introduced Davis to Clark Terry , who would become his recording partner .
15 In his autobiography , Davis recalled : " Mr. Buchanan was the biggest influence on my life up until then .
16 He was definitely the person who took me all the way into music at that time . "

##title
Drake Landing Solar Community
##doc
0 The Drake Landing Solar Community ( DLSC ) is a planned community in Okotoks , Alberta , Canada , equipped with a central solar heating system and other energy efficient technology .
1 This heating system is the first of its kind in North America , although much larger systems have been built in northern Europe .
2 The 52 homes in the community are heated with a solar district heating system that is charged with heat originating from solar collectors on the garage roofs and is enabled for year - round heating by underground seasonal thermal energy storage ( STES ) .
3 The system was designed to model a way of addressing global warming and the burning of fossil fuels .
4 The solar energy is captured by 800 solar thermal collectors located on the roofs of all 52 houses ' garages .
5 It is billed as the first solar powered subdivision in North America , although its electricity and transportation needs are provided by conventional sources .
6 In 2012 the installation achieved a world record solar fraction of 97 % ; that is , providing that amount of the community 's heating requirements with solar energy over a one - year time span .

##title
Faliero coup
##doc
0 The Faliero Coup was a failed 1355 coup designed to overthrow Venice 's established republican government .
1 Strains between the Venetian commoners and the nobility , originally stemming from the catastrophic failure of the nobility in the Battle of Porto - Longo against Venice 's long - time rival , Genoa , are largely considered to be the main cause for the coup .
2 However , traditional stories also point to the marriage of Doge Marino Faliero as a possible cause for the coup .
3 Faliero , an 81 year old man , had recently taken a young bride , who was rumored to be engaged in multiple affairs , including with Michele Steno , a Venetian statesman and future Doge .
4 The consistent rumors and apparent intense arrogance of the established Venetian elite seems to have gotten to Faliero in this explanation for a coup .
5 A more reasonable one , however , is that Faliero wished to transform Venice into a dictatorship , mirroring those of Genoa and other northern Italian city - states .
6 This view is , however , disputed by some historians , who cite Faliero 's apparent regret at his trial , and , his lack of mentioning his belief that a dictatorship would better suit Venice 's interests , a valid argument .
7 These two actions are much more consistent with a man regretting a passionate crime , than one who had executed a calculated plan , some argue .
8 The coup was poorly organized and abortive .
9 Faliero convened with two popular , wealthy , public figures who also had quarlles with the noblility : Bertuccio Isarello and Filippo Calendario .
10 After convincing them of the need for a coup , he laid out his plan : Faliero and Isarello would recruit 20 trusted men who would assist in the overthrow of the government , who would each in turn recruit 40 each .
11 However , due to the incredible variability of any given individuals ' reaction to the plan , rumors of unrest quickly began to spread throughout the city and , the Venetian people , fearing the civil turmoil which was swelling up all around them in northern Italy and Byzantium , reported the rumors to the authorities .
12 One of the most powerful governmental bodies of Republican Venice , the Council of Ten , soon convened to discuss the rumors .
13 They became concerned about the Doge 's role in the plot and , exercising emergency powers , together with the Doge 's councillors , the Signori di Notte , and the six sestieri , ordered the immediate and unquestioned arrest of Calendario and Isarello , who , upon questioning , implicated the Doge .
14 After a series of quick albeit somber trials , the conspirators were imprisoned and executed , including Calendario , Isarello , and Doge Faliero .

##title
Fatih Terim
##doc
0 Fatih Terim , Commendatore OSSI , T.C , ( born 4 September 1953 ) is a Turkish association football manager and former player .
1 He is currently the manager of Galatasaray , a position he previously held three times .
2 Terim has managed several clubs in Italy and Turkey , as well as the Turkish national football team , most recently from 2013 to 2017 .
3 In a survey conducted by the International Federation of Football History & Statistics ( IFFHS ) in 80 countries , he was placed among the best eight managers in the world , receiving his award at a ceremony held in Rothenburg , Germany , on 8 January 2001 .
4 Terim received a nomination for UEFA manager of the year 2008 , and Eurosport named him the best coach at UEFA Euro 2008 .
5 In December 2008 , he was ranked the seventh - best football manager in the world by World Soccer Magazine in 2008 .
6 His Turkish nickname is " İmparator " , and his Italian nickname is " Imperatore " .
7 Both names mean " emperor " .

##title
Charles S. Johnson
##doc
0 Charles Spurgeon Johnson ( July 24 , 1893 – October 27 , 1956 ) was an American sociologist and college administrator , the first black president of historically black Fisk University , and a lifelong advocate for racial equality and the advancement of civil rights for African Americans and all ethnic minorities .
1 He preferred to work collaboratively with liberal white groups in the South , quietly as a " sideline activist , " to get practical results .
2 His position is often contrasted with that of W. E. B.
3 Du Bois , who was a powerful and militant advocate for blacks and described Johnson as " too conservative . "
4 During Johnson 's academic studies and leadership of Fisk University during the 1930s and 1940s , the South had legal racial segregation and Jim Crow discriminatory laws and practices , including having disfranchised most black voters in constitutions passed at the turn of the century .
5 Johnson was unwavering in personal terms in his opposition to this oppressive system , yet worked hard to change race relations in terms of short - term practical gains .
6 His grandson Jeh Johnson served as the United States Secretary of Homeland Security from 2013 to 2017 .

##title
Orongorongo River
##doc
0 The Orongorongo River runs for southwest through the Orongorongo Valley in the southern Rimutaka Ranges of the North Island of New Zealand .
1 The river and its associated catchments lie within the bounds of the Rimutaka Forest Park , which is administered by the Department of Conservation .
2 Orongorongo River is the main artery of the Rimutaka Range , draining an area with rainfall of up to a year , which is twice as much as the rainfall at the mouth of the river at Cook Strait .
3 For much of its course the river is a braided river , with a wide bed of greywacke shingle and gravel and a number of streams of water .
4 The gravel bed can be seen as light - coloured areas of varying width in the adjacent image .
5 Because the rainfall in the Rimutaka Range often comes in high - intensity rainstorms , the river is prone to violent floods .
6 The most severe of these floods sweep away most of the river 's vegetated islands every 15 to 20 years .
7 Between these floods , the shingle islands are gradually colonised by various low growing plants , followed by a host of native shrubs such as tauhinu and manuka , and eventually small trees .

##title
Excitebots: Trick Racing
##doc
0 Excitebots : Trick Racing , known in Japan as , is a racing video game published by Nintendo for the Wii video game console .
1 It was developed by Monster Games , is the fourth main game in the Excite series and is the sequel to Excite Truck .
2 Excitebots was unveiled in a release list from Nintendo of America on February 26 , 2009 .
3 It was released on April 20 , 2009 in North America .
4 Excitebots features animal - themed robot vehicles and short minigames during racing , such as pie throwing , bowling and soccer .
5 The game could be bought packaged with or without the Wii Wheel .
6 Despite a positive reception from critics , the game was never available in stores outside North America .
7 Nintendo Australia 's Managing Director , Rose Lappin has said that Excitebots will not be seeing an Australian release " due to lack of interest . "
8 However , Japanese Club Nintendo members were able to exchange points for a copy starting from over two years of the original release date .

##title
Anthony G. Brown
##doc
0 Anthony Gregory Brown ( born November 21 , 1961 ) is an American lawyer and politician , who is currently serving as the U.S. Representative for Maryland 's 4th congressional district .
1 He previously served as the eighth Lieutenant Governor of Maryland , from 2007 to 2015 .
2 He was elected as lieutenant governor in 2006 on the Democratic ticket with Governor Martin O'Malley , and both were reelected in 2010 .
3 In 2014 he ran unsuccessfully for Governor of Maryland , losing to Larry Hogan .
4 Brown previously served two four - year terms in the Maryland House of Delegates , representing Prince George 's County .
5 He is currently a Colonel in the United States Army Reserve , having served in the U.S. Army for nearly thirty years .
6 While lieutenant governor , Brown was one of the two highest - ranking elected officials in the nation to have served a tour of duty in Iraq .

##title
Raimundo Fernández-Villaverde, Marquis of Pozo Rubio
##doc
0 Don Raimundo Fernández - Villaverde y García del Rivero , iure uxoris Marquis of Pozo Rubio , ( 20 January 1848 – 15 July 1905 ) was a Spanish statesman .
1 Born in Madrid , Raimundo Fernandez Villaverde graduated at age 21 from the Central University of Madrid in Law Studies .
2 He later became Professor of this university after receiving the degree of Doctor of Philosophy .
3 He joined the Conservative Party and was elected to the Spanish Parliament in 1872 as representative for Caldas .
4 On 31 March 1884 , he was appointed civil governor of Madrid .
5 Since 1880 up to his death in 1905 , he held various government ministries including Finance , Justice and Interior , became President of Parliament , and was twice Prime Minister .
6 He is credited with the economic reforms passed in the years 1899 and 1900 that stabilized the nation 's economy after the loss of the last Spanish colonies in the Americas and the Pacific Ocean .

##title
Olympic National Park
##doc
0 Olympic National Park is an American national park located in the State of Washington , on the Olympic Peninsula .
1 The park has four regions : the Pacific coastline , alpine areas , the west side temperate rainforest and the forests of the drier east side .
2 Within the park there are three distinct ecosystems which are subalpine forest and wildflower meadow , temperate forest , and the rugged Pacific coast .
3 President Theodore Roosevelt originally designated Mount Olympus National Monument on 2 March 1909 .
4 The monument was redesignated as a national park by Congress and President Franklin Roosevelt on June 29 , 1938 .
5 In 1976 , Olympic National Park was designated by UNESCO as an International Biosphere Reserve , and in 1981 as a World Heritage Site .
6 In 1988 , Congress designated 95 percent of the park as the Olympic Wilderness .

##title
Chauncey B. Brewster
##doc
0 Chauncey Bunce Brewster ( September 5 , 1848 – April 9 , 1941 ) was the fifth Bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of Connecticut .
1 Brewster was born in Windham , Connecticut , to the Reverend Joseph Brewster and Sarah Jane Bunce Brewster .
2 His father was rector of St. Paul 's Church in Windham and later became rector of Christ Church in New Haven , Connecticut .
3 His younger brother was the future bishop Benjamin Brewster .
4 The family were descendants of Mayflower passenger William Brewster .
5 Brewster attended Hopkins Grammar School , then went to Yale College , where he graduated in 1868 .
6 At Yale he was elected Phi Beta Kappa and was a member of Skull and Bones .
7 He attended Yale 's Berkeley Divinity School the following year .
8 He was consecrated as a bishop on October 28 , 1897 .
9 He was a coadjutor bishop before being diocesan bishop from 1899 to 1928 .

##title
CBBC
##doc
0 CBBC ( short for Children 's BBC ) is a British children 's television strand owned by the BBC and aimed for children aged from 6 to 12 .
1 BBC programming aimed at under six year old children is broadcast on the CBeebies channel .
2 CBBC broadcasts from 7   am to 9   pm on the digital CBBC Channel , available on most UK digital platforms .
3 The CBBC brand was used for the broadcast of children 's programmes on BBC One on weekday afternoons and on BBC Two mornings until these strands were phased out in 2012 and 2013 respectively , as part of the BBC 's " Delivering Quality First " cost - cutting initiative .
4 CBBC programmes were also broadcast in high definition alongside other BBC content on BBC HD , generally at afternoons on weekends , unless the channel was covering other events .
5 This ended when BBC HD closed on 26 March 2013 , but CBBC HD launched on 10 December 2013 .
6 BBC - produced children 's programming , in native languages of Scotland and Wales , also airs on BBC Alba and S4C respectively .

##title
Lookin Ass
##doc
0 " Lookin Ass " ( originally titled " Lookin Ass Nigga " ) is a song by American rapper and singer Nicki Minaj .
1 It was produced by Detail and Choppa Boi .
2 It was recorded by Minaj for the Young Money Entertainment compilation album ( 2014 ) .
3 The music video for the track was released on February 14 , 2014 .
4 The track is a hip hop song whose lyrics criticize stereotypical behaviors commonly associated with men .
5 Its cover also generated controversy for placing an image of activist Malcolm X , next to the derogatory term " nigga " .
6 On March 11 , 2014 , " Lookin Ass " was serviced to urban contemporary radio in the United States as Young Money : Rise of an Empires third official single .
7 It was sent to US rhythmic radio stations on March 18 , 2014 , two weeks after its predecessor , " Trophies " .

##title
Number Ones (video)
##doc
0 Number Ones is a video album by American recording artist Michael Jackson .
1 It was released on DVD on November 13 , 2003 under the Epic Records record label , in conjunction with the promotion for Jackson 's greatest hits album , of the same name ( although the album and DVD have different songs ) .
2 The DVD , which is Jackson 's fourth DVD album , contained fifteen music videos , which was directed and produced by various people .
3 It consists of music videos filmed and released by Jackson from 1979 's Off the Wall to 2001 's Invincible .
4 Just like the album , the DVD has four different covers .
5 Notable music videos included on the DVD were " Beat It " , " Billie Jean " and Thriller — which received heavy rotation on MTV in the 1980s , and are credited as having transformed the music video from a promotional tool and into an art form , and " Black or White " and " Scream " which were also prominent on channels like MTV in the 1990s .
6 Number Ones received praise from contemporary music critics and was commercially successful internationally .
7 The DVD peaked at number one on the Australian Top 40 Music DVD in Australia .
8 Number Ones has been certified twenty two times platinum in Australia by the Australian Recording Industry Association and is the best selling music DVD ever by a male solo artist in Australia .
9 It is also thirteen times platinum in the United States by the Recording Industry Association of America .

##title
Fingerpori
##doc
0 Fingerpori is a Finnish comic strip written and drawn by Pertti Jarla .
1 It started in Helsingin Sanomat in February 2007 , and is currently syndicated in Satakunnan Kansa , Aamulehti , Karjalainen , Keskisuomalainen , Turun Sanomat and Etelä - Saimaa .
2 Several strip collections in album format have also been published .
3 The main setting of the strip is Fingerpori , an imaginary Finnish small town .
4 The main character in the strip is the eyeglass - wearing Heimo Vesa , but other citizens also appear , such as the brash - mouthed café worker Rivo - Riitta .
5 As well as the Fingerpori residents , the strip has included characters such as the Pope , The Phantom , Spider - Man , Adolf Hitler , Kimi Räikkönen and Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim .
6 A few strips , featuring Jesus , have caused controversy in some circles .
7 The humour in Fingerpori is largely verbal and is often based on ( mostly untranslatable ) wordplay and puns .
8 For instance , Vesa works at the multidisciplinary research center Fingerpoli , where " girls with pigtails " is a result of a bungled stem cell experiment .
9 Jokes are often also based on allusions , such as recurrent jokes about the skull ring of The Phantom .
10 Besides this , the strips often have an absurdist element .
11 According to Jarla , his original vision for Fingerpori was to create a milieu of an " East German Duckburg " , but the current Fingerpori is more like a Finnish town still stuck to the 1970s as in Aki Kaurismäki 's films .
12 Although Fingerpori contains some political satire , the author claims it is not a political comic strip .

##title
Eleonora Vallone
##doc
0 Eleonora Vallone ( born 1 February 1955 ) is an Italian actress , model and TV - personality .
1 Born in Rome , the daughter of actors Raf Vallone and Elena Varzi , she made her film debut in 1979 in the " poliziottesco " Gardenia , and later starred in several genre films , also in the more ambitious Alberto Bevilacqua drama film Le rose di Danzica .
2 In 1981 she hosted the Sanremo Music Festival alongside Claudio Cecchetto .
3 In the same years she appeared nude in several men 's magazines such as Playmen and the Italian edition of Playboy .
4 A pioneer and teacher of water gymnastics , Eleonora Vallone founded the first Italian school for water aerobics instructors , and she patented the method " GymNuoto " .
5 She also wrote three books about waterobics , " GymNuoto " , " GymVasca " and " GymSwim " .

##title
Cleopatra's Needle
##doc
0 Cleopatra 's Needle is the popular name for each of three Ancient Egyptian obelisks re - erected in London , Paris , and New York City during the nineteenth century .
1 The obelisks in London and New York are a pair ; the one in Paris is also part of a pair originally from a different site in Luxor , where its twin remains .
2 Although all three needles are genuine Ancient Egyptian obelisks , their shared nickname is a misnomer , as they have no connection with the Ptolemaic Queen Cleopatra VII of Egypt and were already over a thousand years old in her lifetime .
3 The London and New York needles were originally made during the reign of the 18th Dynasty Pharaoh Thutmose III .
4 The Paris needle dates to the reign of the 19th Dynasty Pharaoh Ramesses II , and was the first to be moved and re - erected .
5 The New York needle was the first to acquire the French nickname , " L'aiguille de Cléopâtre " , when it stood in Alexandria .

##title
General Lavalle
##doc
0 General Lavalle ( also known as Ajó ) is a city located in the east of the province of Buenos Aires , Argentina .
1 It 's the administrative center of the partido of General Lavalle , and the General Lavalle municipality .
2 It has a population of 3,046 ( .
3 The city , partido , and municipality , are named after Juan Lavalle ( 1797 - 1841 ) , who was a military and political figure in the early years of the Argentine state .
4 The city is about a two - hour drive from Buenos Aires Ministro Pistarini International Airport .
5 On the shores of the Ajó river , which flows from the interior of the province into Samborombón Bay , it has deep - waters port close to the sea .

##title
House of Orléans
##doc
0 The 4th House of Orléans , sometimes called the House of Bourbon - Orléans ( ) to distinguish it , is the fourth holder of a surname previously used by several branches of the Royal House of France , all descended in the legitimate male line from the dynasty 's founder , Hugh Capet .
1 The house was founded in 1661 by Prince Philippe , Duke of Anjou , younger son of king Louis XIII and younger brother of king Louis XIV , the " Sun King " .
2 From 1709 until the French Revolution , the Orléans dukes were next in the order of succession to the French throne after members of the senior branch of the House of Bourbon , descended from king Louis XIV .
3 Although Louis XIV 's direct descendants retained the throne , his brother Philippe 's descendants flourished until the end of the French monarchy .
4 They held the Crown from 1830 to 1848 , and they still are pretenders to the French throne .

##title
Han Lei
##doc
0 Han Lei (; born February 23 , 1968 ) , also known in Mongolian as Senbor , is a Chinese folk and pop singer - songwriter .
1 Han was born and raised in Hohhot , Inner Mongolia .
2 He is of Mongol descent through his mother , and Han Chinese descent through his father .
3 Han rose to prominence in 1997 on the CCTV New Year 's Gala , performing a song called " 1997 , A.D. " ( 公元一九九七 ) ; in 1998 he returned to the Gala to perform " Zou Sifang " ( 走四方 ) , one of the most memorable performances in the song and dance category of the Gala that year , which became his signature hit and propelled him to national stardom .
4 He has since appeared on the Gala six more times , the most recent performance in the 2014 show .
5 Han has also recorded introductory and conclusion theme songs for various Chinese TV Series , including , perhaps most famously , the introductory theme to Kangxi Dynasty and The Emperor in Han Dynasty , " Xiang Tian Zai Jie Wu Bai Nian " ( 向天在借五百年 ) .
6 He also performed the main theme " I 'll Go with you to the Ends of the Earth " ( 跟着你到天边 ) in the Zhang Yimou film Coming Home .
7 Han also participated and was the winner of the Hunan Television show I Am a Singer ( season 2 ) .

##title
Book of Royal Degrees
##doc
0 The Book of Degrees of the Royal Genealogy ( Степенная книга ) was the first official work of historiography produced in the nascent Tsardom of Russia .
1 It was commissioned by Macarius , Metropolitan of Moscow from Ivan the Terrible 's personal confessor , Andrew , in 1560 .
2 This vast work of codification recast historical data compiled from medieval Russian chronicles so as to suit Ivan 's tastes and ambitions in the wake of his coronation as the first Russian Czar .
3 The book gave shape to the idea of Moscow being the " Third Rome " by tracing Ivan 's patrilineal descent not only from Rurik but from the first Roman emperor , Augustus .
4 This fantasy genealogy was borrowed from the earlier Tale of the Princes of Vladimir .
5 The compilation is subdivided into 17 parts , or degrees ( hence the title ) .
6 Each degree corresponds to a generation of Ivan 's royal ancestors .
7 According to Arthur Voice , the book " glorifies to the utmost the historic past and the present of Muscovite Rus ' , primarily by extolling the rulers as having acted in full accord with the church " .
8 The biographies of Kievan , Vladimir - Suzdal and Muscovite rulers tend to pass over into hagiography .
9 Each monarch is presented as a saint , and his actions are cast as " holy deeds " .
10 The political philosophy of the time tends to be obscured by thick layers of bombast and rhetoric .
##labels

##title
Great Belt Fixed Link
##doc
0 The Great Belt Fixed link ( ) is a multi - element fixed link crossing the Great Belt strait between the Danish islands of Zealand and Funen .
1 It consists of five structures : a road suspension bridge and a railway tunnel between Zealand and the small island Sprogø located in the middle of the Great Belt , and a box girder bridge for both road and rail traffic between Sprogø and Funen .
2 The " Great Belt Bridge " ( Danish : Storebæltsbroen ) commonly refers to the suspension bridge , although it may also be used to mean the box - girder bridge or the link in its entirety .
3 The suspension bridge , officially known as the East Bridge , has the world 's third longest main span ( 1.6   km ) , and the longest outside of Asia .
4 It was designed by the Danish engineering firms COWI and Ramboll .
5 The link replaced the ferry service that had been the primary means of crossing the Great Belt .
6 After more than five decades of speculation and debate , the decision to construct the link was made in 1986 ; the original intent was to complete the railway link three years before opening the road connection , but the link opened to rail traffic in 1997 and road traffic in 1998 .
7 At an estimated cost of DKK 21.4 billion ( 1988 prices ) , the link is the largest construction project in Danish history .
8 The link has reduced travel times significantly ; previously taking about an hour by ferry , the Great Belt can now be crossed in about ten minutes .
9 The construction of the link and the Øresund Bridge ( constr .
10 1995 - 1999 ) have together enabled driving from mainland Europe to Sweden and the rest of Scandinavia through Denmark .
11 Operation and maintenance are performed by A / S Storebælt under Sund & Bælt .
12 Construction and maintenance are financed by tolls on vehicles and trains .
13 Cyclists are not permitted to use the bridge , but cycles may be transported by train or bus .

##title
Titanfall: Assault
##doc
0 Titanfall : Assault is a real - time strategy video game in the Titanfall series for mobile platforms in the style of Clash Royale .
1 It was developed by Particle City and Respawn , published by Nexon , and released for iOS and Android in August 2017 .
2 More titles are expected from Nexon and Respawn 's 2015 mobile game partnership .
3 The Android version is also the first game in the Titanfall franchise not to be given the ESRB 's Mature rating .
4 All servers for Titanfall : Assault were shut down on July 30th , 2018 and ability to download the game from Google Play on July 31 , 2018 .
5 The game shutting down disappointed many titanfall fans as they had a game that was accessible on the android , google , and IOS devices which was a great way to play on the go .

##title
Ștefan Grigorie
##doc
0 Ștefan Costel Grigorie ( born 31 January 1982 ) is a Romanian former footballer who played as a midfielder for teams such as : FC U Craiova , Dinamo București , Politehnica Timișoara , Rapid București or FC Brașov , among others .
1 He is currently a manager in the youth program of Rapid București .
2 Grigorie had only played in two cities before moving to Timișoara ; he spent the first years of his career at Craiova , where he was contracted by Universitatea and moved to Bucharest in 2002 in order to play for Dinamo Bucureşti .
3 He played four years there ( developing an appetite for goals ) until the summer of 2006 when he was bought together with Dan Alexa by Politehnica .
4 In the summer break of 2007 Grigorie returned to Bucharest , this time for Rapid .
5 Grigorie has two caps for the Romanian national team .

##title
WUIS
##doc
0 WUIS ( 91.9 FM ) , is the National Public Radio member station in Springfield , Illinois , United States .
1 It primarily features National Public Radio news and talk programming .
2 The station is owned by and based at the University of Illinois at Springfield .
3 It operates a full - time satellite , WIPA in Pittsfield , Illinois .
4 WIPA serves a small portion of the Quincy market .
5 WUIS originally hit the airwaves on January 3 , 1975 as WSSR , operated by what was then Sangamon State University .
6 It became WSSU in 1989 , and adopted its current calls when Sangamon State merged with the University of Illinois system in 1995 .
7 WIPA was brought online in 1993 .
8 In 2015 , the station rebranded as " NPR Illinois . "

##title
Maybe (Jay Sean song)
##doc
0 " Maybe " is the second single from Jay Sean 's second album My Own Way .
1 It was originally scheduled to be released on 7 April 2008 but was postponed .
2 The digital download was available on iTunes from 20 April 2008 and for wider release on 20 April 2008 , the song physically came out on 28 April 2008 .
3 The song reached the Top 20 in the UK Singles Chart , peaking at # 19 on the week dated 4 May 2008 .
4 It was also Sean 's most successful song in East Asia , where it reached # 7 on the Japan Hot 100 Singles chart .
5 It also reached # 1 on the Japanese Airplay Charts .
6 A Hindi version sung by Sean was released as part of My Own Way in India .
7 A Mandarin Chinese cover version by Coco Lee has also been released in China .

##title
Guido Bonatti
##doc
0 Guido Bonatti ( died between 1296 and 1300 ) was an Italian mathematician , astronomer and astrologer , who was the most celebrated astrologer of the 13th century .
1 Bonatti was advisor of Frederick II , Holy Roman Emperor , Ezzelino da Romano III , Guido Novello da Polenta and Guido I da Montefeltro .
2 He also served the communal governments of Florence , Siena and Forlì .
3 His employers were all Ghibellines ( supporters of the Holy Roman Emperor ) , who were in conflict with the Guelphs ( supporters of the Pope ) , and all were excommunicated at some time or another .
4 Bonatti 's astrological reputation was also criticised in Dante 's Divine Comedy , where he is depicted as residing in hell as punishment for his astrology .
5 His most famous work was his Liber Astronomiae or ' Book of Astronomy ' , written around 1277 .
6 This remained a classic astrology textbook for two centuries .

##title
Fyodor Kulakov
##doc
0 Fyodor Davydovich Kulakov ( ) ( 4 February 1918 – 17 July 1978 ) was a Soviet - Russian statesman during the Cold War .
1 Kulakov served as Stavropol First Secretary from 1960 until 1964 , immediately following Nikita Khrushchev 's ouster .
2 During his First Secretaryship in Stavropol , Kulakov met Mikhail Gorbachev ; Kulakov became Gorbachev 's mentor , and when he left his Stavropol First Secretaryship to enter national politics , Gorbachev took over his former office .
3 Kulakov was elected to several important seats in the 1960s .
4 In 1971 , he was elected to the Political Bureau ( Politburo ) .
5 He became a leading figure of Soviet leadership , and impressed Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev to such an extent that Western commentators believed that Kulakov would become Brezhnev 's successor .
6 This did not happen since Kulakov died in 1978 , four years before Brezhnev .

##title
Black Lake (Michigan)
##doc
0 Black Lake is located in Cheboygan and Presque Isle counties in northern Michigan , United States .
1 With a surface area of , it is the seventh largest inland lake in Michigan .
2 The largest body of water in the Black River watershed , it drains through the Lower Black and Cheboygan rivers into Lake Huron .
3 Black Lake is a summer destination for many families from the suburban Detroit area and from other nearby states as well as residents of the neighboring town of Onaway .
4 Onaway State Park , at the southeastern end of the lake , offers camping , swimming and fishing .
5 Its buildings , built during the Great Depression by the Civilian Conservation Corps , have been deemed eligible for inclusion in the National Register of Historic Places .
6 Businesses on or near the lake include the Black River Marina , The Bluffs Restaurant and the 211 Outpost .
7 Since the late 1960s , the United Auto Workers Union has maintained the Walter and May Reuther Family Education Center on the site of a former private estate .
8 Black Lake is noted for its unusual fishing season .
9 A limited lake sturgeon ice fishing season is permitted in the winter .
10 The fishery is limited to five total fish taken each year , each over 36 inches and taken through the ice with fishing spears .
11 25 anglers are chosen by lottery each day and given a flag to raise when they have caught a fish .
12 When five flags have been raised the season is closed for the year .
13 Seasons have lasted as little as a few hours .

##title
Beyond Good &amp; Evil (video game)
##doc
0 Beyond Good & Evil is a 2003 action - adventure video game developed and published by Ubisoft for the PlayStation 2 , Microsoft Windows , Xbox and GameCube platforms .
1 The story follows the adventures of Jade , an investigative reporter and martial artist , who works with a resistance movement to reveal a planet - wide alien conspiracy .
2 The player controls Jade and allies , solving puzzles , fighting enemies , and obtaining photographic evidence .
3 Michel Ancel , creator of the Rayman series , envisioned the game as the first part of a trilogy .
4 The game was developed under the codename " Project BG&E ; " by 30 Ubisoft Pictures employees with production lasting more than three years .
5 One of the main goals of the game is to create a meaningful story while giving players lots of freedom , though the game adopts a relatively linear structure .
6 The game was received poorly when it was shown at E3 2002 , and it prompted the developers to change some of the game 's elements , including Jade 's design .
7 Ancel also attempted to streamline the game in order to make the game more commercially appealing .
8 Beyond Good & Evil was critically acclaimed .
9 Critics praised the game 's animation , setting , story , and design , but criticized the game 's combat and technical issues .
10 The game received a nomination for " Game of the Year " at the 2004 Game Developers Choice Awards .
11 While the game had a cult following , it was considered a commercial failure at launch .
12 A full HD re - mastered version of the game was released on Xbox Live Arcade in March 2011 and on PlayStation Network in June 2011 .
13 A prequel , Beyond Good and Evil 2 , is in development and was announced at E3 2017 .

##title
Brookston, Minnesota
##doc
0 Brookston is a city in Saint Louis County , Minnesota , United States ; located along the Saint Louis River , opposite the mouth of the Artichoke River .
1 The population was 141 at the 2010 census .
2 Brookston is located 27 miles west of the city of Duluth and 17 miles northwest of the city of Cloquet .
3 U.S. Highway 2 and Saint Louis County Road 31 ( CR 31 ) are two of the main routes in Brookston .
4 The city of Brookston is located within Culver Township geographically but is a separate entity .
5 Brookston is politically independent of the township .
6 Brookston is located on the northern edge of the Fond du Lac Indian Reservation .
7 It is one of three administrative centers of the reservation .
