##title
Todas as Ruas do Amor
##doc
0 " Todas as ruas do amor " ( All the streets of love ) is a song by Portuguese band Flor - de - Lis , and was the Portuguese entry to the Eurovision Song Contest 2009 .
1 The song was composed by Paulo Pereira and Pedro Marques .
2 The song was the winner of the Festival da Canção contest on 28 February 2009 , receiving maximum votes from the juries , and coming second in the public televote .
3 The song competed for Portugal in the first semi - final of Eurovision 2009 , where Flor - de - Lis performed 16th in the running order , following Finland 's Waldo 's People with " Lose Control " and preceding Malta 's Chiara with " What If We " .
4 " Todas as ruas do amor " qualified for the final round , where they performed 6th in the running order preceding Iceland 's Yohanna with " Is It True ? " .
5 The song finished 15th with 57 points .

##title
Villanova Preparatory School
##doc
0 Villanova Preparatory School is an Augustinian Catholic co - ed day and boarding school in the United States , located in the California town of Ojai .
1 Sitting on more than 130 acres , Villanova 's campus has many athletic facilities , two dormitories , sports fields and trails , a gym , and tennis courts .
2 The school is located in the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles , and is a member of the Augustinian Secondary Education Association .
3 Established in October 1924 at the request of Bishop John Cantwell ( John Joseph Cantwell ) , Villanova was founded by Augustinians invited to California from Villanova , Pennsylvania to open parishes in the early 1920s .
4 Villanova is a member of the Augustinian Secondary Education Association ( ASEA ) comprising eight secondary institutions in North America and over 100 schools worldwide .
5 Villanova offers both a day and resident program and is the only co - ed Augustinian boarding school in the country .
6 Villanova has a small chapel that holds mass every Sunday for both students and the public .
7 In 2015 - 16 , student enrollment was 265 .
8 Thirty - four percent of students are boarders , and represent 14 different countries .

##title
Kiss Each Other Clean
##doc
0 Kiss Each Other Clean is the fourth studio album by Iron & Wine , released January 25 , 2011 via 4AD ( worldwide ) and Warner Bros. in the US .
1 The album 's title is taken from the lyrics of " Your Fake Name Is Good Enough for Me " .
2 The first track from the album , " Walking Far from Home , " was released on November 26 in CD single and 12 " vinyl versions as part of a special Record Store Day Black Friday event .
3 The digital download version was released on November 30 .
4 The song " Tree by the River " has also been released , for free download , on Iron & Wine 's website .
5 On January 5 , Iron & Wine performed all but one song from Kiss Each Other Clean live at the Greene Space in New York City for a live broadcast on NPR 's website .
6 The album marks a further change in style – in an interview with Spin , Beam said “ It ’s more of a focused pop record .
7 It sounds like the music people heard in their parent ’s car growing up … that early - to - mid-’70s AM , radio - friendly music . "
8 In 2017 it was ranked number 65 in Paste magazine 's " The 100 Best Indie Folk Albums " list ..

##title
Aino (mythology)
##doc
0 Aino is a figure in the Finnish national epic Kalevala .
1 It relates that she was the beautiful sister of Joukahainen .
2 Her brother , having lost a singing contest to the storied Väinämöinen , promised Aino 's " hands and feet " in marriage if Väinämöinen would save him from drowning in the swamp into which Joukahainen had been thrown .
3 Aino 's mother was pleased at the idea of marrying her daughter to such a famous and well born person , but Aino did not want to marry such an old man .
4 Rather than submit to this fate , Aino drowned herself ( or ended up as a nix ) .
5 However , she returned to taunt the grieving Väinämöinen as a salmon .
6 The name Aino , meaning " the only one " , was invented by Elias Lönnrot who composed the Kalevala .
7 In the original poems she was mentioned as " the only daughter " ( aino tytti ) .

##title
Russification of Finland
##doc
0 The policy of Russification of Finland ( Finnish : sortokaudet / sortovuodet - times / years of oppression ) was a governmental policy of the Russian Empire aimed at limiting the special status of the Grand Duchy of Finland and possibly the termination of its political autonomy and cultural uniqueness in 1899 – 1905 and in 1908 – 1917 .
1 It was a part of a larger policy of Russification pursued by late 19th – early 20th century Russian governments which tried to abolish cultural and administrative autonomy of non - Russian minorities within the empire .
2 The two Russification campaigns evoked widespread Finnish resistance , starting with petitions and escalating to strikes , passive resistance ( including draft resistance ) and eventually active resistance .
3 Finnish opposition to Russification was one of the main factors that ultimately led to Finland 's declaration of independence in 1917 .

##title
Edmund Burke
##doc
0 Edmund Burke (; 12 January [ NS ] 17309 July 1797 ) was an Irish statesman born in Dublin , as well as an author , orator , political theorist and philosopher , who after moving to London in 1750 served as a member of parliament ( MP ) between 1766 and 1794 in the House of Commons with the Whig Party .
1 Burke was a proponent of underpinning virtues with manners in society and of the importance of religious institutions for the moral stability and good of the state .
2 These views were expressed in his A Vindication of Natural Society .
3 Burke criticized British treatment of the American colonies , including through its taxation policies .
4 He also supported the rights of the colonists to resist metropolitan authority , though he opposed the attempt to achieve independence .
5 Burke is remembered for his support for Catholic emancipation , the impeachment of Warren Hastings from the East India Company and for his staunch opposition to the French Revolution .
6 In his Reflections on the Revolution in France , Burke asserted that the revolution was destroying the fabric of good society , traditional institutions of state and society and condemned the persecution of the Catholic Church that resulted from it .
7 This led to his becoming the leading figure within the conservative faction of the Whig Party , which he dubbed the " Old Whigs " , as opposed to the pro - French Revolution " New Whigs " , led by Charles James Fox .
8 In the nineteenth century , Burke was praised by both conservatives and liberals .
9 Subsequently , in the twentieth century he became widely regarded as the philosophical founder of modern conservatism .

##title
Naomi (wrestler)
##doc
0 Trinity Fatu ( née McCray ; born November 30 , 1987 ) is an American wrestler , actress , model , dancer and singer signed to WWE , performing on the SmackDown brand under the ring name Naomi .
1 In August 2009 , McCray signed with World Wrestling Entertainment ( WWE ) and was assigned to its past developmental territory Florida Championship Wrestling ( FCW ) , where she was the inaugural FCW Divas Champion .
2 In August 2010 , she competed in the all - female third season of NXT , where she came in second place .
3 In January 2012 , she made her main roster debut alongside Cameron , forming The Funkadactyls .
4 Since July 2013 , Naomi has appeared as one of the main cast members of the reality television series Total Divas .
5 In February 2017 , Naomi won the WWE SmackDown Women 's Championship at the Elimination Chamber event , becoming the first African - American woman to capture the title .
6 After vacating the title due to injury , Naomi regained the championship two months later at WrestleMania 33 and became the inaugural winner of the WrestleMania Women 's Battle Royal at the following year 's WrestleMania .

##title
Smoke Break
##doc
0 " Smoke Break " is a song recorded by American country music artist Carrie Underwood from her fifth studio album , Storyteller .
1 It was released on August 21 , 2015 , through Sony Music Nashville , as the album 's lead single .
2 It was written by Underwood , Chris DeStefano , and Hillary Lindsey , and was produced by Jay Joyce .
3 Musically , it has lyrics about escaping life 's many stresses .
4 " Smoke Break " was met with critical acclaim , with music critics describing it as " a homage to hard working people in need of a breather " .
5 It quickly became a commercial success , setting an all - time record for the largest first - week adds at country radio .
6 It went on to reach number one on the Billboard Canada Country chart and number two on the Billboard Country Airplay chart in the US , becoming her 20th top - two single on the chart .
7 The song 's accompanying music video was directed by Randee St. Nicholas and won the 2016 CMT Music Award for Female Video of the Year .
8 The song received its first televised performance at The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon , on September 10 , 2015 .

##title
Rock n Roll (Avril Lavigne song)
##doc
0 " Rock n Roll " is a song by Canadian recording artist Avril Lavigne .
1 It was released as the second single from her self - titled fifth studio album by Sony Music Entertainment on August 23 , 2013 .
2 The song was written by Lavigne , David Hodges , Chad Kroeger , Jacob Kasher Hindlin , Rickard B. Göransson and Peter Svensson and was produced by Peter Svensson .
3 " Rock n Roll " is an upbeat pop punk song , and lyrically it is a declaration of rebellion on which the singer puts up her " middle finger to the sky " to " let 'em know that she 's still rock and roll , " refusing to behave like an adult .
4 The song received a critical praise from music critics , and was highlighted as one of the standout tracks on the album .
5 " Rock n Roll " performed moderately on the charts , reaching number one in South Korea and Taiwan , and number five in Japan , respectively .
6 The song failed to make impact elsewhere , peaking at number 37 in Canada and number 91 on the US Billboard Hot 100 chart .
7 The music video directed by Chris Marrs Piliero shows Lavigne in full combat mode , conspiring with Danica McKellar ( playing a character called Winnie Cooperre ) in an attempt to " save rock and roll " .

##title
David Bohigian
##doc
0 David Bohigian serves as the Executive Vice President of the Overseas Private Investment Corporation after being confirmed by the Senate in August 2017 .
1 Bohigian joined OPIC after being the Managing Director of Pluribus Ventures , an advisor to innovative financial service firms and investor in impact - driven companies .
2 Earlier , Bohigian served on the core management team of Bridgewater Associates , the world 's largest hedge fund .
3 Prior to Bridgewater , Bohigian founded E2 Capital Partners , which developed new financing models for energy efficiency projects .
4 Bohigian previously served as an Assistant Secretary of Commerce under George W. Bush , focusing on eliminating barriers to trade and investment for US companies .
5 Earlier , Bohigian led the Department 's Policy Office as the lead economic and energy advisor to two Secretaries .
6 Before the Commerce Department , Bohigian served as a Managing Director of Idealab .
7 Bohigian joined Idealab after it acquired the venture capital firm he founded , VenCatalyst .
8 Prior to founding VenCatalyst , Bohigian was a partner at Jefferson Partners , a Washington , D.C .- based venture capital firm .
9 Bohigian received his law degree from Washington University in St. Louis and a journalism degree from Washington & Lee .

##title
Memories (Elvis Presley song)
##doc
0 " Memories " is a 1968 song originally recorded by Elvis Presley .
1 It was written by Billy Strange and Mac Davis specially for Presley to perform on Elvis , his comeback TV special that would air on NBC on December 3 , 1968 .
2 Later Mac Davis recalled to Billboard : " They had asked for a song about looking back over the years , and oddly enough , I had to write it in one night .
3 I stayed up all night at Billy Strange 's house in Los Angeles .
4 He had a little office set up in his garage .
5 I wrote it right there . "
6 Released in the United States in 1969 as a B - side to " Charro " , the title song from the movie Charro ! , " Memories " reached number 35 on the Billboard Hot 100 for the week of April 12 , 1969 .
7 The song is also included on the album Elvis , the soundtrack album for the NBC TV special at which it was first performed .
8 For the TV show itself the song was recorded live , but the album features a studio version recorded on June 24 .
9 The book Rock Song Index : The 7500 Most Important Songs for the Rock and Roll Era calls the song " Memories " the " hallmark of [ Elvis ' ] later ( fat Elvis ) period " .

##title
Michael Imperioli
##doc
0 Michael Imperioli ( born March 26 , 1966 ) is an American actor , writer and director best known for his role as Christopher Moltisanti on The Sopranos , for which he won the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series in 2004 .
1 He also appeared in the TV drama series Law & Order as NYPD Detective Nick Falco .
2 Imperioli spent the 2008 - 2009 television season as Detective Ray Carling in the US version of Life on Mars .
3 He was starring as Detective Louis Fitch in the ABC police drama Detroit 1 - 8 - 7 until its cancellation .
4 He wrote and directed his first feature film , The Hungry Ghosts , in 2008 .
5 In 2015 , he starred in Mad Dogs , a dark - comic thriller television series available for viewing on Amazon 's Amazon Prime subscription service in the U.S and on Shomi in Canada .

##title
Aleksandr Alekseevich Borovkov
##doc
0 Aleksandr Alekseevich Borovkov ( Александр Алексеевич Боровков , 6 March 1931 , Moscow ) is a Russian mathematician .
1 Borovkov received his Russian candidate degree ( Ph.D. ) in 1959 under Andrey Kolmogorov at Moscow State University and his Russian doctorate ( higher doctoral degree ) in 1963 .
2 He is an academician at the Sobolev Institute of Mathematics of the Siberian Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences and a professor at the Novosibirsk State University .
3 His research deals with probability theory , mathematical statistics , and stochastic processes .
4 He was an Invited Speaker of the ICM in 1966 in Moscow and in 1978 in Helsinki ( Rate of convergence and large deviations in invariance principle ) .
5 He was elected in 1966 a corresponding member and in 1990 a full member of the Russian Academy of Sciences .
6 In 1979 he received the USSR State Prize .

##title
Józef Piłsudski Monument, Warsaw
##doc
0 The Józef Piłsudski Monument in Warsaw was erected to honor Józef Piłsudski , a military leader , Marshal of Poland and one of the main figures responsible for Poland 's regaining its independence .
1 This tall , bronze and granite statue is located near Piłsudski 's Square and the Hotel Europejski , at Tokarzewski - Karaszewicz Street .
2 It bears the inscriptions " Józef Piłsudski " and " Marshal of Poland " .
3 Plans to raise the monument can be traced to 1990 , when the president of Warsaw Stanisław Wyganowski endorsed the request of a group campaigning for the creation of a monument to Piłsudski .
4 The monument , cast in the Polish Navy Shipyards , was unveiled on 14 August 1995 , on the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Warsaw , which was commanded by Piłsudski .
5 The unveiling was attended by the President of Poland , Lech Wałęsa , and Piłsudski 's daughter , Jadwiga Piłsudska .
6 The original plans called for the monument to be raised at Na Rozdrożu Square , but were later modified to site it near the Łazienki .
7 This decision was protested by the supporters of the monument , who declared the new location too minor , and the monument was moved to the current location .
8 The current location has been and still is seen as controversial ; for example the statue 's designer , , expressed his opposition to it in a letter shortly before the monument was unveiled , pointing out that it would cause the monument to be isolated from most ceremonies that take place on the square .
9 Others have specifically criticized the fact that the location of the monument causes Polish soldiers to often face away from it during the guard change ceremony at the nearby Tomb of the Unknown Soldier , Warsaw , and during the observances for Polish Independence Day , which they regard as disrespectful .

##title
The Killers (Bukowski short story)
##doc
0 " The Killers " is a short - story by Charles Bukowski collected in his 1973 collection South of No North , originally published by John Martin 's Black Sparrow Press .
1 The story elucidates Bukowski 's publicly acknowledged artistic debt to Ernest Hemingway , the writer who had the most influence on American writers of Bukowksi 's generation .
2 Like " The Killers " , Bukowski 's story of the same name has as its thematic trope Murder in a nihilistic universe .
3 Unlike Hemingway , the killers actually accomplish their act in the time - frame of the story .
4 Bukowski 's authorial point of view in his version of " The Killers " also is influenced by Hemingway , as he it be seen as a logical outgrowth of the attitude expressed by Hemingway 's fictional alter - ego Nick Adams at the end of the 1927 " Killers " :
5 Bukowski 's fiction is full of attempts to escape the Los Angeles of his childhood and teen - years , all of which are doomed to failure as his fictional alter - ego , Henry Chinaski , finds the same appalling corruption everywhere he travels .
6 In Bukowski 's " The Killers " , there is no escape for the murderers who are the protagonists of the story , mirroring the doomed boxer Ole Andreson in Hemingway 's original .

##title
Outright Distribution
##doc
0 Outright Distribution ( formerly Screentime Partners ) is a global TV distribution company headquartered in London and owned by Warner Bros. Television Productions UK .
1 Outright specialises in format and finished programme distribution .
2 With an expanding library from Shed Media companies ' content and growing quality third party business , Outright Distribution has a large catalogue of programme brands , selling over 2,000 hours in over 125 different territories worldwide .
3 In Broadcast magazine 's Top Ten Most Used UK Distributors survey in March 2008 , Outright Distribution was placed 7th .
4 Outright Distribution became part of the Shed Media Group in September 2006 .
5 On 5 August 2010 , Warner Bros. Television secured a 55.75 % stake in Shed Media .
6 Warner Bros. completed its acquisition of a majority stake in Shed Media on 14 October .
7 Under the deal , Shed Media will remain an independent company but Outright Distribution would be folded into the Warner 's UK operation .

##title
Sappy Records
##doc
0 Sappy Records is an independent record label based in Sackville , New Brunswick , Canada , started by Julie Doiron in 1990 in order to release her own cassette .
1 The first 7 " vinyl release was " Julie and the Porthole to Dimentia " in 1993 , which featured a track each by the members of Eric 's Trip .
2 In 1994 Jon Claytor and Julie Doiron became business partners and ran the label together until 2000 .
3 The label lay dormant for a number of years after Julie Doiron won a Juno Award for Julie Doiron and the Wooden Stars in 2000 , and subsequently signed to Endearing Records in Canada and Jagjaguwar internationally .
4 The label was restarted in 2006 by Julie Doiron , Jon Claytor and Paul Henderson .
5 Sappy Records also hosts the Sappy Records Music Festival ( or SappyFest ) in Sackville , New Brunswick , and has featured notable acts such as The Arcade Fire , Holy Fuck , The Acorn , Attack in Black , Chad VanGaalen , Old Man Luedecke , Ohbijou and Wintersleep .
6 It takes place in the summer .

##title
Triple-threat man
##doc
0 In gridiron football , a triple - threat man is a player who excels at all three of the skills of running , passing , and kicking .
1 In modern usage , such a player would be referred to as a utility player .
2 Triple - threat men were the norm in the early days of football , as substitution rules were stringent .
3 Thus , in addition to the need for passing , running , and kicking skills , they were also required to play defense .
4 As injury awareness grew and substitution rules loosened , teams shifted to kicking specialists , which made the triple - threat man obsolete .
5 One of the last triple - threat men in professional football was George Blanda , a quarterback and kicker who last played for the Oakland Raiders of the National Football League in 1975 .
6 Danny White , a quarterback and punter , retired in 1989 .
7 Since then , non - specialists have placekicked only extremely infrequently in the NFL .
8 One instance occurred when Doug Flutie — also adept at both running and passing as a " scrambling " quarterback — drop kicked an extra point in 2006 during the last play of his career .
9 Danny White of the Dallas Cowboys was the last non - specialist to kick on a regular basis , as he served as the team 's starting quarterback and punter from 1980 until 1984 , after several years as backup to Roger Staubach .
10 There are , however , still dual - threat quarterbacks and wildcat halfbacks , who can both run and pass .
11 A quarterback who played wide receiver in high school or college may sparingly catch passes or be converted into a wide receiver who occasionally passes .
12 For over forty years the NFL single - season scoring record was held by a triple - threat man , Green Bay Packers Hall of Famer Paul Hornung .
13 Hornung set a record of 176 points in 1960 by scoring fifteen touchdowns , kicking forty - one extra points , and also kicking fifteen field goals .
##labels

##title
South Wigston High School
##doc
0 South Wigston High School was founded in 1938 and is a school serving the local community of South Wigston .
1 Today the school is an 11 – 16 yrs Academy .
2 The main feeder primary schools are Glen Hills , Fairfield and Parkland .
3 The school also attracts students from many areas of the city of Leicester and the county of Leicestershire .
4 The school is oversubscribed and is growing year on year .
5 South Wigston is known for its wide range of extra - curricular opportunities and for being a school that is inclusive and at the heart of the community .
6 The school has extensive grounds and a purpose build sports centre opened by Gary Lineker .
7 Notable alumni include Sue Townsend ( 1946 - 1950 ) , author ; Louis Deacon ( 1991 - 1995 ) , Rugby Player for Leicester Tigers and England ; and Brett Deacon ( 1992 - 1996 ) , Rugby Player for Leicester Tigers and England .
8 In 2016 BBC2 produced a documentary entitled , ‘ The Secret Life of Sue Townsend Aged 68 ¾.’ Much of the documentary was filmed at the school and current students participated .

##title
Chrysostom Blashkevich
##doc
0 Chrysostom Blashkevich , OSB ( January 27 , 1915 , Bely , Tver Oblast , Russian Federation - October 3 , 1981 , Niederalteich , Germany ) was a Benedictine monk of Russian origin .
1 Blashkevich was born in a Russian Orthodox family .
2 During World War II was recruited into the Soviet Army , where turned his coat and served as interpreter in the German Army .
3 In 1945 was converted to Catholicism and entered the Benedictine Order , being dean of the Monks of Byzantine Rite in Nideralteich Abbey in Germany .
4 Father Blashkevich was engaged in Catholic ecumenism with other Christian religions but he was also a critic of desacralisation of Catholic doctrine in relation to the dialogue with Protestant denominations and the real intentions of the Orthodox Christians in the ecumenism .

##title
Fyns Hoved
##doc
0 Fyns Hoved is a bight of northeastern Funen , Denmark , curving south to form the approach to Odense Fjord .
1 It is the northernmost point of Hindsholm and is thus Funen 's northernmost point , dividing the Kattegat and the Great Belt .
2 The eastern side of the bight between Fyns Hoved and Skoven , to the south , is irregular , with a beach and hills behind it , and to the south of the bight is a small , shallow bay , Korshavn Bay , with the Korshavn Light in the vicinity .
3 The bay is a natural harbour used by many yachtsmen .
4 Fyns Hoved is located in the dry Great Belt region , where rainfall is about per year compared to the national average of per year .
5 This makes it hospitable to plants that are more common in the dry areas of southern Europe .
6 The area is frequented by many shore birds and is also a resting place for migrating birds , and harbour porpoises can be seen offshore .
7 Numerous artists such as Theodor Philipsen , Johannes Larsen and Fritz Syberg have found inspiration in the light and the scenery .
8 There are many stone walls in the area ; these date back to 1810 , when the seven farmers in the village of Nordskov decided to divide the area between them so that they would each have one northern and one southern strip of land .
9 The seven cottagers had to content themselves with sharing one strip .
10 During the German occupation , barracks , a radar installation and artillery on Fyns Hoved guarded the entrance to the Great Belt .

##title
Harbour Esplanade, Docklands
##doc
0 Harbour Esplanade is a waterfront street and thoroughfare in Docklands , Australia .
1 It runs roughly north - south from Navigation Drive in the south to Docklands Drive in the north .
2 The road also forms the eastern boundary of the Victoria Harbour inlet and is adjacent to Victoria Dock .
3 The esplanade is a core element of the Docklands urban renewal precinct and is known for housing Docklands Stadium and several converted dock buildings that now serve as pubs and function spaces .
4 Harbour Esplanade is also the location of office buildings and restaurants , whilst the Capital City Trail runs parallel along some of its length .
5 It has been described as Melbourne 's waterfront boulevard and its future potential is compared to the successful Circular Quay in Sydney .

##title
Joseph R. Anderson
##doc
0 Joseph Reid Anderson ( February 16 , 1813 – September 7 , 1892 ) was an American civil engineer , industrialist , politician and soldier .
1 During the American Civil War he served as a Confederate general , and his Tredegar Iron Company was a major source of munitions and ordnance for the Confederate States Army .
2 Starting with a small forge and rolling mill in the mid-1830s , It was a flourishing operation by 1843 when he leased it .
3 He eventually bought the company outright in 1848 and forcefully and aggressively built Tredegar Iron Works into the South 's largest and most significant iron works .
4 When the Civil War broke out he entered the Army as a Brigadier General in 1861 .
5 Shortly after he was wounded and then resigned from the Army returning to the iron works .
6 It was the Confederacy 's major ( and for much of the war only ) source of cannons and munitions , employing some 900 workers , most of whom were slaves .
7 His plant was confiscated by the Union army at the end of the war , but returned to him in 1867 and he remained president until his death .
8 Anderson was very active in local civic and political affairs .

##title
Ngoako Ramatlhodi
##doc
0 Ngoako Ramatlhodi ( born 21 August 1955 ) , a senior member of the African National Congress , was South Africa 's Minister of Public Service and Administration from 2015 to March 2017 .
1 In the first Zuma administration he had been an MP and a controversial member of the Judicial Service Commission .
2 He resigned as MP in 2017 .
3 Up to 2015 he was Minister of Mineral Resources .
4 Ramatlhodi claimed in 2017 that Eskom chairperson Ben Ngubane and chief executive Brian Molefe requested that he terminate Glencor 's mining licenses in an apparent ruse to facilitate the sale of its Optimum coal mine to the Gupta family .
5 He was assigned to his subsequent ministerial post after he supposedly did not comply .
6 He was axed in the cabinet reshuffle of March 2017 , allegedly without being given reasons .
7 His position was taken by a known Zuma ally , the then Free State economic development MEC Mosebenzi Zwane .
8 In the same reshuffle , finance minister Pravin Gordhan and his deputy , Mcebisi Jonas , were also replaced .

##title
Load (album)
##doc
0 Load is the sixth studio album by the American heavy metal band Metallica , released on June 4 , 1996 by Elektra Records in the United States and by Vertigo Records internationally .
1 The album showed more of a hard rock side of Metallica than the band 's typical thrash metal style , which alienated much of the band 's fanbase .
2 It also featured influences from genres such as Southern rock , blues rock , country rock and alternative rock .
3 Drummer Lars Ulrich said about Load more exploratory nature , " This album and what we 're doing with it – that , to me , is what Metallica are all about : exploring different things .
4 The minute you stop exploring , then just sit down and fucking die " .
5 At 79 minutes , it is Metallica 's longest studio album .
6 Load debuted and spent four consecutive weeks at number one on the US Billboard 200 chart .
7 Load sold 680,000 units in its first week , making it the biggest opening week for Metallica as well as the biggest debut of 1996 .
8 It was certified 5× platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America ( RIAA ) for shipping five million copies in the United States .
9 Four singles—"Until It Sleeps " , " Hero of the Day " , " Mama Said " , and " King Nothing "— were released as part of the marketing campaign for the album .

##title
Mariana Cook
##doc
0 Mariana Cook ( born 1955 ) is an American fine art photographer specializing in black and white photography and gelatin silver prints .
1 Her work has been exhibited in the Metropolitan Museum of Art , the Museum of Modern Art , the J. Paul Getty Museum , the Boston Museum of Fine Arts , the National Portrait Gallery , the Bibliothèque Nationale , and the Musee d'Art Moderne .
2 She is perhaps best known for her black and white portrait , A Couple in Chicago , which captures a young Barack and Michelle Obama in their 1996 Hyde Park apartment , and the accompanying interview for The New Yorker .
3 Cook , the last surviving protégé of Ansel Adams , currently resides in New York City with her husband and daughter .

##title
Naomi van As
##doc
0 Naomi van As ( born 26 July 1983 ) is a Dutch field hockey player who plays as a forward / midfield for a Dutch club MHC Laren .
1 She made her debut for the Netherlands national team on June 20 , 2003 in a game against South Africa .
2 She was a part of the Dutch squad that became World Champions at the 2006 Women 's Hockey World Cup which also won the 2007 Champions Trophy .
3 Her family lives in South Africa
4 In 2008 Naomi van As became an Olympic Gold medal winner with her national team at the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing , scoring the first goal in their 2 - 0 win over China .
5 At the 2012 Summer Olympics , she was again part of the Dutch team that won gold .
6 She finished her international sportive career at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro in the by shoot - outs lost final against the team of Great Britain .
7 In 2009 and 2016 , she was named FIH Player of the Year .
8 Van As has a long time relationship with longtrack skater Sven Kramer .

##title
Njangalude Veettile Athidhikal
##doc
0 Njangalude Veettile Athidhikal ( The Guests in Our Home ) is a 2014 Malayalam family drama film directed by Sibi Malayil , joining hands with Jayaram after a long gap , opposite Priyamani in the lead .
1 The movie is penned by K. Gireesh Kumar .
2 Narain , Innocent , Kalabhavan Shajon , and Lena play significant roles in the film .
3 Priyamani has been paired up with Jayaram for the first time .
4 The background score and soundtrack are composed by Ratheesh Vega .
5 Kalabhavan Shajon debuts as a singer in the film through the song Maaye Maaye .
6 The film is produced by Milan Jaleel under his banner Galaxy Films .
7 Popcorn Entertainments Australia distributed the film all over Australia , New Zealand , Singapore and Malaysia .
8 The film released on 30 October 2014 , with mixed reviews .

##title
Mono (software)
##doc
0 Mono is a free and open - source project to create an Ecma standard - compliant .NET Framework - compatible software framework , including a C # compiler and a Common Language Runtime .
1 Originally by Ximian , it was later acquired by Novell , and is now being led by Xamarin , a subsidiary of Microsoft and the .NET Foundation .
2 The stated purpose of Mono is not only to be able to run Microsoft .NET applications cross - platform , but also to bring better development tools to Linux developers .
3 Mono can be run on many software systems including Android , most Linux distributions , BSD , macOS , Windows , Solaris , and even some game consoles such as PlayStation 3 , Wii , and Xbox 360 .
4 The Mono project has been controversial within the open - source community , as it implements portions of .NET Framework that may be covered by Microsoft patents .
5 Although standardized portions of .NET Framework are covered under Microsoft Open Specification Promise — a covenant stating that Microsoft will not assert its patents against implementations of its specifications under certain conditions — other portions are not , which led to concerns that the Mono project could become the target of patent infringement lawsuits .
6 Following Microsoft 's open - sourcing of several core .NET technologies since 2014 and its acquisition of Xamarin in the beginning of 2016 , an updated patent promise has been issued for the Mono project ( ) .
7 The logo of Mono is a stylized monkey 's face , mono being Spanish for monkey .

##title
University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust
##doc
0 University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust ( UCLH ) is an NHS foundation trust based in London , United Kingdom .
1 It comprises University College Hospital , University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street , the UCH Macmillan Cancer Centre , the Eastman Dental Hospital , the Hospital for Tropical Diseases , the National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery , the Royal London Hospital for Integrated Medicine and the Royal National Throat , Nose and Ear Hospital .
2 The Trust has an annual turnover of around £ 940 million and employs approximately 8,180 staff .
3 Each year its hospitals treat over 500,000 outpatients appointments and admit over 100,000 patients .
4 In partnership with University College London , UCLH has major research activities is part of the UCLH / UCL Biomedical Research Centre and the UCL Partners academic health science centre .
5 Its hospitals are also major teaching centres and offer training for nurses , doctors and other health care professionals in partnership with City , University of London , Kings College London , London South Bank University and UCL Medical School .

##title
Crupet
##doc
0 Crupet is a village in Wallonia , Belgium .
1 It is part of the municipality of Assesse , although formerly it was itself a municipality .
2 It is a member of the organisation Les Plus Beaux Villages de Wallonie ( French ; in English : Most Beautiful Villages in Wallonia ) .
3 The centre of the village is dominated by the Grotto of St Anthony of Padua .
4 The grotto was designed by the local curate Gerard and inaugurated on 12 July 1903 .
5 It features 22 religious - themed statues .
6 Many of them depict scenes from the life of St Anthony of Padua .
7 The Castle of Crupet , a medieval farm - chateau is situated below the village centre , and a little to the north , next to the river .
8 The postal code of Crupet is 5332 .

##title
The Virgin and Child with St Anne and St John the Baptist
##doc
0 The Virgin and Child with St Anne and St John the Baptist , sometimes called The Burlington House Cartoon , is a drawing by Leonardo da Vinci .
1 The drawing is in charcoal and black and white chalk , on eight sheets of paper glued together .
2 Because of its large size and format the drawing is presumed to be a cartoon for a painting .
3 No painting by Leonardo exists that is based directly on this cartoon .
4 The drawing depicts the Virgin Mary seated on the knees of her mother , St Anne , while holding the Child Jesus as Jesus ' young cousin , St. John the Baptist , stands to the right .
5 It currently hangs in the National Gallery in London .
6 It was either executed in around 1499 – 1500 , at the end of the artist 's first Milanese period , or around 1506 – 1508 , when he was shuttling between Florence and Milan .
7 The majority of scholars prefer the latter date , although the National Gallery and others prefer the former .

##title
Ali Abdullah Ahmed
##doc
0 Ali Abdullah Ahmed , also known as Salah Ahmed al - Salami ( Arabic : علي عبدالله احمد ) ( August 1 , 1979 – June 10 , 2006 ) , was a citizen of Yemen who died whilst being held as an enemy combatant in the United States Guantanamo Bay detainment camps , in Cuba .
1 His Guantanamo Internment Serial Number was 693 .
2 Joint Task Force Guantanamo counter - terror analysts estimated he was born in 1977 , in Ib , Yemen .
3 Ali Abdullah Ahmed died in custody on June 10 , 2006 .
4 His death was announced by the Department of Defense as a suicide , on the same day that the deaths of two other detainees were said to be suicides .
5 Their deaths received wide coverage in the media .
6 His younger brother , Muhammaed Yasir Ahmed Taher , also known as Yasir al - Simli , was also held in Guantanamo , until 2009 .
7 He was killed by a missile , launched from a drone , on March 2 , 2017 .

##title
Penn Line
##doc
0 The Penn Line is a MARC commuter rail service running from Union Station in Washington , D.C. to Perryville , Maryland via Baltimore 's Penn Station on Amtrak 's Northeast Corridor .
1 It is MARC 's busiest and only electric line .
2 Currently the line is the fastest commuter rail line in the country , with trains running at speeds of up to .
3 The service is operated under contract by Amtrak which supplies employees to operate trains , and maintains the right - of - way and MARC 's electric locomotives and passenger cars .
4 The line is administered by MARC , a service of the Maryland Transit Administration ( MTA ) .
5 The Penn Line is the successor to commuter services provided by the Pennsylvania Railroad ( PRR ) , Penn Central , and Conrail as long ago as the mid-19th century .
6 Additionally , Amtrak operated a commuter service named the Chesapeake between 1978 – 1983 .
7 In 1983 , Maryland , along with a number of other Northeastern states , took control of its commuter railroads and the " MARC " ( Maryland Area Regional Commuter ) service name was established .
8 The Penn Line became the replacement for Amtrak 's Chesapeake as well as the minimal former PRR commuter service between Washington and Baltimore .

##title
The Expendables (film series)
##doc
0 The Expendables is an American series of ensemble action films written by and starring Sylvester Stallone and originally created by David Callaham .
1 The film series itself was created to pay homage to the blockbuster action films of the 1980s and ' 90s and also pays gratitude to the action stars of those decades , as well as more recent stars in action .
2 The series consists of three films : The Expendables ( 2010 ) , The Expendables 2 ( 2012 ) and The Expendables 3 ( 2014 ) , with a final fourth film scheduled to be released in the future .
3 The series has received mixed critical reception , in regard to its plots and dialogue between the characters ; however , many critics praised the use of humor and action scenes .
4 The films have been box office successes .

##title
Nonconformist
##doc
0 In English church history , a nonconformist was a Protestant who did not " conform " to the governance and usages of the established Church of England .
1 Broad use of the term was precipitated after the Restoration of the British monarchy in 1660 , when the Act of Uniformity 1662 re - established the opponents of reform within the Church of England .
2 By the late 19th century the term specifically included the Reformed Christians ( Presbyterians , Congregationalists and other Calvinist sects ) , plus the Baptists and Methodists .
3 The English Dissenters such as the Puritans who violated the Act of Uniformity 1559—typically by practising radical , sometimes separatist , dissent — were retrospectively labelled as nonconformists .
4 By law and social custom , nonconformists were restricted from many spheres of public life — not least , from access to public office , civil service careers , or degrees at university — and were referred to as suffering from civil disabilities .
5 In England and Wales in the late 19th century the new terms " free churchman " and " Free Church " started to replace " dissenter " or " Nonconformist " .
6 One influential nonconformist minister was Matthew Henry , who beginning in 1710 published his multi - volume Commentary that is still used and available in the 21st century .
7 Isaac Watts is an equally recognized nonconformist minister whose hymns are still sung by Christians worldwide .
##labels
Presbyterians, Calvinist, subclass of(P279), [2]
Congregationalists, Calvinist, subclass of(P279), [2]
Matthew Henry, Protestant, religion(P140), [0, 6]
Isaac Watts, Protestant, religion(P140), [0, 7]
Calvinist, Protestant, subclass of(P279), [0, 2]
Baptists, Protestant, subclass of(P279), [0, 2]
Methodists, Protestant, subclass of(P279), [0, 2]
Puritans, Protestant, subclass of(P279), [0, 3]
Isaac Watts, Christians, religion(P140), [7]

##title
Flag of Prussia
##doc
0 The state of Prussia had its origins in the separate lands of the Margraviate of Brandenburg and of the Duchy of Prussia .
1 The Margraviate of Brandenburg developed from the medieval Northern March of the Holy Roman Empire , passing to the House of Hohenzollern in 1415 .
2 The Duchy of Prussia originated in 1525 when Albert of Brandenburg - Ansbach , a member of a cadet branch of the Hohenzollerns , secularized the eastern lands of the Teutonic Knights as a Polish fief .
3 Prince - elector John Sigismund , Elector of Brandenburg , inherited the Duchy of Prussia in 1618 , thus uniting Brandenburg and Prussia under one ruler in a personal union ; the Elector 's state became known as Brandenburg - Prussia .
4 The Kingdom of Prussia formed when Elector Frederick III assumed the title of Frederick I , King in Prussia , on 18 January 1701 .
5 Hohenzollern monarchical rule of Prussia ceased in 1918 after the fall of the German Empire in the aftermath of World War I ; the Kingdom becoming instead the Free State of Prussia .
6 The Allied Control Council decreed the formal abolition of the state of Prussia in 1947 following World War II .
##labels

##title
Newsnight
##doc
0 Newsnight is a weekday BBC Television current affairs programme which specialises in analysis and often robust cross - examination of senior politicians .
1 The programme 's regular presenters are currently Kirsty Wark and Emily Maitlis .
2 Several of the programme 's editors over the years have gone on to senior positions within the BBC and elsewhere .
3 Newsnight has been broadcast on BBC Two since 1980 .
4 It goes out on weekday evenings between 10:30pm and 11:15pm .
5 Occasionally it may have an extended edition if there is an especially significant event in the news – as happened on 7 July 2011 , when the closure of the News of the World led to a programme which continued until 11:35 pm .
6 Recent editions are available to view and download for a limited time through the BBC iPlayer .
7 A weekly 26-minute digest edition of Newsnight is screened on the corporation 's international channel , BBC World News .

##title
Scott Porter
##doc
0 Matthew Scott Porter ( born July 14 , 1979 ) is an American actor and occasional singer known for his role as Jason Street in the NBC television drama Friday Night Lights .
1 His character was injured during a football game in the pilot episode and became disabled .
2 The character was inspired by David Edwards , a high school football player .
3 Porter was paired with Alyson Michalka and Vanessa Hudgens in the 2009 film Bandslam .
4 He performed the song " Pretend " , which is featured on the Bandslam soundtrack .
5 In 2010 , he played the role of Blake , a law firm investigator , in CBS ' legal drama The Good Wife .
6 He starred as George Tucker in The CW comedy - drama series Hart of Dixie .

##title
Samsung Galaxy S series
##doc
0 The Samsung Galaxy S ( Super Smart ) series is a line of high - end Android - powered mobile devices produced by Samsung Electronics , a division of Samsung from South Korea .
1 The series consisted initially of smartphones and the first device , the Samsung Galaxy S , was announced in March 2010 and released for sale in June of that year .
2 Since the introduction of the Samsung Galaxy Note in 2011 , the Galaxy S line has co - existed with the Galaxy Note line as being Samsung 's flagship smartphones .
3 Samsung later expanded the Galaxy S line to tablet computers with the announcement of the Galaxy Tab S in June 2014 and released the next month .
4 As of 2018 , the latest smartphones in the Galaxy S series are the Samsung Galaxy S9 and Samsung Galaxy S9 + , both released on 16 March 2018 , and the latest tablet is the Samsung Galaxy Tab S4 released on August 1 , 2018 .

##title
Bernard Cribbins
##doc
0 Bernard Joseph Cribbins , OBE ( born 29 December 1928 ) is an English character actor , voice - over artist and musical comedian with a career spanning over seventy years .
1 He came to prominence in films of the 1960s , and has been in work consistently since his professional debut in the mid-1950s .
2 Cribbins narrated The Wombles , a BBC children 's television programme that ran for 60 episodes between 1973 and 1975 , and played the pretentious guest Mr. Hutchinson in " The Hotel Inspectors " episode of Fawlty Towers ( 1975 ) , and the belligerent barman in Alfred Hitchcock 's Frenzy ( 1972 ) .
3 He also recorded several successful novelty records in the early 1960s and was a regular and prolific performer on the BBC 's Jackanory from 1966 to 1991 .
4 Having appeared as Tom Campbell , a companion to Dr. Who in the 1966 feature film Daleks ' Invasion Earth 2150 A.D. , Cribbins also appeared four decades later as Wilfred Mott , a companion to television 's Tenth Doctor .

##title
Wellywood
##doc
0 Wellywood is an informal name for the city of Wellington , New Zealand .
1 The name — a conflation of Wellington and Hollywood — is a reference to the film production business established in the city by The Lord of the Rings film director Sir Peter Jackson , and Wellington - based special effects companies Weta Workshop and Weta Digital .
2 The businesses operate a number of film - related facilities in the Wellington suburb of Miramar .
3 In March 2010 , the Wellington Airport company announced plans to erect a Hollywood - style sign Wellywood on a hillside next to the Miramar cutting .
4 After the airport considered a range of alternatives , it was announced in May 2011 that the Wellywood sign would be going ahead .
5 However this was met with enormous criticism , and on 1 June 2011 it was announced that a panel would be convened to consider alternative sign options .
6 The panel ran a binding public poll on The Dominion Post website with the ' Wellington Blown Away ' design being chosen .
7 The sign was erected 27 July 2012 .

##title
Christopher Franke
##doc
0 Christopher Franke ( born 6 April 1953 , Berlin ) is a German musician and composer .
1 From 1971 to 1987 he was a member of the electronic group Tangerine Dream .
2 Initially a drummer with The Agitation , later renamed Agitation Free , his primary focus eventually shifted to keyboards and synthesizers as the group moved away from its psychedelic rock origins .
3 While he was not the first musician to use an analog sequencer , he was probably the first to turn it into a live performance instrument , thus laying the rhythmic foundation for classic Tangerine Dream pieces and indeed for the whole Berlin school sound .
4 After his departure from the group , he founded the Sonic Images record label , a new - age music label called Earthtone and the Berlin Symphonic Film Orchestra , and produced a number of solo music works .
5 After leaving Tangerine Dream , his only live concert was on 9 October 1991 at the Astoria Theatre in London .
6 He performed on stage with Edgar Rothermich ( a.k.a .
7 Richard E. Roth ) who is also his producer and engineer on all his solo projects and film music after 1990 .
8 Franke moved to Los Angeles in 1991 to pursue film work .
9 In 1995 he scored the AFI short Requiem .
10 He may be best known for composing the music for the science fiction television series Babylon 5 , as well as the score of the anime movie Tenchi Muyo !
11 in Love and in 2005 the music for German musical Ludwig² ( with Konstantin Wecker ) .

##title
Yi Seok
##doc
0 Yi Seok ( born 3 August 1941 ) is the nominal King of Joseon as the head of the House of Yi , the Korean royal family .
1 He was described as " the last prince still living on Korean soil , the last pretender to an abolished throne " by The New York Times .
2 Yi gained fame as the " singing prince " with the wedding favorite " Pigeon House " , released in 1967 .
3 Since 2004 , he has been employed by the city of Jeonju to promote tourism .
4 He is also a professor of history at Jeonju University .
5 He is a son of Prince Yi Kang , the fifth son of Emperor Gojong of Korea , and his thirteenth wife , Lady Hong Chŏng - sun , a former telephone operator .
6 Currently , Yi Seok resides in a building renovated for his use by the city of Jeonju , 243 kilometers south of Seoul .
7 The city government hopes that Seok 's settlement on the grounds of its Hanok Village will spotlight the historic significance of the city and help it to attract tourists .
8 As part of this arrangement , Seok gives lectures to Jeonju visitors about Korean history .
9 He also frequently lectures elsewhere and is often called upon for ceremonial duties , despite his official status as a private citizen .
10 Recently , Seok authored a book about the late Joseon Dynasty royal court family and has founded an organization , which he now leads , " The Imperial Grandson Association " , dedicated to preserving the culture of the royal court .
11 The Republic of Korea owned website , Korea.net , recognizes King Yi Seok as the only remaining heir in Korea .

##title
Snoopy and His Friends
##doc
0 Snoopy and His Friends is the third album by the Ocala , Florida group The Royal Guardsmen .
1 The group is best known for their hit recording of " Snoopy vs. the Red Baron " , which was first released in 1966 as a 45rpm record single ( it reached No .
2 2 in the US and No .
3 8 in the UK ) .
4 The song , " Snoopy 's Christmas " , is still one of the Top 10 ‘ non - traditional’ Christmas songs played during the month of December each year per BMI and ASCAP .
5 Both songs appear on Snoopy and His Friends .
6 Charles Schulz , creator of the Peanuts comic strip ( and the Snoopy character ) , drew the album artwork .

##title
United States Ambassadors appointed by Donald Trump
##doc
0 This is a list of United States ambassadors appointed by the 45th President of the United States , Donald Trump .
1 Ambassadorships are often used as a form of political patronage to reward high - profile or important supporters of the President .
2 The most visible ambassadorships are often distributed either in this way or to the President 's ideological or partisan confreres .
3 Most ambassadorships , however , are assigned to Foreign Service Officers who have spent their career in the State Department .
4 Regardless , all ambassadors must be formally appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate .
5 While all ambassadors serve at the president 's pleasure and may be dismissed at any time , career diplomats usually serve tours of roughly three years before receiving a new assignment , and political appointees customarily tender their resignations upon the inauguration of a new president .

##title
The Hub (band)
##doc
0 The Hub is an American " computer network music " ensemble formed in 1986 consisting of John Bischoff , Tim Perkis , Chris Brown , Scot Gresham - Lancaster , Mark Trayle and Phil Stone .
1 " The Hub was the first live computer music band whose members were all composers , as well as designers and builders of their own hardware and software . "
2 The Hub grew from the League of Automatic Music Composers : John Bischoff , Tim Perkis , Jim Horton , and Rich Gold .
3 Perkis and Bischoff modified their equipment for a performance at The Network Muse Festival in 1986 at The LAB in San Francisco .
4 Instead of creating an ad - hoc wired connection of computer interaction , they decided to use a hub - a general purpose connection for network data .
5 This was less failure - prone and enabled greater collaborations .
6 The Hub was the first band to do a telematic performance in 1987 at the Clocktower in New York .
7 Since this work represents some of the earliest work in the context of the new live music practice of Networked music performance , they have been cited as the archetypal network ensemble in computer music .
8 The Hub 's best - known piece , Stuck Note by Scot Gresham - Lancaster has been covered by a number of network music bands , including MiLO- the Milwaukee Laptop Orchestra
9 and BiLE- the Birmingham Laptop Ensemble .
10 They have collaborated with Rova Saxophone Quartet , Nick Collins , Phill Niblock , and Alvin Curran .
11 They currently perform around the world after a multi - year hiatus , ending in 2004 .

##title
John of Islay, Earl of Ross
##doc
0 John of Islay ( or John MacDonald ) ( 1434 – 1503 ) was a late medieval Scottish magnate .
1 He was Earl of Ross and the 4th Lord of the Isles as well as being Mac Domhnaill , chief of Clan Donald .
2 John would however prove to be the last of the Lords of the Isles , overmighty subjects of the Stewart Kings of Scotland and virtual kings in their own right in the Western Isles .
3 His struggle for power with King James III of Scotland ended in humiliation , following which his illegitimate son Angus Óg rebelled against his rule .
4 In a bitter civil war , John 's fleet of galleys met those of Angus sometime in the early 1480s off the coast of Mull at the Battle of Bloody Bay , in which John 's cause was defeated .
5 After Bloody Bay he became an inconsequential figure ; and Angus continued to dominate the affairs of Clan Donald up until his murder in 1490 .
6 In 1493 James IV brought the Lordship of the Isles to an end .
7 John died unlamented in 1503 , having witnessed the almost complete destruction of his family inheritance .

##title
Frédéric Talgorn
##doc
0 Frédéric Talgorn ( born 2 July 1961 in Toulouse , France ) is a French composer for film and television .
1 He studied music at the Paris Conservatoire where his teachers included Sabine Lacoraet and Yvonne Loriod , but he completed his studies on his own .
2 In 1987 he moved to the United States where he began to compose film music .
3 He also wrote the official music to accompany the Olympic flame for the 1992 Winter Olympic Games .
4 Notable film scores include Edge of Sanity ( 1989 ) , ( 1990 ) , Robot Jox ( 1990 ) , Fortress ( 1992 ) and The Temp ( 1993 ) .
5 He also has an extensive catalogue of concert music , and has often conducted his own works in concert and recording sessions .
6 He has also conducted and recorded film scores of others with the Royal Scottish National Orchestra .

##title
Robert Burns Fellowship
##doc
0 The Robert Burns Fellowship , established in 1958 as a bicentennial celebration , is claimed to be New Zealand 's premier literary residency .
1 The list of past fellows includes many of New Zealand 's most notable writers .
2 The award was established by an anonymous group ( thought to have been instigated by Charles Brasch ) to be awarded each year to " writers of imaginative literature , including poetry , drama , fiction , autobiography , biography , essays or literary criticism . "
3 The position is based at the University of Otago in Dunedin , New Zealand .
4 It provides a year 's salary along with accommodation and an office for a writer in and around the university .
5 Terms are for one year , although this may be extended to a second year in rare cases .
6 The Robert Burns Fellowship is named after Scotland 's national poet Robert Burns .
7 Dunedin is the city in New Zealand with the highest proportion of people of Scottish descent , and one of its founding fathers was Burns 's nephew Thomas Burns .
8 To commemorate the 50th anniversary of the fellowship , a book - Nurse to the imagination : Fifty years of the Robert Burns Fellowship - was launched in October 2008 , along with commemorations to coincide with Dunedin 's 2008 Arts Festival .

##title
Belmopan
##doc
0 Belmopan ( ) is the capital city of Belize .
1 Its population in 2010 was 16,451 .
2 Although the smallest capital city in the continental Americas by population , Belmopan is the third - largest settlement in Belize , behind Belize City and San Ignacio .
3 Founded as a planned community in 1970 , Belmopan is one of the newest national capital cities in the world .
4 Since 2000 Belmopan has been one of two settlements in Belize to hold official city status , along with Belize City .
5 Belmopan is located in Cayo District at an altitude of above sea level .
6 Belmopan was constructed just to the east of the Belize River , inland from the former capital , the port of Belize City , after that city 's near destruction by Hurricane Hattie in 1961 .
7 The government was moved to Belmopan in 1970 .
8 Its National Assembly Building is designed to resemble a Pre - Columbian Maya temple .

##title
Francesco De Masi
##doc
0 Francesco De Masi ( 11 January 1930 – 6 November 2005 ) was an Italian conductor and film score composer .
1 He studied composition at the San Pietro a Maiella Conservatory in Naples , under the guidance of Achille Longo , his uncle .
2 De Masi became interested in film music when Longo was asked to compose a soundtrack for a film , and he asked De Masi to be his assistant .
3 De Masi 's filmography includes scores for over 200 films and TV series , ranging from spaghetti westerns and sword and sandal epics to gialli and horror films , such as Lucio Fulci 's Lo squartatore di New York ( The New York Ripper ) .
4 De Masi also scored several action films , such as Enzo G. Castellari 's Quel maledetto treno blindato ( The Inglorious Bastards ) , but he is best remembered for his work on spaghetti westerns .
5 Unlike most other composers , De Masi started writing western scores slightly earlier than the genre 's most influential musician , Ennio Morricone .
6 As De Masi 's music was less influenced by Morricone , his style had a distinctive sound .
7 Many of his songs were performed by the low - voiced member of the I Cantori Moderni choir , Ettore " Raoul " Lovecchio .
8 De Masi was also very interested in classical music .
9 He taught at the Santa Cecilia Conservatory , also conducting the conservatory 's orchestra .
10 In an interview , De Masi listed Palestrina , Karlheinz Stockhausen , Ravel and Shostakovich as his main classical influences .
11 De Masi died of cancer at the age of 75 .

##title
Jonathan Joss
##doc
0 Jonathan Joss ( born December 22 , 1965 ) is an American actor .
1 He is best known for portraying the voice of John Redcorn from season 2 to 13 of the animated series King of the Hill , and for his recurring role as Chief Ken Hotate in Parks and Recreation .
2 Born in San Antonio , Texas , Joss is of Spanish , Comanche and White Mountain Apache descent .
3 He attended McCollum High School and later enrolled at Texas State University – San Marcos ( then Southwest Texas State University ) but left before graduating .
4 Joss later attended San Antonio College , before graduating from Our Lady of the Lake University with a degree in theater and speech .
5 Joss is also a musician , and performs as part of the Red Corn Band , an alternative blues group which has won a Grammy Award for Best Native American Music Album .

##title
Lake Hiawatha
##doc
0 Lake Hiawatha is located just north of Lake Nokomis in Minneapolis , Minnesota .
1 It was purchased by the Minneapolis Park and Recreation Board in 1922 for $ 550,000 .
2 At that time the lake was a marsh known as Rice Lake , but over four years , the park system transformed the wetland into a lake surrounded by a park .
3 The lake and park have a fishing dock , wading pool , tennis courts , and softball diamonds .
4 There is a recreation center that hosts activities .
5 The lake borders a municipal golf course .
6 In the winter the park sets up ice and hockey rinks .
7 There is a bike and walking path starting at Lake Hiawatha which veers onto Lake Nokomis or winds down the Minnehaha Creek right to the mouth of the Minnehaha Falls .
8 Lake Hiawatha is one of the few lakes through which Minnehaha Creek flows , and the last one before it reaches Minnehaha Falls and then the Mississippi River .
9 Friends of Lake Hiawatha is a community environmental action group that organizes volunteer efforts to clean the lake and park .

##title
Tropic of Cancer (film)
##doc
0 Tropic of Cancer is a 1970 American drama film directed by Joseph Strick and written by Betty Botley and Joseph Strick .
1 It is based on Henry Miller 's autobiographical novel Tropic of Cancer .
2 The film stars Rip Torn , James T. Callahan , David Baur , Laurence Lignères , Phil Brown and Dominique Delpierre .
3 The film was released on February 27 , 1970 , by Paramount Pictures .
4 Filming took place on location in Paris , produced by Joseph Strick with some help from the author , whose persona was portrayed by Rip Torn and his wife Mona by Ellen Burstyn .
5 The novel had provided a test for American laws on pornography in the early 1960s , and the film was rated X in the United States , which was later changed to an NC-17 rating .
6 In the UK the film was refused a theatrical ' X ' certificate by the BBFC .
7 Strick had previously adapted other works of literature - Jean Genet 's The Balcony and James Joyce 's Ulysses .

##title
Toulouse Business School
##doc
0 Toulouse Business School(TBS ) was founded in 1903 by the Toulouse Chamber of Commerce and Industry , the school 's initial vocation was to respond to the needs of the local business community for able business administrators .
1 TBS is one of the oldest well - known universities in France , it is affiliated to the French elite education system Grandes Ecoles .
2 TBS is a famous aristocratic business school , which enjoys a high reputation in the European traditional uppertendom .
3 Originally housed in a 15th - century monastery in the old town centre , the School 's present premises include a downtown campus , a modern campus located on the perimeter of the city , a modern campus in Barcelona , Spain and three others in Casablanca , Morocco , Paris and London .
4 The downtown main campus is located at the heart of the business complex near the centre of Toulouse .
5 In 2007 , Toulouse Business School became associate member of an alliance between several universities in Toulouse .
6 The school is triple accredited by European Quality Improvement System ( EQUIS ) , Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business ( AACSB ) and Association of MBAs ( AMBA ) and is one of France 's prestigious " Grandes Écoles de Management " .

##title
Independence Pass (Colorado)
##doc
0 Independence Pass , originally known as Hunter Pass , is a high mountain pass in the Rocky Mountains of central Colorado in the United States .
1 It is at elevation on the Continental Divide in the Sawatch Range .
2 The pass is midway between Aspen and Twin Lakes , on the border between Pitkin and Lake counties .
3 State Highway 82 traverses it , in the process reaching the highest elevation of a paved Colorado state highway on a through road .
4 After Cottonwood Pass to the south , it is the second - highest pass with an improved road in the state , the fourth - highest paved road in the state and the highest paved crossing of the Continental Divide in the U.S. Because of the heavy snowfall at its elevation , it is closed in wintertime , isolating Aspen from direct access from the east during the ski season .
5 When the pass is open in warmer weather , it is a popular destination .
6 A scenic overlook near the pass allows visitors to take in the alpine tundra environment above treeline , and offers excellent views to the east of Mount Elbert , Colorado 's highest peak and the second - highest mountain in the contiguous United States .
7 Rock climbers are drawn to nearby bouldering opportunities , and informal paths lead to nearby mountain summits of even higher elevation .
8 Backcountry skiers make use of the slopes during the late spring and early summer .
9 Since 2011 the pass has been on the route of the USA Pro Cycling Challenge .
10 The pass was formed by glacial action and erosion in the region , and its first recorded sighting was by Zebulon Pike in 1806 .
11 Ferdinand Hayden surveyed it in 1873 .
12 As part of the Continental Divide , it was the limit of European settlement in the region at the time , with the land to the west reserved for the Ute people .
13 Prospectors who defied governor Frederick Walker Pitkin 's order crossed the pass on July 4 , 1879 , giving it its current name and setting up a similarly named village ( now a ghost town ) to its west .
14 A toll road built across the pass was abandoned and neglected after a railroad connection was made to Aspen .
15 A new road replaced it in the 1920s ; portions of the old route can still be seen along the western approach .
16 The Independence Pass Foundation , based in Aspen , works to repair damage to the pass 's environment caused by both roads since 1984 .

##title
French Resistance
##doc
0 The French Resistance ( ) was the collection of French movements that fought against the Nazi German occupation of France and against the collaborationist Vichy régime during the Second World War .
1 Resistance cells were small groups of armed men and women ( called the Maquis in rural areas ) , who , in addition to their guerrilla warfare activities , were also publishers of underground newspapers , providers of first - hand intelligence information , and maintainers of escape networks that helped Allied soldiers and airmen trapped behind enemy lines .
2 The men and women of the Resistance came from all economic levels and political leanings of French society , including émigrés , academics , students , aristocrats , conservative Roman Catholics ( including priests ) , and also citizens from the ranks of liberals , anarchists and communists .
3 The French Resistance played a significant role in facilitating the Allies ' rapid advance through France following the invasion of Normandy on 6 June 1944 , and the lesser - known invasion of Provence on 15 August , by providing military intelligence on the German defences known as the Atlantic Wall and on Wehrmacht deployments and orders of battle .
4 The Resistance also planned , coordinated , and executed acts of sabotage on the electrical power grid , transport facilities , and telecommunications networks .
5 It was also politically and morally important to France , both during the German occupation and for decades afterward , because it provided the country with an inspiring example of the patriotic fulfillment of a national imperative , countering an existential threat to French nationhood .
6 The actions of the Resistance stood in marked contrast to the collaboration of the French regime based at Vichy , the French people who joined the pro - Nazi Milice française and the French men who joined the Waffen SS .
7 After the landings in Normandy and Provence , the paramilitary components of the Resistance were organised more formally , into a hierarchy of operational units known , collectively , as the French Forces of the Interior ( FFI ) .
8 Estimated to have a strength of 100,000 in June 1944 , the FFI grew rapidly and reached approximately 400,000 by October of that year .
9 Although the amalgamation of the FFI was , in some cases , fraught with political difficulties , it was ultimately successful , and it allowed France to rebuild the fourth - largest army in the European theatre ( 1.2 million men ) by VE Day in May 1945 .

##title
École des officiers de la gendarmerie nationale
##doc
0 L'École des officiers de la gendarmerie nationale , the French Gendarmerie nationale Officers School , was created in 1901 and based in the Schomberg barracks in Paris .
1 At the time it was simply to give additional training to NCOs likely to enter the officer corps .
2 In 1918 , following the First World War , the school moved to Versailles and diversified by including in its ranks officers from other armies .
3 It was not until 1937 that the school was given a flag .
4 This emblem was officially handed over to the chef de corps , Colonel Picot , 14 July 1937 , on the Champs - Élysées by the President Albert Lebrun .
5 During the Second World War , the school moved to Pau then back to Paris before finding its current home in the Augereau barracks in Melun on 1 October 1945 .

##title
San Pablito, Puebla
##doc
0 San Pablito is a small town located on the side of the Guajalote Mountain in the Sierra Norte de Puebla mountain region in central east Mexico .
1 It belongs to the Pahuatlán municipality of the state of Puebla .
2 Culturally it is dominated by the Otomi although it is part of the La Huasteca region .
3 San Pablito is best known for the commercial production of a bark paper called amate as a handcraft .
4 This paper is mostly sold to Nahua painters in Guerrero , but it is also sold nationally and internationally on its own .
5 The paper is made much the way it was before the arrival of the Spanish .
6 Originally , it was made only by the area 's shamans for ritual purpose but today commercial production is mostly done by the town 's women and children as many men have left to work in the United States .

##title
Hewanorra International Airport
##doc
0 Hewanorra International Airport , located near Vieux Fort Quarter , Saint Lucia , in the Caribbean , is the larger of Saint Lucia 's two airports and is managed by the Saint Lucia Air and Seaports Authority ( SLASPA ) .
1 It is on the southern cape of the island , about 53.4   km ( 33.2   mi ) from the capital city , Castries .
2 The airport is a Fire Category 9 facility that handles 500,000 passengers a year and can accommodate Boeing 747 , Airbus A330 , Airbus A340 , Boeing 777 , and other long - range intercontinental aircraft .
3 Aircraft maintenance is carried out by Caribbean Dispatch Services .
4 The country 's smaller airport , George F. L. Charles Airport , is located in Castries and handles inter - Caribbean passenger flights , which are operated with turboprop and prop aircraft .

##title
Ronald Leonard
##doc
0 Ronald Leonard is an American cellist .
1 He has had a distinguished career as a soloist , chamber musician , principal cellist and teacher .
2 He is currently on the faculties of the USC Thornton School of Music and the Colburn School .
3 He was a winner of the Walter Naumburg Competition while a student at the Curtis Institute of Music , where he studied with Leonard Rose and Orlando Cole .
4 His first professional position was as a cellist in the Cleveland Orchestra , where he sat on the second stand .
5 Two years later Mr. Leonard became principal cellist of the Rochester Philharmonic Orchestra and at that time began teaching at the Eastman School of Music .
6 He taught at Eastman for 17 years , spent one year as cellist of the Vermeer Quartet , and then was appointed principal cellist of the Los Angeles Philharmonic , a post he held for 24 years .
7 During this time , he soloed frequently with the orchestra .
8 During this entire period he has been very active as a soloist , chamber musician and teacher .
9 Conducting is his most recent activity ; Mr. Leonard is the conductor of the Colburn School Chamber Orchestra and he has been very involved at the USC Thornton School of Music , working with the string sections of both the USC Thornton Symphony and the USC Thornton Chamber Orchestra .
10 From 1993 to 2003 , he held the prestigious post of " Gregor Piatigorsky Endowed Chair in Violoncello " at the USC Thornton School of Music .
11 He was only third person to ever hold the position , following Piatigorsky himself and Lynn Harrell ( 1986 – 1993 ) .
12 He is known internationally as " one of the better cellists originally from Rhode Island " .

##title
Lewis of Luxembourg
##doc
0 Lewis of Luxembourg ( or Louis II de Luxembourg ; died 1443 ) was an Archbishop of Rouen , Bishop of Ely , and Cardinal .
1 He was a younger son of John of Luxembourg , Lord of Beauvoir and Marguerite of Enghien .
2 Lewis was elected archbishop of Rouen in 1436 .
3 He was the leading native administrator / collaborator with the Lancastrian regime in France .
4 As its position weakened , his own fortunes and even personal safety became precarious .
5 Although the city of Rouen did not fall to Charles VII of France until late 1449 , well after Luxembourg 's death , Henry VI 's government had long ago decided he needed and deserved remuneration and status based more securely in England .
6 Thus he was provided to Ely ' in commendam ' on 27 September 1437 .
7 This was the fifth wealthiest see in England , yet also amongst the smallest in terms of size or burden .
8 He is not known ever to have visited it .
9 He died on 18 September 1443 .

##title
Skylake (microarchitecture)
##doc
0 Skylake is the codename used by Intel for a processor microarchitecture that was launched in August 2015 succeeding the Broadwell microarchitecture .
1 Skylake is a microarchitecture redesign using the same 14   nm manufacturing process technology as its predecessor , serving as a " tock " in Intel 's " tick - tock " manufacturing and design model .
2 According to Intel , the redesign brings greater CPU and GPU performance and reduced power consumption .
3 Skylake CPUs share its microarchitecture with Kaby Lake , Coffee Lake and Cannon Lake CPUs .
4 Skylake is the last Intel platform on which Windows earlier than Windows 10 will be officially supported by Microsoft , although enthusiast - created modifications exist that allow Windows 8.1 and earlier to continue to receive updates on later platforms .
5 Some of the processors based on the Skylake microarchitecture are marketed as " 6th - generation Core " .
6 On October 8 , 2018 , Intel announced new 9th gen Core X 98xx/99xx series CPUs , with the Core i9 - 9980XE Extreme Edition leading the launch .

##title
Pleistocene coyote
##doc
0 The Pleistocene coyote ( Canis latrans orcutti ) , also known as the Ice Age coyote , is an extinct subspecies of coyote that lived in western North America during the Late Pleistocene era .
1 Most remains of the subspecies were found in southern California , though at least one was discovered in Idaho .
2 It was part of a carnivore guild that included other canids like foxes , gray wolves , and dire wolves .
3 Compared to their modern Holocene counterparts , Pleistocene coyotes were larger and more robust , weighing , likely in response to larger competitors and prey rather than Bergmann 's rule .
4 Their skulls and jaws were significantly thicker and deeper than in modern coyotes , with a shorter and broader rostrum and wider carnassial ( denoting the large upper premolar and lower molar teeth of a carnivore , adapted for shearing flesh ) teeth .
5 These adaptions allowed it to cope with higher levels of stress , when it killed larger prey , compared to modern coyotes .
6 Pleistocene coyotes were also likely more specialized carnivores than their descendants , as their teeth were more adapted to shearing meat , showing fewer grinding surfaces which were better suited for processing vegetation .
7 The lower jaw was also deeper , and the molars showed more signs of wear and breakage than modern populations , thus indicating that the animals consumed more bone than today .
8 Behaviorally , it is likely to have been more social than the modern coyote , as its remains are the third most common in the La Brea Tar Pits , after dire wolves and sabre - toothed cats , both thought to be gregarious species .
9 Their reduction in size occurred within 1,000 years of the occurrence of the Quaternary extinction event , when the climate changed and the majority of their larger prey became extinct .
10 Furthermore , Pleistocene coyotes were unable to successfully exploit the big game hunting niche left vacant after the extinction of the dire wolf , as that gap was rapidly filled by gray wolves .
11 These gray wolves are likely to have actively killed off the larger - bodied coyotes , with natural selection favoring the modern gracile morph .
12 Human predation on the Pleistocene coyote 's dwindling prey base may have also impacted the animal 's change in morphology .
##labels
California, North America, continent(P30), [0, 1]
Idaho, North America, continent(P30), [0, 1]

Pleistocene, Holocene, followed by(P156), []
