##title
Liang Congjie
##doc
0 Liang Congjie (; 4 August 1932 – 28 October 2010 ) was a Chinese historian best known for his work as an environmental activist who established the Friends of Nature in 1994 as the first environmental non - governmental organization to be officially recognized by the government of the People 's Republic of China .
1 Liang 's father , architect Liang Sicheng , had led attempts to prevent the destruction of the walls surrounding Beijing with the land to be used for the construction of highways .
2 His grandfather Liang Qichao spent 14 years in exile in Japan after he advocated on behalf of turning the Qing Dynasty into a constitutional monarchy .
3 His ancestry came to haunt him during the Maoist Cultural Revolution when he was purged for his being the " grandson of China 's biggest royalist " .
4 Liang was ultimately able to attend Peking University .
5 Having learned about the activities of Greenpeace , Liang and three of his colleagues at the Academy for Chinese Culture came to agreement that a corresponding organization was required in China to address growing environmental concerns in that country .
6 The group that they formed , Friends of Nature , eschewed Greenpeace 's more confrontational techniques , choosing to develop grassroots concern about nature through fostering environmental awareness in schools and establishing the nation 's first birdwatching group .
7 The organization worked with the Chinese government to ensure enforcement of existing environmental law , including efforts to protect a Tibetan antelope which were on the path to extinction and videotaping the cutting stands of old - growth forest in Western China that led to a 1999 order by Zhu Rongji prohibiting cutting down such trees .
8 Environmentalist Ma Jun described Liang as having " incubated the first generation of environmentalists in China " and described how he worked in conjunction with the government on a " constructively critical " basis to build support for protecting the environment .
9 Friends of Nature 's Li Bo credited him with " promoting ordinary Chinese 's participation in supervising pollution problems and protecting the environment " .
10 Liang was recognized in 2000 with the Ramon Magsaysay Award , which recognizes Asian contributions to public service , noting that he was able to push environmental issues while having " avoided the pitfall of alienating government " .
11 Liang died at the age of 78 on October 28 , 2010 , due to a lung infection while at a hospital in Beijing .
12 He was survived by his wife , a daughter and a son .

##title
Symphony Hall, Boston
##doc
0 Symphony Hall is a concert hall located at 301 Massachusetts Avenue in Boston , Massachusetts .
1 Designed by McKim , Mead and White , it was built in 1900 for the Boston Symphony Orchestra , which continues to make the hall its home .
2 The hall was designated a U.S. National Historic Landmark in 1999 and is a pending Boston Landmark .
3 It was then noted that " Symphony Hall remains , acoustically , among the top three concert halls in the world ... and is considered the finest in the United States . "
4 Symphony Hall , located one block from Berklee College of Music to the north and one block from the New England Conservatory to the south , also serves as home to the Boston Pops Orchestra as well as the site of many concerts of the Handel and Haydn Society .

##title
Signaling of the New York City Subway
##doc
0 In the New York metropolitan area , the Metropolitan Transportation Authority ( MTA ) runs the New York City Subway , which is mostly manually operated .
1 The subway system currently uses Automatic Block Signaling with fixed wayside signals and automatic train stops .
2 Many portions of the signaling system were installed between the 1930s and 1960s .
3 Because of the age of the subway system , some replacement parts must be custom built for the MTA , as they are otherwise unavailable from signaling suppliers .
4 Additionally , some subway services have reached their train capacity limits and can not operate extra trains with the current system .
5 There are two different schemes of signaling in the system .
6 The most used scheme is found on all of the B Division , which consists of lines originally built to the Brooklyn – Manhattan Transit Corporation ( BMT ) and Independent Subway System ( IND ) 's wider specifications , as well as on most of the A Division , which consists of lines built to the narrower specifications of the Interborough Rapid Transit Company ( IRT ) .
7 An older system was used on all of the A Division , but with the conversion of the IRT Dyre Avenue Line signals to the B Division scheme , this system is no longer in use .
8 As part of the modernization of the New York City Subway , the MTA has plans to upgrade much of the system with communications - based train control ( CBTC ) technology , which will control the speed and starting and stopping of subway trains .
9 The CBTC system is mostly automated and uses a moving block system – which reduces headways between trains , increases train frequencies and capacities , and relays the trains ' positions to a control room – rather than a fixed block system .
10 This will require new rolling stock to be built for the subway system , as only newer trains can use CBTC .

##title
Bonnie Blair
##doc
0 Bonnie Kathleen Blair ( born March 18 , 1964 ) is a retired American speed skater .
1 She is one of the top skaters of her era , and one of the most decorated athletes in Olympic history .
2 Blair competed for the United States in four Olympics , winning five gold medals and one bronze medal .
3 Blair made her Olympic debut in Sarajevo in 1984 where she finished eighth in the 500 meters .
4 At the time , Blair trained in both short - track and long - track speed skating .
5 She won the 1986 short - track world championship .
6 Blair returned to the Olympics in 1988 competing in long - track at the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary .
7 There she won her first Olympic gold medal in the 500 meters and a bronze medal in the 1,000 meter .
8 Blair won two gold medals in the 1992 Winter Olympics in Albertville and her final two Olympic gold medals at the 1994 Lillehammer games .
9 Blair continued competing through 1995 when the World Championships were held in Milwaukee , finally retiring in March 1995 .
10 After retiring from speed skating , Blair became a motivational speaker .
11 She has been inducted into the Chicagoland Sports Hall of Fame , the Wisconsin Athletic Hall of Fame , and the United States Olympic Hall of Fame .

##title
They Shoot Horses, Don't They? (film)
##doc
0 They Shoot Horses , Do n't They ?
1 is a 1969 American depression - era melodrama film based on Horace McCoy 's 1935 novel of the same name and directed by Sydney Pollack .
2 The screenplay was written by James Poe and Robert E. Thompson .
3 The film focuses on a disparate group of characters desperate to win a Depression - era dance marathon and the opportunistic emcee ( MC ) who urges them on to victory .
4 It stars Jane Fonda , Michael Sarrazin , Susannah York , Red Buttons , Bruce Dern , Bonnie Bedelia and Gig Young .
5 The film premiered at the 23rd Cannes Film Festival and was released theatrically in the United States on December 10 , 1969 .
6 The film upon release was a critical and commercial success , grossing $ 12.6 million on a budget of $ 4.86 million , becoming the sixteenth highest grossing film of 1969 .
7 Critics praised its direction , screenplay , depiction of the depression - era and performances , most notably of Fonda 's which marked a significant turning point in her career .
8 The film received nine nominations at the 42nd Academy Awards including Best Director , Best Actress ( for Fonda ) , Best Supporting Actress ( for York ) , Best Adapted Screenplay and winning Best Supporting Actor ( for Young ) .
9 It is the most nominated film in the history of the aforementioned awards without a Best Picture nomination .

##title
Roald
##doc
0 Roald is a village in Giske Municipality in Møre og Romsdal county , Norway .
1 The village is located on the northern part of the island Vigra .
2 Roald is about north of the city centre of Ålesund , connected via two undersea tunnels which opened in 1987 ( and will be going through extensive upgrades starting in 2008 ) .
3 Ålesund Airport , Vigra is south of the village of Roald .
4 Vigra Church is located a short distance south of Roald .
5 The village of Roald has a population ( 2013 ) of 808 , giving the village a population density of .
6 The village of Roald was the administrative centre of the old Roald Municipality that existed from 1890 until 1964 .
7 The former municipality was later renamed Vigra Municipality .
8 Since 1964 , it has been a part of Giske Municipality .

##title
Carl Buchheister
##doc
0 Carl Buchheister ( 17 October 1890 – 2 February 1964 ) was a German constructivist artist noted for his multiple series of " model paintings " at Galerie Lambert Weyl , Paris .
1 which he began in 1925 .
2 He was born in Hanover , Germany .
3 Although he was not officially part of the Bauhaus movement , Buchheister was a close friend of Wassily Kandinsky and paralleled many of the social and artistic goals of the Bauhaus school .
4 With regard to constructivism , Buchheister was typically more playful and improvisational than his contemporaries , becoming interested in the Dada movement after a collaboration with Kurt Schwitters in the late 1920s which led him to incorporate more varied materials such as acrylic glass , aluminum , wood , and twine into his compositions .
5 This direction was given much freer rein after World War II and the end of Nazism .
6 He died in Hanover in 1964 .

##title
Raunaq (album)
##doc
0 Raunaq : Conversation of Music and Poetry is a 2014 studio album composed by A. R. Rahman with lyrics penned by Kapil Sibal .
1 The album is described as a conversation of music and poetry that takes one on a journey of varied emotions .
2 Selected tracks of the album depict social scenario of India through Sibal 's lyrics .
3 The album was a result of Sibal 's anthology of poems to which Rahman added visuals from Raja Ravi Varma 's paintings , thus , developing songs and corresponding videos to it .
4 A. R. Rahman has played the role of a visual storyteller and has conceived the narrative of the music video " Aa Bhi Jaa " .
5 The album was announced through an introductory video backed by the track the same song .
6 The album being a visual story telling sort of , the marketing strategies developed were to have each song 's individual marketing and promotional activity released over a period of time .
7 The album had an introductory launch by Salman Khan at an event held in Mumbai on February 27 , 2014 .
8 The album was released on September 29 , 2014 .
9 The album was dedicated to Vogue Empower , a social awareness initiative that draws attention to women 's empowerment .

##title
Washington v. Texas
##doc
0 Washington v. Texas , 388 U.S. 14 ( 1967 ) , is a United States Supreme Court case in which the Court decided that the Compulsory Process Clause of the Sixth Amendment to the Constitution ( guaranteeing the right of a criminal defendant to force the attendance of witnesses for their side ) is applicable in state courts as well as federal courts .
1 Jackie Washington had attempted to call his co - defendant as a witness , but was blocked by Texas courts because state law prevented co - defendants from testifying for each other , under the theory that they would be likely to lie for each other on the stand .
2 The Supreme Court reasoned that the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment made the right to be able to compel defense witnesses to testify necessary for a defendant 's " due process " rights to fair proceedings , which applies to the states .
3 Only Justice John Marshall Harlan II parted from the Court 's " due process " focus , though he agreed with the outcome , as he regularly did in cases involving whether to apply federal rights to state courts .
4 The impact of Washington was narrowed by a later case , Taylor v. Illinois ( 1988 ) , in which the Court said that " countervailing public interests " , like the need to move through cases quickly , could be balanced against a defendant 's right to present witnesses .
5 In Taylor , the Supreme Court upheld a judge 's order blocking defense witnesses from testifying due to the defense attorney 's deliberate failure to disclose evidence to prosecutors earlier in the trial .
6 The defense attorney 's actions resulted in a lengthy delay in the proceedings which the trial judge felt was unjustified .
7 Legal scholars have seen this new grant of discretion to trial judges as a change to relying on " efficient justice " , a more limited vision of trial rights than the " right to present a defense " created in Washington .
##labels

##title
Battle of Chiari
##doc
0 The Battle of Chiari was fought on 1 September 1701 during the War of the Spanish Succession .
1 The engagement was part of Prince Eugene of Savoy 's campaign to seize the Spanish controlled Duchy of Milan in the Italian peninsula , and had followed his victory over Marshal Catinat at the Battle of Carpi in July .
2 Marshal Villeroi replaced Catinat as commander of the Franco – Spanish – Savoyard forces in the theatre , carrying with him orders from King Louis XIV to push the Imperialists out of Italy .
3 Foreseeing Villeroi 's intention of attacking at any price , Eugene entrenched himself in front of the small fortress of Chiari , and waited for the attack .
4 In a battle that lasted several hours the Austrians inflicted heavy casualties on Villeroi 's forces , gaining an overwhelming victory .
5 The campaign established Eugene in Lombardy , and helped to persuade the Maritime Powers to come to the aid of the Emperor .
6 Within a week of the battle England , the Dutch Republic , and Leopold I , had signed the second treaty of the Grand Alliance .

##title
Mendenhall Glacier
##doc
0 Mendenhall Glacier ( also Sitaantaagu ) is a glacier about long located in Mendenhall Valley , about from downtown Juneau in the southeast area of the U.S. state of Alaska .
1 The glacier and surrounding landscape is protected as part of the Mendenhall Glacier Recreation Area , a federally designated unit of the Tongass National Forest .
2 The Juneau Icefield Research Program has monitored the outlet glaciers of the Juneau Icefield since 1942 , including Mendenhall Glacier .
3 The glacier has also retreated since 1929 , when Mendenhall Lake was created , and over since 1500 .
4 The end of the glacier currently has a negative glacier mass balance and will continue to retreat in the foreseeable future .
5 Given that average yearly temperatures are currently increasing , and the outlook is for this trend to continue , it is actually possible that the glacier might experience a period of stabilization or slight advance during its retreating march .
6 This is because increasing amounts of warm , moist air will be carried up to the head of the icefield , where colder ambient temperatures will cause it to precipitate as snow .
7 The increased amount of snow will feed the icefield , possibly enough to offset the continually increasing melting experienced at the glacier 's terminus .
8 However , this interesting phenomenon will fade away if temperatures continue to climb , since the head of the glacier will no longer have cold enough ambient temperatures to cause snow to precipitate .

##title
Bajofondo
##doc
0 Bajofondo is a Río de la Plata - based music band consisting of eight musicians from Argentina and Uruguay , which aims to create a more contemporary version of tango and other musical styles of the Río de la Plata region .
1 It was founded in the early 2000s as a studio experiment , which culminated into the successful album Bajofondo Tango Club .
2 This led to touring and eventually to the current lineup .
3 Bajofondo calls itself a collaborative as all members have solo careers as well .
4 The group has toured around the world , particularly in Latin America , the United States , Europe and parts of Asia .
5 Their music is known to a wider audience than those who know their name as their music has been used in film and television .

##title
Christie Elliott
##doc
0 Christie Elliott ( born 26 May 1991 ) is an English footballer who plays for Partick Thistle in the Scottish Premiership .
1 Having previously played for English lower league sides Jarrow and Whitley Bay , Elliott signed a two - year deal with then Scottish First Division side Partick Thistle .
2 He was loaned in 2012 to Scottish Second Division side Albion Rovers before returning to Firhill in January 2013 .
3 Originally he was signed as a striker , but Elliott has proven a very flexible player , featuring in numerous positions for the Jags over the years .
4 He is now settled in his role in defence , playing the majority of games at right - back , providing the occasional cover at left - back or on the wing .

##title
Cassin's finch
##doc
0 Cassin 's finch ( Haemorhous cassinii ) is a bird in the finch family , Fringillidae .
1 This species and the other " American rosefinches " are placed in the genus Haemorhous .
2 Adults have a short forked brown tail and brown wings .
3 They have a longer bill than the purple finch .
4 Adult males are raspberry red on the head , breast , back and rump ; their back and undertail are streaked .
5 Adult females have light brown upperparts and light underparts with brown streaks throughout ; their facial markings are less distinct than those of the female purple finch .
6 Their breeding habitat is coniferous forest in mountains of western North America as far south as northern New Mexico and Arizona ; also Southern California near Baja California .
7 They nest in large conifers .
8 They move to lower elevations in winter .
9 Northernmost breeding birds migrate south , as do some birds throughout the range of the species ; many birds are permanent residents , however .
10 Some non - breeding birds winter as far south as central interior Mexico .
11 These birds forage in trees , sometimes in ground vegetation .
12 They mainly eat seeds , buds and berries , some insects .
13 When not nesting , they often feed in small flocks .
14 This bird was named after John Cassin , who was a curator at the Philadelphia Academy of Natural Sciences .

##title
Pskhu
##doc
0 Pskhu ( , Pskhu ; , Ps'hwy ; , Pskhu ) is a village in the Sukhumi district of Abkhazia , a disputed region on the Black Sea coast .
1 Its population was about 150 ( as of 2005 ) with ethnic Russians constituting a majority .
2 The village is situated in the eponymous valley between the Greater Caucasus and Bzyb ranges .
3 The river Bzyb and several of its tributaries flow near the village .
4 The valley was inhabited by the Abazins tribe which was one of the last peoples of the Caucasus to be conquered by Russia .
5 After their subjection in 1864 almost all of them escaped to Turkey ; many perished at the Black sea coast from hunger and malaria , during the transportation to Ottoman Empire .
6 Pskhu was the only settlement in the Transcaucasia to be occupied by Wehrmacht during the Battle of the Caucasus of World War II in the autumn of 1942 .
7 The small hydro - electric power station supplies the energy to the village .
8 Pskhu also has an airport with grass - covered surface .
9 There are no regular flights although it is still used occasionally by tourists and by the local inhabitants .
10 Several dolmens and the ruins of the mediaeval fortress remained near Pskhu .
11 The nearby Inal - kuba ( Pskhu - Nykha ) mountain ( 1290 m ) is one of the seven shrines of the Abkhaz people .

##title
Joyce Godenzi
##doc
0 Joyce Mina Godenzi (; born 1965 ) is a former actress and winner of the Miss Hong Kong pageant of 1984 .
1 Godenzi was encouraged to join the Miss Hong Kong pageant by her modeling agency , which had groomed one of its models , Maggie Cheung , to compete the year before .
2 Heavily favored , she won the title , in addition to the Miss Photogenic award .
3 After her unsurprising victory , many expected her to do well in Miss Universe 1984 in Miami ( her father is Australian and her mother is ethnically Chinese ) .
4 She was unplaced eventually , but did win third prize in the national costume competition .
5 After her reign , Godenzi started a film career and was in several action films .
6 She appeared in several films alongside kung fu film actor Sammo Hung before marrying him in 1995 .
7 She was nominated for Best Supporting Actress at the 1988 Hong Kong Film Awards for her role in Eastern Condors .
8 Godenzi has since retired from acting .

##title
Friends of Peter G.
##doc
0 " Friends of Peter G. " is the tenth episode of the ninth season of the animated comedy series Family Guy .
1 It aired on Fox in the United States on February 13 , 2011 .
2 The episode follows Peter and Brian as they are forced to join Alcoholics Anonymous , due to their excessive drinking , much to their chagrin .
3 Soon , however , Peter crashes his car while driving home drunk , and is approached by Death , who shows him what his life will be like if he continues to drink alcohol , as well if he had never drank at all .
4 The episode was written by Brian Scully and directed by John Holmquist .
5 It received mostly mixed reviews from critics for its storyline and many cultural references .
6 According to Nielsen ratings , it was viewed in 5.99 million homes in its original airing .
7 The episode featured guest performances by H. Jon Benjamin , Adam Carolla , Carrie Fisher , Phil LaMarr , Jessica Stroup and Laura Vandervoort , along with several recurring guest voice actors for the series .
8 It was first announced at the 2010 San Diego Comic - Con International .

##title
Mark Harmsworth
##doc
0 Mark Harmsworth is an American politician .
1 A Republican , he has served in the Washington House of Representatives since November 25 , 2014 , when he was sworn in early after winning election that month .
2 Harmsworth was elected to succeed Mike Hope , who resigned in summer 2014 .
3 He was local Republican leaders ' first choice for appointment to Hope 's seat in 2014 , but Governor Jay Inslee appointed Doug Roulstone instead .
4 He has been a staunch opponent of tolling in Washington State opposing the I-405 tolls and proposed US2 trestle tolls .
5 Harmsworth has proposed car tab reductions and accountability to Sound Transit by directly electing the board members .
6 Harmsworth previously served as a city councilor in Mill Creek , Washington .
7 He was first elected in 2007 and resigned effective December 31 , 2014 , after being sworn in as a state legislator .
8 Harmsworth served as Mayor Pro - Tem from January 2014 until he resigned from the Mill Creek City Council .

##title
Tomcats Screaming Outside
##doc
0 Tomcats Screaming Outside is the first ( and to date only ) solo album from British musician Roland Orzabal of the group Tears for Fears , and was released on 2 April 2001 .
1 Although Orzabal had effectively made two solo albums under the Tears for Fears moniker in the 1990s ( following the departure of bandmate Curt Smith ) , this was the first recording to be released under his own name .
2 This album was Orzabal 's last to feature contributions from Alan Griffiths , who co - wrote most of the tracks on this album as well as the previous two Tears for Fears albums .
3 The album was given a low - key release and did not chart , but earned some critical acclaim for its clever melding of pop songwriting and drum ' n bass , ambient techno and trip hop textures .
4 Dan Gennoe claimed in Amazon.com 's editorial review : " Solo album or not , Tomcats Screaming Outside is the best Tears for Fears album in a decade . "
5 In a 2000 interview Orzabal commented on his influences for the album : " I started out with an absolute concrete vision of where I wanted to go so I started with a very different rhythm approach , with drum and bass / jungle ... and I ended up with something that was n't the original plan . "
6 The US release of the album ( on Gold Circle Records ) had the unfortunate coincidence to be released on September 11 , 2001 the same day the United States experienced its worst - ever terrorist attack , and drew little notice outside TFF 's core fan base .

##title
Abbas Kiarostami
##doc
0 Abbas Kiarostami ( ; 22 June 1940 – 4 July 2016 ) was an Iranian film director , screenwriter , poet , photographer and film producer .
1 An active film - maker from 1970 , Kiarostami had been involved in over forty films , including shorts and documentaries .
2 Kiarostami attained critical acclaim for directing the Koker trilogy ( 1987 – 94 ) , Close - Up ( 1990 ) , Taste of Cherry ( 1997 ) – which was awarded the Palme d'Or at the Cannes Film Festival that year – and The Wind Will Carry Us ( 1999 ) .
3 In his later works , Certified Copy ( 2010 ) and Like Someone in Love ( 2012 ) , he filmed for the first time outside Iran : in Italy and Japan , respectively .
4 Kiarostami had worked extensively as a screenwriter , film editor , art director and producer and had designed credit titles and publicity material .
5 He was also a poet , photographer , painter , illustrator , and graphic designer .
6 He was part of a generation of filmmakers in the Iranian New Wave , a Persian cinema movement that started in the late 1960s and includes pioneering directors such as Bahram Beyzai , Nasser Taghvai , Ali Hatami , Masoud Kimiai , Dariush Mehrjui , Sohrab Shahid - Saless and Parviz Kimiavi .
7 These filmmakers share many common techniques including the use of poetic dialogue and allegorical storytelling dealing with political and philosophical issues .
8 Kiarostami had a reputation for using child protagonists , for documentary - style narrative films , for stories that take place in rural villages , and for conversations that unfold inside cars , using stationary mounted cameras .
9 He is also known for his use of Persian poetry in the dialogue , titles , and themes of his films .
10 Kiarostami 's films contain a notable degree of ambiguity , an unusual mixture of simplicity and complexity , and often a mix of fictional and documentary elements .
11 The concepts of change and continuity , in addition to the themes of life and death , play a major role in Kiarostami 's works .

##title
Washington Place (West Virginia)
##doc
0 Washington Place ( William Washington House ) is one of the first homes built by freed slaves after the Emancipation Proclamation of 1863 in Hampshire County , West Virginia , United States .
1 Washington Place was built by William and Annie Washington in north Romney between 1863 and 1874 on land given to Annie by her former owner , Susan Blue Parsons of Wappocomo plantation .
2 William Washington later acquired other properties on the hills north of Romney along West Virginia Route 28 and became the first African - American land developer in the state of West Virginia .
3 One of his subdivisions is the " Blacks Hill " neighborhood of Romney , adjacent to the Washington Place homestead .
4 Washington Place was bought and restored by Ralph W. Haines , a local attorney and historic preservationist .

##title
Guillermo Endara
##doc
0 Guillermo David Endara Galimany ( May 12 , 1936 – September 28 , 2009 ) was President of Panama from 1989 to 1994 .
1 Raised in a family allied to Panameñista Party founder Arnulfo Arias , Endara attended school in exile in the United States and Argentina following Arias 's removal from power .
2 Endara later received a law degree in Panama .
3 He subsequently served as a member of Panama 's National Assembly , and briefly as a government minister before heading into exile again following Arias ' third overthrow .
4 After Arias ' death in 1988 , Endara became a leading opponent of the Manuel Noriega military dictatorship , heading the opposition coalition in the 1989 presidential election .
5 Though his coalition was judged by international observers as having defeated pro - Noriega candidate Carlos Duque , the results were annulled by the government , and Endara and his running mates were attacked in the streets by the paramilitary Dignity Battalions .
6 The assaults received widespread coverage in international media , helping to build support within the U.S. for military action against Noriega .
7 Seven months later , the United States invaded Panama .
8 Endara was sworn in as the new president on the first night of the invasion on a U.S. military base .
9 During his presidency , Endara abolished the Panamanian military and replaced it with a national police force .
10 Endara 's term saw steady economic growth and a return of democratic institutions , but also high unemployment rates .
11 His administration was marked by internal fighting , and his popularity plummeted .
12 He was succeeded by opposition candidate Ernesto Pérez Balladares on September 1 , 1994 .
13 Endara ran for office again in 2004 and 2009 , but lost to Democratic Revolutionary Party candidate Martín Torrijos and to independent candidate Ricardo Martinelli .
14 He died of a heart attack on September 28 , 2009 , several months after his last campaign .

##title
FLAMA
##doc
0 The Frente de Libertação do Arquipélago da Madeira ( ) , or FLAMA ( which could be read as an archaic Portuguese word for " flame " , flama ) , was a right - wing terrorist paramilitary organisation from Madeira , whose main goal was to achieve Madeira 's independence from mainland Portugal .
1 FLAMA carried out more than 70 armed and bomb attacks between 1974 - 1976 , during the revolutionary period that followed the Portuguese Carnation Revolution ( April 25 , 1974 ) .
2 The Carnation Revolution effectively changed the Portuguese regime from an authoritarian dictatorship ( the Estado Novo ) to a democracy ( the Third Republic ) , but only after two years of a transitional period known as PREC ( Processo Revolucionário Em Curso , Portuguese for Ongoing Revolutionary Process ) , characterized by social turmoil and power dispute between left and right wing political forces .
3 During this period the new government withdrew from Angola and Mozambique , the last Portuguese colonies on mainland Africa .
4 Some in Madeira thought that their area should be the next to separate .
5 FLAMA 's demands were more a right - wing political reaction by some of the regional elites to the left - wing nature of the Revolution and its main actors , than a truly ethnic or nationalist separatist goal .
6 After the normalization of the Portuguese political system , early in 1976 , and the constitutional grant of autonomy to the Portuguese North Atlantic archipelagos of Madeira and Azores ( where a similar organization existed , the Frente de Libertação dos Açores ) , the organization vanished .
7 Allegedly one of FLAMA 's most important activists was the controversial Alberto João Jardim , the former President of the regional government of Madeira , co - founder of the Madeiran branch of the popular centre - right - wing Portuguese party PSD and former Vice - president of the European People 's Party .

##title
Economic history of Cambodia
##doc
0 Cambodia was a farming area in the first and second millennia BC .
1 States in the area engaged in trade in the Indian Ocean and exported rice surpluses .
2 Complex irrigation systems were built in the 9th century .
3 The French colonial period left the large feudal landholdings intact .
4 Roads and a railway were built , and rubber , rice and corn grown .
5 After independence Sihanouk pursued a policy of economic independence , securing aid and investment from a number of countries .
6 Bombing and other effects of the war during the Vietnam War damaged rice production .
7 Lon Nol had a policy of liberalising the economy .
8 This was followed by the victory of the Khmer Rouge and the emptying of the cities .
9 After the defeat of the Khmer Rouge , a Five Year Plan was adopted , aiming to improve agriculture , industry and distribution , with a slogan of " export and thrift " .
10 Today , Cambodia remains a largely agricultural economy and industrial development is slow .
##labels

Lon Nol, Vietnam War, conflict(P607), []
Vietnam War, Lon Nol, participant(P710), []
Lon Nol, Vietnam War, participant of(P1344), []

##title
National Executive Committee of the African National Congress
##doc
0 The National Executive Committee of the African National Congress is the chief executive organ of the South African political party , the African National Congress .
1 It is elected at every National Conference ; the executive committee , in turn , elects a National Working Committee for day - to - day decision - making responsibilities .
2 On 22 September 2008 , ANC chose deputy leader Kgalema Motlanthe to replace Thabo Mbeki as president until at least April 2009 , when new elections will be held .
3 ANC parliamentary caucus Spokesman KK Khumalo said : " Motlanthe will be the president , not interim , he will be the president of the republic until the election . "
4 The South African constitution provides that " parliament elects the president from among its members , dominated by the ANC since 1994 . "

##title
Burseraceae
##doc
0 The Burseraceae are a moderate - sized family of 17 - 19 genera and about 540 species of flowering plants .
1 The actual numbers differ according to the time period in which a given source is written describing this family .
2 The Burseraceae are also known as the torchwood family , the frankincense and myrrh family , or simply the incense tree family .
3 The family includes both trees and shrubs , and is native to tropical regions of Africa , Asia , and the Americas .
4 Just as the family size ( in terms of genera and species ) differs according to the time period of the study , so , too , does its placement in the higher ranks .
5 Nevertheless , the family is a genetically supported monophyletic group currently and frequently cited within the Sapindales and is recognized as a sister group to the Anacardiaceae .
6 The Burseraceae are characterized by the nonallergenic resin they produce in virtually all plant tissue and the distinctive smooth , yet flaking , aromatic bark .
7 The origins of the family can be traced to the Paleocene ( about 65 Mya ) when Beiselia mexicana first diverged in Mexico .
8 The subsequent divergences in the family lineage and migration of the species in the Eocene ( 53 Mya ) from North America have led to the current distributions of the species that are primarily associated with the tropics .
9 Though the family likely originated in North America , the greatest generic diversity presently is in the Southern Hemisphere .
10 Tabonuco ( Dacryodes excelsa ) and gumbo limbo ( Bursera simaruba ) represent the economic , ethnobotanical , and ecological significance of the Burseraceae in the Western Hemisphere , while frankincense ( Boswellia sacra ) and myrrh ( Commiphora myrrha ) represent the same in the Eastern Hemisphere .
##labels
Tabonuco, Burseraceae, parent taxon(P171), [10]
gumbo limbo, Burseraceae, parent taxon(P171), [10]
frankincense, Burseraceae, parent taxon(P171), [10, 2]
myrrh, Burseraceae, parent taxon(P171), [10, 2]
North America, Mexico, has part(P527), []
Burseraceae, Sapindales, parent taxon(P171), []

##title
Luan Bo
##doc
0 Luan Bo ( born April 16 , 1965 in Harbin , Heilongjiang ) is a Chinese pair skater who currently works as a coach .
1 With partner Yao Bin , she was the first pair skater to represent China at the World Figure Skating Championships .
2 In the closed society of mid-20th century China , Luan and Yao had only photographs from which to learn their moves .
3 At the 1980 World Figure Skating Championships in Dortmund , West Germany , they finished 15th , in last place .
4 They competed at the World Championships twice more in 1981 and 1982 , finishing last both times .
5 They represented China at the 1984 Winter Olympics and placed 15th .
6 She works as a coach .
7 Her current and former students include Ding Yang & Ren Zhongfei , Sui Wenjing & Han Cong , and Zhu Qiuying .

##title
Ici Paris
##doc
0 Ici Paris is a French magazine , founded in 1941 .
1 The magazine is owned by Lagardère .
2 The publisher of the magazine , based in Paris , is Hachette Filipacchi Associes , SNC .
3 It is published on a weekly basis and covers articles on celebrity and entertainment news .
4 During World War II it was a journal of the resistance with editors such as Raymond Burgard , Émile Coornaert , Suzanne Feingold , Marietta Martin , Henri de Montfort and Paul Petit .
5 In 1986 it had a circulation of 700,000 copies and in 2006 , a more modest circulation of 405,000 copies .
6 The magazine is also sold in Algeria and at the beginning of the 1970s it was one of the best - selling weeklies in the country .

##title
Cy Becker, Edmonton
##doc
0 Cy Becker is a neighbourhood in northeast Edmonton , Alberta , Canada and named after one of Alberta 's first bush pilots and finest wartime flying aces , Cy Becker staked his claim in history by making the first air mail delivery to remote northern communities .
1 Since then , in recognition of his contributions and those of many others , the City of Edmonton has identified an area in Edmonton 's northeast side as Pilot Sound .
2 Subdivision and development of the neighbourhood will be guided by the Cy Becker Neighbourhood Structure Plan ( NSP ) once adopted by Edmonton City Council .
3 It is located within Pilot Sound and was originally considered Neighbourhood 5 within the Pilot Sound Area Structure Plan ( ASP ) .
4 Cy Becker is bounded on the west by the McConachie neighbourhood , north by Anthony Henday Drive , east by the future Gorman neighbourhood , and south by the Brintnell and Hollick - Kenyon neighbourhoods .
5 The community is represented by the Horse Hill Community League , established in 1972 .

##title
Cranford Agreement
##doc
0 The Cranford Protocol or Cranford Agreement was an oral undertaking given in 1952 by the British Government to the residents of Cranford in London regarding the usage of the runways at London Heathrow Airport to reduce the impact of aircraft noise on local residents .
1 Under normal operations the agreement prohibited take - off on the northern runway towards the east ( over London ) because of the proximity of Cranford to the east end of this runway ; however this runway could be used in exceptional cases , for example when the southern runway was not available for departures or when departure delays are excessive .
2 Although no formal written agreement exists , the Government acknowledges that an oral undertaking was given by a senior government official at a meeting of the Cranford Residents ' and District Amenities Association on 31 July 1952 .
3 The protocol is included in the Heathrow Manual of Air Traffic Services and the airport 's noise abatement notification , and thus is a part of the airport 's operating rules .
4 On 15 January 2009 , the Labour Government announced that it was ending the Cranford Agreement as part of the controversial expansion of London Heathrow Airport .
5 Although in May 2010 the Coalition Government cancelled the Heathrow expansion plans , in September 2010 it reaffirmed the decision to end the Cranford Agreement .
6 This decision was welcomed by the Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead , to the west .
7 To the east , the London Borough of Hounslow called for mitigation or compensation to be offered by BAA to those affected by ending the Cranford Agreement .
8 In May 2013 Heathrow Airport Holdings ( who own and operate the airport ) submitted planning permission to the London Borough of Hillingdon to build new access taxiways , which would allow the implementation of full runway alternation on easterly operations .
9 This permission was rejected in March 2014 ; Heathrow Airport appealed with a planning enquiry in June 2015 .
10 On 2 February 2017 the Planning Inspectorate recommended that the appeal be allowed and planning permission granted .
11 The decision has not yet been implemented as the airport is considering the Governments airspace management proposals for London and their own plans for expansion .

##title
Truth in Music Advertising
##doc
0 The Truth in Music Advertising act or bill , also known as Truth in Music Performance Advertising or simply Truth in Music , is legislation , adopted into state law by most U.S. states , that aims to protect the trademark of musical recording artists .
1 The legislation provides that the name of a famous musical group can not be used by a group of performers unless they include at least one member of the original group .
2 The intent of the legislation is to prevent unfair or deceptive trade practices , and to protect the livelihood of musicians who were in famous musical groups .
3 The legislation , co - authored by former Sha Na Na member Jon " Bowzer " Bauman and promoted by him and Mary Wilson of the Supremes , was not passed by the U.S. Congress , but has been enacted in 34 of the 50 states .
4 The legislation has been tested in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit .

##title
Toyota Avalon
##doc
0 The Toyota Avalon is a full - size car produced by Toyota in the United States , and is Toyota 's largest front - wheel - drive sedan in the United States , Canada , Puerto Rico , and the Middle East .
1 It was also produced in Australia from April 2000 until June 2005 , when it was replaced in November 2006 by the Toyota Aurion .
2 The first production Avalon rolled off the TMMK assembly line in Georgetown , Kentucky , in September 1994 .
3 A second - generation model was released in the United States and Japan in 1999 .
4 Toyota marketed the Avalon as a replacement for the Toyota Cressida , a model discontinued for the American market in 1992 .
5 While the Cressida was an upper - level midsize rear - wheel - drive car with a straight - six engine , the Avalon is front - wheel - drive , powered by a V6 engine .
6 In recent years , there has been considerable overlapping with its platform mates , the Toyota Camry V6 and the Lexus ES , although the third - generation Avalon was distinguished by offering extra legroom .
7 For its fourth generation , the Avalon was introduced on a platform that is shared with the Lexus ES .
8 As of 2013 , the Toyota Avalon is available in the United States , Canada , Puerto Rico , South Korea , and the Middle East .
9 Avalon is a legendary island featured in the Arthurian legend , fitting it in with Toyota 's tradition of naming their sedans the word for " crown " in various languages ( Crown , Corona , Camry , Corolla ) , types of crowns ( Tiara ) , or other things associated with royalty ( Scepter ) .

##title
Achilles Last Stand
##doc
0 " Achilles Last Stand " is a song by English rock group Led Zeppelin .
1 Guitarist Jimmy Page and singer Robert Plant began writing it in the summer of 1975 and were influenced by Eastern music , mythology , and travels .
2 At ten and a half minutes , it is one of the group 's longest studio recordings and one of their most complex , with different interwoven sections and multiple overdubbed guitar parts .
3 It was released in March 1976 as the opening track for their seventh studio album , Presence .
4 The song received positive reviews , with comparisons to other epic - style Led Zeppelin songs , such as " Kashmir " .
5 Between 1977 and 1980 , it was a feature of the group 's concerts and a live performance from 1979 is included on the Led Zeppelin DVD ( 2003 ) .
6 In several interviews , Page named it as his favourite Led Zeppelin piece and places his guitar solo on a par with " Stairway to Heaven " .

##title
Robert K. Huntington
##doc
0 Robert Kingsbury Huntington ( 13 March 1921 – 5 June 1942 ) , was a naval aircrewman and member of Torpedo Squadron 8 ( or VT-8 ) .
1 He was radioman / gunner to Ensign George Gay 's TBD Devastator aircraft .
2 Along with his entire squadron , Huntington was shot down during the Battle of Midway , on 4–5 June 1942 .
3 Born in Los Angeles , California , enlisted in the United States Navy 21 April 1941 .
4 He served on board Lexington ( CV-2 ) and was rated aviation radioman third class before being transferred to Torpedo Squadron 8 on board Hornet ( CV-8 ) .
5 He received the Distinguished Flying Cross for heroism and extraordinary achievement as rear gunner in a torpedo plane during an attack against enemy Japanese forces in the Battle of Midway 4 June 1942 .
6 Flying without fighter support and with insufficient fuel to return to their carrier , Huntington and his fellow crewmember pressed home their attack with utter disregard for their own personal safety , in the face of a tremendous antiaircraft barrage and overwhelming fighter opposition .
7 Huntington was one of 29 from Torpedo Squadron 8 who gave their lives in this attack .

##title
White Sea
##doc
0 The White Sea ( , Béloye móre ; Karelian and , lit .
1 Dvina Sea ; , Serako yam ) is a southern inlet of the Barents Sea located on the northwest coast of Russia .
2 It is surrounded by Karelia to the west , the Kola Peninsula to the north , and the Kanin Peninsula to the northeast .
3 The whole of the White Sea is under Russian sovereignty and considered to be part of the internal waters of Russia .
4 Administratively , it is divided between Arkhangelsk and Murmansk Oblasts and the Republic of Karelia .
5 The major port of Arkhangelsk is located on the White Sea .
6 For much of Russia 's history this was Russia 's main centre of international maritime trade , conducted by the Pomors ( " seaside settlers " ) from Kholmogory .
7 In the modern era it became an important Soviet naval and submarine base .
8 The White Sea – Baltic Canal connects the White Sea with the Baltic Sea .
9 The White Sea is one of the four seas named in English ( and in other languages such as French ) after common colour terms   — the others being the Black Sea , the Red Sea , and the Yellow Sea .

##title
Google Springboard
##doc
0 Google Springboard is an AI - powered assistant which aid users to quickly find relevant information , as and when they need it across all associated Google apps , including ( but not restricted to ) Gmail , Google Docs , Google Drive , Google Calendar , Google Contacts and others alike .
1 It also provides “ actionable information & recommendations ” to users based on statistical probability gathered using Machine Learning .
2 Springboard also integrates with Google Sites – a tool for creating web pages .
3 The updated app now supports collaboration between users and lets them add content from services like Google Docs , Calendar and Google Maps .
4 Some of its applications could be to quickly build things like guides and how - to(s ) .

##title
Quokka
##doc
0 The quokka ( , Setonix brachyurus ) , the only member of the genus Setonix , is a small macropod about the size of a domestic cat .
1 Like other marsupials in the macropod family ( such as kangaroos and wallabies ) , the quokka is herbivorous and mainly nocturnal .
2 Quokkas are found on some smaller islands off the coast of Western Australia , particularly Rottnest Island , just off Perth , and also Bald Island near Albany , and in isolated scattered populations in forest and coastal heath between Perth and Albany .
3 A small colony exists at the eastern limit of their range in a protected area of Two Peoples Bay Nature Reserve , where they co - exist with the critically endangered Gilbert 's potoroo .

##title
El Tren de los Momentos
##doc
0 El Tren de los Momentos is the eighth studio album recorded by Spanish singer - songwriter Alejandro Sanz , It was released by WEA Latina on November 7 , 2006 ( see 2006 in music ) .
1 which counts with the collaborations of Juanes , Antonio Carmona ( ex - Ketama ) , Shakira and Calle 13 .
2 It contains ten songs produced by him and Lulo Pérez and this diversity of voices allows approaching social , political and faith topics from differing points of view .
3 It was recorded in Havana , Miami , Bahamas and Madrid , with most recording taking place in a studio that Sanz has at his house in Miami .
4 The album won the Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album at the 50th Annual Grammy Awards .
5 Also was nominated for a Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year , in the 8th Annual Latin Grammy Awards which was awarded to La Llave de Mi Corazón by Juan Luis Guerra .

##title
Panlongcheng
##doc
0 Panlongcheng ( ) or Panlong City is an archaeological site associated with the Erligang culture .
1 The site is located just north of the Yangtze river in Huangpi , Wuhan , Hubei , China .
2 Panlongcheng is the largest excavated Erligang site ( 1   km² at its peak ) , showing the southernmost reach of the Erligang culture at its peak .
3 It was discovered in 1954 , and excavated in 1974 and 1976 .
4 The site at Panlongcheng was sparsely inhabited during the Erlitou period , consisting mainly of several small settlements and occupying an area of around 200,000 m² .
5 During the early Erligang period , the site suddenly grew rapidly , reaching an area of around with a walled center of 75,000 m² .
6 Panlongcheng may have been an Erligang outpost used to control regional resources , such as copper mines .
7 The construction and bronze casting techniques at Panlongcheng are identical with the techniques employed at Erligang and Zhengzhou ; however , the pottery style is different .
8 The style of Erligang elite burials is almost an exact replica of the burials at Zhengzhou ; however , later layers show that the Erligang style disappeared during the later stages of the Erligang culture .
9 The site declined until it was abandoned altogether at the end of the Erligang culture .
10 Panlongcheng 's decline may have been affected in part by the growth of the site at Wucheng .
11 In Hubei Province , other sites such as Jingnansi and Baimiaozhu also feature Erlitou or Late Erlitou – Early Erligang type of ceramics .

##title
Bessang Pass Natural Monument
##doc
0 The Bessang Pass Natural Monument is a protected area and memorial that commemorates the victory on 14 June 1945 by Filipino soldiers serving the U.S. Army Forces in the Philippines Northern Luzon ( USAFIP - NL ) over the Imperial Japanese Army in the Battle of Bessang Pass which led to Japan 's eventual surrender and end to World War II in the Philippines .
1 It covers an area of and a buffer zone of in the municipality of Cervantes in Ilocos Sur .
2 The mountain pass was initially a component of the Tirad Pass National Park , declared in 1938 through Proclamation No .
3 294 by then President Manuel Luis Quezon .
4 On 10 August 1954 , it was established as the Bessang Pass National Shrine with an area of by virtue of Proclamation No .
5 55 signed by President Ramon Magsaysay .
6 The national shrine was finally declared and reclassified as a natural monument under the National Integrated Protected Areas System in April 2000 through Proclamation No .
7 284 by President Joseph Estrada .

##title
Committee against the Finnish White Terror
##doc
0 The Committee against the Finnish White Terror ( ) was an organization in Sweden , formed at the end of the Finnish Civil War .
1 The formation of the Committee was preceded by a call from the Social Democratic Left Party published in Politiken in February 1918 to mobilize protests around the country to counter the official Swedish government position on the Finnish question .
2 The Committee sought to unite the Swedish labour movement for a common position against what they termed the ” White Terror ” in Finland .
3 The Committee raised funds for humanitarian aid to the victims of the repression .
4 The Committee also opposed denials of political asylum for Finnish refugees .
5 Sven Linderot was one of the three members of the Committee .
6 The Committee managed to gather 21,851.53 kronor , 14,518.73 for Finnish refugees in Sweden and 6,920 kronor for affected in Finland .
7 The Committee published 100,000 leaflets titled ' Truth about Finland ' , and more than 100 public meetings were organized .

##title
Foots Creek, Oregon
##doc
0 Foots Creek is an unincorporated community and census - designated place ( CDP ) in Jackson County , in the U.S. state of Oregon .
1 It lies along Oregon Route 99 near the mouth of Foots Creek , where it empties into the Rogue River .
2 Interstate 5 and Valley of the Rogue State Park are on the side of the river opposite Foots Creek .
3 For statistical purposes , the United States Census Bureau has defined Foots Creek as a census - designated place ( CDP ) .
4 The census definition of the area may not precisely correspond to local understanding of the area with the same name .
5 As of the 2010 Census , the population was 799 .
6 The community " has been known as ' Bolt ' since pioneer days . "
7 The stream takes its name from O. G. Foot , a miner who prospected along the stream in the 19th century .
8 A post office named Foots Creek had a brief existence in this vicinity in 1878 – 79 .
9 Silas Draper was the postmaster .

##title
Guarenas Cathedral
##doc
0 The Our Lady of Copacabana Cathedral ( ) or simply Cathedral of Guarenas , is the name given to a religious building belonging to the Catholic Church and is located at Ambrosio Plaza Street on one side of the Bolívar Square , in the city of Guarenas , a city in the municipality Ambrosio Plaza , Miranda state , which serves as a " satellite city " of Caracas , in the South American country of Venezuela .
1 It has objects and relics of great historical and religious value .
2 The first church on the site was built in rudimentary form in 1621 .
3 It was hit by an earthquake in 1766 .
4 In the early nineteenth century was rebuilt to make it much larger .
5 in 1950 he became a major refurbishment with plans of Oreste Giovanni Della Piana .
6 In January 1997 it is recognized as the Cathedral of the Diocese of Guarenas ( Dioecesis Guarenensis ) by decision of Pope John Paul II by the bull Maiori christifidelium .
7 As its name indicates is dedicated to the Virgin Mary in her title of Our Lady of Copacabana , whose veneration has its origins in the territory that today is Bolivia and spread throughout Spanish America from 1583 .

##title
Argentine heavy metal
##doc
0 The Argentine heavy metal is a heavy metal music movement that originated in Argentina in the 1980s .
1 The first popular artist was Pappo , who created the band Riff influenced by the contemporary new wave of British heavy metal .
2 V8 was formed at that time as well , and most of its members created notable bands after their respective departures from the band : Ricardo Iorio and Walter Giardino , currently in Almafuerte and Rata Blanca , are still popular .
3 The second half of the 1980s saw the success of hard rock bands such as Kamikaze , Alakran and Rata Blanca , with an aesthetic similar to the contemporary glam metal .
4 Thrash metal bands , such as Hermética , Horcas and Lethal , appeared in the early 1990s .
5 Rata Blanca declined its popularity in the 1990s and eventually broke up .
6 Hermética became more popular than V8 during its short existence , and broke up in a controversy between the leader Ricardo Iorio and the other members .
7 Iorio created a new band , Almafuerte , and the former members of Hermética stayed together for some time as Malón .
8 Rata Blanca had a revival later , and the band was rejoined .

##title
Durán, Ecuador
##doc
0 Durán , is a canton located in the province of Guayas , Ecuador , near the confluence of the Daule & Babahoyo rivers , where the Guayas River enters the ocean .
1 Its township or capital is Eloy Alfaro .
2 The canton was created in 1986 during the presidential period of Leon Febres Cordero through a presidential decree .
3 The name " Eloy Alfaro " was chosen because of the Ecuadorian ex - president Eloy Alfaro Delgado .
4 According to the National census in 2010 , there are 235,769 people residing within the canton limits .
5 Many of its inhabitants commute to other places for work and it can be considered a " dormitory town " .
6 However , many people who live in Durán find work within the canton by opening " comedores " or small restaurants , selling produce at the market , or even opening little stores with basic produce and house necessities .
7 The towns Durán , Samborondón , and Guayaquil are connected by the bridge Rafael Mendoza Avilés .
8 Durán is also well known for being the first railroad hub in Ecuador .
9 Since July 2007 , a government program for the railroad reactivation began as well as the railroad connecting Duran with other cities located in the highlands of Ecuador .

##title
Bookbinder soup
##doc
0 Bookbinder 's soup is a type of soup pioneered in the United States of America in 1893 when Samuel Bookbinder created Old Original Bookbinder 's restaurant in Philadelphia .
1 The soup is served at some other restaurants including the Drake Hotel in Chicago .
2 The soup is tomato - based with typical stew vegetables such as carrots , celery , bell peppers , onions , leeks , mushrooms , and garlic .
3 It is commonly made with snapping turtle .
4 The soup made by the Drake Hotel in Chicago has been written about by several different sites and is said to take less than an hour and a half to make .
5 The Chicago Tribune released a list of ingredients and directions on how to prepare the Drake ’s version of the soup .
6 The authors say that this was given to them by the executive chef at the Drake .

##title
Irish experiment
##doc
0 The Irish Experiment is the popular name for the interest , primarily from VFL / AFL clubs , in bringing Irish Gaelic footballers over to Australia to play Australian rules football professionally .
1 The AFL 's focus on Gaelic footballers is due to the similarities between the sports .
2 The Irish Experiment began in the mid-1980s as an informal project of the Melbourne Football Club .
3 Despite its initial success , enthusiasm for the project lapsed until the 2000s , when it again became ongoing and currently increasing due to globalisation and professionalism in sport .
4 The highest profile product of the experiment to date has been Medal of the Order of Australia and Brownlow Medal recipient Jim Stynes , who was an early recruit .
5 Irishman Tadhg Kennelly was a key player in the Sydney Swans 2005 AFL Grand Final victory .
6 The highest profile Gaelic footballer to sign an AFL contract is Tommy Walsh .
7 Over the years the Irish experiment has attracted media and public interest in both Ireland and Australia .

##title
Piton des Neiges
##doc
0 The Piton des Neiges ( Snow Peak ) is a massive 3,069   m ( 10,069   ft ) shield volcano on Réunion , one of the French volcanic islands in the Mascarene Archipelago in the southwestern Indian Ocean .
1 It is located about east of Madagascar .
2 Piton des Neiges is the highest point on Réunion and is considered to be the highest point in the Indian Ocean .
3 The volcano was formed by the Réunion hotspot and emerged from the sea about two million years ago .
4 Now deeply eroded , the volcano has been inactive for 20,000   years and is surrounded by three massive crater valleys , the Cirques .
5 Piton des Neiges forms the northwestern two thirds of Réunion , with the very active Piton de la Fournaise comprising the rest .
6 As it name suggests , snow is occasionally seen on its summit in winter .
7 The volcanic island is considered to be about three million years old ( Pliocene ) ; the other two islands in the archipelago , Mauritius and Rodrigues , are 7.8   million ( Miocene ) and 1 million ( Pleistocene ) years old , respectively .
8 The island possesses a high endemism of flowering plants ( about 225 ) ; this has justified the creation of a biological reserve on the lower slopes of the Piton des Neiges .

##title
Holden New Zealand
##doc
0 Holden New Zealand Limited , named until 1994 as General Motors New Zealand Limited , is a subsidiary of General Motors of Detroit and distributes General Motors ' motor vehicles , engines , components and parts in New Zealand .
1 Its Buick , Chevrolet , Oakland , Oldsmobile and Cadillac brands were all well - established before the first World War .
2 This company was incorporated on 4 January 1926 to build and operate a local assembly plant , General Motors ' first owned not leased overseas plant .
3 Its popular cars , including British Vauxhalls , remained common household brands until well after the second World War .
4 Postwar British sourced Vauxhalls continued to keep the plant running together with limited numbers ( restricted by currency shortages ) of Chevrolets .
5 In the late 1950s the Vauxhall and the now expansive Chevrolet and Pontiac cars began to be replaced with Australian sourced Holden vehicles supplemented by the smallest Vauxhalls and Holdens and the move to the Holden brand was completed in the 1970s .
6 The assembly of vehicles ended in 1990 and since then the business has been distribution of complete imported vehicles and spare parts .

##title
Arthur Percival
##doc
0 Lieutenant - General Arthur Ernest Percival , ( 26 December 1887 – 31 January 1966 ) was a senior British Army officer .
1 He saw service in the First World War and built a successful military career during the interwar period but is most noted for his defeat in the Second World War , when he commanded British Commonwealth forces during the Japanese Malayan Campaign and the subsequent Battle of Singapore .
2 Percival 's surrender to the invading Imperial Japanese Army force , the largest surrender in British military history , undermined Britain 's prestige as an imperial power in East Asia .
3 His defenders , such as Sir John Smyth , have argued that under - funding of Malaya 's defences and the inexperienced , under - equipped nature of the Commonwealth army , not Percival 's leadership , were ultimately to blame .

##title
Panama during World War II
##doc
0 The history of Panama during World War II begins in 1939 .
1 Due to the American - controlled Panama Canal cutting across the center of the country , Panama was of major strategic importance to the Allied war effort , as well as the most important strategic location in Latin America during World War II .
2 It provided an invaluable link between the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans that was vital to both commerce and the defense of the Western Hemisphere .
3 Therefore , the defense of the Canal Zone was the United States ' chief concern in the American Theater .
4 Panama never received Lend - Lease assistance , but in return for the rights to build military infrastructure within Panamanian territory , the United States undertook large - scale public works projects , which did much to modernize the country and boost the economy .

##title
Statue of Jan Smuts, Parliament Square
##doc
0 A life - size bronze statue of Jan Smuts by the British artist Jacob Epstein stands on the north side of Parliament Square in London , United Kingdom , between a statue of Lord Palmerston and a statue of David Lloyd George .
1 Smuts served as an army general and as a member of the Imperial War Cabinet in the First World War , and then served as Prime Minister of South Africa twice , from 1919 to 1924 and from then 1939 to 1948 .
2 The statue depicts him in his military uniform as a field marshal , leaning forward with his left leg advanced , as if walking forward .
3 The statue stands on a pedestal of granite from South Africa , which bears the inscription .
4 After Winston Churchill won the 1951 UK general election in October 1951 , he proposed erecting a statue in Parliament Square as a memorial to Smuts , who had died in September 1950 .
5 Churchill retired as prime minister in 1955 , and was too ill to perform the unveiling in November 1956 ; it was unveiled instead by the Speaker of the House of Commons , William Morrison .
6 The statue became a Grade II listed building in 1970 .

##title
James P. Maher
##doc
0 James Paul Maher ( November 3 , 1865 – July 31 , 1946 ) was a U.S. Representative from New York .
1 Born in Brooklyn , New York , Maher graduated from St. Patrick 's Academy in Brooklyn .
2 Apprenticed to the hatter 's trade , he moved to Danbury , Connecticut in 1887 and was employed as a journeyman hatter .
3 He became treasurer of the United Hatters of North America in 1897 .
4 Maher returned to Brooklyn in 1902 .
5 He was an unsuccessful candidate for election to the Sixty - first Congress in 1908 .
6 Maher was elected as a Democrat to the Sixty - second and to the four succeeding Congresses ( March 4 , 1911 – March 4 , 1921 ) .
7 He served as chairman of the Committee on Expenditures in the Department of Labor ( Sixty - third through Sixty - fifth Congresses ) .
8 He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1920 to the Sixty - seventh Congress .
9 Maher entered the real estate business in Brooklyn , moved to Keansburg , New Jersey , and continued in real estate .
10 He was elected mayor of Keansburg in 1926 .
11 Maher died in Keansburg on July 31 , 1946 .
12 He is buried in St. Joseph 's Cemetery , Keyport , New Jersey .

##title
Lappeenranta
##doc
0 Lappeenranta ( ) is a city and municipality situated on the shore of the lake Saimaa in southeastern Finland , about from the Russian border .
1 It belongs to the region of South Karelia .
2 With approximately inhabitants ( ) Lappeenranta is the largest city in Finland .
3 The neighboring municipality of Joutseno was consolidated with Lappeenranta on January 1 , 2009 , and the neighboring municipality of Ylämaa on January 1 , 2010 .
4 Lappeenranta is known as an international university city in Finland with Lappeenranta University of Technology and Saimaa University of Applied Sciences which together have approximately 13,000 students from 68 countries .
5 Lappeenranta is also a commercial centre of South - East Finland and the meeting point of the EU and Russia , 215   km from both Helsinki and St. Petersburg .
6 Location on the southern shore of Lake Saimaa makes the city the region ’s centre for tourism .
7 Lappeenranta is the second most visited city by Russian tourists in Finland after Helsinki and it competes with Helsinki for the largest share of tax - free sales in Finland .
8 Lappeenranta is a model for renewable energies and a clean living environment .
9 Lappeenranta was the only Finnish city among the 14 finalists in the international Earth Hour City Challenge 2014 , organized by WWF .

##title
How to Save a Life (Grey's Anatomy)
##doc
0 " How to Save a Life " is the twenty - first episode of the eleventh season of the American television medical drama Grey 's Anatomy , and is the 241st episode overall .
1 It aired on April 23 , 2015 on ABC in the United States .
2 The episode was written by showrunner Shonda Rhimes and directed by Rob Hardy , making it the first episode Rhimes has written since the season eight finale " Flight " .
3 The installment marked the death and final appearance of the series’ male lead character , Derek Shepherd ( Patrick Dempsey ) , who had starred on the series since its inception .
4 In this episode , Shepherd is involved in an accident while attempting to help the victims of a car accident .
5 He is later pronounced brain dead , in part due to the surgeons not providing him with a timely CT scan .
6 Only six regular cast membersEllen Pompeo , Patrick Dempsey , Chandra Wilson , Kevin McKidd , Sarah Drew and Caterina Scorsone appear in the episode .
7 " How to Save a Life " also marks the first appearance of Dr. Penelope Blake ( Samantha Sloyan ) .
8 The episode 's original broadcast was watched by 9.55 million viewers and registered the show as the week 's highest - rated drama and third - highest rated scripted series in the 18–49 demographic .
9 It received mixed reviews from the critics who were divided on the show 's handling of Shepherd 's death .
10 However , they were largely laudatory of Pompeo , with critic Rick Porter deeming it the best performance of her career .

##title
Joan Burton
##doc
0 Joan Burton ( born 1 February 1949 ) is an Irish Labour Party politician who served as Tánaiste and Leader of the Labour Party from 2014 to 2016 , Minister for Social Protection from 2011 to 2016 , Deputy Leader of the Labour Party from 2007 to 2014 , Minister of State at the Department of Foreign Affairs from 1994 to 1997 and Minister of State at the Department of Social Welfare 1993 to 1994 .
1 She has been a Teachta Dála ( TD ) for the Dublin West constituency since 2002 , and previously from 1992 to 1997 .
2 Burton was first elected to Dáil Éireann at the 1992 general election .
3 From 1995 to 1997 , she was Minister of State at the Department of Foreign Affairs .
4 She lost her seat at the 1997 general election , but was re - elected to the Dáil at the 2002 general election .
5 She was deputy leader of the Labour Party under Eamon Gilmore , between 2007 and 2014 .
6 She was Tánaiste ( Deputy Prime Minister ) from 2014 to 2016 and Minister for Social Protection from 2011 to 2016 .
7 She resigned as Labour Party leader in May 2016 , following heavy losses by the party in the 2016 general election .

##title
Jerry Steiner
##doc
0 Jerry Steiner ( January 7 , 1918 – February 1 , 2012 ) was an American professional basketball player .
1 He played two seasons in the National Basketball League ( NBL ) , one of the two leagues that merged to form the National Basketball Association .
2 Steiner , a 5'7 " point guard was a basketball player for Butler University from 1937 to 1940 .
3 He made the 1940 All - American team as a senior for the Bulldogs .
4 After graduating from Butler , Steiner played for one season for the Indianapolis Kautskys of the NBL for the 1945–46 season .
5 After serving in World War II until 1946 , Steiner took a job teaching and coaching at Shortridge High School in Indianapolis while playing for the Fort Wayne Zollner Pistons .
6 He left the game after the 1946–47 season .
7 Steiner died on February 1 , 2012 , in Bonita Springs , Florida .

##title
US Airways Group
##doc
0 US Airways Group Inc. was an airline holding company based in Tempe , Arizona .
1 US Airways Group operated US Airways , along with its subsidiaries PSA Airlines , Inc. and Piedmont Airlines , Inc. , which are wholly owned but marketed under the branding of US Airways Express .
2 It merged with America West Holdings Corporation , parent of America West Airlines , in 2005 , and the combined company adopted the better - known US Airways name ; the two airlines ' operating certificates merged in 2007 .
3 It also operates additional companies that provide associated services .
4 ACE Aviation Holdings , the Canadian parent of Air Canada retained a roughly 6.1 % investment stake in US Airways Group .
5 The route network covered destinations in 47 states , as well as international destinations .
6 The company merged with AMR Corporation ; the combined business began trading under the new name of American Airlines Group on December 9 , 2013 .
7 The combined airlines formed the largest airline in the world .
8 US Airways ' CEO , Doug Parker , became CEO of the new company .

##title
Carl Dix
##doc
0 Carl Dix is a founding member , and a representative , of the Revolutionary Communist Party , USA ( RCP ) .
1 He is a regular contributor to Revolution newspaper .
2 Dix has long been associated with Bob Avakian .
3 In 1996 , Dix co - founded the October 22nd Coalition to Stop Police Brutality , Repression and the Criminalization of Generation .
4 Most recently , Dix has been a central figure in the campaign to Stop " Stop and Frisk " aimed at opposing the New York City stop - and - frisk program to stop hundreds of thousands of people in New York City and frisk them for weapons , drugs or other items .
5 As of August 2017 , Dix is a member of Refuse Fascism , an organization founded in 2016 to oppose the presidency of Donald Trump .

##title
Brigden, Ontario
##doc
0 Brigden is a community in the township of St. Clair , Lambton County , Ontario , Canada .
1 The community is located at the crossroads of Courtright Line and Brigden Road , between Kimball to the west and Oil City to the east , and about southeast of the city of Sarnia .
2 Brigden has a population of about 500 and is the centre of a thriving agricultural district .
3 The community is situated on the former Michigan Central Railroad line and thus is named after William Wharton Brigden , one of the engineers who surveyed the railway in 1936 .
4 Brigden died of a heart attack on May 26 , 1939 in Battle Creek , Michigan , where he was the superintendent of the city waterworks .
5 Brigden was a Police village governed by a Village Chairman and a Board of Trustees .
6 The annual Brigden Fair is the last fair of the season in Lambton County occurring on Canadian Thanksgiving long weekend .
7 Other annual events include the Brigden Community Fest .
8 It is also the birthplace of businessman JR Shaw , founder and executive chairman of Shaw Communications .

##title
Babyfingers
##doc
0 Babyfingers was a release by the avant garde / experimental rock band The Residents , containing music written for their 1977 album , Fingerprince .
1 As Fingerprince was originally meant to be a three - sided album ( a concept abandoned due to expense and Monty Python 's Matching Tie and Handkerchief beating them to the punch ) , much of the material was abandoned and the third side remained unfinished until November 1977 although most tracks from the EP was shown at the Residents Radio Special in September 1977 .
2 Thus , the group reduced the third side to an extended play record entitled ' " Babyfingers ' " , and released it in 1979 to people who had been waiting for their copy of The Third Reich and Roll box sets .
3 A second printing was made for members of the W.E.I.R.D.
4 fan club in 1981 , and a last pressing , on pink vinyl , in 1985 .
5 It has been incorporated into most CD versions of Fingerprince , beginning in 1988 .

##title
Thirteens (album)
##doc
0 Thirteens is an album by Leona Naess , released in the U.S. on 16 September 2008 by Verve Forecast Records , and released in the UK on 11 May 2009 by Polydor Records .
1 The album was influenced by the death of Naess ’s father , Arne Næss , Jr. , in a mountaineering accident in January 2004 .
2 Naess returned to London from New York City and eventually began writing and recording songs with music producer Samuel Dixon .
3 Naess recorded with almost no budget , asking friends to contribute , and completed thirteen albums’ worth of material .
4 Eleven songs were selected for the release , titled Thirteens .
5 Described as " a sweet and poignant collection " by New York magazine , much of the album deals with the onset of maturity .
6 The album consists of first takes , which were then overdubbed .
7 A digital download of the album available on the iTunes Store includes a bonus track featuring singer - songwriter Ryan Adams ; an exclusive edition available through retailer Barnes & Noble includes two bonus tracks .
8 The UK release includes two bonus tracks unavailable on previous releases of the album .

##title
Hooshang Seyhoun
##doc
0 Houshang Seyhoun , ( ) ( August 22 , 1920 – May 26 , 2014 ) was an Iranian architect , sculptor , painter , scholar and professor .
1 He studied fine arts at the École nationale supérieure des Beaux - Arts in Paris , and earned a degree in architecture from University of Tehran .
2 Seyhun is noted specially for his innovative and creative architectural design .
3 His architectural legacy includes countless monuments and over one thousand private villas .
4 After the Iranian Revolution he moved to Vancouver and lived in exile until his death .
5 Seyhoon became famous for his design work in the 1950s in Iran , including : Tehran 's Central Railway Station and tombs of scientific / literary figures ( such as the Avicenna Mausoleum in Hamadan ) .
6 He has been a faculty member of Tehran University 's College of Architecture , where he also served as Dean of the College of Fine Arts ( Beaux arts ) of Tehran University for six years .

##title
Trane's Blues
##doc
0 Trane 's Blues is a compact disc credited to the jazz musician John Coltrane , released in 1999 on Blue Note Records , catalogue 98240 .
1 It comprises recordings from sessions for Blue Note and United Artists Records as a sideman for Paul Chambers , Sonny Clark , Johnny Griffin , and Cecil Taylor that were issued respectively on their Whims of Chambers , Sonny 's Crib , A Blowin ' Session , and Hard Driving Jazz albums .
2 Two selections are from Coltrane 's own 1957 Blue Train , and " One for Four " had been previously unissued .
3 " Trane 's Blues " had been issued on the compilation High Step in 1975 , previously known as " John Paul Jones " and named after himself , the bass player Chambers , and the drummer Philly Joe Jones .
4 Like Prestige Records before them , as Coltrane 's fame grew long after he had stopped recording for the label , Blue Note used varied recordings , often those where Coltrane had been merely a sideman , and reissued them as a new album with Coltrane 's name prominently displayed .
5 In this case , the Big Four conglomerate EMI continued that earlier practice .

##title
Ages of consent in Oceania
##doc
0 The ages of consent for sexual activity vary by jurisdiction across Australia , New Zealand and Oceania , ranging from age 15 to age 18 .
1 The specific activity engaged in or the gender of its participants can also be affected by the law .
2 Below is a discussion of the various laws dealing with this subject .
3 The highlighted age refers to an age at or above which an individual can engage in unfettered sexual relations with another who is also at or above that age .
4 Close in age exceptions may exist and are noted when relevant .
5 In Vanuatu the homosexual age of consent is set higher at 18 , while the heterosexual age of consent is 15 .
6 Same sex sexual activity is illegal at any age for males in Papua New Guinea , Kiribati , the Cook Islands , Samoa , Tonga and Tuvalu ; it is outlawed for both men and women in the Solomon Islands .
7 In all other places the age of consent is equal , regardless of sexual orientation or gender .
8 The below is a list of all jurisdictions in Oceania as listed in List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Oceania .
##labels
Australia, Oceania, continent(P30), []
Cook Islands, Oceania, continent(P30), []
Samoa, Oceania, continent(P30), []

##title
Mavis Grind
##doc
0 Mavis Grind ( or , meaning " gate of the narrow isthmus " ) is a narrow isthmus joining the Northmavine peninsula to the rest of the island of Shetland Mainland in the Shetland Islands , UK .
1 It is just wide at its narrowest point .
2 It carries the main A970 road to Hillswick in the north west of Shetland and is about two miles west of the settlement of Brae .
3 Mavis Grind is said to be the only place in the UK where you can toss a stone across land from the North Sea to the Atlantic Ocean .
4 It is a regular crossing point for otters , which in Shetland are sea - dwelling .
5 In 1999 , local volunteers successfully helped to demonstrate whether Viking ships could be carried across the isthmus , instead of sailing around the end of the island .
6 Remains of a late Bronze Age settlement have been found close by .
