##title
Ocean Waves (film)
##doc
0 Ocean Waves , also known as , is a 1993 Japanese anime television film directed by Tomomi Mochizuki and written by Kaori Nakamura based on the 1990 novel of the same name by Saeko Himuro .
1 It was animated by Studio Ghibli for Tokuma Shoten and the Nippon Television Network .
2 Ocean Waves first aired on May 5 , 1993 on Nippon TV .
3 The film is set in the city of Kōchi , on the Japanese island of Shikoku .
4 It concerns a love triangle that develops between two good friends and a new girl who transfers to their high school from Tokyo .
5 Ocean Waves was an attempt by Studio Ghibli to allow their younger staff members to make a film reasonably cheaply .
6 However , it ended up going both over budget and over schedule .
7 In December 2016 , GKIDS announced that the film would be remastered for a limited theatrical release , beginning on December 28 , 2016 , with a home video release in Spring 2017 .

##title
Daniel Ajayi-Adeniran
##doc
0 Daniel Ajayi - Adeniran is a Pentecostal pastor from Nigeria .
1 As of 2011 , he heads the expansion of the African - based Redeemed Christian Church of God in North America .
2 An educated man who worked as a civil servant in Nigeria , Ajayi - Adeniran experienced problems with alcohol , and in 1989 visited the Redeemed Christian Church of God across the street from his home near Ibadan .
3 In 1990 , he converted to the doctrines of the Redeemed Christian Church and was ordained through that denomination 1994 .
4 He moved to the United States in 1995 because of the political conditions under the dictator Sani Abacha in Nigeria .
5 After arriving in the U.S. , Ajayi - Adeniran became part of the first parish of the Redeemed Christian Church of God in North America located on Roosevelt Island .
6 Soon after , he became the pastor of a newly formed branch of the church , meeting in a Bronx storefront .
7 Ajayi - Adeniran states his goal is to inform others of the mission of the Redeemed Christian so that in each household in the world there will be at least one member of Redeemed Christian Church of God .

##title
The Two Mrs. Nahasapeemapetilons
##doc
0 " The Two Mrs. Nahasapeemapetilons " is the seventh episode of The Simpsons ' ninth season .
1 It originally aired on the Fox network in the United States on November 16 , 1997 .
2 It was written by Richard Appel and directed by Steven Dean Moore .
3 The episode sees Apu Nahasapeemapetilon marry Manjula , and incorporates several aspects of Hindu wedding ceremonies , which the writers researched during the episode 's production .
4 Appel pitched the episode several years before season nine but the idea was not used until Mike Scully became showrunner .
5 The episode 's subplot , which sees Homer stay at the Springfield Retirement Castle , was initially conceived as a separate episode , but could not be developed in enough detail .
6 The episode received mixed reviews .

##title
Arjuna
##doc
0 Arjuna ( in Devanagari : अर्जुन ) is the main central character of the ancient Indian epic Mahabharata and plays a key role in the Bhagavad Gita alongside Krishna .
1 It is believed that Arjuna was best archer in the world at their time .
2 Arjuna was the son of Indra , the king of the celestials , born of Kunti , the first wife of King Pandu in the Kuru Kingdom .
3 In a previous birth he was a saint named Nara who was the lifelong companion of another saint Narayana an incarnation of Lord Vishnu who took rebirth as Lord Krishna .
4 He was the third of the Pandava brothers and was married to Draupadi , Ulupi , Chitrāngadā and Subhadra ( Krishna 's and Balarama 's sister ) at different times .
5 His children included Srutakarma , Iravan , Babruvahana , and Abhimanyu .

##title
Patrick Stettner
##doc
0 Patrick Stettner is an American film director and writer .
1 His first film , Flux , was released in 1996 as a short , and starred Allison Janney in an early role .
2 He went on to direct and write the screenplay for The Business of Strangers in 2001 , which earned him a Grand Jury Prize nomination at the Sundance Film Festival of that year and earned lead actress Stockard Channing an AFI nomination for Best Female Actress .
3 In 2006 , he then wrote and directed The Night Listener , an adaptation of Armistead Maupin 's eponymous semi - autobiographical 2000 novel , which landed less than stellar reviews from critics .
4 He has not directed any films since The Night Listener .
5 He is an alumnus of Columbia University School of the Arts ' Film division .

##title
John Henry Dearle
##doc
0 John Henry Dearle or J. H. Dearle ( 1859 in London – 15 January 1932 ) was a British textile and stained - glass designer trained by the artist and craftsman William Morris who was much influenced by the Pre - Raphaelite Brotherhood .
1 Dearle designed many of the later wallpapers and textiles released by Morris & Co. , and contributed background and foliage patterns to tapestry designs featuring figures by Edward Burne - Jones and others .
2 Beginning in his teens as a shop assistant and then design apprentice , Dearle rose to become Morris & Co. 's chief designer by 1890 , creating designs for tapestries , embroidery , wallpapers , woven and printed textiles , stained glass , and carpets .
3 Following Morris 's death in 1896 , Dearle was appointed Art Director of the firm , and became its principal stained glass designer on the death of Burne - Jones in 1898 .
4 Morris 's reputation overshadowed Dearle 's work throughout Dearle 's career : Dearle exhibited early patterns under Morris 's name and Dearle designs continue to be sold as Morris patterns .
5 Critical assessment of Dearle 's work then underwent a significant change , during the final decades of the twentieth century , recognizing Dearle 's mature work as having a unique artistic vision of its own .
6 Dearle always remained close to Morris 's esthetic , but from the 1890s onward he incorporated a distinctive set of Persian and Turkish influences .
##labels

##title
King Louie
##doc
0 King Louie is a fictional character introduced in Walt Disney 's 1967 animated musical film , The Jungle Book .
1 Unlike the majority of the adapted characters in the film , Louie was not featured in Rudyard Kipling 's original works .
2 King Louie was portrayed as an orangutan who was the leader of the other jungle primates , and who attempted to gain knowledge of fire from Mowgli , in order to become more human .
3 King Louie was voiced by Louis Prima in the original 1967 film .
4 Initially , the filmmakers considered Louis Armstrong for the role , but to avoid the likely controversy that would result from casting a black person to voice an ape , they instead chose Prima , a white singer .
5 Christopher Walken voiced King Louie in the 2016 live - action / CGI The Jungle Book film .

##title
Financial District, Manhattan
##doc
0 The Financial District of Lower Manhattan , also known as FiDi , is a neighborhood located on the southern tip of Manhattan Island , where the City of New York itself originated in 1624 .
1 The district comprises the offices and headquarters of many of the city 's major financial institutions , including the New York Stock Exchange and the Federal Reserve Bank of New York .
2 Anchored on Wall Street in the Financial District , New York City has been called both the most financially powerful city and the leading financial center of the world , and the New York Stock Exchange is the world 's largest stock exchange by total market capitalization .
3 Several other major exchanges have or had headquarters in the Financial District , including the New York Mercantile Exchange , NASDAQ , the New York Board of Trade , and the former American Stock Exchange .
4 The neighborhood roughly overlaps with the boundaries of the New Amsterdam settlement in the late 17th century .
5 The population of the Financial District has grown to an estimated 61,000 residents as of 2018 , up from 43,000 as of 2014 , which in turn was nearly double the 23,000 recorded at the 2000 Census .

##title
Tomasz Bohdanowicz-Dworzecki
##doc
0 Tomasz Bohdanowicz - Dworzecki (; Foma Osipovich Dvorzhetsky - Bogdanovich ; 1859 – April 1920 ) was a Polish architect active in Moscow .
1 He was born into a family of Polish nobility in Vitebsk , Russian Empire ( now Belarus ) .
2 Bohdanowicz - Dworzecki graduated from the Academy of Fine Arts in Saint Petersburg .
3 From 1893 , he was a professor at the Moscow School of Painting , Sculpture and Architecture .
4 He worked there with Stanislaw Nowakowski .
5 Starting in 1899 , Bohdanowicz - Dworzecki was a member of the construction of the board of Moscow and designed several churches in the Gothic style in many cities of Russia , in particular the Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception of the Holy Virgin Mary , as well as several in the Byzantine style .
6 He also oversaw the construction of the Riga Central Railway Station ( 1897 - 1901 ) and collaborated with the renowned architects Alexander Pomerantsev and Alexander Lednicki .

##title
Tulelake camp
##doc
0 The Tule Lake camp was a federal work facility and WRA isolation center located in Siskiyou County , five miles west of Tulelake , California .
1 It was established by the United States government in 1935 during the Great Depression for vocational training and work relief for young men , in a program known as the Civilian Conservation Corps .
2 The camp was established initially for CCC enrollees to work on the Klamath Reclamation Project .
3 During World War II , in 1942 the Tule Lake War Relocation Center was built next to the camp as one of ten concentration camps in the interior of the US for the incarceration of Japanese Americans who had been forcibly relocated from the West Coast , which was defined as an Exclusion Zone by the US military .
4 Two - thirds of the 120,000 incarcerated individuals were United States citizens .
5 Renamed the Tule Lake Isolation Center , this facility was adapted in the wartime years to shelter Japanese - American strikebreakers used against resisters at the main segregation camp , imprison Japanese - American dissidents , and house Italian and German prisoners of war ( POWs ) who were assigned to work as farm laborers in the region .
6 After the war , on 25 April 1946 , the camp was transferred from the Army to the Fish and Wildlife Service , which had managed it just prior to the establishment of the segregation camp .
7 The four remaining buildings are being restored in a project to return the camp to its 1940s appearance .

##title
Ramapo High School (New Jersey)
##doc
0 Ramapo High School is a comprehensive four - year public high school located in the New York City suburb of Franklin Lakes , in Bergen County , New Jersey , United States .
1 The school is a part of the Ramapo Indian Hills Regional High School District , serving students in ninth through twelfth grades from Franklin Lakes , Oakland and Wyckoff ( FLOW ) .
2 The other high school in the district is Indian Hills High School , located in Oakland .
3 Students in eighth grade in the three sending districts have the opportunity to choose between Ramapo and Indian Hills by February in their graduating year .
4 As of the 2015 - 16 school year , the school had an enrollment of 1,054 students and 103.6 classroom teachers ( on an FTE basis ) , for a student – teacher ratio of 10.2:1 .
5 There were 17 students ( 1.6 % of enrollment ) eligible for free lunch and none eligible for reduced - cost lunch .

##title
Alecu Russo
##doc
0 Alecu Russo ( born in March 17 , 1819 , near Chişinău , died on February 5 , 1859 , in Iaşi ) , was a Moldavian Romanian writer , literary critic and publicist .
1 Russo is credited with having discovered one of the most elaborate forms of the Romanian national folk ballad Mioriţa .
2 He was also a contributor to the Iaşi periodical Zimbrul , in which he published one of his best - known works , Studie Moldovană ( " Moldovan Studies " ) , in 1851 - 1852 .
3 He also wrote Iaşii şi locuitorii lui în 1840 " Iaşi and its inhabitants in 1840 " – a glimpse into Moldavian society during the Organic Statute administration , and two travel accounts ( better described as folklore studies ) , Piatra Teiului and Stânca Corbului .
4 Russo is also notable for his Amintiri ( " Recollections " ) , a memoir .

##title
Osmund Ueland
##doc
0 Osmund Ueland ( born 27 September 1947 ) is a Norwegian civil servant and former CEO of Norges Statsbaner ( NSB ) .
1 An engineer by education , he worked for Aker from 1975 to 1990 .
2 From 1990 to 1994 he headed the Lillehammer Olympic Organising Committee ( LOOC ) .
3 In 1994 he was hired as CEO for NSB Gardermobanen ; the next year he was promoted to become CEO in the Norwegian State Railways .
4 In 1996 the Norwegian State Railways was demerged to create two entities ; Norges Statsbaner and the Norwegian National Rail Administration .
5 Ueland was the director of both , leaving the National Rail Administration in 1999 .
6 He was then fired after heavy criticism related to his leadership of NSB in 2000 .

##title
Clear and Present Danger (film)
##doc
0 Clear and Present Danger is a 1994 American spy thriller film directed by Phillip Noyce and based on Tom Clancy 's novel of the same name .
1 It was preceded by the 1990 film The Hunt for Red October and the 1992 film Patriot Games , all three featuring Clancy 's character Jack Ryan .
2 It is the last film version of Clancy 's novels to feature Harrison Ford as Ryan and James Earl Jones as Vice Admiral James Greer , as well as the final installment directed by Noyce .
3 As in the novel , Ryan is appointed CIA Acting Deputy Director , and discovers he is being kept in the dark by colleagues who are conducting a covert war against a drug cartel in Colombia , apparently with the approval of the President .
4 The film premiered in theaters in the United States on August 3 , 1994 , and was a major financial success , earning over $ 200 million at the box office .

##title
Big Muddy Creek (Missouri River tributary)
##doc
0 Big Muddy Creek is a tributary of the Missouri River , approximately 191   mi ( 307   km ) long , in the Canadian province of Saskatchewan and the U.S. state of Montana .
1 It flows through the Big Muddy Badlands .
2 It rises in southern Saskatchewan at Willow Bunch Lake , on the plains north of the international border and approximately 20   mi ( 32   km ) northwest of Big Beaver .
3 It flows southeast through the Big Muddy Badlands and through Big Muddy Lake , then south into Sheridan County , Montana , past Redstone , then east , past Plentywood , then south , forming the eastern border of Fort Peck Indian Reservation .
4 It joins the Missouri west of Culbertson .
5 It was explored in 1805 by the Lewis and Clark Expedition , who called it Martha 's River in their journals and noticed on their return voyage in 1806 that it had changed its mouth on the Missouri .
6 Along with the Milk River and the Poplar River , it is one of three waterways in Canada that drain into the Gulf of Mexico .

##title
Brother Man
##doc
0 Brother Man ( 1954 ) is a novel by Jamaican Roger Mais , about a Messianic folk Rastafarian healer , ' Bra ' Man ' ( in dialect ) John Power .
1 The book is significant as the first serious representation of the Rastafari movement in literature .
2 Mais foresaw the defining power of the Rasta movement to Jamaican society 20 years before the era of Bob Marley and Reggae mainstream .
3 It is also significant as an exploration of life in the ghetto of Kingston .
4 It shows how the people relate to leaders , both making them deities and throwing them away when they fail to entertain them .
5 The novel is written in prose with a layout that is seemingly cinematic and episodic ; little is done to describe the environment beyond the claustrophobic ghetto of ' The Lane ' in the slums of Kingston , Jamaica .

##title
Ellerbusch Site
##doc
0 The Ellerbusch Site ( 12-W-56 ) is a small but significant archaeological site in the southwestern part of the U.S. state of Indiana .
1 Unlike many sites created by people of the same culture , it occupies an upland site near a major river floodplain .
2 Its existence appears to have been the result of the coincidence of periods of peace and growth in the related Angel Site , which led some townspeople to leave their homes for new villages that were more convenient for resource gathering .
3 Researched partly because of its small size , Ellerbusch has produced information that greatly increases present awareness of other small sites and of its culture 's overall patterns of settlement in the region .
4 Because of its archaeological value , the site was declared a historic site in the late twentieth century .

##title
Joseph Israel
##doc
0 Joseph Israel ( about 1780 – 4 September 1804 ) was an officer in the United States Navy during the Quasi - War with France and the First Barbary War .
1 Israel entered the Navy as Midshipman 15 January 1801 .
2 He served in Maryland during the Quasi - War with France and in Chesapeake , New York , and Constitution during operation in the Mediterranean against the Barbary pirates .
3 Midshipman Israel was killed 4 September 1804 when ketch Intrepid exploded in the harbor of Tripoli during the night effort to destroy the enemy shipping led by Lieutenant Richard Somers .
4 A monument to the memory of Israel and his fellow officers and men stands on the grounds of the United States Naval Academy at Annapolis .
5 Israel was reported to be of the Jewish faith , although " there was no evidence that Israel is a Jew or of Jewish ancestry . "
6 USS Israel ( DD-98 ) was named in honor of him .

##title
William Hepburn Armstrong
##doc
0 William Hepburn Armstrong ( September 7 , 1824 – May 14 , 1919 ) was a Republican member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Pennsylvania .
1 William H. Armstrong was born in Williamsport , Pennsylvania .
2 He graduated from Princeton College in 1847 .
3 He studied law , was admitted to the bar and commenced practice in Williamsport .
4 He served in the Pennsylvania State House of Representatives in 1860 and 1861 .
5 He declined a commission as president judge of the twenty - sixth judicial circuit of Pennsylvania in 1862 .
6 Armstrong was elected as a Republican to the Forty - first Congress .
7 He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1870 .
8 He declined the office of commissioner of Indian affairs tendered by President Ulysses S. Grant .
9 He served as commissioner of railroads from 1882 to 1885 .
10 He resumed the practice of law in Washington , D.C. , and Philadelphia , until 1898 , when he retired from active business pursuits .
11 He moved to Wilmington , Delaware , where he died in 1919 .
12 Interment in Wilmington and Brandywine Cemetery .

##title
CKNL-FM
##doc
0 CKNL - FM is a Canadian radio station that broadcasts a mainstream rock format at 101.5 FM in Fort St. John , British Columbia .
1 The station is branded as 101.5 The Bear and is owned by Bell Media .
2 It is one of three " Bear " rock stations in Canada ; the others are CFBR - FM in Edmonton , Alberta , and CKRX - FM in Fort Nelson , British Columbia .
3 The station originally began broadcasting June 20 , 1962 at 970 AM , and later moved to 560 AM and finally to the FM dial at 101.5 FM in 2003 .
4 When the FM flip was approved , the station was to continue the country music format of the former 560 CKNL .
5 However , likely in response to the recent licensing of CKFU - FM in the same market at that time , when the station flipped to FM the format was switched to a rock station .

##title
Kitigan Zibi
##doc
0 Kitigan Zibi ( also known as River Desert , and designated as Maniwaki 18 until 1994 ) is a First Nations reserve of the Kitigan Zibi Anishinabeg First Nation , an Algonquin band .
1 It is situated at the confluence of the Désert and Gatineau Rivers , and borders south - west on the Town of Maniwaki in the Outaouais region of Quebec , Canada .
2 Having a total area of , it is the largest Algonquin Nation in Canada , in both area and population .
3 Present in the reserve are grocery and hardware supermarkets , gas station , elementary and secondary schools with a library accessible to the whole community , gift shops , a community radio station , a day - care , a community hall , a health centre , a police department , a youth centre , a wildlife centre , and an educational and cultural centre .

##title
Vanya Mishra
##doc
0 Vanya Mishra ( born 27 February 1992 ) is an Indian actress , engineer , entrepreneur and beauty pageant titleholder who was crowned Femina Miss India World in 2012 .
1 Vanya was born in Jalandhar , Punjab , raised in Chandigarh and studied electrical engineering at Punjab Engineering College .
2 She represented India at the Miss World 2012 event in China in August 2012 .
3 She finished at 7th rank , and won the other two , Miss Social Media and Beauty with a Purpose titles .
4 She was leading the scoreboard at the Miss World pageant after scoring one of the highest scores in the personal interview round and winning two sub - contests back - to - back unlike no pageant contestant before .
5 Unlike most of her contemporaries , she chose to pursue her entrepreneurial dream , after declining various Bollywood and TV offers .
6 She currently is the co - founder and managing director at her fashion discovery portal , SummerLabel , launched on Android .

##title
Kokumin Dōmei
##doc
0 In 1931 , Home Minister Adachi Kenzō spoke out strongly in support of the Imperial Japanese Army ’s unauthorized incursions into Manchuria and against the diplomatic policies pursued by Kijūrō Shidehara , and was expelled from the ranks of the Rikken Minseitō .
1 Joining together with Nakano Seigō , Akira Kazami , and others , Adachi formed the right - wing political organization Kokumin Dōmei in December 1932
2 The Kokumin Dōmei advocated a form of state socialism or corporatism with government control of strategic industries and financial institutions , and the creation of a Japan - Manchukuo economic union .
3 The new party consisted mainly of defectors from the Minseitō , and had an original strength of 32 seats in the Diet of Japan .
4 In 1934 , it demanded an inquiry into the Teijin Incident in an effort to bring down the cabinet of Prime Minister Saitō Makoto .
5 However , in 1935 , many members returned to the Minseitō fold , and in 1936 , Nakano left the party to form the Tōhōkai the following year , and Kazami joining Fumimaro Konoe ’s think tank , the Shōwa Kenkyūkai .
6 In the 1937 General Election , the party 's strength fell from 32 seats to 11 seats .
7 In June 1940 , The Kokumin Dōmei was merged into the Imperial Rule Assistance Association as part of Hideki Tōjō 's efforts to create a one - party state , and thereafter ceased to exist .

##title
Jeanne Thérèse du Han
##doc
0 Jeanne Thérèse du Han de Martigny ( 30 October 1707 in Lunéville – 7 May 1748 in Nancy ) was born and baptized the same day in Lunéville , in the duchy of Lorraine , now part of France .
1 She was the daughter of Philippe - Louis du Han , comte de Martigny ( 1678 – 1733 ) and his wife Catherine Françoise de Roquefeuil de Puydebar ( c.1680 – 1764 ) .
2 The Du Han de Martigny were an important noble family of Lorraine , with estates in the north of the duchy .
3 Louis - Philippe held posts as conseiller d'état , Chamberlain and Grand Veneur under Duke Léopold I , and his daughters were among the court beauties .
4 In 1731 , Jeanne - Thérèse was maid of honour to the Dowager Duchess and Regent of Lorraine , Léopold 's widow .
5 After the outbreak of the War of the Austrian Succession , Granville Elliott spent most of his time away fighting .
6 Jeanne Thérèse and her husband Granville appear regularly in the Madame de Graffigny correspondence .

##title
Schiedea haleakalensis
##doc
0 Schiedea haleakalensis is a rare species of flowering plant in the pink family known by the common name Haleakalā schiedea .
1 It is endemic to Hawaii , where it is known only from Haleakalā National Park on the island of Maui .
2 It is threatened by the degradation of its habitat .
3 It was federally listed as an endangered species of the United States in 1992 .
4 This plant is a shrub growing up 30 to 60 centimeters tall .
5 The leaves have narrow blades measuring up to 8 centimeters long but just a few millimeters in width .
6 The inflorescence is a cluster of flowers with tiny green sepals and no petals .
7 This shrub is known from two locations in Haleakalā National Park ; it is named for the volcano Haleakalā .
8 It has been threatened by the presence of feral goats in its habitat , but most of these have been excluded .

##title
Lunula (amulet)
##doc
0 A lunula ( plural : lunulae ) was a crescent moon shaped pendant worn by girls in ancient Rome .
1 Girls ideally wore them as an apotropaic amulet , the equivalent of the boy 's bulla .
2 In the popular belief the Romans wore amulets usually as a talisman , to protect themselves against evil forces , demons and sorcery , but especially against the evil eye .
3 In Plautus ' play , Epidicus asks the young girl Telestis : " Do n't you remember my bringing you a gold lunula on your birthday , and a little gold ring for your finger ? "
4 An explicit definition is provided by Isidore of Seville : " Lunulae are female ornaments in the likeness of the moon , little hanging gold bullae . "
5 But in Plautus ' play Rudens , Palaestra says her father gave her a golden bulla on the day of her birth .
6 There is also some indication that babies of both sexes wore phallic amulets .
##labels
Rudens, Plautus, author(P50), [5]

Plautus, Rudens, notable work(P800), []
Palaestra, Plautus, creator(P170), []
Palaestra, Rudens, present in work(P1441), []

##title
Joe Gates
##doc
0 Joseph Daniel Gates ( October 3 , 1954 – March 28 , 2010 ) was a professional baseball player .
1 He played parts of two seasons in Major League Baseball for the Chicago White Sox .
2 His only extra base hit was a triple on May 13 , 1979 against the Kansas City Royals .
3 He had come on as a pinch hitter for Don Kessinger and stayed in the game and played second base .
4 The pitcher for the Royals was Eduardo Rodriguez .
5 The hit drove in Greg Pryor in the bottom of the 9th .
6 The final score of the game was Royals 14 , White Sox 5 .
7 After his major league career , he entered the coaching ranks .
8 He was the bench coach of the Gary SouthShore RailCats of the Northern League at the time of his death at age 55 .

##title
LEC billing
##doc
0 LEC billing is a form of billing for Internet - based or other usually electronic services where the user is charged through his account with the local telephone company ( also known as the local exchange carrier or LEC ) , rather than directly from the provider of the service .
1 LEC billing is permitted in the United States as the breakup of the Bell System forced local telcos out of the long distance business ; each client would otherwise receive multiple monthly bills ( one for local service , one for long distance ) .
2 There is no LEC billing for alternate long distance carriers in Canada as Bell Canada and Telus remain in the long - distance business and do not collect on behalf of their competitors .
3 The LEC billing system is subject to abuse by vendors .
4 Cramming is a form of phone fraud in which a third - party vendor adds unauthorised charges to a subscriber 's local telephone bill .
##labels

Bell Canada, Canada, country(P17), [2]

Bell Canada, Canada, located in the administrative territorial entity(P131), [2]

##title
Leandro Mbomio Nsue
##doc
0 Leandro Mbomio Nsue Edú - Aguong , born 5 January 1938 ( Río Muni , Bata ) , died 12 November 2012 ( Malabo ) at Evinayong , Spanish Guinea , is an Equatorial Guinean sculptor and artist , and former minister of Education and minister of information , tourism , art and culture .
1 In October 2007 Mbomio was nominated Artist for Peace by the UNESCO , he has several knighthoods including one from the French Republic for merit to art .
2 Leandro studied art in Spain where he lived in exile for many years during the Franco period .
3 He always favoured a Free Equatorial Guinea , and in 1979 he took possession by force of the Former Embassy of Equatorial Guinea in Madrid .
4 When the New President called on him he left all for Equatorial Guinea .
5 He was an African Partisan and was always close to President Teodoro Obiang .
6 He lived in Malabo ( RGE ) , Germany , Madrid , Barcelona , etc . , and he was the
7 President of the Council of Science and Technology of Equatorial Guinea and organ of the Presidency of Equatorial Guinea .

##title
Lost Verizon
##doc
0 " Lost Verizon " is the second episode of The Simpsons ' twentieth season .
1 It first aired on the Fox network in the United States on October 5 , 2008 .
2 Bart becomes jealous of his friends and their cell phones .
3 Working at a golf course , Bart takes the cell phone of Denis Leary after the star comedian throws it away in anger .
4 Marge , per Leary 's advice , activates the GPS system on the phone to track down Bart 's every move ; catching on , Bart attaches the GPS chip to a bird that migrates to Machu Picchu , Peru .
5 Leary and Brian Grazer ( who also appeared in " When You Dish Upon a Star " as himself ) both guest star as themselves .
6 It was directed by Raymond S. Persi and written by John Frink .

##title
Malpai Borderlands
##doc
0 Malpai Borderlands is a region , or areal feature , along the U.S .- Mexico border at the Arizona and New Mexico state line .
1 It encompasses the extreme southeast corner of Arizona and the southwest corner of New Mexico describe the general vicinity .
2 It includes areas inside the U.S. states of Arizona and New Mexico as well as the Mexican states of Chihuahua and Sonora .
3 The lowest elevations in this area are about 3,700 feet in the San Bernardino National Wildlife Refuge area .
4 Highest elevation is roughly 8,500 feet above mean sea level ( AMSL ) .
5 Mountain ranges generally run north - south .
6 Terrain is described as including desert shrub , Tobosa grassland , Ponderosa Pine forest , and Douglas Fir .
7 Some cattle ranching takes place in the region .
8 The geomorphic provinces include Madrean and Chihuahuan deserts .
9 The name " Malpai " , relates to a type of " desert pavement " , formed by wind ( eolian ) processes , and is called Malapai .

##title
Pete Murray
##doc
0 Peter Kenneth Murray ( born 14 October 1969 ) is an Australian singer - songwriter whose first three full - length albums reached number 1 on the Australian music charts .
1 He has been nominated several times at the ARIAs and has had several songs reach the top forty in Australia .
2 His first LP , Feeler , reached number 1 a few months after its mid-2003 release , and his follow - up record , See The Sun , had a similar level of success , with all of the singles receiving widespread airplay .
3 His third studio album , Summer At Eureka , was released in May 2008 .
4 To date , Murray has sold over 1 million records .
5 Some of the greatest influences on his career are Nick Drake , Neil Young and Bob Dylan .
6 In November 2013 , Murray toured Canada with Paul Langlois and Rob Baker of The Tragically Hip .

##title
Gregorio Pacheco
##doc
0 Gregorio Pacheco Leyes ( 4 July 1823 – 20 August 1899 ) was the constitutional President of Bolivia from 1884 to 1888 .
1 A native of Livilivi , Province of Potosí , Pacheco won a disputed election that was a virtual three - way tie between him , Conservative leader Aniceto Arce , and Liberal chief Eliodoro Camacho .
2 Pacheco was self - made a wealthy man ( he was born poor ) and the country 's foremost philanthropist .
3 He made his money purchasing shares in defunct silver mines which he rehabilitated .
4 By the mid 19th century Pacheco emerged as a wealthy , efficient , progressive , and pragmatic silver tycoon .
5 Bolivia 's state of instability , fraught with coups and international conflicts concerned him greatly .

##title
Amos Hochstein
##doc
0 Amos J. Hochstein ( born January 4 , 1973 ) is a U.S. businessman , former diplomat and national security and energy expert .
1 He has worked in the U.S. Congress , has testified before congressional panels and has served under the Barack Obama administration under Secretaries of State Clinton and Kerry .
2 He was appointed Deputy Assistant Secretary of State in 2011 and as Special Envoy and Coordinator for International Energy Affairs .
3 In 2015 , President Barack Obama nominated Hochstein to be the Assistant Secretary of State for Energy Ressources .
4 While at the State Department , Hochstein worked as a close advisor to Vice - President Joe Biden .
5 He served in the administration from 2011 to 2017 .
6 In March 2017 , he joined Tellurian , a private Houston - based LNG company , where he serves as Senior Vice President Marketing .
7 He serves on the supervisory board of Naftogaz as well as the Board 's of the Atlantic Council and U.S .- India Business Council .

##title
Astana International Financial Centre
##doc
0 The Astana International Financial Centre ( AIFC ) is a financial hub in Astana , Kazakhstan that officially launched on July 5 , 2018 .
1 On 20 May 2015 , the President of Republic of Kazakhstan Nursultan Nazarbayev announced the “ 100 Concrete Steps ” Plan of the Nation to implement the five institutional reforms , designed to provide a strong national platform needed to achieve country ’s ambition of joining the top 30 developed countries by 2050 .
2 As part of the Plan of the Nation , the AIFC was established with a special legal status to be based on the EXPO-2017 International Specialized Exhibition infrastructure .
3 The Constitutional Law " On the Astana International Financial Centre " approved on 7 December 2015 provides a legal framework for the functioning of the AIFC as well as a favourable environment for its participants .
4 The Astana International Financial Centre plays one of the main roles in attracting financial resources .
5 It is positioned as a financial hub for the countries of Central Asia , the Caucasus , Eurasian Economic Union ( EAEU ) , Middle East , Western China , Mongolia and Europe .

##title
Riksakten
##doc
0 The Riksakten was the 1815 Act of Union that regulated the terms of the constitutional personal union between Sweden and Norway established in 1814 .
1 The fundamental documents of the union were only the Convention of Moss and the revised Norwegian constitution of 4 November 1814 .
2 The Norwegian constitution had been adapted to the union before it was entered into , but the Swedish one was never adjusted correspondingly .
3 The conservative Swedish Riksdag had not allowed the Swedish constitution of 1809 to be revised .
4 Therefore , a bilateral treaty had to be negotiated in order to clarify procedures for treating constitutional questions that had to be decided jointly by both governments .
5 The Act of Union ( Riksakten ) was negotiated during the spring of 1815 , with prime minister Peder Anker leading the Norwegian delegation .
6 The treaty contained twelve articles dealing with the king 's authority , the relationship between the two legislatures , how the executive power was to be exercised if the king should die before the crown prince had attained majority , and the relationship between the cabinets .
7 It also confirmed the practice of treating questions of foreign policy in the Swedish cabinet , with the Norwegian prime minister present .
8 Vital questions pertaining to the Union were to be treated in a joint cabinet meeting , where all the Norwegian ministers in Stockholm would be present .
9 The Act was passed by the Storting 31 July 1815 and by the Riksdag 6 August , and sanctioned by the king on 15 August .
10 In Sweden the Act of Union was a set of provisions under regular law , but the Norwegian Storting gave it constitutional status , so that its provisions could only be revised according to the procedures laid down in the constitution .
11 The Riksakten contained 12 paragraphs :

##title
Goght
##doc
0 Goght (; formerly Goghot ) is a village in the Kotayk Province of Armenia , located on the right bank of the upper - Azat River .
1 It is known from 13th - century manuscripts as Goghot .
2 It is located near Garni and sits along the road leading to Geghard Monastery .
3 The village has a small ruined basilica from the 17th or 18th century located straight down a dirt road from the main square .
4 Some khachkars are built into the exterior walls of the church , as well as at its altar .
5 Goght sits overlooking a large gorge and upon a promontory on the other side is the 11th- to 13th - century monastery of Havuts Tar .
6 It may be reached by foot from the town , but more easily from Garni via the Garni Gorge .
7 The community has a school , kindergarten , house of culture , and a library .
8 The local economy is heavily dependent on agriculture , based primarily on grain farming , orchard cultivation , and cattle - breeding .

##title
Horst Eidenmüller
##doc
0 Horst Eidenmüller ( born 23 October 1963 ) is the Freshfields Professor of Commercial Law in the Faculty of Law at the University of Oxford and a Fellow of St. Hugh ’s .
1 Eidenmüller was born in Munich , Germany .
2 He is a graduate of Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich and of Cambridge ( LLM 1989 ) .
3 Prior to joining Oxford , Eidenmüller held professorships at the universities of Münster ( 1999 - 2003 ) and Munich ( 2003 - 2015 ) .
4 He was visiting professor at Cambridge ( 2007 ) , Oxford ( 2009 - 2014 ) , Harvard ( 2011 ) , Tulane ( 2011 ) , NYU ( 2013 and 2015 ) , and Stanford ( 2015 ) , as well as fellow of the Institute for Advanced Study , Berlin ( 2008 - 2009 ) .
5 Eidenmüller is a member of the Berlin - Brandenburg Academy of Sciences and Humanities ( since 2008 ) and of the European Academy of Sciences and Arts ( since 2016 ) .
6 Eidenmüller ’s research focuses on commercial contracts , company law , insolvency law , and alternative dispute resolution .
7 He is known for economic and empirical studies in these fields .

##title
William James Wallace
##doc
0 William James Wallace ( April 14 , 1837 – March 11 , 1917 ) was a federal judge in the United States .
1 A native of Syracuse , New York , Wallace attended Syracuse University and obtained a law degree from Hamilton College .
2 He spent 15 years as a lawyer in private practice in Syracuse before serving as mayor of that city in 1873 – 74 .
3 In 1874 , President Ulysses S. Grant appointed Wallace as a judge of the United States District Court for the Northern District of New York .
4 In 1882 , President Chester A. Arthur promoted Wallace to the United States Circuit Court for the Second Circuit in New York .
5 In 1891 , the Evarts Act converted Wallace 's judgeship to a position on the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit .
6 Wallace retired from the Second Circuit in 1907 and returned to private practice in Syracuse until his death ten years later .

##title
Chachalaca
##doc
0 Chachalacas are galliform birds from the genus Ortalis .
1 These birds are found in wooded habitats in far southern United States ( Texas ) , Mexico , and Central and South America .
2 They are social , can be very noisy and often remain fairly common even near humans , as their relatively small size makes them less desirable to hunters than their larger relatives .
3 As invasive pests , they have a ravenous appetite for tomatoes , melons , beans , and radishes and can ravage a small garden in short order .
4 They travel in packs of six to twelve .
5 They somewhat resemble the guans , and the two have commonly been placed in a subfamily together , though the chachalacas are probably closer to the curassows .
6 The generic name is derived from the Greek word όρταλις , meaning " pullet " or " domestic hen . "
7 The common name is an onomatopoeia for the four - noted cackle of the plain chachalaca ( O. vetula ) .
8 Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequence data tentatively suggest that the chachalacas emerged as a distinct lineage during the Oligocene , somewhere around 40–20 mya , possibly being the first lineage of modern cracids to evolve ; this does agree with the known fossil record – including indeterminate , cracid - like birds – which very cautiously favors a north - to - south expansion of the family .

##title
Çağlar Söyüncü
##doc
0 Çağlar Söyüncü ( born 23 May 1996 ) is a Turkish professional footballer , who plays as a defender for Premier League side Leicester City and the Turkish national team .
1 Joining SC Freiburg in 2016 Bundesliga summer transfer window , he is the first Turkish footballer who made a transfer to Bundesliga directly from TFF First League , the second highest professional level football league of Turkey .
2 Making his senior national team debut in 2016 , Söyüncü is the first Altınordu S.K.
3 player called up to Turkey national football team after 78 years , since Sait Altınordu , the iconic player of the club , was selected in 1937 .
4 He is also the first player called up to national team from any İzmir - based football clubs since 1997 .

##title
X-Men Legends II: Rise of Apocalypse
##doc
0 X - Men Legends II : Rise of Apocalypse is an action role - playing game developed primarily by Raven Software and published by Activision .
1 It is the follow up to 2004 's X - Men Legends .
2 It was released in September 2005 for the GameCube , Microsoft Windows , N - Gage , PlayStation 2 , PlayStation Portable and Xbox .
3 It is set after the events of X - Men Legends and features the mutant supervillain Apocalypse as the primary antagonist .
4 The developers intended the game to have a greater sense of scale than its predecessor , and writers created a story where the villains known as the Brotherhood of Mutants would need to ally themselves with the heroic X - Men to defeat a greater threat .
5 High quality cinematics were created by Blur Studio .
6 Online multiplayer was also added .
7 The game was well received by gaming critics on all platforms .
8 Critics felt that the inclusion of online play , additional mutant powers , and a larger cast made the game an improvement over its predecessor .
9 Some reviewers were critical of the game 's voice acting and felt that the gameplay was repetitive .
10 It sold enough copies to be added to the budget line known as PlayStation 2 's Greatest Hits .

##title
Great South Australian Coastal Upwelling System
##doc
0 The Great South Australian Coastal Upwelling System is a seasonal upwelling system in the eastern Great Australian Bight , extending from Ceduna , South Australia , to Portland , Victoria , over a distance of about .
1 Upwelling events occur in the austral summer ( from November to May ) when seasonal winds blow from the southeast .
2 These winds blow parallel to the shoreline at certain areas of the coast , which forces coastal waters offshore via Ekman transport and draws up cold , nutrient - rich waters from the ocean floor .
3 Because the deep water carries abundant nutrients up from the ocean floor , the upwelling area differs from the rest of the Great Australian Bight , especially the areas offshore of Western Australia and the Nullabor in South Australia , which are generally nutrient - poor .
4 Every summer , the upwelling sustains a bountiful ecosystem that attracts blue whales and supports rich fisheries .
5 The Great South Australian Coastal Upwelling System ( GSACUS ) is Australia 's only deep - reaching coastal upwelling system , with nutrient - enriched water stemming from depths exceeding .
6 Recently , a new upwelling centre has been discovered on the western shelf of Tasmania .
7 Since this new upwelling centre is located outside South Australian waters , the entire upwelling system should be rather called the Great Southern Australian Coastal Upwelling System .

##title
I Knew You Were Trouble
##doc
0 " I Knew You Were Trouble . "
1 is a song recorded by American singer - songwriter Taylor Swift for her fourth studio album , Red ( 2012 ) .
2 It was released on October 9 , 2012 , in the United States by Big Machine Records as the third promotional single from the album .
3 Later , " I Knew You Were Trouble " was released as the third single from Red on November 27 , 2012 , in the United States .
4 It was written by Swift , Max Martin and Shellback , with the production handled by the latter two .
5 " I Knew You Were Trouble " received generally positive reviews from music critics , who commended its mainstream appeal yet noted Swift 's experimentation with dubstep as relatively limited .
6 Due to strong digital sales , the song debuted at number three on the Billboard Hot 100 chart in the United States , selling more than 416,000   copies within its first week ; it later peaked at number two in January 2013 , blocked from the top spot by Bruno Marss " Locked Out of Heaven " .
7 At the inaugural YouTube Music Awards in 2013 , " I Knew You Were Trouble " won the award for YouTube phenomenon .
8 The single has been certified sextuple platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America ( RIAA ) .
9 The song had sold 5 million copies in the United States alone by 2014 .

##title
Independent Democratic Action
##doc
0 The Independent Democratic Action ( ) is a political party in São Tomé and Príncipe .
1 It was established in 1994 by the then president Miguel Trovoada and is a politically centrist party .
2 It took part in the 29 July 2001 presidential elections , in which its candidate , Fradique de Menezes , won 55.2 % of the vote and was elected president .
3 After the elections Fradique de Menezes joined a new party - the Force for Change Democratic Movement - Liberal Party .
4 In the legislative election held on 3 March 2002 , the Independent Democratic Action was the main party in the Uê Kédadji alliance , that won 16.2 % of the popular vote and 8 out of 55 seats .
5 It left this alliance and won in the 2006 election 11 out of 55 seats .
6 In the July 2006 presidential election , its leader Patrice Trovoada ran as the only major opposition candidate , but he was defeated by Menezes .
7 Trovoada became Prime Minister in February 2008 , but was defeated in a May 2008 vote of confidence proposed by the Movement for the Liberation of São Tomé and Príncipe / Social Democratic Party ( MLSTP / PSD ) , and in June Menezes asked the MLSTP / PSD to form a new government .
8 The ADI denounced Menezes ' designation of the MLSTP / PSD to form a government as unconstitutional , arguing that it was too late in the parliamentary term to do so , and it took the matter to the Supreme Tribunal of Justice .

##title
Camp Caves
##doc
0 Camp Caves was a US Army training camp north of the city of Rockhampton , Queensland , Australia .
1 Built during World War Two , the camp was in use from September 1943 until early in 1944 .
2 It was one of a number of US training camps in the area including Camp Nerimbera , Camp Thompson ’s Point , Camp Keppel Sands , Camp Yeppoon and Camp Wallaroo .
3 Camp Caves was the camp for the 24th Infantry Division , which was also called the Hawaiian Division .
4 It was called Camp Caves after the small town , The Caves , which was close to the campsite .
5 The site was along the side of the Bruce Highway .
6 It included medical services , warehouses , ammunition dumps , landing strips , and a small arms firing range .
7 Work on building the camp began in November 1942 but was soon stopped .
8 It started again in July 1943 .
9 The camp was no longer used after March 1944 .

##title
Zevs (artist)
##doc
0 Zevs ( born Christophe Aguirre Schwarz on 17 November 1977 in Saverne , France ) is a French street artist , best known for his trademark " liquidation " technique .
1 He was an early and influential graffiti artist and active as a tagger in Paris in the 1990s .
2 He is named after a regional train , Zeus , that almost ran him over one day he was down in the metro .
3 Working with other French artists in the second half of the 1990s like André and Invader , Zevs has been among the prominent figures who pioneered the French street art scene .
4 By the end of the 1990s he became known for his poetic drawings of shadows in Paris , shortly after the departure of Facundo Newbery from Paris .
5 Later he ' bombed ' models on the billboards between the eyes .
6 Though his interventions have been very popular , it has been discussed in France whether it is vandalism or art .
7 In 2008 Zevs had his first major survey exhibition at the classical art museum the Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek in Copenhagen , Denmark .
8 His work , including selections of all of his major series to that point , was displayed alongside masterpieces in the museum 's permanent collections such as Édouard Manet 's The Absinthe Drinker and Auguste Rodin 's The Thinker .

##title
Puskás
##doc
0 Puskás is a Hungarian surname .
1 Notable people with the surname include :
2 Ferenc Puskás ( 1927 – 2006 ) , Hungarian football player and manager
3 FIFA Puskás Award , the player judged to have scored the most aesthetically significant and " most beautiful " goal of the year
4 Ferenc Puskás Stadium , a multi - purpose stadium in Budapest , Hungary
5 Puskás Akadémia FC , the young team of Videoton Football Club of Felcsút , Hungary
6 Puskás Cup , an international football tournament founded by the Puskás Akadémia FC
7 Puskás Ferenc Stadion ( Budapest Metro ) , a station of the M2 ( East - West ) line of the Budapest Metro
8 Tivadar Puskás ( 1844 – 1893 ) , Hungarian inventor of the telephone exchange
9 Tivadar Puskás ( politician ) ( 1952- ) , Hungarian politician
10 Ferenc Puskás I ( 1903–1952 ) , Hungarian football player and manager , father of Ferenc Puskás
11 Lajos Puskás ( 1944- ) , Hungarian footballer
12 Imre Puskás ( 1966- ) , Hungarian jurist and politician
13 Zoltán Puskás ( 1993- ) , Hungarian footballer

##title
Mike Padden
##doc
0 Michael John " Mike " Padden ( born November 13 , 1946 ) is a lawyer and politician from Spokane Valley , Washington .
1 He is a member of the Washington State Senate representing Washington 's 4th Legislative District .
2 Padden is well known as a " faithless elector " , a Presidential Elector who casts his vote for someone other than for whom he has pledged to vote .
3 In the 1976 U.S. presidential election , Gerald Ford , the Republican candidate and incumbent , had lost the race to Democrat , and former Georgia Governor Jimmy Carter .
4 Rather than vote as pledged , for President Ford , Padden instead cast his vote for Ronald Reagan , who had lost the Republican nomination to Ford earlier that year .
5 He entered the Washington House of Representatives in January 1981 and served there until 1995 when he was appointed to serve as a district court judge in the Spokane County District Court .
6 On June 13 , 2006 , Padden announced he would not run for re - election as judge .
7 In 2007 , evidence surfaced that Padden used his influence as a judge to help direct more than $ 7.5 million in fees and interest payments to a former employer .
8 At Padden ’s request , the state Commission on Judicial Conduct has issued a statement confirming that it examined complaints about Padden ’s 1999 selection of a former client as the official collection agency for District Court but found nothing to support an ethics violation .
9 The commission typically acknowledges complaints only if it imposes discipline or sanctions .
10 The agency , however , refused to disclose how it arrived at its conclusion or what the initial examination entailed .
11 Padden was elected to the Washington Senate in November 2011 .

##title
National Turkey Federation
##doc
0 The National Turkey Federation ( NTF ) is the non - profit national trade association based in Washington , D.C. , United States , representing the turkey industry and its allies and affiliates .
1 NTF advocates for all segments of the turkey industry , providing services and conducting activities which increase demand for its members ' products .
2 The NTF represents its members before the U.S. Congress and the various regulatory agencies , such as the U.S. Department of Agriculture 's Food Safety and Inspection Service .
3 Among members of the general public , NTF is best known for its role in the National Thanksgiving Turkey Presentation , an annual ceremony where a live domestic turkey is presented to the President of the United States just before Thanksgiving Day .
4 NTF began presenting the National Thanksgiving Turkey during the presidency of Harry Truman .
5 The custom of " pardoning " the turkey started with Bush I in 1989 , Two birds are brought to the White House for final selection and the President invariably grants a " pardon " to both birds .
6 Its official website , EatTurkey.com , is home to thousands of turkey recipes , cooking and preparation tips , and educational information on the turkey industry .

##title
List of songs recorded by Rage Against the Machine
##doc
0 Rage Against the Machine is an American rap metal band from Los Angeles , California .
1 Formed in 1991 , the group consists of vocalist Zack de la Rocha , guitarist Tom Morello , bassist Tim Commerford and drummer Brad Wilk .
2 After a self - issued demo , the band signed with Epic Records and released its self - titled debut album Rage Against the Machine in 1992 , the material for which was written by all four members of the group .
3 After contributing the single " Year of tha Boomerang " to the Higher Learning soundtrack in 1995 , the band released its second studio album Evil Empire in 1996 , on which " Year of tha Boomerang " was featured as the closing track .
4 In 1997 the band released a cover version of Bruce Springsteen 's " The Ghost of Tom Joad " , and the following year contributed " No Shelter " to the soundtrack to the film Godzilla , as well as releasing it as a single .
5 In 1999 the band released its final album of original material , The Battle of Los Angeles , which again credited all four members equally for songwriting .
6 The group disbanded in October 2000 , after de la Rocha departed to focus on producing his first solo album .
7 After the group 's breakup , Epic released Renegades in December 2000 , which featured cover versions of songs originally recorded by several hip hop artists , rock bands and other artists .

##title
Sarah Gibb
##doc
0 Sarah Gibb is an English illustrator whose drawings have appeared in national newspapers , magazines , and greetings cards , although she is predominantly an illustrator of children 's books .
1 She studied at London 's St. Martin 's College before completing an MA in Sequential Illustration at Brighton College of Art .
2 Gibb has illustrated at least a dozen books in The Tiara Club series by Vivian French , which carry titles such as Princess Alice and the Glass Slipper , Princess Charlotte and the Birthday Ball , and so on .
3 ( The Library of Congress catalogues 12 volumes featuring 6 named princesses with U.S. editions released in 2007 . )
4 Recently she illustrates picture books by Ursula Jones — a retired British actress and the surviving sister of Diana Wynne Jones .
5 The Princess Who Had No Kingdom was the first , published by Orchard Books in 2010 .

##title
Metropolitan statistical area
##doc
0 In the United States , a metropolitan statistical area ( MSA ) is a geographical region with a relatively high population density at its core and close economic ties throughout the area .
1 Such regions are neither legally incorporated as a city or town would be , nor are they legal administrative divisions like counties or separate entities such as states ; because of this , the precise definition of any given metropolitan area can vary with the source .
2 A typical metropolitan area is centered on a single large city that wields substantial influence over the region ( e.g. ,   New York City or Philadelphia ) .
3 However , some metropolitan areas contain more than one large city with no single municipality holding a substantially dominant position ( e.g. ,   Dallas – Fort Worth metroplex , Norfolk - Virginia Beach ( Hampton Roads ) , Riverside – San Bernardino ( Inland Empire ) or Minneapolis – Saint Paul ( Twin Cities ) ) .
4 MSAs are defined by the U.S. Office of Management and Budget ( OMB ) and used by the Census Bureau and other federal government agencies for statistical purposes .

##title
Carol II of Romania
##doc
0 Carol II ( 15 October 18934 April 1953 ) reigned as King of Romania from 8 June 1930 until his coerced abdication on 6 September 1940 .
1 Carol was the eldest son of Ferdinand I and became crown prince upon the death of his grand - uncle , King Carol I in 1914 .
2 He was the first of the Hohenzollern kings of Romania to be born in the country ( both of his predecessors were born and grew up in Germany and only came to Romania as adults ) .
3 Carol , by contrast , spoke Romanian as his first language and was the first member of the Romanian royal family to be raised in the Orthodox faith .
4 He possessed a hedonistic personality that contributed to the controversies marring his reign , and his life was marked by numerous scandals , among them marriages to Zizi Lambrino and Princess Helen of Greece and Denmark , daughter of King Constantine I of Greece .
5 His continued affairs with Magda Lupescu obliged him to renounce his succession rights in 1925 and leave the country .
6 Princess Helen eventually divorced him in 1928 .
7 King Ferdinand died in 1927 and Carol 's five - year - old son ascended the throne as Michael I. Carol then returned to Romania in 1930 and replaced his son and the regency that had been in place .
8 His reign was marked by re - alignment with Nazi Germany , adoption of anti - semitic laws and ultimately evolved into a personal dictatorship beginning in 1938 .
9 On 6 September 1940 , he was forced by his Prime Minister Ion Antonescu to leave the country and withdraw abroad into exile .
10 He was succeeded by his son Michael .

##title
Torrejonian
##doc
0 The Torrejonian North American Stage on the geologic timescale is the North American faunal stage according to the North American Land Mammal Ages chronology ( NALMA ) , typically set from 63,300,000 to 60,200,000 years BP lasting .
1 It is usually considered to overlap the Selandian and Thanetian within the Paleocene .
2 The Torrejonian is preceded by the Puercan and followed by the Tiffanian NALMA stages .
3 The Torrejonian is considered to be contained within the Danian and contains the following substages :
4 To3 : Lower boundary source of the base of the Torrejonian ( approximate ) .
5 To2 : Lower boundary source of the base of the Torrejonian ( approximate ) and upper boundary source of the base of the Selandian ( approximate ) .
6 To1 : Upper boundary source ( 61.7 Ma ) of the base of the Selandian ( approximate ) .

##title
Greatest Hits (A-Teens album)
##doc
0 Greatest Hits is A - Teens ' last album .
1 It is a compilation including their biggest worldwide hits , such as " Mamma Mia " , " Upside Down " , " Halfway Around the World " , " Floorfiller " , and many others .
2 Every track included on the album ( except for the new tracks ) reached the Top 20 in at least one country .
3 The album was planned to be released in early 2004 , but due to problems with Stockholm Records / Universal Music , A - Teens released the album on May 5 , 2004 .
4 For the release of this album , the A - Teens called all their fans through their website asking for pictures , and they included the pictures on the booklet of the album .
5 The tracks " The Final Cut " and " With or Without You " were written by the members of the band , giving messages of " goodbye " and " thanks " to their fans .
6 This album was not released worldwide .
7 Instead , it was released in selected territories where Universal thought it would do well .
8 These included Mexico , Argentina , Germany , and some other European and Asian countries .
9 The album went on to sell over 10,000 copies in Argentina and another 3,000 in Brazil ; overall , the album sold relatively well in Latin America and some parts of Europe , where " I Promised Myself " was a huge hit .
10 An American edition was planned for this album , and it was going to be released through Interscope Records in late 2004 .
11 However , the A - Teens were already finishing their Greatest Hits Tour in Sweden and they did n't want to promote in America as Dhani was about to release his first solo single there , so Interscope cancelled the release .

##title
Kahului Airport
##doc
0 Kahului Airport is a regional airport in the state of Hawai'i , United States , located east of the Kahului CDP in Maui County on the island of Maui near Haleakala .
1 It has offered full airport operations since 1952 .
2 Most flights into Kahului Airport originate from Daniel K. Inouye International Airport in Honolulu ; the Honolulu – Kahului corridor is one of the busiest air routes in the US , ranking 13th in 2004 with 1,632,000 passengers .
3 The airport code pays homage to aviation pioneer Bertram J. Hogg who worked for what is now Hawaiian Airlines flying aircraft ranging from eight - passenger Sikorsky S-38 amphibians to Douglas DC-3s and DC-9s into the late 1960s .
4 It is included in the Federal Aviation Administration ( FAA ) National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems for 2017 – 2021 , in which it is categorized as a medium - hub primary commercial service facility .

##title
Christian Atsu
##doc
0 Christian Atsu Twasam ( born 10 January 1992 ) is a Ghanaian professional footballer who plays for Premier League club Newcastle United , and the Ghanaian national team .
1 He primarily plays as a winger , although he has also been deployed as an attacking midfielder .
2 He began his career with Porto , also spending a season on loan at Rio Ave .
3 In 2013 , he was signed by Chelsea for £ 3.5 million , who subsequently loaned him to Vitesse Arnhem , Everton , AFC Bournemouth and Málaga .
4 After spending the 2016–17 season on loan at Newcastle United , he completed a permanent transfer to the club in May 2017 .
5 A full international with over 30 caps since his debut in 2012 , Atsu has represented Ghana at the 2014 FIFA World Cup and two Africa Cup of Nations tournaments .
6 He helped the team finish as runners - up at the 2015 Africa Cup of Nations , in which he also won Player of the Tournament and Goal of the Tournament .

##title
Joseph Octave Mousseau
##doc
0 Joseph Octave Mousseau ( April 25 , 1844 – December 13 , 1898 ) was a physician and political figure in Quebec .
1 He represented Soulanges in the House of Commons of Canada from 1891 to 1892 as an Independent member .
2 He was born in Berthier , Canada East , the son of Louis Mousseau , who was the son of Alexis Mousseau , and Sophie Duteau , dit Grandpré .
3 Mousseau was educated at Montreal and Nicolet .
4 He served on the town council for Saint - Polycarpe and also served as mayor .
5 Mousseau married Marie Rose - Avelina Cadieux .
6 He ran unsuccessfully for a seat in the House of Commons in 1887 .
7 His election to the House of Commons in 1891 was overturned in 1892 and he was defeated by James William Bain in the two by - elections which followed .
8 He was the brother of Joseph - Alfred Mousseau .
9 His son Joseph - Octave was a member of the Quebec legislative assembly .

##title
Abdul Jabar Sabet
##doc
0 Abdul Jabar Sabet is an Afghan politician .
1 In May 2006 Hamid Karzai appointed him Attorney General of Afghanistan .
2 Sabet is an ethnic Pashtun .
3 Sabet was a long time aide to former Afghan Prime Minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar .
4 After leaving Afghanistan , he worked in the U.S. for Voice of America .
5 After living in Montreal , Sabet returned to Afghanistan to work for a human rights organization , before being appointed special adviser at the Interior Ministry .
6 He was promoted to Attorney General in May 2006 .
7 Sources close to the President Hamid Karzai say that Sabet was promoted with U.S. support in exchange for giving positive comments about the Guantanamo Bay detention facility .
8 He has however been critical of the Guantanamo release policy .
9 A series of articles on former Guantanamo captives , published by the McClatchy News Service , quoted Sabet commenting that the release of Guantanamo captives seemed to be divorced from the captives ' role in the Taliban , and to be focussed largely on whether the captives complied with the camp rules .
10 In April 2007 , Sabet launched a violent raid on Tolo TV ( the country 's largest private TV chain ) for what he thought was a " distorted " report on his comments regarding the country 's judicial system .
11 Seven journalists from the TV station were taken to his office by force without warrants and severely beaten .

##title
Georg Jochmann
##doc
0 Georg Jochmann ( 11 October 1874 , in Liegnitz – 6 January 1915 , in Berlin ) was a German internist and bacteriologist , who specialized in infectious diseases .
1 In 1898 he received his medical doctorate at the University of Freiburg , and following graduation , worked as an assistant to Bernhard Fischer at the institute of hygiene in Kiel .
2 Afterwards , he worked in the department of internal medicine at Hamburg - Eppendorf Hospital under Theodor Rumpel , and at the university medical clinic in Breslau under Alfred Kast and Adolph Strümpell .
3 In 1904 he obtained his habilitation for internal medicine at the University of Breslau .
4 In 1906 he was named head of the department of infections at Rudolf - Virchow - Krankenhaus in Berlin , and four years later received the title of professor .
5 He died in 1915 at the age of 40 from spotted typhus , contracted while treating Russian prisoners of war .

##title
Mount Shinn
##doc
0 Mount Shinn is a mountain 4,661 meters in elevation , standing 6   km ( 4   miles ) southeast of Mount Tyree in the Sentinel Range , Ellsworth Mountains in Antarctica .
1 It surmounts Ramorino Glacier to the north , upper Crosswell Glacier to the northeast , Goodge Col to the southeast , and Branscomb Glacier to the south - southwest .
2 The peak was discovered on IGY reconnaissance flights in January 1958 , and named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names ( US - ACAN ) for Lieutenant Commander Conrad S. ( Gus ) Shinn , U.S. Navy , a pilot on some of these flights .
3 Shinn was pilot of the Navy R4D aircraft carrying Admiral Dufek which , on October 31 , 1956 , made the first plane landing at the geographic South Pole .
4 It had been thought to be over 4800 m high , but was re - measured in 2001 by Damien Gildea and Rodrigo Fica of the Omega Foundation , using a Trimble 5700 GPS receiver and the Australian government 's AUSPOS processing system .

##title
Dan Chupong
##doc
0 Chupong Changprung ( Thai ; ชูพงษ์ ช่างปรุง ; RTGS : Dan Chupong ) ; born March 23 , 1981 in Kalasin Province , Thailand , Thai nickname : " Deaw " เดี่ยว is a Thai martial arts film actor .
1 He is also known by his Westernized name , Dan Chupong ( the given name is alternatively spelled Choopong or Choupong , and the first name is sometimes Danny ) .
2 Starting out as part of the stunt team of martial - arts choreographer Panna Rittikrai , Chupong 's first film credit was as " Bodyguard 4 " in .
3 He then went on to leading roles in the 2004 film , Born to Fight and 2006 film Dynamite Warrior .
4 He has also appeared in Nonzee Nimibutr 's Queen of Langkasuka ( 2008 ) , Somtum ( 2008 ) , Ong Bak 2 ( uncredited ) and portrayed the main antagonist in Ong Bak 3 .
5 He graduate bachelor 's degree from Srinakarinwirot Institute of Physical Education
6 To stay prepared for his film roles , Chupong has a regular workout routine that includes running and gymnastics .
7 He took acting lessons to prepare for his role in Dynamite Warrior .

##title
Ali Akbar Moradi
##doc
0 Ali Akbar Moradi ( Kurdish ʿElî Ekber Muradî , عەلی ئەکبەر مورادی ; born 1957 ) is a well known Kurdish musician and composer .
1 He was born in Gahwareh , Kermanshah Province , Iran .
2 He started music at a very early age , and learned the Kurdish maqam repertoire and tanbur ( Kurdish lute ) under the supervision of Kurdish masters such as Mirza Sayyed Ali Kafashyan , Kaki Allah Morad Hamidi and Sayyed Vali Hosseyni .
3 He gave his first recital in 1971 in Kermanshah .
4 In 1981 , he began collaborating with the Kurdish singer Shahram Nazeri , and performed throughout Europe and North America .
5 He is an expert on the tanbur instrument , which is considered sacred in Kurdish sufi music .
6 He has performed music in New York , San Francisco and London .
7 On September 30 , 2006 , he gives a special program as part of Voices of Kurdistan in San Francisco World Music Festival , he has been appointed as one of fifty of the best musicians around the globe by a British music magazine .

##title
Calueque
##doc
0 Calueque is a town next to a dam and pumping station of the same name on the Kunene River in the Kunene Province of southern Angola .
1 The water project is linked to Ruacana , away in Namibia , where the Ruacana Power Station is .
2 This dam is one of the last landmarks along the Kunene River , prior to the Kunene becoming a border feature between Angola and Namibia .
3 A pipeline and canal extends across the border into Namibia , supplying towns as far away as Oshakati in Ovamboland with water .
4 The dam was completed in 1976 .
5 However , due to the onset of the Angolan civil war following independence , the full master plan for the scheme was not realised by the South African and Portuguese governments .

##title
Hope Town
##doc
0 Hope Town is one of the districts of the Bahamas , on the Abaco islands as well as a small village on Elbow Cay , located in Abaco .
1 The area had a population of 458 in 2010 .
2 Golf carts are the main source of transportation , and most of the supplies for the area are brought in by barge each week .
3 In Hope Town , neither cars nor golf carts are permitted in the main part of town .
4 Only bicycles and walking are permitted .
5 Cars and golf carts are permitted on the outskirts of town , however .
6 All the buildings that are built must adhere to Bahamian Architecture at the discretion of Town Planning .
7 The seat of the Hope Town District Council is in Hope Town , and most of the meetings are held there .

##title
Beijing Ducks
##doc
0 The Beijing Shougang Ducks ( simplified Chinese : 北京鸭篮球俱乐部 ) , also known as Beijing Shougang or Beijing Ducks , are a professional basketball team based in Beijing , China , which plays in the North Division of the Chinese Basketball Association .
1 The Shougang Corporation is the club 's corporate sponsor while its mascot is a duck .
2 The team was formerly known as the Beijing Jinyu Ducks or Beijing Jinyu ( 北京金隅 , běijīng jīnyü ) .
3 The name change was due to a change in corporate sponsorship .
4 This organization should not be confused with the Beijing Olympians , a different club , which was founded in 1955 .
5 For at least part of the 2003–04 CBA season , the Ducks were known as Beijing Wanfeng Aote ( 北京万丰奥特 ) .
6 Their naming rights were then assumed by the " Beijing Jinyu Group Co. , Ltd. " , a prominent construction materials conglomerate in China .

##title
Pete Ham
##doc
0 Peter William Ham ( 27 April 1947 – 24 April 1975 ) was a Welsh singer , songwriter and guitarist , best known as the lead vocalist and composer of the 1970s rock band Badfinger , whose hit songs include " No Matter What " , " Day After Day " and " Baby Blue " .
1 He also co - wrote the ballad " Without You " , a worldwide number one hit for Harry Nilsson which has become a standard song covered by hundreds of artists .
2 Ham was granted two Ivor Novello Awards related to the song in 1973 .
3 Ham committed suicide in 1975 , when he became depressed while embroiled in band - related issues , such as label and manager problems , as well as a lack of funds .

##title
The Swingle Singers
##doc
0 The Swingles are a vocal group formed in 1962 in Paris , France by Ward Swingle with Anne Germain , Claude Germain , Jeanette Baucomont , Christiane Legrand , Claudine Meunier , Jean - Claude Briodin , and Jean Cussac .
1 Until 2011 , the group consisted of eight voices : two sopranos , two altos , two tenors and two basses .
2 The French group performed and recorded typically with only a double bass and drums as accompaniment .
3 In 1973 , the original French group disbanded and Ward Swingle moved to London and hired members who debuted as Swingle II .
4 The current group performs primarily a cappella .
5 The group later performed and recorded under the name The Swingles , then The New Swingle Singers and The Swingle Singers before settling on The Swingles .
6 The group has never disbanded .
7 As individual members have left the group , remaining members have held auditions for replacements .

##title
U.S. European Command State Partnership Program
##doc
0 The United States European Command State Partnership Program ( EUCOM SPP ) , according to its own mission , is a National Guard program that " links U.S. states with designated partner countries to ... support the command ’s security cooperation objectives . "
1 Currently , 22 Partnerships exist " with former Soviet , Yugoslav and Warsaw Pact countries in the EUCOM Area of Responsibility . "
2 Becoming independent on the dissolution of the Soviet Union on December 26 , 1991 , these countries shortly requested the advice and assistance of the United States in creating new self - defense forces .
3 They had been acquired by the Soviet Union from the European Theatre of World War II .
4 The requests began among the Baltic states , notably Latvia , which had approached NATO .
5 It sent a delegation from five member countries , including the U.S. , which chose the National Guard Bureau as most appropriate spokesman , considering that Latvia could not afford a standing army .
6 EUCOM thus became the first of the six geographic Combatant Commands that make up the
7 " global SPP , " and the NG , which is divided into state - sized contingents , became the host of each state - sized new national force , typically , but not necessarily , one - to - one , totally voluntarily .
8 A country member must begin by requesting membership .
9 The very first Partnership Program was with Latvia .

##title
Oecophora bractella
##doc
0 Oecophora bractella is a species of gelechioid moth .
1 It belongs to the subfamily Oecophorinae of the concealer moth family ( Oecophoridae ) .
2 As the type species of its genus Oecophora , its affiliations and phylogeny ( which are not completely known however ) determine the delimitation of that family and subfamily .
3 It is native to Europe , where it inhabits woodland .
4 The species is not often found in the outlying regions ; in the UK for example it has only been recorded from a few patches of old - growth forest in the English Midlands ( e.g.
5 Wyre Forest ) , southern England , and southern Wales ( e.g.
6 in the Wye valley ) .
7 The adults ' wingspan is 12–16   mm .
8 Conspicuously bicolored black and yellow , they also have some iridescent blue markings on the forewings .
9 The adult moths fly from May to July depending on the location ; they are semi - diurnal and can be encountered during the day , but usually are active at dawn .
10 The caterpillars feed on dead and decaying wood , and possibly also on fungi .

##title
Tire, İzmir
##doc
0 Tire ( ) is a populous district , as well as the center town of the same district , in İzmir Province in western Turkey .
1 By excluding İzmir 's metropolitan area , it is one of the prominent districts of the province in terms of population and is largely urbanized at the rate of 55.8 % .
2 Tire 's center is situated at a distance of to the south - east from the point of departure of the traditional center of İzmir ( Konak Square in Konkak ) and lies at a distance of inland from the nearest seacoast in the Gulf of Kuşadası to its west .
3 Tire district area neighbors the district areas of Selçuk ( west ) Torbalı ( north - west ) , Bayındır ( north ) and Ödemiş ( east ) , all part of İzmir Province , while to the south it is bordered by the districts of Aydın Province .
4 The district area 's physical features are determined by the alluvial plain of Küçük Menderes River in its northern part and in its south by the mountains delimiting the parallel alluvial valley of Büyük Menderes River flowing between Aydın and the Aegean Sea .
5 There is a Jewish community .
6 Advantaged by its fertile soil and suitable climate , Tire district 's economy largely relies on production and processing of agricultural products , especially of figs , cotton , corn and other grains , cash crops like tobacco and sesame , fruits like watermelons , cherries , peaches and grenadines and dry fruits like walnuts and chestnuts .
7 Tire center has an attractive old quarter with many impressive examples of Islamic architecture , and lively Tuesday and Friday markets , where the influence of the multicultural population of the surrounding villages can be observed .
8 These two markets on two days of the week are famous across the larger region and among visitors on excursion and tourists for the handcrafted items found on sale and they attract a large customer base .
9 A yearly event that also draws crowds to Tire is one of the liveliest and the most rooted ( since 1403 ) celebrations in western Turkey of Nevruz Day on the third Sunday of every March .
10 A famous local speciality is Tire kebab .

##title
George Prévost
##doc
0 Lieutenant - General Sir George Prévost , 1st Baronet ( 19 May 1767 – 5 January 1816 ) was a British Army officer and colonial administrator .
1 Born in New Jersey , the eldest son of Genevan Augustine Prévost , he joined the British Army as a youth and became a captain in 1784 .
2 Prévost served in the West Indies during the French Revolutionary Wars and the Napoleonic Wars , and was commander of St. Vincent from 1794 to 1796 .
3 He became Lieutenant - Governor of Saint Lucia from 1798 to 1802 and Governor of Dominica from 1802 to 1805 .
4 He is best known to history for serving as both the civilian Governor General and the military Commander in Chief in British North America ( now part of Canada ) during the War of 1812 between Britain and the United States .
