##title
Extreme Makeover: Home Edition
##doc
0 Extreme Makeover : Home Edition ( EM : HE ; sometimes informally referred to as Extreme Home Makeover ) is an American reality television series providing home improvements for less fortunate families and community schools .
1 The show was hosted by former model , carpenter and veteran television personality Ty Pennington .
2 Each episode features a family that has faced some sort of recent or ongoing hardship such as a natural disaster or a family member with a life - threatening illness , in need of new hope .
3 The show 's producers coordinate with a local construction contractor , which then coordinates with various companies in the building trades for a makeover of the family 's home .
4 This includes interior , exterior and landscaping , performed in seven days while the family is on vacation ( paid for by the show 's producers ) and documented in the episode .
5 If the house is beyond repair , they replace it entirely .
6 The show 's producers and crew film set and perform the makeover but do not pay for it .
7 The materials and labor are donated .
8 Many skilled and unskilled volunteers assist in the rapid construction of the house .
9 EM : HE is considered a spin - off of Extreme Makeover , an earlier series providing personal makeovers ( often including plastic surgery ) to selected individuals .
10 Unusual for a spin - off , Home Edition outlasted its mother show by several seasons .
11 This show displays extreme changes to help recreate someone 's space .
12 However , the format differs considerably ; in the original Extreme Makeover , for instance , participants were not necessarily chosen based on any recent hardship , whereas the family 's backstory is an important component of Home Edition .
13 EM : HE also has similarities to other home renovation series such as Trading Spaces , on which Pennington was previously a key personality .
14 The series was produced by Endemol USA ( the people behind Big Brother , Fear Factor , Deal or No Deal , Wipeout , and other reality shows ) in association with Disney - ABC Television Group 's Greengrass Television .
15 The Executive Producers were Brady Connell and George Verschoor .
16 The program originally aired on Sunday evenings but was moved to Friday nights as of October 21 , 2011 .
17 Upon the airing of its final episode in series form , and for the 2012 special holiday run , it remained ABC 's last series to air solely in standard definition and never converted to a high definition or widescreen presentation .
18 On December 15 , 2011 , ABC announced that Extreme Makeover : Home Edition would end its run on January 13 , 2012 .
19 It will , however , continue to air as a special on the network .

##title
Mehmet Çetingöz
##doc
0 Mehmet Çetingöz ( born May 12 , 1991 in Şanlıurfa , Turkey ) is a Turkish wheelchair basketball player in center position .
1 He is a 4 point player competing for Beşiktaş JK wheelchair basketball team .
2 He is part of the Turkey men 's junior national wheelchair basketball team and captain of the U23 team .
3 Çetingöz became paralyzed at his right leg as a result of polio he contracted when he was four years of age .
4 He began with wheelchair basketball with fourteen in a disabled sports club in Şanlıurfa .
5 After playing eight years for Şanlıurfa Wheelchair , he was transferred in August 2013 to Beşiktaş JK , which competes in the Turkish Wheelchair Basketball Super League .
6 Çetingöz became champion with the national junior team at the 5th Fazza International Wheelchair Basketball Championships held on April 17–23 , 2013 in Dubai and was named Top Scorer .

##title
Die Haut
##doc
0 Die Haut ( German for the skin ) were an experimental German post - punk and post - rock band , who enjoyed some local success in Berlin during the 1980s and 1990s , with such records as the Nick Cave collaboration Burnin ' the Ice .
1 The only constant member was Christoph Dreher .
2 Formed as an instrumental rock quartet , many of their recordings and live performances featured an array of international guest vocalists .
3 Their last full - length album was " Spring " ( 1997 ) followed by a remix album called " Springer " ( 1998 ) .
4 At the same time the band went on hiatus , Remo Park and Christoph Dreher have continued to work as separate acts , and Jochen Arbeit with Rudi Moser joined the Berlin - based underground legend Einstürzende Neubauten .

##title
Rachel Proctor
##doc
0 Rachel Christine Proctor ( born August 11 , 1974 ) is an American country music artist .
1 Before signing to a record deal , she co - wrote Martina McBride 's 2002 single " Where Would You Be " .
2 By 2003 , Proctor had signed to BNA Records , releasing her debut single " Days Like This " that year .
3 This song , which peaked at number 24 on the country charts , was the first of four singles from her 2004 debut album Where I Belong .
4 Proctor 's only album for the label , it also produced her highest - charting single in the number 18 " Me and Emily " .
5 Although she has not charted a single since 2004 , she has written singles for Jessica Simpson and Jesse Lee .
6 Proctor has also had songs recorded by Blake Shelton , Gary Allan , Jana Kramer , Lauren Alaina , and Kenny Loggins .
7 In March 2013 Rachel signed an exclusive songwriting agreement with Big Tractor Music Publishing .
8 Big Tractor is owned by producer Scott Hendricks .

##title
Perpetual virginity of Mary
##doc
0 The perpetual virginity of Mary is a Marian doctrine , taught by the Catholic Church and held by a number of groups in Christianity , which asserts that Mary ( the mother of Jesus ) was " always a virgin , before , during and after the birth of Jesus Christ . "
1 This doctrine also proclaims that Mary had no marital relations after Jesus ' birth nor gave birth to any children other than Jesus .
2 While the Bible mentions brothers of Jesus , Catholic , Orthodox , and some traditional Protestant interpretations offer various explanations that align with the doctrine of Mary 's perpetual virginity ; that these siblings were either children of Joseph from a previous marriage , cousins of Jesus , or were closely associated with the Holy Family .
3 By the fourth century , the doctrine was widely supported by the Church Fathers , and by the seventh century it had been affirmed in a number of ecumenical councils .
4 The doctrine is part of the teaching of Catholicism and Anglo - Catholics , as well as Eastern and Oriental Orthodoxy , as expressed in their liturgies , in which they repeatedly refer to Mary as " ever virgin " ( ) .
5 The Assyrian Church of the East , which is derived from the Church of the East , also accepts the perpetual virginity of Mary by titling her the " Ever Virgin " , after the " Second Heaven " .
6 Some early Protestant reformers such as Martin Luther supported the doctrine , and founder figures of Anglicanism such as Hugh Latimer and Thomas Cranmer " followed the tradition that they had inherited by accepting Mary as ' ever virgin ' " .
7 Reformed teaching , however , largely abandoned it .
8 The doctrine of perpetual virginity is currently maintained by some Anglican and Lutheran theologians .
9 In addition , John Wesley , the founder of Methodism , affirmed the perpetual virginity of Mary .

##title
Hélé Béji
##doc
0 Hélé Béji (; born 1948 ) is a Tunisian writer .
1 The daughter of Tunisian politician Mondher Ben Ammar , she was born in Tunis , passed her Agrégation de lettres modernes and went on to teach literature at the University of Tunis .
2 She later joined UNESCO in Paris .
3 In 1998 , she founded the Collège international de Tunis .
4 She has expressed a great admiration for the author Marcel Proust and his influence can be seen in her fiction .
5 In 1983 , she received the Prix de l’Afrique méditerranéenne awarded by the Association des écrivains de langue française .
6 She has contributed to the magazines Le Débat and Esprit .
7 She is the sister of movie producer Tarak Ben Ammar .
8 Her niece Yasmine Torjeman - Besson married French politician Éric Besson .

##title
John Alexander Boyd
##doc
0 Sir John Alexander Boyd , ( April 23 , 1837 – November 23 , 1916 ) was a Canadian lawyer and judge .
1 Educated at Upper Canada College , the University of Toronto , Boyd began his career in 1860 when he was articled to David Breakenridge Read .
2 Later , his decision in Regina v. St. Catharines Milling and Lumber Company was to have a long - lasting influence on the interpretation of First Nations land claims in Canada .
3 Boyd was Chancellor of the High Court of Justice of the Province of Ontario .
4 He was appointed a Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George ( KCMG ) during the visit to Canada of TRH the Duke and Duchess of Cornwall and York ( later King George V and Queen Mary ) in October 1901 .
5 In 1903 , Boyd and William Glenholme Falconbridge were appointed to a Royal Commission to investigate charges of bribery brought forward by Robert Roswell Gamey against the Liberal Government of the time .
6 Although the commission found no proof for these allegations , the provincial Conservatives won the general election that followed two years later .

##title
Franck Piccard
##doc
0 Franck Piccard ( born 17 September 1965 ) is a French former Alpine skier .
1 A native of Les Saisies , Piccard won a total of four Alpine skiing World Cup races .
2 At the 1988 Olympics in Calgary he won a gold medal in the Super - G competition ( the first Olympic gold - medal for a French ski racer since 1968 , when Jean - Claude Killy became a three - times gold - medalist ) and a bronze medal in the downhill .
3 At the 1992 Olympics in Albertville he won a silver medal in the downhill .
4 He also could achieve a bronze - medal in the Super - G - Race at the FIS Alpine Skiing World Championships 1991 .
5 Another results in the FIS Alpine Skiing World Championships :
6 After retiring from downhill skiing , Piccard competed in long - distance cross - country skiing at the national level in 2006 – 2009 .
7 In 1988 , he was awarded the Prix de la ville de Paris by the French Academy of Sports .
8 His father gave him the name Franck in tribute to Frank Sinatra . Piccard 's siblings Leila Piccard , Ian Piccard and Jeff Piccard also competed as alpine skiers , as does his daughter Lucie .
9 Another brother , Ted Piccard , has competed in both alpine skiing and skiercross .

##title
Joy Division discography
##doc
0 The discography of English rock band Joy Division consists of two studio albums , four live albums , twelve compilation albums , three extended plays , and five singles .
1 The list does not include material performed by former members of Joy Division that was recorded as New Order ( formed by the surviving members of the band after the death of singer Ian Curtis ) or related side projects .
2 Joy Division was formed in 1976 by guitarist Bernard Sumner and bassist Peter Hook , later recruiting singer Ian Curtis and drummer Stephen Morris .
3 The band released its debut album , Unknown Pleasures , in 1979 on independent label Factory .
4 On 18 May 1980 , the eve of the band 's first American tour , Curtis was found dead in his home .
5 Unable to continue as Joy Division , the remaining members disbanded the group .
6 The band 's second album , Closer , was released two months later to critical acclaim .
7 Since then , several posthumous releases have been issued from the band .

##title
Rob James (singer)
##doc
0 Rob James ( born October 30 , 1977 ) is a Canadian singer and songwriter from Winnipeg , Manitoba and went to M.B.C.I , who is known for being a former member of the pop group McMaster & James and the seventh - place finalist in the 2006 season of Canadian Idol .
1 In 1997 , he formed McMaster & James with Luke McMaster , and released a certified Canadian Gold album with the group in 2000 , featuring their hit singles " Love Wins Everytime " , " Thank You " , " I Understand " , and " Sweet Sensation " while opening for pop artists like Christina Aguilera and ' N Sync .
2 After the group 's success faded and their album deal expired , James auditioned for Canadian Idol in 2006 .
3 James was ranked among the show 's Top 10 , becoming the first - ever finalist from the province of Manitoba .
4 He was eliminated after making it into the top 7 .
5 As a writer , James has had much success , penning singles for the original Canadian Idol , Juno - nominated Ryan Malcolm , Grammy - nominated rapper Fresh I.E. , pop / country star Jesse Labelle , and has worked with some of the industry 's most acclaimed songwriters , including Chris Perry , Randy Bachman , Jess Cates , Justin Gray , Jeremy Ruzumna and Simon Perry .

##title
Kirnitzschtal tramway
##doc
0 The Kirnitzschtal tramway , also known as the Kirnitzschtalbahn ( Kirnitzsch Valley Tramway ) , is an electric tramway in Saxony , Germany .
1 The line runs through the valley of the Kirnitzsch river in Saxon Switzerland , from the town of Bad Schandau up to the Lichtenhain Waterfall , in the municipality of Sebnitz .
2 The line is principally a tourist service , being the only tramway to serve a National Park in Germany , and uses historical rolling stock built between 1925 and 1968 .
3 The line is operated by the Oberelbische Verkehrsgesellschaft Pirna Sebnitz mbH ( OVPS ) , which translates to the Upper Elbe Public Transport Company Pirna Sebnitz Ltd.
4 This company also operates local bus services in the area around and between Pirna and Sebnitz , together with boat services on the Elbe river .

##title
Louise Faure-Favier
##doc
0 Louise Faure - Favier ( December 12 , 1870 – March 5 , 1961 ) was a French writer and aviator .
1 She is considered by some to be the first French woman to work as a professional journalist .
2 She was born Jeanne Lucie Augustine Claudia Faure - Favier in Firminy .
3 Faure - Favier travelled on the first civil aviation flight in France .
4 She developed the first official guides in France for aviation tourism .
5 With , she set a speed record for a flight between Paris and Dakar in 1919 and , in 1930 , set a speed record for the return flight .
6 She was a passenger on the first commercial night flight between Paris and London and wrote about it in the magazine L'Illustration .
7 She took part in the first live radio broadcast from a plane flying over Paris .
8 Her 1928 novel Blanche et Noir reflects her optimism about race relations in France and her belief in the civilizing influence of women .
9 Faure - Favier also wrote the first French novel about civil aviation .
10 In 1945 , she published a memoir about her friend Guillaume Apollinaire .

##title
Barry University School of Podiatric Medicine
##doc
0 The Barry University School of Podiatric Medicine is one of the nine podiatric medical schools in the United States .
1 It is located in Miami Shores , Florida .
2 The school was founded in 1985 as the first podiatric medical college to be part of a university .
3 It is one of several schools of Barry University .
4 Barry University School of Podiatric Medicine has graduated more than 1000 podiatric physicians since its inception in 1985 .
5 The Center for Community Health and Minority Medicine , the first of several medical sciences facilities for the Doctor in Podiatry and Physician Assistant Master students , began construction in 2007 .
6 A short walk west from the main campus , it is currently the new location of Barry University 's School of Podiatric medicine .
7 The school has affiliations with such Miami hospitals as : Mount Sinai Medical Center & Miami Heart Institute , Mercy Hospital , DVA Miami , North Shore Medical Center and Jackson Memorial Hospital .
8 The Dean of the school is Albert Armstrong , DPM .

##title
Khooni Khanjar
##doc
0 Khooni Khanjar ( Fighting Blade ) is a 1930 Indian silent film directed by V. Shantaram .
1 The film was a costume action drama film co - directed by Keshavrao Dhaiber .
2 It was produced by Prabhat Film Company .
3 The cinematography was by Sheikh Fattelal and Vishnupant Govind Damle .
4 The cast included Mane Pahelwan , Ganpat G. Shinde , P. Jairaj , Sakribai and Shankarrao Bhosle .
5 Shantaram had formed Prabhat Film Company in 1929 with Dhaiber , Damle and Fattelal and their first film Gopal Krishna was a big success commercially , which helped them produce five silent films in 1930 - 31 .
6 Khooni Khanjar was the first of them followed by Rani Saheba ( 1930 ) , Udaykal ( 1930 ) , Chandrasena ( 1931 ) and Zulum ( 1931 ) .

##title
Ripton (fictional town)
##doc
0 Ripton is a fictitious town in Massachusetts , United States .
1 Hugh Davis , brother of Hester A. Davis and a professor at the University of Massachusetts Amherst , sought to demonstrate and protest the ignorance of the state bureaucracy in Boston of the rural portions of the commonwealth .
2 To do so , he invented the town of Ripton .
3 He then proceeded to apply for various grants and other official assistance , and the town was allotted funds in the state budget .
4 Several checks were issued , and deposited in an escrow account , before the hoax was uncovered .
5 The funds were returned and the matter dropped .
6 In 1985 , Representatives of the town of Ripton contacted the US Air Force and invited them to situate antennas for a post - nuclear war communication system in their town .
7 Robbins Phillips , chairman of the Board of Selectmen of Ripton , stated that the antennas would make good nesting places for eagles .
8 As a protest of the issue today , some signposts in the western portion of Massachusetts still contain " directions " to Ripton .
9 Lawmakers in western Massachusetts continued to humorously reference the incident in proposed state budgets .

##title
Eva Bosáková
##doc
0 Eva Bosáková - Hlaváčková , née Věchtová ( 18 December 1931 in Mladá Boleslav – 10 November 1991 in Prague ) was a Czech gymnast whose career spanned at least from the 1954 World Championships to the 1962 World Championships .
1 Her father was also a gymnast for the Czech national team at the 1936 Berlin Olympics .
2 She and Věra Čáslavská led the Czech women 's gymnastics team to three successive World / Olympic silver medals in a row ( 1958 Worlds , 1960 Olympics , 1962 Worlds ) , establishing their nation as the foremost challengers to the dominant Soviet women 's team during that era .
3 On balance beam , where she is credited for being the first woman gymnast to compete a cartwheel ( at the 1956 Olympics ) , she was World ( 1962 ) and Olympic ( 1960 ) champion , and she was good enough on all four events combined to become All - Around silver medalist at two consecutive World Championships ( 1958 , 1962 ) .
4 After her competitive career was over , she became a member of the Czechoslovak Song and Dance Ensemble and later became a coach in her home country .

##title
Sycamore Canyon Wilderness
##doc
0 Sycamore Canyon Wilderness is a 56,000-acre ( 22,662 ha ) wilderness area in the Coconino , Kaibab and Prescott national forests in the U.S. state of Arizona .
1 Encompassing Sycamore Canyon and its surrounds from south of Williams to the confluence of Sycamore Creek with the Verde River , the wilderness is about 40 miles ( 64 km ) southwest of Flagstaff .
2 The canyon is one of several in Arizona that cut through the Mogollon Rim .
3 Relevant United States Geological Survey ( USGS ) map quadrangles are Davenport Hill , White Horse Lake , May Tank Pocket , Perkinsville , Sycamore Basin , and Clarkdale .
4 Red Rock - Secret Mountain Wilderness borders Sycamore Canyon Wilderness on the east .
5 Ring - tailed cats , black bears , mountain lions , elk , deer , rattlesnakes , scorpions , canyon wrens , hermit thrushes , and many other creatures frequent the wilderness .
6 Vegetation , which varies with elevation and the availability of water , includes stands of pine , fir , sycamore , walnut , and cottonwood .
7 The canyon walls include exposures of red sandstone , white limestone , and brown lava .
8 Parts of the wilderness are open for dispersed camping ; many trails are open for horseback riding as well as hiking .

##title
Susan Pharr
##doc
0 Susan J. Pharr ( born March 16 , 1944 ) is an academic in the field of political science , a Japanologist , and Edwin O. Reischauer Professor of Japanese Politics , Director of Reischauer Institute of Japanese Studies and the Program on U.S .- Japan Relations at Harvard University .
1 Her current research focuses on the changing nature of relations between citizens and states in Asia , and on the forces that shape civil society over time .
2 In the spring of 2008 , the Japanese government acknowledged Pharr 's life 's work by conferring the Order of the Rising Sun , Gold Rays with Neck Ribbon , which represents the third highest of eight classes associated with this award .
3 Accompanying the badge of the Order was a certificate explaining the award as recognition of the extent to which Prof . Pharr has " contributed to promoting intellectual exchange between Japan and the United States of America , and to guiding and nurturing young Japanologists . "

##title
Leone Marucci
##doc
0 Leone Marucci ( born March 28 , 1973 , Youngstown , Ohio ) is an American filmmaker , and founder of Independent Film and Media company Steelyard Pictures through which he wrote , directed and produced the 2012 film The Power of Few , which featured the ensemble cast of Christopher Walken , Christian Slater , Q'orianka Kilcher , Anthony Anderson , Jesse Bradford , Moon Bloodgood , Nicky Whelan , Devon Gearhart , Juvenile and others .
1 Through The Power of Few website , Marucci and producing partner Q'orianka Kilcher developed and delivered a ground breaking interactive experience embarked upon in 2006 .
2 From online casting to online editing , the global audience was provided original material from the film ( and an online editing system ) and invited to help create the finished film .
3 Marucci 's interactive approach was featured in The Hollywood Reporter 's article on " Digital - Do - It - Yourself . "
4 Leone Marucci is repped by Stuart Manashil at William Morris Endeavor .

##title
Ahmet Kaya
##doc
0 Ahmet Kaya ( 28 October 1957 – 16 November 2000 ) was a folk singer from Malatya , Turkey .
1 He was of mixed Kurdish - Turkish origin and often identified himself as a " Kurd of Turkey " .
2 Many of his albums broke sales records .
3 Kaya , with over 20 albums , is by far one of the most influential and controversial artists of the 20th century in Turkey who was very vocal on social and political issues ; had to flee Turkey for France and died in exile .
4 An elegy " Ya beni sararsa memleket hasreti / What if I am homesick " tells the story of his agony , suffering , longing for the people and homeland he was torn away from .
5 Many believe this led to his sudden death at a very young age .
6 Ahmet Kaya paid a huge price announcing his wish " to sing in the Kurdish language " when he was invited to stage to receive award at an award ceremony live on TV in 1999 .
7 He was declared a villain by authorities ; targeted with fabricated news as a " traitor " by newspapers and TV stations nationwide .
8 Turkish Media portrayed Kaya as " Part of the Kurdistan Worker 's Party and " with Abdullah Ocalan " as a result of his declaration of him being Kurdish .

##title
Inner Life
##doc
0 Inner Life was an American club - oriented soul studio project formed in 1979 that enjoyed success with " I 'm Caught Up ( In a One Night Love Affair ) " ( 1979 ) and " Ai n't No Mountain High Enough " ( 1981 ) .
1 Both tracks featured the vocals of Jocelyn Brown and Leroy Burgess ( formerly of Black Ivory ) .
2 Produced and arranged by Patrick Adams and engineered by Bob Blank and Joe Arlotta , the album was originally produced for executive producer Greg Carmichael , whose Red Greg Records was an early and prolific disco label based in New York .
3 They also had a minor hit on Salsoul Records in 1981 with " Knock Out ( Let 's Go Another Round ) " .

##title
Wayne Gretzky Drive
##doc
0 Wayne Gretzky Drive is a freeway in Edmonton , Alberta , Canada .
1 Originally Capilano Drive , it was officially renamed October 1 , 1999 after NHL hockey player Wayne Gretzky , as a tribute to his years with the Edmonton Oilers .
2 The same day , Wayne Gretzky 's number 99 jersey was retired at the Skyreach Centre , which lies just west of Wayne Gretzky Drive , at 118   Avenue .
3 66/75   Street is a major arterial road in east Edmonton which serves residential and industrial areas .
4 Wayne Gretzky Drive and 75   Street , both located between Whitemud Drive and Yellowhead Trail , is part of Edmonton 's eastern leg of its Inner Ring Road .
5 Wayne Gretzky Drive and 75   Street are part of a continuous roadway that runs from 41   Avenue   SW to 33   Street   NE ( Edmonton 's northeastern city limit ) and includes portions of 66   Street and Fort Road , as well as all of Manning Drive .

##title
Shihlin Electric
##doc
0 Shihlin Electric and Engineering Corporation is a company based in Taipei , Taiwan , which manufactures electrical and power transformers , switchgear , automation , controls and automotive electrical devices .
1 The technology for the manufacturing originally involved technology transfers from Mitsubishi Electric ( Japan ) and France Transfo , a Schneider Electric Company ( France ) .
2 Shihlin Electric was founded in 1955 .
3 The company is listed on the Taiwan Stock Exchange ( TSE 1503 ) , and Mitsubishi Electric ( Japan ) is a 20 % share holder .
4 Shihlin Electric , in Q1 2009 , lists 15 sales subsidiaries and over 100 distribution partners worldwide .
5 Additionally , Shihlin Electric operates manufacturing factories in Taiwan ( 3 in Hsinchu ) , Mainland China ( 10 in Xiamen , Suzhou , Wuxi , Changzhou , Fuzhou and Wuhan ) and Vietnam ( 1 in Southern Vietnam ) .

##title
Christine Razanamahasoa
##doc
0 Christine Harijaona Razanamahasoa is a Malagasy politician .
1 She served as a Minister of Justice between 2009 and 2013 , and as the president of the Malagasy National Assembly from February till May 2014 , becoming the first woman in this position .
2 Christine Razanamahasoa is a lawyer by education .
3 On 17 March 2009 , as a result of 2009 Malagasy political crisis , president Marc Ravalomanana was removed from his position , and the High Transitional Authority , led by Andry Rajoelina , was formed .
4 The High transition authority elected Rajoelina the president of Madagascar , and Albert Camille Vital became the Prime Minister and formed the government .
5 Christine Razanamahasoa became the Minister of Justice in that government .
6 On 28 October 2011 , Rajoelina dismissed the government and asked Omer Beriziky to form the new one .
7 Razanamahasoa joined the new government , and on 31 October 2013 resigned and was replaced by Florent Rakotoarisoa .
8 The reason for her resignation was that she intended to participate in forthcoming national elections .
9 In 2013 , she was elected to the National Assembly from Ambatofinandrahana District representing the MAPAR party , founded by the former president Andry Rajoelina .
10 On 5 May 2014 , the parliament elected the new president , and dismissed Razanamahasoa .
11 The High Constitutional Court later confirmed that the voting was legal .
12 She remained the deputy and the national coordinator of MAPAR .

##title
Bombtrack
##doc
0 " Bombtrack " is a song by American rap metal band Rage Against the Machine that opens their self - titled debut album .
1 Like most of Rage Against the Machine 's songs , the song 's lyrics discuss social inequality , proclaiming that " landlords and power whores " were going to " burn " .
2 The riffs were composed by Rage Against the Machine bassist Tim Commerford .
3 The song is one of three on the album in the key of F along with " Know Your Enemy " and " Fistful of Steel " .
4 Impressed by their song , Rage Against the Machine named it Bombtrack in reference to hip hop terminology where the word ' bomb ' means ' the greatest ' , making the song title literally mean ' the greatest track ' .
5 A music video was released , depicting support for the Peruvian Maoist terrorist organization , Sendero Luminoso and its leader Abimael Guzman .
6 The video clip did not appear on the group 's first home video , citing Rage 's first altered political opinion .
7 In 2003 , the video finally appeared as bonus material on their Live at the Grand Olympic Auditorium DVD .
8 The single artwork features Cuban photographer Alberto Korda 's famous image of Che Guevara , Guerrillero Heroico .
9 A mirrored version of the iconic two - tone portrait by Irish artist Jim Fitzpatrick ( T - shirt version ) .
10 Perhaps the song 's most notable appearance outside of the music industry would be its appearance in Oliver Stone 's controversial film Natural Born Killers , when Mickey breaks out of his prison cell in search of Mallory .

##title
Bound Brook (Raritan River tributary)
##doc
0 Bound Brook is a tributary of the Raritan River in Middlesex County , New Jersey , in the United States .
1 Its name comes from a boundary in an Indian deed .
2 The stream is referred to as Sacunk , a Native American name meaning " slow sluggish stream " , on early maps of the area .
3 It rises in Edison ( near Interstate 287 and County Route 501 ) and flows through the Dismal Swamp .
4 It then flows through South Plainfield and the Cedar Brook joins it southwest of Spring Lake .
5 It continues through Piscataway into New Market Pond , through Middlesex where it flows into the Green Brook at the northwest corner of Mountain View Park .
6 It gives its name to the borough of Bound Brook , New Jersey .

##title
N. C. Wyeth
##doc
0 Newell Convers Wyeth ( October 22 , 1882 – October 19 , 1945 ) , known as N. C. Wyeth , was an American artist and illustrator .
1 He was the pupil of artist Howard Pyle and became one of America 's greatest illustrators .
2 During his lifetime , Wyeth created over 3,000 paintings and illustrated 112 books , 25 of them for Scribner 's , the Scribner Classics , which is the work for which he is best known .
3 The first of these , Treasure Island , was one of his masterpieces and the proceeds paid for his studio .
4 Wyeth was a realist painter just as the camera and photography began to compete with his craft .
5 Sometimes seen as melodramatic , his illustrations were designed to be understood quickly .
6 Wyeth , who was both a painter and an illustrator , understood the difference , and said in 1908 , " Painting and illustration can not be mixed — one can not merge from one into the other . "
7 He is the father of Andrew Wyeth and the grandfather of Jamie Wyeth , both known American painters .
##labels
Andrew Wyeth, Jamie Wyeth, child(P40), [7]

##title
Urgut
##doc
0 Urgut (; ) is a town in the Samarqand Region of Uzbekistan and the capital of Urgut District .
1 It is known for the grove of plane trees , some of which are more than 1000 years old .
2 Urgut is located in mountainous areas .
3 Urgutlik ( also known as Urguti in Tajik ) people are a subgroup of ethnic Uzbeks who track their ancestry to people from a town of Urgut .
4 There are almost 500,000 people who describe themselves as Urgutlik .
5 Urgutlik people frequently use Tajik words in their daily conversation .
6 Majority of the population speak Tajik and Uzbek .
7 Urguti people are heavily involved in basic mercantile trading in their respective locations and in farming .
8 In the town craftsmanship is also well - known which has been maintained traditionally throughout the centuries .
9 Urgut 's biggest market with varied and relatively inexpensive merchandise attracts folks even from Samarkand , the capital of the Region .

##title
Kurt Tucholsky
##doc
0 Kurt Tucholsky (; 9 January 1890 – 21 December 1935 ) was a German - Jewish journalist , satirist , and writer .
1 He also wrote under the pseudonyms Kaspar Hauser ( after the historical figure ) , Peter Panter , Theobald Tiger and Ignaz Wrobel .
2 Born in Berlin - Moabit , he moved to Paris in 1924 and then to Sweden in 1929 .
3 Tucholsky was one of the most important journalists of the Weimar Republic .
4 As a politically engaged journalist and temporary co - editor of the weekly magazine Die Weltbühne he proved himself to be a social critic in the tradition of Heinrich Heine .
5 He was simultaneously a satirist , an author of satirical political revues , a songwriter and a poet .
6 He saw himself as a left - wing democrat and pacifist and warned against anti - democratic tendencies – above all in politics , the military and justice – and the threat of National Socialism .
7 His fears were confirmed when the Nazis came to power in January 1933 .
8 In May of that year he was among the authors whose works were banned as " un - German " , and burned ; he was also among the first authors and intellectuals whose German citizenship was revoked .

##title
Raymond Hermantier
##doc
0 Raymond Hermantier ( 13 January 1924 – 11 February 2005 ) was a French actor , born in Lyon , France as Raymond Maroutian .
1 Raymond Hermantier aspired to acting since the age of 17 .
2 His training was interrupted by World War II during which he served in the Free French Forces , until the liberation of Paris .
3 Decorated by General Charles de Gaulle , he resumed his acting career immediately after the end of the war .
4 Supported by André Malraux and Albert Camus , he ascended to fame at the Festival de Nîmes , France , in his role of Julius Caesar .
5 After several movies and theater successes , he was offered the Directorship of the fledgling Senegalese National Theater by the King who aspired to a world - class national theater .
6 This culminated in the National Theater of Senegal being the first African Shakespearean to tour major European capitals in 1974 .
7 This success was followed by many successful tours of Europe over the next 13 years .

##title
Siberia Governorate
##doc
0 Siberia Governorate ( ) was an administrative division ( a guberniya ) of the Tsardom of Russia and then the Russian Empire , which existed from 1708 until 1782 .
1 Its seat was in Tobolsk ( initially spelt as Tobolesk ) .
2 The governorate was located in the east of Russian Empire and bordered China in the south , Kazan Governorate in the southwest , and Archangelgorod Governorate in the northwest .
3 In the north and the east , the governorate was limited by the seas of the Arctic and Pacific Oceans .
4 In therms of the area , Siberia Governorate was by far the biggest among all the governorates , as it included areas in the Urals , Siberia , and the Russian Far East some of which were not yet even settled by Russians at the time .

##title
Oberliga Rheinland-Pfalz/Saar
##doc
0 The Oberliga Rheinland - Pfalz / Saar , formerly the Oberliga Südwest , is the highest regional football league for the Rhineland - Palatinate and Saarland states of Germany , organized by the Southwestern Regional Football Association .
1 It is the fifth tier of the German football league system .
2 It is one of fourteen Oberligas in German football , the fifth tier of the German football league system .
3 Until the introduction of the 3 .
4 Liga in 2008 it was the fourth tier of the league system , until the introduction of the Regionalligas in 1994 the third tier .
5 From January 1946 up until the creation of the Bundesliga in 1963 , the Oberliga Südwest was one of the five highest divisions in Germany .
6 The current league originates from 1978 .

##title
Michael Giacchino
##doc
0 Michael Giacchino (; born October 10 , 1967 ) is an American composer of music for films , television and video games .
1 He composed the scores to the television series Lost , Alias and Fringe , the video game series Medal of Honor and Call of Duty and many films such as The Incredibles , , Ratatouille , Star Trek , Up , Super 8 , , Star Trek Into Darkness , Dawn of the Planet of the Apes , Jurassic World , Inside Out , Zootopia , Star Trek Beyond , Doctor Strange , Rogue One , , War for the Planet of the Apes , Coco , and Incredibles 2 .
2 Giacchino has received an Emmy Award and multiple Grammy Awards , as well as a Golden Globe Award and an Academy Award for his work on Up .

##title
Upper Ammonoosuc River
##doc
0 The Upper Ammonoosuc River is a tributary of the Connecticut River that flows through Coös County in northern part of the northeastern U.S. state of New Hampshire .
1 Despite its name , the river is not an upstream portion of the Ammonoosuc River , but instead a separate tributary of the Connecticut River flowing from to the north of the Ammonoosuc .
2 The Upper Ammonoosuc rises in Pond of Safety in the town of Randolph , runs first generally north through rural portions of Berlin ( where it flows through the Godfrey Dam ) , Milan and a corner of Dummer , then west through Stark and then Northumberland where it drains into the Connecticut near the village of Groveton .
3 The end points of that course are approximately 25 air miles ( 38 km ) apart .
4 From Milan to Groveton it is fairly closely paralleled by New Hampshire Route 110 .
5 Fort Wentworth was built in 1755 at the junction of the Upper Ammonoosuc and the Connecticut Rivers ( now near the village of Groveton ) .
6 The fort was used sporadically during both the French and Indian War and the American Revolutionary War .
7 The watershed area includes the northern Crescent Range , eastern Pliny Range and the eastern and northern Pilot Range , all in the White Mountains .
8 Major tributaries of the Upper Ammonoosuc include :

##title
Boltenhagen
##doc
0 Boltenhagen is a German seaside resort in Mecklenburg - Vorpommern situated on the Baltic Sea coast 30   km east of Lübeck .
1 It offers a wide view of the Bay of Lübeck ; a 5   km stretch of a wide and sandy beach , a boardwalk , restaurants and health spas .
2 Boltenhagen is considered to be part of the German Riviera .
3 It is close to the cities of Lübeck , Wismar and Schwerin and is part of the Hamburg Metropolitan Region .
4 Because of its location it is one of the most famous German seaside resorts at the Baltic Sea .
5 A marina with fishing harbour connects to the resort at its easternmost end , offering hotels and private beaches overlooking the vast Wohlenberger Wiek , a shallow bay in between Boltenhagen and Wismar .
6 West of the town and close to the seaside lies the picturesque little castle of Gross - Schwansee , recently refurbished and converted into a luxury hotel .
7 South of it , Bothmer Mansion , a remarkable Tudor - style manor house in the nearby village of Klütz can be visited .
8 Even historically Boltenhagen has been a popular holiday resort in Eastern Germany as being the second town , where bathing wagons have been placed .
9 Today the town offers nearly 10.000 beds , also because of health reasons , the town counts as a well known and highly recommended holiday resort .

##title
Downy
##doc
0 Downy ( Lenor in Europe , Russia and Japan ) is a brand name of fabric softener produced by Procter & Gamble and sold in the United States .
1 It entered the U.S. test market in August 1960 and went nationwide in December 1961 .
2 It was also sold in the Philippines , Malaysia , Indonesia , Singapore , Thailand , Vietnam , South Korea , Egypt , Kenya and Latin America .
3 Lenor is a brand name of fabric softener and dryer sheets , also produced by Procter & Gamble , sold in Europe , Russia and Japan .
4 Lenor fabric softener had entered China in 2007 but ceased later .
5 Scent beads under the brand Downy have been sold in China since Dec. 2017 .
6 Plans to rebrand Lenor as Downy in the UK were dropped in 2002 .
7 Amy Sedaris and Tituss Burgess have been used to promote Downy / Lenor Unstoppables range in both the U.S. and the UK .
8 The commercials were filmed by Grey Advertising .

##title
Ne crois pas
##doc
0 " Ne crois pas " ( , Do n't believe ) is a song that was performed in the Eurovision Song Contest 1956 by French singer Michèle Arnaud .
1 It was the first of two Luxembourgish entry in the contest and was performed in French .
2 In contrast to most of the other entries of this Contest , the song is an up - tempo number , with Arnaud telling a friend or lover that the fact that he looks good at the moment is largely meaningless .
3 She tells him that his looks are due to his youth and that , as for the rest of humanity , he will lose his hair , gain weight and possibly lose his teeth as well .
4 Thus , she tells him that he should " take advantage of it " , rather than simply enjoying his looks at the time .
5 The song was performed sixth on the night ( following France 's Mathé Altéry with " Le temps perdu " and preceding Italy 's Franca Raimondi with " Aprite le finestre " ) .
6 As the scoreboard of this Contest has never been released , definitive statements about scores and positions are impossible to make , however the song did not win .
7 The song was accompanied at the 1956 contest by Arnaud with " Les amants de minuit " and was succeeded as Luxembourgish representative at the 1957 contest by Danièle Dupré with " Amours mortes ( tant de peine ) " .

##title
Energy and Environmental Security Initiative
##doc
0 Established in 2003 , the Energy and Environmental Security Initiative ( EESI ) is an interdisciplinary Research & Policy Institute located at the University of Colorado Law School .
1 The fundamental mission of EESI is to serve as an interdisciplinary research and policy center concerning the development and crafting of State policies , U.S. energy policies , and global responses to the world 's energy crisis ; and to facilitate the attainment of a global sustainable energy future through the innovative use of laws , policies and technology solutions .
2 In pursuit of this mission , EESI 's primary operational function is that of an enabling environment for teaching , research and policy analysis vis - à - vis the impact of laws and policies on the scientific , technological , sociopolitical , commercial , and environmental dimensions of sustainable energy .

##title
Le Ventre de Paris
##doc
0 Le Ventre de Paris ( 1873 ) is the third novel in Émile Zola 's twenty - volume series Les Rougon - Macquart .
1 It is set in and around Les Halles , the enormous , busy central market of 19th - century Paris .
2 Les Halles , rebuilt in cast iron and glass during the Second Empire was a landmark of modernity in the city , the wholesale and retail center of a thriving food industry .
3 Le Ventre de Paris ( translated into English under many variant titles but literally meaning The Belly of Paris ) is Zola 's first novel entirely on the working class .
4 The protagonist is Florent , an escaped political prisoner mistakenly arrested after the French coup of 1851 .
5 He returns to his step - brother Quenu , a charcutier and his wife Lisa Quenu ( formerly Macquart ) , with whom he finds refuge .
6 They get him a job in the market as a fish inspector .
7 After getting mixed up in an ineffectual socialist plot against the Empire , Florent is arrested and deported again .
8 Although Zola had yet to hone his mastery of working - class speech and idioms displayed to such good effect in L'Assommoir , the novel conveys a powerful atmosphere of life in the great market halls and of working class suffering .
9 There are a number of vivid descriptive passages , the most famous of which , his description of the olfactory sensations experienced upon entering a cheese shop , has become known as the " Cheese Symphony " due to its ingenious orchestral metaphors .
10 Throughout the book , the painter Claude Lantier , a relative of the Macquarts and later the protagonist of L'Œuvre ( 1886 ) - shows up to provide a semi - authorial commentary , playing the role of chorus .
11 It is an interesting and often powerful work , though not usually considered as being on a par with the novelist 's achievements later in the Rougon - Macquart cycle .

##title
Foulsyke
##doc
0 Foulsyke is a small hamlet on the boundary between the civil parishes of Holme Abbey and Holme St. Cuthbert in Cumbria , United Kingdom .
1 It is located just under one mile to the east of Pelutho , three - quarters of a mile south - east of Highlaws , and two - and - a - half miles south - east of Abbeytown .
2 Other nearby settlements include Aldoth , three - quarters of a mile to the south - east , Tarns , one - and - a - half miles to the south - west , and Beckfoot , two - and - a - half miles due east as the crow flies , or four - and - a - half miles by road .
3 Cumbria 's county town , Carlisle , is located twenty - one miles away to the north - east .

##title
German torpedo boat Kondor
##doc
0 Kondor was the fifth of six Type 23 torpedo boats built for the German Navy ( initially called the Reichsmarine and then renamed as the Kriegsmarine in 1935 ) .
1 The boat made multiple non - intervention patrols during the Spanish Civil War in the late 1930s .
2 During World War II , she played a minor role in the attack on Oslo , the capital of Norway , during the Norwegian Campaign of 1940 .
3 Kondor spent the next several months escorting minelayers as they laid minefields and damaged heavy ships back to Germany before she was transferred to France around September .
4 She started laying minefields herself that month and continued to do so for the rest of the war .
5 The boat returned to France in 1942 and helped to escort blockade runners , commerce raiders and submarines through the English Channel and the Bay of Biscay .
6 Damaged by a mine shortly before the Allied Invasion of Normandy in June 1944 , Kondor was under repair on the day of the landings .
7 Recognizing that she could not be repaired quickly , the boat was decommissioned later that month and was then further damaged by British bombers so that she was declared a constructive total loss .

##title
Cove Lake State Park
##doc
0 Cove Lake State Park is a state park in Campbell County , Tennessee , in the southeastern United States .
1 The park consists of situated around Cove Lake , an impoundment of Cove Creek created by the completion of Caryville Dam in 1936 .
2 The park 's location is adjacent to the town of Caryville and just west of Jacksboro .
3 Cove Lake is an extension of the much larger Norris Reservoir , which extends across the lower of Cove Creek downstream from Caryville Dam .
4 Cove Lake State Park was one of several state and local parks developed in the 1930s as part of the Norris Dam Project .
5 The park includes a large campground , several small walking trails , and a wildlife observation area .
6 A leg of the Cumberland Trail passes near the park 's northern boundary , connecting the park to nearby mountaintops .

##title
Across the Black Waters
##doc
0 Across the Black Waters is an English novel by the Indian writer Mulk Raj Anand first published in 1939 .
1 It describes the experience of Lalu , a sepoy in the Indian Army fighting on behalf of Britain against the Germans in France during World War I.
2 He is portrayed by the author as an innocent peasant whose poor family was evicted from their land and who only vaguely understands what the war is about .
3 The book has been described as Anand 's best work since the Untouchable .
4 In Lalu 's tragedy lied the tragedy of the Indian village and Anand dramatizes a poignant truth : to disposses any one of land is to deny him an identity .— Basavaraj Naikar
5 The book is part of a trilogy ( along with The Village and The Sword and the Sickle ) that chronicles the life of Lalu as he struggles to rise from the bottom of Indian society .
6 In the background is India 's fight for independence .
7 This book is the only Indian English novel that is set in World War I and portrays the experiences of Lalu , who only wants to reclaim the piece of land his family lost as a reward for serving .
8 But when he returns from war , he finds his family destroyed and his parents dead .
9 The novel 's larger themes are that of war and death Lalu encounters Western culture .

##title
Catholic Church in the Maldives
##doc
0 The Catholic Church in the Maldives is part of the worldwide Catholic Church , under the spiritual leadership of the Pope in Rome .
1 The Annals of the Propagation of the Faith mentions that in 1833 after the consecration of Clément Bonnand as the Vicar Apostolic of Pondicherry , he was authorized by the Holy See to send missionaries to the Maldive Islands where the Christian faith has not reached .
2 But there is not and has never been any Catholic territorial jurisdiction in the Maldives , but has been covered by the Archdiocese of Colombo in Sri Lanka since 1886 .
3 The constitution of the island does not allow citizenship of those who are not Muslims , and those found with non - Islamic religious materials can be subject to arrest .
4 It currently has the smallest amount of Catholics attending mass .

##title
Loopline Bridge
##doc
0 The Loopline Bridge ( or the Liffey Viaduct ) is a railway bridge spanning the River Liffey and several streets in Dublin , Ireland .
1 It joins rail services from south of Dublin to Connolly Station and lines north .
2 Designed by John Chaloner Smith ( engineer to the Dublin , Wicklow and Wexford Railway ) , the bridge was built between 1889 and 1891 .
3 It consists of wrought iron lattice girders on a double row of piers with five spans .
4 The viaduct is approximately six metres above street level and supports two railway tracks .
5 During original planning and construction ( in the late 19th century ) the project was subject to much opposition and controversy , because the structure blocks the view down river to The Custom House .
6 However , the bridge was deemed necessary as a rail link between north and south Dublin , and to facilitate the movement of transatlantic mail coming from Kingstown ( Dún Laoghaire ) and Queenstown ( Cobh ) .
7 100 years later , the visage of the bridge remains the subject of some debate .
8 Already arguably less attractive than some of Dublin 's other bridges , the façades of the Loopline have been used by Iarnród Éireann for billboard advertising .
9 , the company has scaled back the bridge 's use for this purpose to reduce impact on the city skyline , following input from An Bord Pleanála and Dublin City Council .
10 A prominent feature in the city landscape since 1891 , the Loopline Bridge appears in one of the most famous literary works associated with Dublin :

##title
Parks in Greater St. Louis
##doc
0 Parks in Greater St. Louis are administered by a variety of state , county , and municipal authorities .
1 The region also is home to the Gateway Arch National Park , site of the Gateway Arch , the only National Memorial in the state of Missouri .
2 Among the largest municipal parks is Forest Park , which is and is located in the city of St. Louis , although both Greensfelder County Park and Creve Coeur Park in St. Louis County are larger , at respectively .
3 St. Louis County is also the location of two large state parks , Babler State Park with and Castlewood State Park with .
4 The largest state park in the region is Meramec State Park , located near Sullivan , Missouri , with of parkland .

##title
Tōkai region
##doc
0 The is a subregion of the Chūbu region and Kansai region in Japan that runs along the Pacific Ocean .
1 The name comes from the Tōkaidō , one of the Edo Five Routes .
2 Because Tōkai is a sub - region and is not officially classified , there is some disagreement about where exactly the region begins and ends , however Japanese maps widely conclude that the region includes Shizuoka , Aichi , Gifu and Mie prefectures .
3 The largest major city in the region is Nagoya and the Chūkyō Metropolitan Area ( Nagoya Metropolitan Area ) makes up a large portion of the region and has Japan 's third strongest economy .
4 The business influence of this urban area sometimes extends out into the outlying areas of the three prefectures centered on Nagoya which are Aichi , Gifu , and Mie ; this area is sometimes referred to as the Chūkyō region .
5 Tōkai is a heavy manufacturing area and is one of the most industrial regions in Japan .
6 Its coast is lined with densely populated cities with economies that thrive on factories .
7 The Tōkai region has experienced a number of large earthquakes in the past , including the two great earthquakes in 1944 ( also known as the " Tonankai earthquake " ) and 1945 ( also known as the " Mikawa earthquake " ) .
8 Following the work of Kiyoo Mogi , it is predicted that there is a possibility that the area will be subject to a shallow magnitude 8.0 earthquake in the near future .
9 Nagoya , Shizuoka , and other large cities would be greatly damaged , with potential casualties in the tens of thousands .
10 The Coordinating Committee for Earthquake Prediction designated the region as an Area of Specific Observation in 1970 , and upgraded it to an Area of Intensified Observation in 1974 .

##title
Gloria Estefan albums discography
##doc
0 The album discography of the Cuban - American singer Gloria Estefan consists of twenty studio albums , nine compilations , and seven EPs ( combining Estefan 's releases with her band , the Miami Sound Machine , and her solo releases ) .
1 With estimated sales of 100 million of albums worldwide , she and Selena Quintanilla are the most successful female Latin crossover artists ever .
2 Although they had been recording since the mid-1970s , Estefan 's breakthrough came when Miami Sound Machine released the single " Dr.
3 Beat " in Europe in 1984 .
4 Though a major hit there , the band did n't make a commercial impact in the United States until the following year with the release of the single , " Conga " , which became a signature - song for Estefan .
5 Both of the corresponding albums ( Eyes of Innocence and Primitive Love ) were credited to Miami Sound Machine .
6 Their next album , 1987 's Let It Loose ( titled as Anything For You in Europe ) was credited to Gloria Estefan and Miami Sound Machine .
7 All further albums after 1989 's Cuts Both Ways onwards were credited solely to Estefan herself , though Miami Sound Machine continues to be her backing band and perform with her live to the present day .
8 Estefan has also recorded many albums in Spanish , and her 1993 album , Mi Tierra , is one of the most successful Spanish - language albums released in the USA .
9 The album was also an international hit and became the first album in Spain to gain a Diamond certification ( for sales in excess of 1 million copies ) .

##title
Paul Morphy
##doc
0 Paul Charles Morphy ( June 22 , 1837   – July 10 , 1884 ) was an American chess player .
1 He is considered to have been the greatest chess master of his era and an unofficial World Chess Champion .
2 A chess prodigy , he was called " The Pride and Sorrow of Chess " because he had a brilliant chess career but retired from the game while still young .
3 Bobby Fischer ranked him among the ten greatest players of all time , and described him as " perhaps the most accurate player who ever lived " .
4 Morphy was born in New Orleans to a wealthy and distinguished family .
5 He learned to play chess by simply watching games between his father and uncle .
6 His family soon recognized the boy 's talent and encouraged him to play at family gatherings , and by the age of nine he was considered to be one of the best players in the city .
7 At just twelve years of age , Morphy defeated visiting Hungarian master Johann Löwenthal in a match of three games .
8 After receiving his degree in 1857 , Morphy was not yet of legal age to practice law and found himself with free time .
9 At his uncle 's urging , he accepted an invitation to play at the First American Chess Congress in New York City .
10 After winning the tournament , which included strong players such as Alexander Meek and Louis Paulsen , Morphy was hailed as the chess champion of the United States and stayed in New York playing chess through 1857 , winning the vast majority of his games .
11 In 1858 , Morphy traveled to Europe to play European Champion Howard Staunton .
12 Morphy played almost every strong player in Europe , usually winning easily .
13 The match with Staunton never materialized , but Morphy was acclaimed by most in Europe as the world 's best player .
14 Returning to the United States in triumph , Morphy toured the major cities playing chess on his way back to New Orleans .
15 By 1859 , on returning to New Orleans , Morphy declared he was retiring from chess to begin his law career .
16 However , Morphy was never able to establish a successful law practice and ultimately lived a life of idleness , living off his family 's fortune .
17 Despite appeals from his chess admirers , Morphy never returned to the game , and died in 1884 from a stroke at the age of 47 .
##labels

##title
Ali Kuli Khan Khattak
##doc
0 Ali Kuli Khan Khattak ( Urdu : على قلى خان ; HI(M ) , is a retired Pakistani three - star rank general officer and former field commander of X Corps .
1 Prior to this field assignment , he was the chief of general staff and also directed the directorate - general of the Military Intelligence ( DGMI ) during his career .
2 Khattak was also an instructor in the National Defence University ( NDU ) before being elevated to the senior staff appointments .
3 He has been credited for foresight in predicting the dangers of terrorism and the public appraised reputation when thwarting the conspiracy hatched by infiltrated rogue officers against the government of Prime minister Benazir Bhutto .
4 He opposed the Kargil War and was notably superseded by the former Prime minister Nawaz Sharif after approving the appointment of Khattak 's course - mate , General Pervez Musharraf to four - star rank and chief of army staff .

##title
Link River
##doc
0 The Link River is a short river connecting Upper Klamath Lake to Lake Ewauna in the city of Klamath Falls in the U.S. state of Oregon .
1 Draining a basin of , the river begins at the southern end of Klamath Lake and flows a short distance to the Link River Dam and continues to the head of Lake Ewauna .
2 The " falls " from which Klamath Falls derives its name , and which in reality are best described as rapids rather than falls , are visible a short distance below the dam , though the water flow is generally insufficient to provide water flow over the rocks .
3 The Klamath River begins at the narrow southern end of Lake Ewauna and flows from there to the Pacific Ocean .
4 Before settlers came to the Klamath Basin , the Link River was known to the local Klamaths as Yulalona , meaning " back and forth . "
5 At times , strong winds blew the water upstream into Klamath Lake and partly drained the riverbed .
6 After its founding in 1867 , Klamath Falls was originally named Linkville .
7 The name was changed to Klamath Falls in 1892 – 93 .

##title
The Hurting
##doc
0 The Hurting is the debut studio album by the British rock / pop band Tears for Fears .
1 It was released on 7 March 1983 , and peaked at No .
2 1 on the UK Albums Chart in its second week of release .
3 The album was certified Gold by the BPI within three weeks of release , and reached Platinum status in January 1985 .
4 The album contains Tears For Fears ' first three hit singles – " Mad World " , " Change " , and " Pale Shelter " – all of which reached the Top 5 in the UK .
5 It also contains a new version of the band 's first single , " Suffer the Children " , which had originally been released in 1981 .
6 The album was remastered and reissued in 1999 , and included four remixes as bonus tracks and an extensive booklet with liner notes about the album 's creation .
7 A 30th Anniversary reissue was released on 21 October 2013 , in both double - CD and deluxe 4-disc boxed set editions .

##title
Jared Allen
##doc
0 Jared Scot Allen ( born April 3 , 1982 ) is a former professional American football defensive end .
1 After playing college football for Idaho State University , he was drafted by the Kansas City Chiefs of the National Football League ( NFL ) in the fourth round of the 2004 NFL Draft .
2 After four years with the Chiefs , Allen was traded to the Minnesota Vikings in exchange for three draft picks , including a first - rounder .
3 He spent six years with the Vikings before joining the Chicago Bears as a free agent in 2014 .
4 During the 2015 season , he was traded to the Carolina Panthers , with whom he played in his only career Super Bowl .
5 A five - time Pro Bowl and four - time All - Pro selection , Allen tallied 136 quarterback sacks during his 12-year career .

##title
Blank Page
##doc
0 " Blank Page " is a song recorded by American singer - songwriter Christina Aguilera , taken from her seventh studio album , Lotus ( 2012 ) .
1 It was written by Aguilera , Chris Braide and Sia Furler , with production done by Braide .
2 Aguilera had worked with Furler on her previous two albums Bionic and Burlesque , both released in 2010 .
3 Following the release of Lotus , Aguilera revealed that Furler is one of her favorite people to work with and that she is very inspiring .
4 " Blank Page " is a minimalist piano - driven ballad which received frequent comparisons to Aguilera 's 2002 single " Beautiful " .
5 It garnered strong critical acclaim from music critics , who praised its simplistic arrangement as well as Aguilera 's raw and strong vocal performance on the song .
6 Following the release of Lotus , it peaked at number 53 on the South Korea international singles chart .
7 Aguilera performed the song live for the first time at the 39th People 's Choice Awards , where she was awarded with the People 's Voice Award .

##title
Amandeep Khare
##doc
0 Amandeep Narayan Khare ( born 5 August 1997 , Durg , Madhya Pradesh now Chhattisgarh ) is an Indian cricketer who plays for Chhattisgarh cricket team .
1 In December 2015 , he scored a century for India national under-19 cricket team against Sri Lanka national under-19 cricket team and help his team to win a four - run D / L win over Sri Lanka Under-19s at the Premadasa Stadium .
2 He made his first - class debut for Chhattisgarh in the 2016–17 Ranji Trophy on 6 October 2016 .
3 He scored a century in his second match against Andhra Pradesh to help Chhattisgarh recover in their first innings .
4 He made his Twenty20 debut for Chhattisgarh in the 2016–17 Inter State Twenty-20 Tournament on 29 January 2017 .
5 He made his List A debut for Chhattisgarh in the 2016–17 Vijay Hazare Trophy on 25 February 2017 .

##title
Alberto Valenzuela Llanos
##doc
0 Alberto Valenzuela Llanos ( San Fernando , Chile , August 29 , 1869 – Santiago , Chile , July 23 , 1925 ) , was one of Chile 's greatest painters and one of the four Great Chilean Masters , along with Pedro Lira , Alfredo Valenzuela Puelma and Juan Francisco González .
1 He was a landscape painter and left an estimated 1,000 paintings .
2 Highlights of his work include paintings of the snow - topped mountains in France and views of Paris .
3 Valenzuela Llanos was a pupil of the Chilean artists Cosme San Martín and Juan Mochi , both directors of the Chilean National Museum of Fine Arts in Santiago , Chile , with Mochi having the greatest influence on Valenzuela Llanos’ work .
4 He was also taught by the Chilean romantic painter Onofre Jarpa .

##title
Samuel C. Brightman
##doc
0 Samuel C. Brightman ( 1911 – 1992 ) was a journalist , war correspondent , freelance writer and adult educator .
1 Brightman started his career with the Louisville ( KY ) Courier - Journal covering education and politics and eventually becoming their Washington correspondent .
2 In 1939 he spent seven months travelling a Europe on the verge of war , writing a series of articles for the Courier - Journal ( his last installment was written from Poland shortly before Hitler invaded ) .
3 He enlisted in the army in World War II and was assigned as a Public Relations Officer , responsible for transport , billeting , and general assistance for a group of newspaper reporters .
4 He and his collection of reporters landed on Omaha Beach on D - Day with the American forces ; Brightman 's were the first reports to reach the U.S. after the landing , despite the fact that their equipment landed nearly a mile away and there was no reliable route for their stories .
5 Brightman received a Bronze Star for his efforts .
6 After the war he took a position with the Democratic National Committee , an organization he remained with for nearly twenty years in various capacities including Deputy Director of Publicity , Director of Publicity , and managing editor of their monthly publication , The Democratic Digest , later called The Democrat .
7 He was involved in several Democratic National Conventions in the 1950s and 1960s , generating publicity , press releases , and informational brochures for the party .
8 Throughout his career he wrote extensively — columns , newsletters , essays , and speeches — on health care , the perils of aging , politics and political humor and , in his later years , on the importance of education in a democratic society and on ways to encourage civic literacy in the general population .
9 He was the founding editor of " Adult and Continuing Education Today " and the first journalist to become devoted fully to covering adult education .

##title
Young Wild Things Tour
##doc
0 The Young Wild Things Tour was a four - band fall 2007 arena concert tour by Fall Out Boy with supporting acts Gym Class Heroes , Plain White T 's , Cute Is What We Aim For , and Doug ( from November 9 on ) .
1 This is Fall Out Boy 's biggest tour to date , grossing over $ 30 million .
2 The tour sold out in five hours , with over 1.5 million tickets sold .
3 The tour was first announced on the Fall Out Boy website , but instead of the traditional method of announcing tour dates in the same release as the announcement of the tour itself , the bands chose an unusual method .
4 Fans would text a certain number and would be given a code for their state / area .
5 That code would then be entered on a website .
6 After an unknown amount of codes were entered , the tour date would be unlocked .
7 The 31-date tour was only held in America , except for two Canadian dates .
8 The tour began on October 18 and ran through December 2 .
9 Inspired by Maurice Sendak 's 1963 children 's book Where the Wild Things Are , the concert tour included sets designed by artist Rob Dobi , containing images from the book .
10 Fall Out Boy bassist Pete Wentz explained , " Where the Wild Things Are is a great narrative .
11 It encapsulates pretty much every FOB song ever written : You know , tantrums and monster islands and all . "
12 " There 's also a play on words of the young wild thing idea that everybody has with Hollywood and starlets right now . "

##title
ABBA Live
##doc
0 ABBA Live is an album of live recordings by Swedish pop group ABBA , released by Polar Music in 1986 .
1 A live album was something that many ABBA fans had demanded for several years .
2 ABBA themselves had toyed with the idea on a couple of occasions , but always decided against it .
3 Finally , four years after the members went their separate ways , a live collection was released after all .
4 The resultant album , ABBA Live , contained recordings from 1977 , 1979 and 1981 .
5 The tracks were mostly taken from ABBA ’s concerts at Wembley Arena in London in November 1979 , with a few additional songs taken from the tour of Australia in March 1977 and the Dick Cavett Meets ABBA television special , taped in April 1981 .
6 When this LP / CD was released , the band 's popularity was at an all - time low and none of the members themselves were involved in the production of the album .
7 Much to the dismay of both music critics and ABBA fans it also had 80 's synth drums overdubbed on most tracks , taking away the true live feeling of the performances .
8 Neither did it feature any of the tracks that the band had performed live on their tours but never included on any of their studio albums , such as " I Am an A " , " Get on the Carousel " , " I 'm Still Alive " , or the original live versions of the songs from the 1977 mini - musical The Girl with the Golden Hair : " Thank You for the Music " , " I Wonder ( Departure ) " and " I 'm a Marionette " , all of which had slightly different lyrics and/or musical arrangements to the subsequent studio recordings included on .
9 Several tracks had also been heavily edited , in the case of the 1979 live recording of " Does Your Mother Know " by as much as five minutes since it originally was performed on that tour as a medley with " Hole in Your Soul " .
10 ABBA Live was the first ABBA album to be simultaneously released on LP and CD , the CD having three " extra tracks " .
11 The album did not perform very well , internationally or domestically , peaking at # 49 in Sweden and only staying in the charts for two weeks .
12 It was remastered and rereleased by Polydor / Polar in 1997 , but is currently out of print .

##title
Silvan Elves
##doc
0 Silvan ( wood elves ) are a type of Elves in J.R.R.
1 Tolkien 's fictional universe of Middle - earth , mainly the Elves of Mirkwood and Lothlórien .
2 They are commonly known as Wood - elves .
3 In the First Age the Elves of Ossiriand , or Laiquendi , were also referred to as wood - elves .
4 Silvan Elves are mainly Nandor in descent but also mixed with Avari .
5 Many of them were later ruled over by a small population of social elites who were Sindar ( Grey Elves ) or even Noldor ( High Elves ) .
6 For example , Thranduil king of northern Mirkwood , as well as his son Legolas , were Sindarin Elves who ruled over a primarily Silvan population .
7 Similarly Amdír and his son Amroth , the last Sindarin prince of Lorien , were Sindar .
8 After Amroth was lost at sea , Galadriel and Celeborn came to rule over Lórien .
9 Galadriel was a High Elf who belonged to the House of Finarfin , though she was actually of mixed Vanyar / Noldor / Telerin parentage , while Celeborn was also Sindarin ( Sindar being a subset of the Teleri ) .
10 Silvan Elves are described as being less wise than other Eldar , and some of them are almost indistinguishable from the Avari , those who never joined the Great Journey .

##title
Vesper sparrow
##doc
0 The vesper sparrow ( Pooecetes gramineus ) is a medium - sized American sparrow .
1 It is the only member of the genus Pooecetes .
2 Adults have light brown upperparts and light underparts , both with darker streaking .
3 They have a white eye ring and a long dark brown tail which shows white outer feathers in flight .
4 Their breeding habitat is open grassy areas across most of North America .
5 The nest is an open cup on the ground under a clump of grass .
6 These birds migrate to the southern and central United States and Mexico .
7 These birds forage on the ground , mainly eating insects and seeds .
8 Outside the nesting season they often feed in small flocks .
9 The male sings from a higher perch , such as a shrub or fencepost , which indicates his ownership of the nesting territory .
10 The musical song begins with two pairs of repeated whistled notes and ends in a series of trills , somewhat similar to that of the song sparrow .
11 This bird 's numbers are declining in the eastern parts of its range due to habitat loss .
##labels

##title
Tiana (Disney)
##doc
0 Tiana is a main character who appears in Walt Disney Pictures ' 49th animated feature film The Princess and the Frog ( 2009 ) .
1 Created by directors Ron Clements and John Musker and animated by Mark Henn , Tiana is voiced by Anika Noni Rose as an adult , while Elizabeth M. Dampier voices the character as a child .
2 Tiana is loosely based on two princesses : Princess Emma , the heroine of E. D. Baker 's novel The Frog Princess , and the princess from the Brothers Grimm fairy tale " The Frog Prince " , which inspired Baker 's novel .
3 A hardworking waitress who dreams of opening her own restaurant , Tiana finds her progress stalled when she transforms into a frog after desperately kissing a prince who has been turned into one by an evil witch doctor .
4 The ninth Disney Princess , Tiana is the first to be of African - American heritage .
5 Tiana has been mostly positively received , with critics praising her personality and values .
6 However , the depiction of Tiana and her community has been criticized for lacking " emphasis on racial issues " .
7 The decision to depict the two main characters , Tiana and Naveen , as frogs for the majority of the movie has also caused controversy , with some saying that it is equating people of color to animals .

##title
East Asia Economic Caucus
##doc
0 The East Asia Economic Caucus ( EAEC ) or East Asia Economic Group ( EAEG ) was a regional free trade zone ( FTA ) proposed in 1997 by Malaysian Prime Minister Dr. Mahathir bin Mohamad and encompasses the Association of Southeast Asian Nations ( ASEAN ) member states , China , Japan , and the Republic of Korea .
1 Japan though refused participation due to the exclusion of the Western nations , which were already members of APEC and many other notable regional organizations in East Asia .
2 The EAEC was a reaction to ASEAN 's integration into the Asia - Pacific Economic Cooperation ( APEC ) by Dr. Mahathir , who is known for his strong Asian standpoint .
3 His suggestion apparently articulated his dissatisfaction with ASEAN joining APEC , which includes Western nations , an idea he was strongly opposed to .
4 Therefore , EAEC was basically an APEC without North America and Australia .
5 Nevertheless , it was never put into action officially .
6 Recently the ASEAN+3 rounds might be called the successor of EAEC , which prompted Malaysia to state that EAEC was a reality .
7 In 2005 , due to Japan 's support of the agreement , ASEAN Plus Three(ASEAN+3 or APT)agreed to include Australia , New Zealand , and India during the East Asia Summit .

##title
Il regalo più grande
##doc
0 " Il Regalo Più Grande " ( English : " The Greatest Gift " ) is a song by Italian singer Tiziano Ferro .
1 The song was written by Ferro for his fourth studio album , Alla Mia Età .
2 The track was released as the album 's second single on January 9 , 2009 .
3 Three different versions of the song were also recorded in Spanish under the title " El Regalo Más Grande " .
4 The first is a solo version by Ferro .
5 The second version features Anahí and Dulce María of the Mexican pop group RBD .
6 These two versions were included on the Latin American edition of A Mi Edad , the Spanish - language version of Alla Mia Età .
7 This second version served as the second Spanish single from A Mi Edad .
8 Although the single credited Anahí and Dulce María as solo acts , the Latin American edition of A Mi Edad credited RBD as the guest act in the CD itself .
9 Lastly , a third Spanish version featuring former La Oreja de Van Gogh member , Amaia Montero , was also recorded .
10 This version was included in the edition of A Mi Edad released for Spain , and served as the official Spanish - language version of the single promoted in the country .

##title
Regal Mountain
##doc
0 Regal Mountain is an eroded stratovolcano or shield volcano in the Wrangell Mountains of eastern Alaska .
1 It is located in Wrangell - Saint Elias National Park about east of Mount Blackburn , the second highest volcano in the United States , and southeast of the massive Nabesna Glacier .
2 Regal Mountain is the third highest thirteener ( a peak between 13,000 and 13,999 feet in elevation ) in Alaska , ranking just behind its neighbor , Atna Peaks .
3 Because the mountain is almost entirely covered in glaciers , no geological studies have been done , but published references state and the geological map shows that the mountain is an old eroded volcanic edifice .
4 Several major glaciers flow from the steep and heavily eroded flanks of Regal Mountain .
5 The Rohn Glacier and Regal Glacier head east and southeast to join the Nizina Glacier , while the Root Glacier flows south to join the Kennicott Glacier just above the town of McCarthy .
6 Each of those large glaciers exceeds in width , but largest of all on Regal Mountain is a massive unnamed glacier , over across , which flows northwest just over to join the mighty Nabesna .

##title
João Paulo de Silva
##doc
0 João Paulo de Leiria e Silva ( born 13 November 1964 in Luanda ) is an Angolan sport shooter .
1 He became the only sport shooter to represent Angola at the 2000 Summer Olympics , and the second from his country to do so in Olympic history ( the first being done by Paulo Morais in Atlanta 1996 ) .
2 De Silva competed for the Angolan squad in the men 's trap at the 2000 Summer Olympics through a Tripartite Commission Invitation .
3 He shuttered the lowest score in the qualifying round with 99 hits out of a possible 125 , placing him in last from a field of forty - one shooters .
4 At the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro , he competed in the men 's trap competition thanks to another Tripartite Commission invitation .
5 He finished 33rd in the qualification round and did not advance .
6 He was the oldest member of Angola 's 2016 Olympic team .

##title
Ernesto D'Alessio
##doc
0 Ernesto D'Alessio ( born Ernesto Alonso Vargas Contreras on June 3 , 1977 in Mexico City , Mexico ) is a Mexican actor and singer .
1 D'Alessio was born in Mexico City in 1977 .
2 He is son of Mexican singer and actress Lupita D'Alessio and the singer and actor Jorge Vargas .
3 Has a one older brother Jorge Francisco ( deceased ) and a younger brother , two younger half - sisters of the second marriage of his father , and a younger half - brother of the fifth marriage of his mother .
4 In 1990 his debut as an actor .
5 In 1997 starred in telenovela El alma no tiene color .
6 In 1999 played as Mateo in .
7 In 2005 starred in Contra viento y marea as main antagonist .
8 In 2006 his participated in reality show Cantando por un sueño and finished in 3rd place .
9 The same year his participated in another reality show , in Reyes de la canción and finished in 2nd place .

##title
This Little Girl of Mine
##doc
0 " This Little Girl of Mine " is a rhythm and blues single written and released as a single by Ray Charles in 1955 on the Atlantic label .
1 " This Little Girl of Mine " played off " This Little Light of Mine " , much like the previous " I Got a Woman " and the later " Hallelujah I Love Her So " played off other classic gospel hymns .
2 And much like those songs , replaced sacred lyrics with secular blues lyrics with doo - wop call and response harmonies .
3 The song was the B - side to Charles ' number - one R&B ; single , " A Fool for You " , and was a charted hit on its own , peaking at number nine on the chart .
4 The tune was re - made to top 40 pop status in 1958 by The Everly Brothers .
5 It should not be confused with the 1981 Gary U.S. Bonds hit " This Little Girl . "

##title
Tigran Petrosian
##doc
0 Tigran Vartanovich Petrosian ( June 17 , 1929   – August 13 , 1984 ) was a Soviet Armenian Grandmaster , and World Chess Champion from 1963 to 1969 .
1 He was nicknamed " Iron Tigran " due to his almost impenetrable defensive playing style , which emphasised safety above all else .
2 Petrosian was a Candidate for the World Championship on eight occasions ( 1953 , 1956 , 1959 , 1962 , 1971 , 1974 , 1977 and 1980 ) .
3 He won the World Championship in 1963 ( against Mikhail Botvinnik ) , successfully defended it in 1966—against Boris Spassky — and lost it to Spassky in 1969 .
4 Thus he was the defending World Champion or a World Championship Candidate in ten consecutive three - year cycles .
5 He won the Soviet Championship four times ( 1959 , 1961 , 1969 , and 1975 ) .
6 Petrosian is widely known for popularizing chess in Armenia .
