##title
María la del Barrio
##doc
0 María la del Barrio ( Lit : Maria of the Slums / English title : Humble Maria ) is a Mexican telenovela produced by Angelli Nesma Medina for Televisa in 1995 .
1 The series is a remake of Los Ricos También Lloran .
2 María la del barrio is considered one of the world 's most popular and successful shows ever , having been broadcast in over 180 countries .
3 It is the last part of the Trilogía de las Marías .
4 The main protagonists are Thalía and Fernando Colunga .
5 With Ludwika Paleta and Osvaldo Benavides are co - protagonists , while Itatí Cantoral is main antagonist .
6 With are stellar performances are Ana Patricia Rojo , Sebastián Ligarde , Ariel López Padilla , Mauricio Aspe , Yuliana Peniche and leading actors Ricardo Blume , Irán Eory , Carmen Salinas , Meche Barba and René Muñoz .
7 With the special participation of Aurora Molina and Manuel Saval .

##title
John R. Thurman
##doc
0 John Richardson Thurman ( October 6 , 1814 – July 24 , 1854 ) was a U.S. Representative from New York .
1 Born in New York City , Thurman graduated from Columbia University in 1835 .
2 He moved to Chestertown , Warren County and engaged in agricultural pursuits .
3 He was also involved in several businesses , including serving as a Director of the Sacket 's Harbor and Saratoga Railroad .
4 He also speculated in land , as evidenced by the fact that his widow and children sold some of their holdings to the Delaware and Hudson Railroad during its construction .
5 He held several local offices , including Associate Judge of the Warren County Court .
6 Thurman was elected as a Whig to the Thirty - first Congress ( March 4 , 1849 – March 3 , 1851 ) .
7 He declined to be a candidate for renomination in 1850 .
8 After leaving Congress Thurman returned to managing his farm and other interests .
9 He died at his home near Friends Lake in Chestertown on July 24 , 1854 .
10 He was interred in the family cemetery .
11 He was reinterred in Oakwood Cemetery , Troy , New York .

##title
Paul Beliën
##doc
0 Paul Beliën ( born 1959 ) , is a Flemish Belgian journalist , author and founder of the far - right blog The Brussels Journal .
1 Beliën is a master of law with specialisations in European and social security law from the University of Ghent and has a PhD in international studies from the University of Buckingham .
2 He is vice president of the International Free Press Society and a senior editor at the Hudson Institute .
3 He has written in a large number of international publications .
4 He is an advocate of Flemish independence , free trade and is an opponent of abortion , euthanasia and gay marriage .
5 He is a strong Americophile and has been actively opposed to immigration into Europe by Islamic fundamentalists .
6 Beliën published a book about the political history of Belgium , and what he sees as parallels in the creation of the European Union in A Throne in Brussels .
7 Beliën is married to Alexandra Colen , a former member of the Belgian Federal Parliament , and the political party Vlaams Belang .
8 They have homeschooled all of their children .

##title
Schizoanalysis
##doc
0 Schizoanalysis (; schizo- from Greek σχίζειν skhizein , meaning " to split " ) is a concept created by philosopher Gilles Deleuze and psychoanalyst Félix Guattari and first expounded in their book Anti - Oedipus ( 1972 ) .
1 Its formulation was continued in their follow - up work , A Thousand Plateaus .
2 Schizoanalysis acquires many different definitions during the course of its development in their collaborative work and individually in the work of Guattari .
3 In Chaosmosis , Guattari explains that " rather than moving in the direction of reductionist modifications which simplify the complex " , schizoanalysis " will work towards its complexification , its processual enrichment , towards the consistency of its virtual lines of bifurcation and differentiation , in short towards its ontological heterogeneity " .

##title
Winnebago War
##doc
0 The Winnebago War , also known as the Winnebago Uprising , was a brief conflict that took place in 1827 in the Upper Mississippi River region of the United States , primarily in what is now the state of Wisconsin .
1 Not quite a war , the hostilities were limited to a few attacks on American civilians by a portion of the Winnebago ( or Ho - Chunk ) Native American tribe .
2 The Ho - Chunks were reacting to a wave of lead miners trespassing on their lands , and to false rumors that the United States had sent two Ho - Chunk prisoners to a rival tribe for execution .
3 Most Native Americans in the region decided against joining the uprising , and so the conflict ended after U.S. officials responded with a show of military force .
4 Ho - Chunk chiefs surrendered eight men who had participated in the violence , including Red Bird , who American officials believed to be the ringleader .
5 Red Bird died in prison in 1828 while awaiting trial ; two other men convicted of murder were pardoned by President John Quincy Adams and released .
6 As a result of the war , the Ho - Chunk tribe was compelled to cede the lead mining region to the United States .
7 The Americans also increased their military presence on the frontier , building Fort Winnebago and reoccupying two other abandoned forts .
8 The conflict convinced some officials that Americans and Indians could not live peaceably together , and that the Natives should be compelled to move westward , a policy known as Indian removal .
9 The Winnebago War preceded the larger Black Hawk War of 1832 , which involved many of the same people and concerned similar issues .

##title
Breakout (video game)
##doc
0 Breakout is an arcade game developed and published by Atari , Inc. , released on May 13 , 1976 .
1 It was conceptualized by Nolan Bushnell and Steve Bristow , influenced by the 1972 Atari arcade game Pong , and built by Steve Wozniak aided by Steve Jobs .
2 Breakout was the basis and inspiration for certain aspects of the Apple II personal computer .
3 The game was ported to the Atari 2600 and was followed by a 1978 sequel , Super Breakout , which four years later became the pack - in game for the Atari 5200 console .
4 Breakout spawned an entire genre of Breakout clones , and the concept found new legs with Taito 's 1986 Arkanoid which itself found dozens of imitators .
5 In Breakout , a layer of bricks lines the top third of the screen .
6 A ball travels across the screen , bouncing off the top and side walls of the screen .
7 When a brick is hit , the ball bounces away and the brick is destroyed .
8 The player loses a turn when the ball touches the bottom of the screen .
9 To prevent this from happening , the player has a movable paddle to bounce the ball upward , keeping it in play .

##title
Liverpool Neurological Infectious Diseases Course
##doc
0 The Liverpool Neurological Infectious Diseases Course ( or NeuroID ) is an annual two - day course aimed at medical professionals and students with an interest in neurological infectious diseases .
1 The course is organised by the Liverpool Brain Infections Group , a division of the Institute of Infection and Global Health at the University of Liverpool , in collaboration with the Walton Centre NHS Foundation Trust , Alder Hey Children ’s NHS Trust , Royal Liverpool University Hospital , and Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine , and is chaired by the neurologist Tom Solomon .
2 It takes place during May at the historic Liverpool Medical Institution , in Liverpool , UK .
3 A variety of both national and international speakers contribute to a programme which covers clinical aspects of common central nervous system infections such as meningitis and encephalitis , as well as rarer neurological infections and talks on recent advances in related research .
4 The course is accredited by the UK Royal College of Physicians , and attracts delegates from many countries worldwide .

##title
Outline of South Sudan
##doc
0 The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to South Sudan :
1 South Sudan – landlocked country in east - central Africa that is part of the United Nations subregion of Eastern Africa .
2 It previously known as Southern Sudan .
3 It is located south of Sudan , and includes the vast swamp region of the Sudd , formed by the White Nile and known locally as the Bahr al Jabal .
4 South Sudan became an independent state on 9 July 2011 , following a referendum that passed with 98.83 % of the vote .
5 It is a United Nations member state , a member state of the African Union , and a member state of the Intergovernmental Authority on Development .
6 In July 2012 , South Sudan signed the Geneva Conventions .
7 Its current capital is Juba , which is also its largest city .
8 The capital city is planned to be changed to the more centrally located Ramciel in the future .

##title
Your Disco Needs You
##doc
0 " Your Disco Needs You " is a song performed by Australian recording artist and songwriter Kylie Minogue , taken from her seventh studio album Light Years ( 2000 ) .
1 The song was written by Minogue , Guy Chambers and Robbie Williams and produced by Chambers and Steve Power .
2 Lyrically , " Your Disco Needs You " talks about the power of disco music .
3 The song peaked inside the top forty in Australia , Switzerland and Germany .
4 Hugely popular as an album track , it was never released as a single in the United Kingdom , but charted at # 152 on the basis of import sales .
5 Minogue has also performed the song on most of her 2000 and onward tours , including On a Night Like This Tour , , KylieX2008 , For You , For Me Tour , Kiss Me Once Tour , and most recently on her Kylie Summer 2015 Tour .

##title
Dieudonné Gnammankou
##doc
0 Dieudonné Gnammankou ( born 1963 ) is a Beninese historian and translator .
1 Gnammankou was born in 1963 in Benin .
2 He studied in the former Soviet Union , earning a degree from the Patrice Lumumba University in Moscow .
3 Gnammankou 's work has centered on African studies and the history of the African Diaspora .
4 In 1996 , he published a seminal biography of the Russian military leader Abram Petrovich Gannibal .
5 The Russian translation coincided with the 1999 bicentennial anniversary of the birth of the writer Alexander Pushkin , Gannibal 's great - grandson .
6 Gnammankou 's research , together with that of Hugh Barnes , conclusively established that Gannibal was born in Logone - Birni , Central Africa , in an area bordering Lake Chad , nowadays Cameroon .

##title
Anthony Steel (actor)
##doc
0 Anthony Maitland Steel ( 21 May 1920 – 21 March 2001 ) was an English actor and singer best known for his appearances in British war films of the 1950s such as The Wooden Horse ( 1950 ) , and his marriage to Anita Ekberg .
1 He was described as " a glorious throwback to the Golden Age of Empire ... the perfect imperial actor , born out of his time , blue - eyed , square - jawed , clean - cut . "
2 As another writer put it , " whenever a chunky dependable hero was required to portray grace under pressure in wartime or the concerns of a game warden in a remote corner of the empire , Steel was sure to be called upon . "

##title
Ost Autobahn
##doc
0 The ( Austrian ) Ost Autobahn A4 or " Eastern Motorway " is part of the European route E60 and goes from Vienna to the town of Nickelsdorf , on the Hungarian border .
1 The road begins at the A23 at the Prater junction in Vienna , travels through Simmering , Schwechat , Vienna International Airport , Fischamend , Bruck an der Leitha , Parndorf , Weiden am See and Mönchhof to the border town of Nickelsdorf .
2 Crossing the border into Hegyeshalom , the road becomes the Hungarian M1 motorway which then continues on to Budapest .
3 The road is 66   km long .
4 During the overflow of asylum seekers traveling from Hungary during September 2015 , the highway was closed intermittently preventing the traffic between Hungary and Austria , and it was reported that Austrian army was deployed on the border .

##title
List of colleges and universities in Connecticut
##doc
0 The following is a list of colleges and universities in the U.S. state of Connecticut .
1 This list includes all schools that grant degrees at an associates level or higher , and are either accredited or in the process of accreditation by a recognized accrediting agency .
2 The state 's flagship public university is the University of Connecticut , which is also the largest school in the state .
3 The remainder of the state 's public institutions constitute the Connecticut State Colleges & Universities , comprising four state universities , twelve community colleges , and an online school , Charter Oak State College .
4 Connecticut is also the home of one of the five federally - run service academies , the United States Coast Guard Academy .
5 The oldest college in the state , founded in 1701 , is Yale University , one of the most prestigious schools in the world .

##title
Angleton High School
##doc
0 Angleton High School is a public high school located in the city of Angleton , Texas ( United States ) in Brazoria County .
1 It is classified as a 5A school by the UIL .
2 It is a part of the Angleton Independent School District located in south central Brazoria County .
3 In 2015 , the school was rated " Met Standard " by the Texas Education Agency .
4 Several previous school locations were destroyed by hurricanes .
5 The high school was once located in what is now Central Elementary , as well as the former Angleton Intermediate School .
6 The recently built high school is located at 1 Campus Dr. on the outskirts of Angleton .
7 The varsity football stadium and baseball field is located next to Angleton High School .
8 Angleton ISD serves Angleton as well as the Village of Bonney , parts of the unincorporated area of Rosharon , and the unincorporated areas of Chocolate Bayou , Lochridge , Otey , and Sandy Point .

##title
Can't Take My Eyes Off You
##doc
0 " Ca n't Take My Eyes Off You " is a 1967 single credited to Frankie Valli .
1 The song was among his biggest hits , earning a gold record and reaching No .
2 2 on the Billboard Hot 100 for a week , stuck behind " Windy " by The Association .
3 It was co - written by producer Bob Crewe and Bob Gaudio , a bandmate of Valli 's in The Four Seasons .
4 It was Valli 's biggest solo hit until he hit # 1 in 1974 with " My Eyes Adored You " .
5 " Ca n't Take My Eyes Off You " has had hundreds of cover versions , many of which have been on the charts in different countries .
6 The song is a staple of television and film soundtracks , even being featured as part of the plot of some films , such as when the lead characters sing or arrange their own version of the song .
7 Its chorus has also become a popular football chant , with supporters of various teams inserting their club 's name or a popular player 's name into the beat .
8 The Valli version was also used by NASA as a wake - up song on the STS-126 space shuttle mission , to celebrate the anniversary of astronaut Christopher Ferguson , one of the mission 's crew members .

##title
War of the Quadruple Alliance
##doc
0 The War of the Quadruple Alliance ( 1717 – 1720 ) was a result of the ambitions of Bourbon King Philip V of Spain , his wife , Elisabeth Farnese , and his chief minister Giulio Alberoni to retake territories in Italy lost to the Habsburgs in Vienna , and perhaps even to claim the French throne .
1 It saw the defeat of Spain by an alliance of Britain , France , Austria ( then a state of the Holy Roman Empire ) , and the Dutch Republic .
2 Savoy later joined the coalition as the fifth ally .
3 Although fighting began as early as 1717 , war was not formally declared until December 1718 .
4 It was brought to an end by the Treaty of The Hague in 1720 .

##title
Vase de Noces
##doc
0 Vase de Noces ( also known as Wedding Trough and The Pig Fucking Movie ) a 1974 Belgian avant - garde art exploitation film directed by Thierry Zéno and starring Dominique Garny .
1 The film deals openly , and sometimes graphically , with zoophilia .
2 It features both real and simulated animal killings and coprophagia , and has been labeled obscene by many sources , notably by the OFLC of Australia .
3 The film was banned in Australia by the Australian Classification Board in the mid 1970s with two failed attempts , according to the Australian Classification Board .
4 The film went before the Australian Classification Board on April 1 , 1977 , and was banned again for the third time .
5 The ban status on the film in Australia has remained largely unchanged since then , due to in part that the film violates Australian obscenity laws .

##title
O'Shaughnessy Dam (Ohio)
##doc
0 The O'Shaughnessy Dam is located on the Scioto River near Dublin , Ohio , United States .
1 The dam forms O'Shaughnessy Reservoir , which is a major source of drinking water for the city of Columbus .
2 It was completed in 1925 following recommendations of then superintendent Jerry O'Shaughnessy ( for whom the dam was named ) .
3 At the time , the reservoir was described as " the finest inland waterway in the United States . "
4 Located upstream of the smaller Griggs Dam , it provides a large area for various forms of recreation in addition to its water supply duties .
5 The reservoir holds over a surface area of .
6 The Columbus Zoo and Aquarium is located on the east bank of the reservoir , near the dam .
7 In 1990 , the dam was listed on the National Register of Historic Places .

##title
Clark Lake (Gogebic County, Michigan)
##doc
0 Clark Lake is a lake located in Gogebic County in the U.S. state of Michigan .
1 Clark Lake is one of about two dozen clear , clean lakes located in the Sylvania Wilderness of Ottawa National Forest a few miles ( 6 to 8   km ) to the west of the town of Watersmeet .
2 The shoreline is undeveloped except for a picnic area and boat launch at the northern end .
3 The lake possesses several islands and numerous bays and coves .
4 Large boulders strewn about the shoreline and lake bed add to the scenic beauty of this lake .
5 It is not uncommon to see nesting loons and eagles around the lake 's islands , and black bear and wolves inhabit the old - growth forest around the lake .
6 The total surface area of the lake is , with maximum depths of .
7 Like all lakes in Sylvania , Clark Lake has numerous special regulations designed to protect and ensure its wilderness quality for future generations .
8 No motorized watercraft are allowed , and a catch and release policy is in place for bass species .

##title
Zabiele, Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship
##doc
0 Zabiele ( ) is a village in the administrative district of Gmina Wielbark , within Szczytno County , Warmian - Masurian Voivodeship , in northern Poland .
1 It lies approximately north - east of Wielbark , south of Szczytno , and south - east of the regional capital Olsztyn .
2 Before 1945 the area was part of Germany ( East Prussia ) .
3 In the East Prussian plebiscite of 1920 , which was largely boycotted by ethnic Poles , the inhabitants voted to remain in Germany .
4 After World War II the region was placed under Polish administration by the Potsdam Agreement under territorial changes demanded by the Soviet Union .
5 Most Germans fled or were expelled and replaced with Poles expelled from the Polish areas annexed by the Soviet Union or Ukrainians forced to settle in the area through Operation Vistula in 1947 .

##title
Vineeth Sreenivasan
##doc
0 Vineeth Sreenivasan ( born 1 October 1985 ) is an Indian playback singer , actor , director , producer and screenwriter , who works in Malayalam cinema .
1 Vineeth is son of the actor and screenwriter Sreenivasan .
2 He made his film debut in 2003 as a playback singer with the song " Kasavinte Thattamittu " from Kilichundan Mampazham , and later also worked in music albums .
3 Vineeth made his acting debut in Cycle ( 2008 ) , and since then he has acted in numerous films .
4 His directorial debut was in 2010 with Malarvaadi Arts Club , also written by him .
5 He scripted and directed the film Thira in 2013 , which introduced his younger brother Dhyan Sreenivasan as an actor .
6 Vineeth 's second directorial venture Thattathin Marayathu ( 2012 ) became one of the highest grossing films of 2012 .
7 His first script for another director was Oru Vadakkan Selfie ( 2015 ) , directed by G. Pajith .
8 His most recent directorial was Jacobinte Swargarajyam ( 2016 ) .
9 Vineeth established the film production house named Habit of Life and produced its debut film Aanandam in 2017 .

##title
Jimmy Frise
##doc
0 The Canadian cartoonist James Llewellyn " Jimmy " Frise ( , 16 October 1891   – 13 June 1948 ) is best known for his work on the comic strip Birdseye and his illustrations of humorous prose pieces by Greg Clark .
1 Born in Scugog Island , Ontario , Frise moved to Toronto at 19 and found illustration work on the Toronto Stars Star Weekly supplement .
2 His left hand was severely injured at the Battle of Vimy Ridge in 1917 during World War   I , but his drawing hand was unhurt , and he continued cartooning at the Star upon his return .
3 In 1919 he began his first weekly comic strip , Life 's Little Comedies , which evolved into the rural - centred humorous Birdseye in 1923 .
4 He moved to the Montreal Standard in 1947 , but as the Star kept publication rights to Birdseye Center , Frise continued it as Juniper Junction with strongly similar characters and situations .
5 Doug Wright took over the strip after Frise 's sudden death from a heart attack in 1948 , and it went on to become the longest - running strip in English - Canadian comics history .

##title
Aspren
##doc
0 Aspren or Asprenas ( ) was a 1st - century Christian saint and venerated as the first Bishop of Naples .
1 Aspren lived at the end of the 1st century and in the early 2nd century , as confirmed by archaeological studies regarding the early Neapolitan Church as well as the fact that " Aspren " was a common name during the days of the Roman Republic and the early years of the Roman Empire and afterwards fell into disuse .
2 The Marble Calendar of Naples ( Calendario Marmoreo di Napoli ) attests to Aspren 's existence and the fact that he lived during the reigns of Trajan and Hadrian ; Aspren 's episcopate is stated as lasting twenty - three years .
3 Nothing is known of his life , but an ancient legend holds that Saint Peter , on his way to Rome , stopped at Naples and converted an old woman ( identified as Candida the Elder ) after he cured her of an illness .
4 Numerous other converts to Christianity were made during this time in Naples , including Aspren , who was converted either by Peter or Candida herself and who had also been ill .
5 The legend holds that Peter consecrated Aspren as bishop of Naples and asked him to construct the oratory of Santa Maria del Principio , which would form the basis for the basilica of Santa Restituta ; San Pietro ad Aram was also said to have been built during this time .

##title
Jefferson Madeira
##doc
0 Jefferson Madeira da Silva , or simply Jefferson Madeira ( born 15 February 1988 ) is a Brazilian football forward playing with Duque de Caxias
1 Born in Duque de Caxias , Madeira started his career playing with Sport Recife in 2007 making his debut in the Campeonato Brasileiro Série A.
2 After loan spells with Metropolitano and Treze during 2008 , he joined on January 2009 FK Teleoptik - a club owned by FK Partizan Belgrade - playing in the 2008 – 09 Serbian League Belgrade playing along compatriots Washington Santana da Silva , Alex dos Santos Gonçalves and Elton Martins , helping Teleoptik to finish 2nd in the 2008 – 09 Serbian League Belgrade , one of Serbian 3rd tiers , thus earning promotion to the 2009 – 10 Serbian First League .
3 In summer 2009 he returned to Brazil and played until the end of the year with Olaria , before returning to Sport Recife .

##title
Navy, Army and Air Force Institutes
##doc
0 The Navy , Army and Air Force Institutes ( NAAFI ) is an organisation created by the British government in 1921 to run recreational establishments needed by the British Armed Forces , and to sell goods to servicemen and their families .
1 It runs clubs , bars , shops , supermarkets , launderettes , restaurants , cafés and other facilities on most British military bases and also canteens on board Royal Navy ships .
2 Commissioned officers are not usually supposed to use the NAAFI clubs and bars , since their messes provide these facilities and their entry , except on official business , is considered to be an intrusion into junior ranks ' private lives .
3 NAAFI personnel serving aboard ship are part of the Naval Canteen Service ( NCS ) , wear naval uniform and have action stations , but remain ordinary civilians .
4 NAAFI personnel can also join the Expeditionary Force Institutes ( EFI ) , which provides NAAFI facilities in war zones .
5 EFI personnel are members of the Territorial Army serving on special engagements , bear ranks and wear uniform .
6 NCS personnel can similarly volunteer to join the Royal Navy when it goes on active service .
7 Petty Officer John Leake , NCS canteen manager in HMS Ardent , was awarded the Distinguished Service Medal ( DSM ) in the 1982 Falklands War for his courage while manning a machine gun .

##title
Anatoly Chubais
##doc
0 Anatoly Borisovich Chubais (; born 16 June 1955 ) is a Russian politician and businessman who was responsible for privatization in Russia as an influential member of Boris Yeltsin 's administration in the early 1990s .
1 During this period , he was a key figure in introducing market economy and the principles of private ownership to Russia after the fall of the Soviet Union .
2 From 1998 to 2008 , he headed the state - owned electrical power monopoly RAO UES .
3 A 2004 survey conducted by PricewaterhouseCoopers and the Financial Times named him the world 's 54th most respected business leader .
4 Currently , he is the head of the Russian Nanotechnology Corporation ( RUSNANO ) .
5 He has been a member of the Advisory Council for JPMorgan Chase since September 2008 and a member of global board of advisers at the Council on Foreign Relations ( CFR ) since October 2012 .

##title
List of Property Brothers episodes
##doc
0 Property Brothers is a Canadian reality television series that is produced by Cineflix .
1 It has aired on W Network and HGTV Canada in Canada and on HGTV in the United States .
2 The series features identical twin brothers Jonathan Scott and Drew Scott ( born April 28 , 1978 ) who help home buyers to purchase and renovate " fixer - uppers . "
3 Property Brothers debuted on the W Network on January 4 , 2011 , and aired on the channel until its owner , Corus Entertainment , decided to shift the channel 's focus to more dramatic content .
4 Starting with 2017/2018 broadcast season , the show began to be broadcast on HGTV Canada in its country of origin .
5 It airs on HGTV in the United States , and with other affiliates in over 150 other countries .
6 The show is also carried on streaming services such as Netflix and Amazon Video .

##title
Nikos Aliagas
##doc
0 Nikos Aliagas ( / Níkos Aliágas ; born Νικόλαος Αλιάγας / Nikólaos Aliágas on 13 May 1969 in Paris ) is a Greek - French journalist and entertainer , known for being the host of the French reality program named Star Academy .
1 His Greek parents are Andreas and Harula Aliagas .
2 One of his parents came from the area of Stamna in Aetolia - Acarnania in Greece .
3 He lived between France and Greece during childhood .
4 He was a guest star on a Greek program Koita ti Ekanes in late-2003 and featured clips from Star Academy .
5 He has published a book called " I was born Greek : The mythology or The school of life " ( ) .
6 He was the presenter of a show on Alpha TV called " Gros Plan " where he met international stars like Celine Dion , Jean Paul Gaultier , Sylvester Stallone and Helena Paparizou .
7 He 's the French presenter of .
8 He speaks five languages ( as of 2003 ) including English .

##title
Luis Roche
##doc
0 Luis Roche was an important Venezuelan urbanist and was the Venezuelan ambassador to Argentina .
1 He was also an amateur film director .
2 In the 1930s , Roche advocated for the redesign of Caracas , to include developed corridors to a multi - purpose center .
3 His suggestion involved a 36-meter - wide avenue based on Avenue des Champs - Élysées .
4 He was responsible in great measure for the development of Caracas ' east side during the 1940s .
5 He contributed to the development of neighborhoods such as La Castellana , Altamira and La Florida .
6 Roche was a relevant diplomatic figure as well , being appointed as Venezuela 's ambassador to Argentina .
7 He married a Colombian / French lady by the name of Beatrice Dugand , with whom he had four children , Beatrice Roche , Lilianne Roche , Marcel Roche and Luis Armando Roche .
8 An important avenue in Altamira ( Caracas ) bears the name Luis Roche in his honor .

##title
Beibu Gulf Economic Rim
##doc
0 The Beibu Gulf Economic Rim or Beibu Economic Belt ( ) also known as Gulf of Tonkin Economic Belt in ( Vietnamese : Vành đai kinh tế vịnh Bắc Bộ ) defines the economic region or rim surrounding around China 's southwestern coastal region and cities around the Gulf of Tonkin .
1 The region is part of Chinese government 's " Go West " strategy , to boost its less developed western regions .
2 The implementation of the campaign , has resulted in many construction projects in cities on the Beibu Gulf Rim , especially in Guangxi .
3 The Beibu Gulf economic rim has emerged as a new highlight of China - ASEAN cooperation , especially between Vietnam , who is also cooperating in this economic zone .
4 It covers Guangdong , Hainan and Guangxi , and northern and central Vietnam .

##title
Gujranwala
##doc
0 Gujranwala ( Punjabi , ) is a city in Punjab , Pakistan , that is located north of the nearby provincial capital of Lahore .
1 The city is Pakistan 's 7th most - populous metropolitan area , and its 5th most populous city proper .
2 Founded in the 18th century , Gujranwala is a relatively modern town compared to the many nearby millennia - old cities of northern Punjab .
3 The city served as the capital of the Sukerchakia Misl state between 1763 and 1799 , and is the birthplace of the founder of the Sikh Empire , Maharaja Ranjit Singh .
4 Gujranwala is now Pakistan 's third largest industrial centre after Karachi and Faisalabad , and contributes 5 % of Pakistan 's national GDP .
5 The city is part of a network of large urban centres in north - east Punjab province that forms one of Pakistan 's mostly highly industrialized regions .
6 Along with the nearby cities of Sialkot and Gujrat , Gujranwala forms part of the so - called Golden Triangle of industrial cities with export - oriented economies .

##title
Chopin and his Europe
##doc
0 The International Music Festival ‘ Chopin and his Europe’ – an international music festival organised in Warsaw since 2005 by the Fryderyk Chopin Institute , presenting European music within the context of its links with the life and work of the Polish pianist , composer and teacher Fryderyk Chopin ( 1810 – 1849 ) .
1 The project is realised as part of the government programme ‘ Fryderyk Chopin Heritage 2010’ .
2 It is one of the annual cultural events of the summer in Poland , devised by artistic director Stanisław Leszczyński .
3 One important strand to the festival programme is historical performance – presenting works as they were originally heard , on period pianos in the possession of the Fryderyk Chopin Institute : an Erard from 1849 , a Pleyel from 1846 and a Graf ( a copy of an instrument from c. 1819 ) .
4 The festival is organised in collaboration with the Warsaw Philharmonic , Teatr Wielki – Polish National Opera and Polish Radio II .
5 Each year , the invited guests include performers from around the world , many of whom have a special connection with the festival , including Marta Argerich , Nelson Goerner , Dina Yoffe , Tobias Koch , Ivo Pogorelich , Garrick Ohlsson and Jan Lisiecki .
6 The festival also features performances by finalists and other participants in the Chopin Competition .

##title
Philippine Commission
##doc
0 The Philippine Commission was the name of two bodies , both appointed by the President of the United States to assist with governing the Philippines .
1 The first Philippine Commission was appointed by President William McKinley on January 20 , 1899 to make recommendations .
2 The second Philippine Commission , also known as the Taft Commission , was a body appointed by the President to exercise legislative and limited executive powers in the Philippines .
3 It was first appointed by President McKinley in 1900 under his executive authority .
4 The Philippine Organic Act was passed by the United States Congress in 1902 ; this enshrined into law the Commission 's legislative and executive authority .
5 As stipulated in the Philippine Organic Act , the bicameral Philippine Legislature was established in 1907 , with the Commission as the upper house and the elected Philippine Assembly acting as lower house .
6 The Jones Act of 1916 ended the Commission , replacing it with an elected Philippine Senate as the Legislature 's upper house .

##title
Leonessa
##doc
0 Leonessa is a town and comune in the far northeastern part of the Province of Rieti in the Lazio region of central Italy .
1 Its population in 2008 was around 2,700 .
2 Situated in a small plain at the foot of Mt.
3 Terminillo , one of the highest mountains of the Apennine range , in the winter Leonessa is known mostly as a low - key staging center for the ski slopes of the Terminillo , and in the summer as a weekend vacation town frequented for the most part by Romans with local roots .
4 Historically , the town is known mostly as the birthplace of St. Giuseppe di Leonessa .
5 Until 1927 it was part of the province of L'Aquila .
6 The town suffered one of the worst German reprisals during World War II when the Wehrmacht and the SS killed 51 inhabitants in early April 1944 .
7 A monument dedicated to the dead was erected in 1959 .
8 Typical food production include the local variety of potato , known as patata di Leonessa .
9 Leonessa is twinned with the French town of Gonesse .

##title
Bohumín
##doc
0 Bohumín (; ; , ) is a town in Karviná District , Moravian - Silesian Region , Czech Republic on the border with Poland .
1 The confluence of the Oder ( Odra ) and Olza rivers is situated just north of the town .
2 The town lies in the historical region of Cieszyn Silesia .
3 Bohumín consists of Old Bohumín and industrial New Bohumín , while several villages are administratively part of the town .
4 The majority of citizens are Czech ; many citizens have Polish ancestry , although the Polish minority in Bohumín is small .
5 Before World War II , the town was inhabited by a large German community .
6 Nowadays the city is known as having one of the largest communities of Romani people in the Czech Republic .

##title
Johan Gottlieb Gahn
##doc
0 Johan Gottlieb Gahn ( 19 August 1745 – 8 December 1818 ) was a Swedish chemist and metallurgist who discovered manganese in 1774 .
1 Gahn studied in Uppsala 1762 – 1770 and became acquainted with chemists Torbern Bergman and Carl Wilhelm Scheele .
2 1770 he settled in Falun , where he introduced improvements in copper smelting , and participated in building up several factories , including those for vitriol , sulfur and red paint .
3 He was the chemist for The Swedish Board of Mines Bergskollegium from 1773 – 1817 .
4 Gahn was however very reluctant to publish his scientific findings himself , but freely communicated them to Bergman and Scheele .
5 One of Gahn 's discoveries was that manganese dioxide could be reduced to manganese metal using carbon , becoming the first to isolate this element in its metal form .
6 In 1784 , Gahn was elected a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences .
7 He also made a managerial career in Swedish mining .

##title
Christian worship
##doc
0 In Christianity , worship is reverent honor and homage paid to God .
1 In the New Testament various words are used for worship .
2 The word proskuneo " to worship " means to bow down to God or kings .
3 Throughout most of Christianity 's history , corporate Christian worship has been liturgical , characterized by prayers and hymns , with texts rooted in , or closely related to , the Scripture , particularly the Psalter ; this form of sacramental and ceremonial worship is still practiced by the Roman Catholic , Eastern Orthodox , and Anglican churches , as well as some Protestant denominations such as Lutheranism and Methodism .
4 In Evangelicalism , worship is viewed like an act of adoration of God , with a more informal conception .
5 The term liturgy is derived from the Greek leitourgia meaning " public service " and is formed by two words : " laos " ( people ) and " ergon " ( work ) , literally " work of the people " .
6 Responsorial prayers are a series of petitions read or sung by a leader with responses made by the congregation .
7 Set times for prayer during the day were established ( based substantially on Jewish models ) , and a festal cycle throughout the Church year governed the celebration of feasts and holy days pertaining to the events in the life of Jesus , the lives of the saints , and aspects of the Godhead .
8 A great deal of emphasis was placed on the forms of worship , as they were seen in terms of the Latin phrase lex orandi , lex credendi ( " the rule of prayer is the rule of belief")—that is , the specifics of one 's worship express , teach , and govern the doctrinal beliefs of the community .
9 According to this view , alterations in the patterns and content of worship would necessarily reflect a change in the faith itself .
10 Each time a heresy arose in the Church , it was typically accompanied by a shift in worship for the heretical group .
11 Orthodoxy in faith also meant orthodoxy in worship , and vice versa .
12 Thus , unity in Christian worship was understood to be a fulfillment of Jesus ' words that the time was at hand when true worshipers would worship " in spirit and in truth " ( John 4:23 ) .
##labels

Lutheranism, Protestant, subclass of(P279), [3]

##title
Enasa
##doc
0 ENASA ( Empresa Nacional de Autocamiones S.A. ) was a Spanish vehicle manufacturing company , incorporated in 1946 having bought the automotive assets of the Spanish arm of Hispano - Suiza .
1 It produced trucks , buses and military armored vehicles under the Pegaso and , for a short while , Sava brands .
2 Enasa belonged to the state - owned INI industrial holding .
3 From 1983 Enasa also owned Seddon Atkinson , which it received from International Harvester as compensation for a planned engine plant which had failed to materialize .
4 International Harvester pulled out as the market for truck engines was contracting at the time , while there were also problems with Spain 's admittance to the European Economic Community ( EEC ) .
5 In 1990 Enasa was sold to Iveco .

##title
Kriegers Flak
##doc
0 Kriegers Flak is a reef located in the Baltic Sea , north of Rügen , south of Skåne with its west most point about 15   km east of Møn .
1 It is named after the Danish naval officer Christian Krieger , who in 1840 mapped the Baltic Sea .
2 The Danish part of the reef has at its most shallow place a depth of 16   m.
3 The reef spans the exclusive economic zones of Denmark , Germany and Sweden and is estimated to be able to accommodate 1600   MW worth of offshore wind farms of these three countries .
4 As such , it is the site of the German 288   MW offshore wind farm Baltic 2 , and of the proposed Danish 600   MW offshore wind farm Kriegers Flak .

##title
Zakhary Lyapunov
##doc
0 Zakhary Petrovich Lyapunov ( ) ( ?
1 - after 1612 ) was a Russian political figure of the early 17th century , brother of Prokopy Lyapunov .
2 In 1605 , Zakhary Lyapunov took the side of False Dmitri I.
3 Upon the latter 's death in 1606 , he took part in the Bolotnikov Uprising in 1606 – 1607 .
4 In 1607 , he joined the ranks of Vasily Shuisky and became a commander of a unit of the Ryazan dvoryane during the struggle against the rebellious peasants and supporters of False Dmitri II .
5 In July 1610 , Zachary Lyapunov took an active part in deposing Vasily Shuisky .
6 In September 1610 , he was included in a diplomatic mission , sent to the outskirts of Smolensk to sign a treaty with the Polish king Sigismund III Vasa regarding the accession of his son Wladislaus to the Russian throne .
7 Then he returned to Moscow and remained in the city until its liberation from the Polish invaders by the army of Kuzma Minin and Dmitry Pozharsky .

##title
Velocifero
##doc
0 Velocifero is the fourth studio album by English electronic music band Ladytron and their first to be released by Nettwerk .
1 The album was made available on the iTunes Store as of 19 May 2008 , followed by a physical release on 2 June in the United Kingdom and on 3 June elsewhere .
2 Velocifero peaked at number 75 on the UK Albums Chart , becoming the band 's second highest - charting album to date in the UK ( after Gravity the Seducer reached number 72 in 2011 ) .
3 It was also their first album to chart on the US Billboard 200 , reaching number 131 .
4 According to band member Reuben Wu , " velocifero " literally means " bringer of speed " , and is also the name of a classic retro - styled scooter .
5 " Black Cat " and " Kletva " are both sung entirely in Bulgarian .
6 " Kletva " ( which means " oath " ) is a cover of a song from a solo album by Kiril Marichkov of Bulgarian rock band Shturtzite .
7 Daniel Hunt provided additional vocals on " Versus " .
8 Velocifero spawned three singles : " Ghosts " , " Runaway " and " Tomorrow " .

##title
List of Square Enix video games
##doc
0 Square Enix is a Japanese video game development and publishing company formed from the merger on April 1 , 2003 of video game developer Square and publisher Enix .
1 The company is best known for its role - playing video game franchises , which include the Final Fantasy , Dragon Quest , and Kingdom Hearts series .
2 Of its properties , the Final Fantasy franchise is the best - selling , with total worldwide sales of over 130   million units .
3 The Dragon Quest series has sold over 71   million units worldwide and is one of the most popular video game series in Japan , while the Kingdom Hearts series has sold over 24 million copies worldwide .
4 Since its inception , the company has developed or published hundreds of titles in various video game franchises on numerous gaming systems .
5 Square Enix has owned Taito Corporation , which continues to publish its own video games , since September 2005 , and acquired game publisher Eidos Interactive in April 2009 , which has been merged with Square Enix 's European publishing wing and renamed as Square Enix Europe .
6 This list includes retail games developed or published by Square Enix after its formation .
7 It does not include games published by Taito , but does include games published by Square Enix Europe .
8 For games released before the merger , see List of Square video games and List of Enix games .
9 For mobile games released by the company , see List of Square Enix mobile games .
10 For games released by Taito , both before and after the acquisition , see List of Taito games , and see List of Eidos Interactive games for games published by Eidos prior to acquisition , and List of Square Enix Europe games for games published afterwards .

##title
Between Five and Seven
##doc
0 Between Five and Seven is as the name suggests , the sixth studio album by folk singer - songwriter John Gorka .
1 It was released in August 1996 .
2 It is the last of the five albums Gorka recorded for Windham Hill / High Street Records before returning to the smaller , Red House label .
3 Gorka produced the album with John Jennings who also produced Gorka 's previous record , Out of the Valley .
4 Unlike the previous record made in Nashville , Tennessee , the recording was done at Paisley Park Studios , Chanhassen , Minnesota and the instrumentation has been described as " more acoustic , less pop - oriented . "
5 Paisley Park is southwest of Minneapolis and is the studio designed and owned by the artist , Prince .
6 The album includes several lyrical portraits of Gorka 's misfit characters , love songs , and philosophical musings .
7 The songs are also full of the wordplay for which Gorka has become known .
8 The album features an impressive array of supporting musicians .
9 Lucy Kaplansky and Jennifer Kimball add carefully placed harmony vocals to many tracks .
10 John Jennings also brings along several other members of Mary Chapin Carpenter 's band including drummer Robbie Magruder , guitarist Dean Magraw , and pianist Jonathan Carroll .
11 Gorka 's fellow Minnesotan Peter Ostroushko sits in on mandolin .
12 As with many of Gorkas recordings Michael Manring plays fretless bass on nearly half of the songs .
13 The tracks alternate between two different sets of instrumentalists which varies the pace of the music .
14 The two bass players styles are distinct enough for the listener to recognize the difference .

##title
Surreal (song)
##doc
0 " Surreal " ( stylized as " SURREAL " ) is a song by Japanese recording artist Ayumi Hamasaki , taken from her third studio album Duty ( 2000 ) .
1 It was written by Hamasaki and produced by Max Matsuura .
2 The song is a rock with elements of alternative rock .
3 " Surreal " describes Hamasaki 's madness and sense of confusion , while the themes of " Surreal " are based on Hamasaki 's concept of loneliness , chaos , confusion , and the burden of her responsibilities , aimed mostly toward her public image as a recording artist .
4 It was released as the fourth single from the album on 27 September 2000 by Avex Trax and Avex Taiwan .
5 Critical reception towards " Surreal " has been positive ; the majority of critics commended the songwriting and musical delivery , and highlighted it as an album and career standout .
6 In Japan , " Surreal " became her sixth number one on the Oricon Singles Chart , and also reached the top spot on the Japanese Count Down TV chart .
7 " Surreal " was certified platinum by the Recording Industry Association of Japan ( RIAJ ) for shipments of 250,000 units .
8 Released as a DVD Single in December 2000 , it reached number three on the Oricon DVD Chart .
9 The accompanying music video was directed by Wataru Takeishi , featuring Hamasaki walking along a beach front .
10 With mysterious lighting hovering over several objects , she enters a jungle - like room to find a clone of herself ; the clone wears the same outfit for the Duty and " Surreal " photo shoot .
11 " Surreal " has been included on several concert tours and New Year Countdown shows held and hosted by Hamasaki , and has featured on majority of her greatest hits compilations .

##title
Cry for Help
##doc
0 " Cry for Help " is the title of the first single taken from British dance - pop singer Rick Astley 's third studio album , Free .
1 It was written by Rick Astley and Rob Fisher .
2 The Andraé Crouch Choir provided backing vocals .
3 Released as a single in January 1991 , " Cry for Help " reached number seven on both the UK Singles Chart and the US Billboard Hot 100 .
4 It also reached number four in Canada and was a number - one hit on both the US and Canadian Adult Contemporary charts .
5 The song 's number - seven UK chart placing meant that Astley became the first male solo artist to have his first eight singles reach the British top 10 .
6 The song is a soul ballad , unlike Astley 's other more dance - oriented hit singles such as " Never Gon na Give You Up " .
7 It was co - written by British singer Rob Fisher , formerly one half of the 1980s pop outfits Naked Eyes and Climie Fisher .
8 To date , the song was Astley 's last appearance in the top 10 in either the US or UK .
9 The song has been sung by Rick Astley in duet with Soren Sko and covered by Thomas Anders ( ex - Modern Talking ) .

##title
United States Naval Forces Germany
##doc
0 United States Naval Forces Germany ( NAVFORGER ) was a command of the United States Navy , active from 1944 to 1958 .
1 It also had the designation Task Force 104 ( TF-104 ) .
2 NAVFORGER was responsible for all US naval activities in Germany .
3 Its first commander was Vice Admiral Robert L. Ghormley ( 1944 – 45 ) .
4 After the formation of the command , it was first necessary to take under U.S. control the German warships assigned to the U.S. as war prizes ( for example , the heavy cruiser Prinz Eugen ) .
5 To this end , in Bremerhaven , a Naval Service Unit ( MDG ) was established .
6 After the initial , purely administrative order , the settlement of the German Kriegsmarine and the merchant navy was in cooperation with the other allies , finished , the command was greatly reduced .
7 It was intended to completely dissolve the command in 1948 .
8 However , the American military governor General Lucius D. Clay and since July 1948 COMNAVFORGER Rear Admiral Wilkes convinced the leadership in Washington to leave some naval forces in Germany .
9 The now allotted backup and reconnaissance tasks were to deal with three main elements : the Naval Advanced Base Bremerhaven , the Rhine River Patrol and the Intelligence Unit stationed in Berlin .
10 The tasks also included the supervision and management of commercial shipping on the inland waters of the United States Zone .

Lucius D. Clay, US, country of citizenship(P27), [8]

##title
Think Bike
##doc
0 The Think Bike Campaign was started by biking enthusiasts in South Africa , and is run by bikers , in the interests of road safety and public awareness .
1 Many motorcycle accidents happen because of a lack of awareness of the issues among the general motoring public .
2 The aim of the campaign is to correct that through the use of stickers , leaflets , and information distributed in other ways .
3 During 2005 , a number of bikers were using an online forum to discuss the alarming number of unnecessary motorcycle accidents ; avoidable accidents caused by inattentiveness , ignorance , incompetence and failure to exercise due care .
4 The Think Bike sticker campaign started by Tony Day of Cape Town in the 1980s , and its short life were discussed , and it was decided then and there to revive the campaign and expand on its goals and methods .
5 The campaign , while strongest in the Gauteng province , has representation in Western Cape , KwaZulu Natal and the Free State .
6 It has dozens of trained marshals available for various events such as cycle races and is deeply involved in numerous other projects , such as the annual Toy Run .
7 A number of studies have been done in the past , most notably in the United States and United Kingdom , that show that an alarming number of motorcycle accidents are directly caused by other vehicles .
8 Being as vulnerable as they are , bikers very often emerge from these avoidable accidents seriously injured , maimed or dead .
9 The campaign is also aimed at the biking community , to educate about safety issues and encourage the use of protective clothing .
10 The Hurt Report , published in the United States in 1981 , showed some alarming trends .
11 More than 900 motorcycle accidents were investigated in the Los Angeles area , and the results showed that :
12 Approximately three fourths of motorcycle accidents involve collision with another vehicle , usually a passenger automobile .
13 In these accidents , the driver of the other vehicle violated the motorcycle right of way and caused the accident in two thirds of cases .
14 The failure of motorists to detect and recognise motorcycles in traffic is the predominating cause of motorcycle accidents .
15 The driver of the other vehicle involved in collision with the motorcycle did not see the motorcycle before the collision or did not see the motorcycle until too late to avoid the collision .

##title
Two Doors Down
##doc
0 " Two Doors Down " was a song written and performed by Dolly Parton , which provided a 1978 U.S. country and pop hit for her .
1 The song was sung from the perspective of a woman who has just broken up with her boyfriend and is debating attending a party two doors down the hall from her apartment .
2 She decides to go , meets a new man and returns with him to her own apartment " two doors down " .
3 It was included on Parton 's 1977 Here You Come Again album , but before Parton could release it as the album 's second single in March 1978 , singer Zella Lehr released a cover version that became a top ten U.S. country hit .
4 While Lehr 's version was on the country charts , the title cut of Here You Come Again was becoming a much bigger pop hit than Parton had anticipated .
5 Wanting to capitalize on her newfound pop success ( and also not wanting to compete with Lehr 's country version of the song ) Parton rerecorded a more loose , pop - oriented version of " Two Doors Down " with a slight disco flavoring .
6 She released the new version on a double - A - sided single , with the other side , " It 's All Wrong , but It 's All Right " intended for country airplay , and " Two Doors Down " intended for the pop airplay .
7 The single topped the U.S. country charts , and was a top-20 pop hit for Parton , and went on to be one of her most popular hits .
8 Also in 1978 Joe Thomas did his own disco cover of this song .
9 Parton also had the new version of " Two Doors Down " ( which omitted the first verse , and included an upbeat " sing - along " bridge ) replace the previous version on all subsequent pressings of Here You Come Again , making the earlier version something of a collectors ' item among Parton 's fans .
10 The original version of " Two Doors Down " was subsequently issued on CD in 2000 on the 3-CD Australian compilation Legendary Dolly Parton , which is now out of print .
11 In 2009 , Jill Johnson recorded the song on the cover album Music Row II .

##title
Martin Ulrich
##doc
0 Martin Ulrich ( born December 16 , 1969 ) is a retired Austrian ice hockey defenceman .
1 He was the captain of the Austrian national ice hockey team .
2 Born in Vienna , Austria , Ulrich began his career with three seasons at Vienna before joining Graz EC in 1991 again in a three - year spell .
3 After a brief return to Vienna , Ulrich moved to the Deutsche Eishockey Liga in Germany , playing for the Adler Mannheim for two seasons .
4 He returned to Vienna for a third time before returning to the DEL in 1999 , with spells for the Berlin Capitals and the DEG Metro Stars where he spent four seasons .
5 In 2005 , Ulrich returned to Austria and signed for Red Bull Salzburg , where he played two more seasons before ending his player career in 2008 with the lower class team of EK Zell am See .
6 In October 2009 Ulrich was named Head Coach of the Austrian U-18 national ice hockey team .

##title
Fyllingen Fotball
##doc
0 Fyllingen Fotball was a Norwegian association football club from Fyllingsdalen , Bergen , Hordaland .
1 It was founded as a formally independent section of the alliance sports club Fyllingen IL on 1 January 1994 .
2 Fyllingen IL was founded on 6 June 1946 .
3 Fyllingen Fotball still uses Fyllingen IL 's logo .
4 The club played in the Norwegian Premier League in 1990 , 1991 and 1993 , and reached the Norwegian Cup final in 1990 , where they lost 5–1 against Rosenborg .
5 This earned them a place in the 1991–92 European Cup Winners ' Cup , where they were eliminated by Atlético Madrid in the first round .
6 Fyllingen played in the First Division from 1994 to 1996 and in the Second Division from 1997 till 2009 .
7 The last two seasons of its existence , the club played in the Third Division .
8 After the 2011 season , Fyllingen merged with Løv - Ham to create FK Fyllingsdalen , and the two clubs ceased to exist .

##title
Björn von der Esch
##doc
0 Carl Gösta Björn Joachim von der Esch ( 11 January 1930 – 10 March 2010 ) was a Swedish Christian democratic politician , member of the Riksdag 1998 – 2006 .
1 Esch had a farming business and did a Ph.D. in business administration at Uppsala University in 1972 .
2 Before joining the Christian Democrats , he had previously represented Moderate Party in the Riksdag 1991 – 1994 , replacing Per Westerberg during his time as a minister .
3 At the time of the Swedish 1994 referendum on membership in the European Union , Esch clashed with the Moderate Party as he campaigned on the " no " side .
4 When he subsequently formed a list of EU critics that ran in the 1995 European Parliament election in Sweden , he was expelled from the party .
5 This list was unsuccessful in the election , and von der Esch returned to parliamentary politics in 1998 as a Christian Democrat .
6 In the 2003 referendum on joining the Economic and Monetary Union and the euro , he again campaigned on the " no " side .
7 He later joined the June List , became its vice chairman in 2008 , and was on second place on the June List ballot in the 2009 European Parliament election in which the party lost its representation in the European Parliament .

##title
Ramada (shelter)
##doc
0 In the southwestern United States , a ramada is a temporary or permanent shelter equipped with a roof but no walls , or only partially enclosed .
1 Ramadas have traditionally been constructed with branches or bushes by aboriginal Americans living in the region ( deriving from the Spanish rama , meaning " branch " ) .
2 However , the term today is also applied to permanent concrete , wooden , or steel structures used to shelter objects or people from the sun .
3 For example , public parks in desert areas of the United States may contain ramadas with picnic tables , restrooms , water sources , etc .
4 Since sunlight is more of an environmental hazard than wind or snow or rain in this part of the world , a roof alone provides substantial shelter .
5 And because there are no walls in the structure , airflow is unrestricted , helping to keep the temperature below the roof substantially cooler than ambient .
6 An example of a large modern - day ramada can be seen at the Casa Grande Ruins National Monument in Arizona , where it is used to protect ancient ruins .
##labels

##title
Won-yong
##doc
0 Won - yong is a Korean masculine given name .
1 Its meaning differs based on the hanja used to write each syllable of the name .
2 There are 35 hanja with the reading " won " and 24 hanja with the reading " yong " on the South Korean government 's official list of hanja which may be registered for use in given names .
3 Additionally , there is one character with the reading " ryong " ( , meaning " dragon " ) which may also be written and pronounced " yong " in South Korea .
4 People with this name include :
5 Kang Won - yong ( 1917 – 2006 ) , South Korean Presbyterian leader
6 Kim Won - yong ( 1922 – 1993 ) , South Korean archaeologist
7 Wonyong Sung ( born 1950s ) , South Korean professor of electronic engineering
8 Jung Won - yong ( born 1992 ) , South Korean swimmer

##title
The Yorkshire Post
##doc
0 The Yorkshire Post is a daily broadsheet newspaper , published in Leeds in northern England .
1 It covers the whole of Yorkshire as well as parts of north Derbyshire and Lincolnshire but goes beyond just local news and its masthead carries the slogan " Yorkshire 's National Newspaper " .
2 Alongside The Scotsman it is one of the flagship titles owned by Johnston Press .
3 Founded in 1754 , it is one of the oldest newspapers in the country .
4 Its focus on international and national news gives it a wider focus than that usually associated with a provincial newspaper ; editions are available throughout the United Kingdom .
5 It has satellite offices in Harrogate , Hull , Scarborough , Sheffield and York , as well as correspondents in Westminster and the City of London .
6 The current editor is James Mitchinson .

##title
Kyoto Imperial Palace
##doc
0 The is one of the active palaces of the Emperor of Japan and has the longest history as the capital of Japan .
1 The Emperor declared Meiji Restoration and Charter Oath at this place in 1868 .
2 The following year , the Emperor moved into Edo castle , currently Tokyo Imperial Palace , but he ordered the preservation of the Kyoto Imperial Palace in 1877 , which is still used as an active palace .. Today , the grounds are open to the public , and the Imperial Household Agency hosts public tours of the buildings several times a day .
3 The Kyoto Imperial Palace is the latest of the imperial palaces built at or near its site in the northeastern part of the old capital of Heian - kyō after the abandonment of the larger original that was located to the west of the current palace during the Heian Period .
4 The Palace lost much of its function at the time of the Meiji Restoration , when the capital functions were moved to Tokyo in 1869 .
5 However , the Taishō and Shōwa Emperors still had their enthronement ceremonies at the palace .

##title
Rogaland County Municipality
##doc
0 Rogaland County Municipality ( ) is the governing administration of Rogaland county , Norway .
1 The responsibilities of the county municipality include the running of 29 upper secondary schools as well as managing the county roadways , public transport , dental care , cultural affairs , and cultural heritage .
2 The county municipality also coordinates regional planning and economic development .
3 The Rogfast is a major road project that is being financed by the county municipality .
4 The county council has 47 members , and county mayor is Janne Johnsen ( Conservative Party ) and the deputy mayor is Terje Halleland ( Progress Party ) .
5 The council and mayor are the legislative and executive bodies of the county .
6 Harald Thune is the County Governor of Rogaland .
7 The Governor is the representative of the King and Government of Norway in each county , functioning as the connection between the state and the municipalities .
8 The administration is located in the city of Stavanger .

##title
List of Prime Ministers of Thailand
##doc
0 The Prime Minister of Thailand is the head of government of the Kingdom of Thailand .
1 The prime minister is also the chairman of the cabinet of Thailand and represents the government at home and the country abroad .
2 The post of prime minister has existed since 1932 , after a bloodless revolution forced the absolutist King Prajadhipok to grant for the people of Siam their first constitution .
3 Under the newly established constitutional monarchy , the first prime minister of Siam was Phraya Manopakorn Nititada .
4 At first , the office was called the President of the People 's Committee , it was later changed to Prime Minister of Siam when the king deemed it too communistic .
5 Constitutionally the prime minister is required to be a member of the lower house of the National Assembly ( the House of Representatives ) .
6 He must also gain their approval through a resolution before an official appointment by the king can take place .
7 As a result , the prime minister might succumb to a vote of no confidence and removal in the House .
8 However , this has never happened up to date .
9 Throughout the post 's existence it has mostly been occupied by military leaders from the Royal Thai Army , three holding the rank of field marshal and seven the rank of general .
10 The post of prime minister is currently held by General Prayut Chan - o - cha , who was formally appointed to the office on 24 August 2014 .
11 Previously he was the de facto head of government as leader of the National Council for Peace and Order , since the coup d'état on 22 May 2014 .
12 Note : The list includes leaders of military juntas and acting prime ministers .
13 However , they are not counted in the official list as provided by the Royal Thai Government

##title
Joseph in Islam
##doc
0 Yūsuf ibn Yaʿqūb ibn Is - ḥāq ibn Ibrāhīm ( ) is a Nabi ( , Prophet ) mentioned in the Qurʾān , the scripture of Islam , and corresponds to Joseph ( son of Jacob ) , a person from the Tanakh , the Jewish religious scripture , and the Christian Bible , who was estimated to have lived in the 16th century BCE .
1 It is one of the common names in the Middle East and among Muslim nations .
2 Of all of Jacob 's children , Joseph was the one given the gift of prophecy .
3 Although the narratives of other prophets are mentioned in various Surahs , the complete narrative of Joseph is given only in one Surah , Yusuf , making it unique .
4 It is said to be the most detailed narrative in the Qur'an and bears more details than the Biblical counterpart .
5 Yusuf is believed to have been the eleventh son of Yaʿqūb ( , Jacob ) , and , according to many scholars , his favorite .
6 According to Ibn Kathir , " Jacob had twelve sons who were the eponymous ancestors of the tribes of the Israelites .
7 The noblest , the most exalted , the greatest of them was Joseph . "
8 The story begins with Joseph revealing a ru'ya ( , ' dream ' or ' vision ' ) to his father , which Jacob recognizes .
9 In addition to the role of God in his life , the story of Yusuf and Zulaikha ( Potiphar 's wife of the Old Testament ) became a popular subject in Persian literature , where it became considerably elaborated over the centuries .
10 More recently , and relying on the Quran and Muslim , Christian and Jewish scholarly sources , Yusuf 's story has been depicted in a 45-part TV series ( originally in Persian but also dubbed in multiple other languages ) .

##title
The Christian Manifesto
##doc
0 " Direction of Endeavor for Chinese Christianity in the Construction of New China " , commonly known as " The Christian Manifesto " or " The Three - Self Manifesto " , was a political manifesto of Protestants in China whereby they backed the newly - founded People 's Republic of China ( PRC ) and the leadership of the Communist Party of China ( CPC ) .
1 Published in 1950 , the manifesto paved the way for the government - controlled Three - Self Patriotic Movement ( TSPM ) of Protestants .
2 This movement proclaimed the three principles of self - government , self - support , and self - propagation .
3 The drafting and content of the manifesto was , and remains , controversial to this day .
4 The manifesto was devised after Protestant leaders presented their concerns with religious freedom to Zhou Enlai , the Premier of China .
5 Instead of receiving their report , Zhou demanded them to come up with a statement in support of the new communist leadership .
6 Y. T. Wu and other leftist clergymen espoused the task and presented a draft manifesto that , after some opposition and changes , became a foundational text of Christianity in the new People 's Republic .
7 It condemns missionary activities in China as a form of imperialism , pledges loyalty to the communist leadership , and encourages the Church to take up an indigenous Chinese stance toward Christianity .
8 Published on the front page of the People 's Daily , the manifesto was accompanied by a campaign to gather signatures .
9 Many Christian leaders and laymen signed , while others refused to do so .
10 After the Korean War broke out , the campaign became an increasingly politicized test of loyalty that became merged with the Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries .
11 Some view the manifesto as a betrayal of the Church , while others find sympathy for the position of Chinese Christians struggling to reconcile their faith with the changed political realities .
12 The manifesto ended missionary activities in China and the separation of church and state .
13 It led to the founding the TSPM and brought persecution to dissidents .

##title
Cranks and Shadows
##doc
0 Cranks and Shadows is a crime novel by the American writer K.C.
1 Constantine set in 1990s Rocksburg , a fictional , blue - collar , Rustbelt town in Western Pennsylvania ( modeled on the author 's hometown of McKees Rocks , Pennsylvania , adjacent to Pittsburgh ) .
2 Mario Balzic is the protagonist , an atypical detective for the genre , a Serbo - Italian American cop , middle - aged , unpretentious , a family man who asks questions and uses more sense than force .
3 The novel opens with Balzic being told to lay off five members of his police department .
4 Balzic confronts members of the Conemaugh Foundation , a clandestine organization out to seize control of Rocksburg .
5 It is the eleventh book in the 17-volume Rocksburg series .

##title
Nexus Q
##doc
0 Nexus   Q is a discontinued digital media player developed by Google .
1 Unveiled at the Google I / O developers ' conference on June 2012 , the device was expected to be released to the public in the United States shortly thereafter for US$ 300 .
2 The Nexus Q was designed to leverage Google 's online media offerings , such as Google Play Music , Google Play Movies & TV , and YouTube , to provide a " shared " experience .
3 Users could stream content from the supported services to a connected television , or speakers connected to an integrated amplifier , using their Android device and the services ' respective apps as a remote control for queueing content and controlling playback .
4 The Nexus   Q received mixed reviews from critics following its unveiling .
5 While its unique spherical design was praised , the Nexus Q was criticized for its lack of functionality in comparison to similar devices such as Apple TV , including a lack of third - party content services , no support for streaming content directly from other devices using the DLNA standard , as well as other software issues that affected the usability of the device .
6 The unclear market positioning of the Nexus Q was also criticized , as it carried a significantly higher price than competing media players with wider capabilities ; The New York Times technology columnist David Pogue described the device as being ' wildly overbuilt ' for its limited functions .
7 The Nexus   Q was given away at no cost to attendees of Google I / O 27 - 29 June 2012 , but the product 's consumer launch was postponed in July 2012 , purportedly to collect additional feedback .
8 Those who had pre - ordered the Nexus   Q following its unveiling received the device at no cost .
9 The Nexus   Q was quietly shelved in January 2013 , and support for the device in the Google Play apps was phased out beginning in May 2013 .
10 Some of the Nexus   Q 's concepts were repurposed for a more - successful device known as Chromecast , which similarly allows users to wirelessly queue content for playback using functions found in supported apps , but is designed as a smaller HDMI dongle with support for third - party services .

##title
Mark McNamara
##doc
0 Mark McNamara ( born June 8 , 1959 ) , is an American former professional basketball player who was selected by the Philadelphia 76ers in the first round ( 22nd overall ) of the 1982 NBA draft .
1 A 6'11 " power forward - center from the University of California , McNamara played in 8 NBA seasons from 1982 to 1985 and from 1986 to 1991 .
2 He played for the 76ers , San Antonio Spurs , Kansas City Kings , Los Angeles Lakers and Orlando Magic .
3 McNamara 's best year as a professional came during the 1983–84 season as a member of the Spurs , appearing in 70 games and averaging 5.5 ppg .
4 In his NBA career , McNamara played in 278 games and scored a total of 980 points .
5 McNamara was assistant coach of the boys ' basketball team at Haines High School , Alaska ( March 2010 ) and now helps out at basketball camps around Alaska .

##title
Toufique Imrose Khalidi
##doc
0 Toufique Imrose Khalidi has been the publisher , editor - in - chief , and co - owner of the Bangladeshi newspaper / media group bdnews24.com since 2006 .
1 Khalidi has national and international standing as a journalist , media executive , and commentator .
2 Prior to bdnews24.com , Khalidi acquired experience of journalism at major broadsheet newspapers in Bangladesh both in editorial as well as managerial capacities and for a period was a presenter , producer , and editor at the BBC in the UK .
3 He was educated and trained in Dhaka as well as London , Paris , and Tokyo .
4 As a broadcast , print and digital journalist in Bangladesh and abroad he has covered business , politics , economics , development and foreign affairs among other subjects .
5 He has provided leader commentaries for dissemination in Bangladesh as well as internationally .
6 Khalidi supports press independence and has publicly spoken of bdnews24.com's commitment to steering clear of political partisanship .
7 It is an ethical stance that has drawn bipartisan support across Bangladesh 's polarised society , including in 2013 from the country 's Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina as well as the Leader of the Opposition Khaleda Zia .
8 Khalidi has recently been awarded ( December 2017 ) by the Government with a “ Special Recognition / Honour ” along with two other leading personalities for contribution to the development of ‘ Digital Bangladesh’ .

##title
Pittsburgh Catholic
##doc
0 The Pittsburgh Catholic is the weekly Catholic newspaper for the Roman Catholic Diocese of Pittsburgh , published for lay people and priests .
1 It labels itself as the oldest Catholic newspaper in continuous publication .
2 The newspaper was established in 1844 by Pittsburgh 's first bishop , Michael O'Connor .
3 According to its website , the Catholic has a total market of 111,250 Catholics .
4 The Catholic is available for free at most churches and Catholic outlets or centers in the Diocese of Pittsburgh , as churches purchase the newspaper in bulk for 21 cents per copy .
5 Articles include news about events occurring throughout the diocese , articles on local diocesan schools , features on community and charity programs orchestrated by local Catholic organizations , reviews and commentary on contemporary media , question - and - answer forums by priests to explain church doctrine , and editorials on Church issues .
6 The former Bishop of Pittsburgh , Donald Wuerl , was generally seen as a conservative bishop .
7 As a result , the Pittsburgh Catholic is a conservative publication as well .
8 However , because the newspaper is oriented towards the local region , it rarely contains extensive commentary on national issues .
9 According to the Pittsburgh Business Times Book of Lists , the Pittsburgh Catholic is the largest weekly publication in western Pennsylvania and the second - largest newspaper in western Pennsylvania .
10 The Pittsburgh Catholic is a member of the Catholic Press Association .
11 Its general manager , Robert P. Lockwood , was nominated as finalist for the association 's annual St. Francis de Sales Award .

##title
Manon Balletti
##doc
0 Manon Balletti ( 1740 – 1776 ) was the daughter of Italian actors performing in France and lover of the famous womanizer Giacomo Casanova .
1 She was ten years old when she first met him ; she happened to be the daughter of Silvia Balletti , an actress of the Comédie Italienne company and younger sister of Casanova 's closest friend .
2 The lovers started their relationship when Casanova was thirty - two years old and Manon was seventeen .
3 ( Although Manon 's mother was associated with acting , considered disreputable at the time , mother and daughter were observed by Casanova to be of a " pure nature " . )
4 She wrote forty - two letters full of love and deep feelings for him ; a well - known quote from these letters describes Casanova as : " My lover , my husband , my friend " .
5 Casanova 's sexual passions caused him to be unfaithful , causing their three - year relationship to have numerous ups and downs .
6 Yet she continued to share his home , found in Rue du Petit - Lion - St . Sauveur .
7 Manon was at the time engaged to her clavichord teacher , but broke it off at Casanova 's request , thus starting a new engagement with him .
8 This did not keep him from having various sexual relations with other women , yet Manon remained faithful to him .
9 His memoirs record his regret for being unkind to her when having these affairs .
10 Once Casanova was imprisoned after he was sued by creditors in Paris .
11 Manon sent a pair of diamond earrings with which she bought him out .
12 Subsequently she ended the engagement and returned his portrait and letters .
13 Manon married the architect Jacques - François Blondel a short while after , disappointing Casanova , who believed that he would one day be able to settle down with her .
14 Manon died at the age of 36 , questionably from pulmonary hypertension .
15 Casanova wrote in his memoirs that he believed his behavior shortened her life .

##title
Morogoro Region
##doc
0 Morogoro Region is one of Tanzania 's 31 administrative regions .
1 The regional capital is the municipality of Morogoro .
2 According to the 2012 national census , the region had a population of 2,218,492 , which was higher than the pre - census projection of 2,209,072 .
3 For 2002 - 2012 , the region 's 2.4 percent average annual population growth rate was tied for the fourteenth highest in the country .
4 It was also the 22nd most densely populated region with 31 people per square kilometer .
5 Morogoro Region is bordered to the north by the Tanga Region , to the east by the Pwani and Lindi Regions , to the south by the Ruvuma Region and to the west by the Iringa and Dodoma Regions .
6 The regional commissioner of the Morogoro Region is Dr . Kebwe Steven Kebwe .

##title
South Gondar Zone
##doc
0 Debub Gondar ( Amharic : ደቡብ ጎንደር ) ( or South Gondar ) is a Zone in the Ethiopian Amhara Region .
1 This zone is named for the city of Gondar , which was the capital of Ethiopia until the mid-19th century , and has often been used as a name for the local province .
2 Debub Gondar is bordered on the south by Misraq Gojjam , on the southwest by Mirab Gojjam and Bahir Dar , on the west by Lake Tana , on the north by Semien Gondar , on the northeast by Wag Hemra , on the east by Semien Wollo , and on the southeast by Debub Wollo ; the Abbay River separates Debub Gondar from the two Gojjam Zones .
3 The highest point in Debub Gondar is Mount Guna ( 4,231 meters ) .
4 Towns and cities in this zone include Addis Zemen , Debre Tabor and Wereta .
