##title
Australia–Chile Free Trade Agreement
##doc
0 The Australia – Chile Free Trade Agreement is a trade agreement between the countries of Chile and Australia .
1 It was signed on July 30 , 2008 and went into effect in the 1st quarter of 2009 .
2 The agreement was intended to go into effect on January 1 , 2009 , but was delayed due to Chile not being able to finish its ratification in time .
3 Trade between Chile and Australia is modest , involving $ 856 m in 2007 .
4 Australia is the fourth largest provider of foreign direct investment in Chile with over $ 3 billion in 2007 .
5 Chile ranks as Australia 's 41st trading partner .
6 Australia 's main exports to Chile were coal ( $ 94 million ) and civil engineering equipment ( $ 21 million ) .
7 Trade from Chile is copper ( $ 96 million ) , and pulp and waste paper ( $ 57 million ) .
8 When enacted , the Agreement calls for Chile to eliminate tariffs on 91.9 % of tariffs which cover 96.9 % of trade from Australia .
9 Australia will cut 90.8 % of tariffs which cover 97.1 % of trade from Chile .
10 By year six of the Agreement ( 2015 ) , all tariffs will be discarded except for Chile 's sugar tariff which will remain subject to its current ‘ price band’ system .
11 The tariffs in Australia , that will stay in place until 2015 , will be relating to textile and the clothing industry along with table grapes .
12 In Chile , the agreement will protect the textile and clothing industry and some other manufactured products .
13 According to the Australian Government , the government hopes to use the Agreement as a model for other free trade agreements with other countries .
14 Before passage of the Agreement farmers and horticulturists protested the Agreement in front of the Australian Parliament .
15 The protesters claim that this agreement would undercut Australian food producers by allowing in cheap food goods from Chile .
16 Simon Crean , Australia 's Minister for Trade , responded to the farmers concerns by stating that tariffs are quite low or in some cases nonexistent due to previous international trade agreements .
17 Chile and Australia agreed in principle to start negotiations on December 8 , 2006 .
18 Negotiations started on July 18 , 2007 and after four rounds of talks , concluded on May 27 , 2008 .

##title
Railroad Revival Tour
##doc
0 The Railroad Revival Tour was an annual music tour that featured popular roots , folk , country , rock , bluegrass and Americana acts that began in 2011 .
1 The musicians travel between shows across the American Southwest in a dozen or so vintage train cars from the 1950s and 1960s .
2 The outdoor concert locations , sometimes attracting over 10,000 fans , are often a stone 's throw from the train .
3 The bands eat , sleep and engage in impromptu jam sessions on the train between stops , giving them a chance to collaborate .
4 On stage at night , they often join in on each other 's sets , sometimes bringing around 30 musicians up to create a rare and rowdy performance .
5 The organic American roots feeling of the tour also prompts participating musicians to honor U.S. railway history , like Mumford & Sons ' tribute to Woody Guthrie in 2011 .
6 The inaugural tour in 2011 included performances by Mumford & Sons , Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros , and Old Crow Medicine Show .
7 A documentary of this first year , called Big Easy Express , directed by Emmett Malloy premiered at SXSW 2012 and won a Grammy Award in 2013 .
8 The film is currently available on iTunes and DVD / Blu - ray Disc .
9 In 2011 , Railroad Revival Tour bands Mumford & Sons , Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros , and Old Crow Medicine Show together closed their shows at every stop with " This Train . "
10 The 2012 tour was slated to include performances by Willie Nelson , Band of Horses , Jamey Johnson , and John Reilly and Friends .
11 However , the tour was cancelled for 2012 .

##title
Lehmann Bernheimer
##doc
0 Lehmann Bernheimer ( 27 December 1841 - 29 May 1918 ) was a German antique dealer , who built the Bernheimer - Haus in Munich .
1 He was born on 27 December 1841 in Buttenhausen in Münsingen , Württemberg , the third child of Meier Bernheimer ( 1801 - 1870 ) and his wife Sarah , née Kahn ( 1803 - 1881 ) .
2 In 1887 , Bernheimer bought a small coffee house and beer garden , owned and run by an Englishman , and called the English Café .
3 In its place was built the Bernheimer - Haus , which was opened in December 1889 by Prince Regent Luitpold .
4 Initially the focus was on high - quality textiles , with the manufacture of luxury goods being slowly added .
5 After a fire in 1897 , the building was extended and antiques , tapestries and carpets were added .
6 On his death in 1918 , his son , Otto Bernheimer took over .

##title
Carey Business School
##doc
0 The Johns Hopkins Carey Business School , also referred to as Carey Business School or JHUCarey or simply Carey , is the business school of the Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore , Maryland .
1 As " the newest school in America 's first research university , " the school offers full - time and part - time MBA degrees , master of science degrees , several dual degrees with other Johns Hopkins schools — including medicine , public health , arts and sciences , engineering , and nursing — and Maryland Institute College of Art , as well as a number of graduate certificates .
2 The Carey Business School is accredited by the Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business ( AACSB ) .
3 James Carey ( 1751 - 1834 ) , the namesake of the Carey Business School , is a relative to Johns Hopkins ( founder of Johns Hopkins University and Hospital ) , a co - founder of the Gilman School , and ancestor to several founding trustees of the university and hospital .
4 His sixth - generation decedent , William P. Carey , has been in active pursuit of establishing a business school for Johns Hopkins University since the 1950s and realized his " lifelong dream " in 2006 .

##title
Henrik Angell
##doc
0 Henrik August Angell ( 22 August 1861 – 26 January 1922 ) was a Norwegian military officer , sportsman , and writer .
1 He was a ski pioneer and the first Norwegian delegate to the International Olympic Committee .
2 Henrik Angell was born at Luster in Sogn og Fjordane and grew up in Bergen , Norway .
3 He was the son of Johan Mølmann Anderson Lysholm Angell ( 1820 – 88 ) and his wife Marie With Bonnevie ( 1830 – 1904 ) .
4 He received an education at the Norwegian Military Academy and entered the Norwegian Army .
5 He was a Colonel and Regiment Chief from 1911 .
6 He was commander leader of the Søndermør Infantry Regiment until 1914 and of the Smaalenene Infantry Regiment until 1918 .
7 He joined the French Foreign Legion in 1918 , and participated on the Western Front for France in World War I.
8 Angell was admitted to the skiing club SK Ull in 1898 and was a sports advocate .
9 He wrote several books promoting skiing and Norwegian nationalism .
10 He also wrote a series of military history books .
11 He died during 1922 in Kristiania ( now Oslo ) , Norway .
12 His statue by Gustav Lærum is located at Holmenkollen in Oslo .

##title
Eivind Bolle
##doc
0 Eivind Bolle ( 13 October 1923 – 10 June 2012 ) was a Norwegian politician for the Labour Party .
1 He was born in Hol .
2 He was elected to the Norwegian Parliament from Nordland in 1973 , and was re - elected on two occasions .
3 He had previously served as a deputy representative during the term 1969 – 1973 .
4 He was the Minister of Fisheries from 1973 to 1981 during three different cabinets : second cabinet Bratteli , cabinet Nordli and first cabinet Brundtland .
5 During these three periods he was replaced in the Parliament by Eindride Sommerseth , Karl Ingebrigtsen and Finn Knutsen respectively .
6 On the local level he was a member of Hol municipality council from 1959 to 1963 , and later in Hol 's successor municipality Vestvågøy .
7 He served as mayor from 1971 to 1973 , during which term he was also a member of Nordland county council .
8 Outside politics he worked as a fisher from 1938 to 1974 .

##title
Foix (river)
##doc
0 The Foix ( ) is a river in Catalonia in the province of Barcelona , northeastern Spain .
1 Its source is near La Llacuna in the Comarca of Anoia 800 m above the sea .
2 Later it runs through the Comarca of Alt Penedès , where it feeds a reservoir in the nature reserve of Parc del Foix since 1928 , which is highly important for the drinking water supply of the densely populated coastal plain between Barcelona and Tarragona .
3 Then it goes through the Comarca of Garraf from north to the south where it ends into the Mediterranean Sea west of the village of Cubelles .
4 This little delta became an important natural reserve and recreational area after the campground ″Camping Paradiso″ was removed in the late 1990s .
5 For most of the year , the river is dried up because of the dam and because of hot - summer climatical reasons .
6 That can suddenly change in the winter months when heavy rain comes down in the mountains .

##title
Edward Rowan Finnegan
##doc
0 Edward Rowan Finnegan ( June 5 , 1905 – February 2 , 1971 ) was a U.S. Representative from Illinois from 1961 to 1964 .
1 Finnegan was born in Chicago and graduated with a BA from Loyola University Chicago and a law degree from the DePaul University School of Law in 1930 .
2 He started practicing as an attorney in 1931 and then served as an Assistant State 's attorney in Cook County .
3 Later , Finnegan served as the Assistant Corporation Counsel for Chicago .
4 Finnegan unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for the position of a Chicago municipal court judge in 1939 .
5 In 1960 , Finnegan was elected to Congress from Illinois ' 12th district .
6 After redistricting , Finnegan 's district was merged with the neighboring 9th District of fellow Democrat Sidney Yates .
7 Finnegan transferred to the 9th , since Yates was giving up his seat to run for the United States Senate .
8 Yates lost , and Chicago 's machine bosses persuaded Finnegan to stand down in 1964 and hand the 9th back to Yates .
9 In return for his co - operation , Finnegan was appointed as a judge for the Circuit Court of Cook County .
10 He resigned his seat in Congress on December 6 , 1964 and commenced his service on the bench the following day .
11 He continued to serve until his death in 1971 .

##title
Westmere, New York
##doc
0 Westmere is a hamlet in the town of Guilderland , Albany County , New York .
1 Since the 1970 Census a census - designated place ( CDP ) has been established with the name of Westmere for tabulating the population of what the census has defined as the boundaries for Westmere .
2 The population was 7,284 at the 2010 census .
3 It is a suburb of the neighboring city of Albany .
4 U.S. Route 20 ( Western Avenue ) bisects the community and is the major thoroughfare and main street .
5 Along Western Avenue are numerous strip malls , shopping plazas , and commercial buildings , with residential use on the side streets to the north and south .
6 Crossgates Mall , the Capital District 's largest shopping mall , is in Westmere 's northeastern corner .

##title
Mola di Bari
##doc
0 Mola di Bari , commonly referred to simply as Mola ( Barese : ) , is a town and comune of the Metropolitan City of Bari , in the region of Apulia , in Southern Italy , on the Adriatic Sea .
1 In recent times , the town was best known for having primarily whitewashed buildings , however , growth , modern construction , and building design have changed the image significantly , particularly in the northern ( and more modern ) part of the town .
2 Mola 's city center is its main piazza , Piazza XX Settembre near the port and it also boasts a church ( Chiesa Matrice , i.e.
3 Mother Church ) dating back to the 13thcentury .
4 Bakeries in Mola are known for their focaccia food .
5 Until the early 1990s , there were two privately owned public firewood ovens available to the inhabitants of Mola , one located on Via Nino Bixio , on the southern part of the town , and the other located on Via Pesce , on the opposite side of the main Piazza .
6 These businesses served the local residents by providing a place to cook baked goods , primarily focaccia and breads .
7 Typically , focaccia pans were quite large ( some approaching half a meter in diameter ) and were difficult to cook in one ’s home .
8 The tradition of sending items to be baked by the local oven has passed .
9 Mola is also home to a large fishing industry that supplies fresh fish throughout the southern Italian region .

##title
Paul Desmarais Jr.
##doc
0 Paul Desmarais Jr. ( born July 3 , 1954 ) is a Canadian businessman in his hometown of Montreal .
1 He is the eldest son of Paul Desmarais Sr . and Jacqueline ( Maranger ) Desmarais .
2 Currently he is the Chairman and Co - Chief Executive Officer of Power Corporation of Canada .
3 Desmarais was born in Sudbury , Ontario .
4 He was educated at Lakefield College School in Lakefield , Ontario , McGill University in Montreal , Quebec , and at INSEAD in Fontainebleau , France , where he earned a Master of Business Administration .
5 He is a Roman Catholic .
6 Paul Desmarais is married to Hélène Desmarais , Chairman of the Board and CEO of the Centre d’entreprises et d’innovation de Montréal ( CEIM ) .
7 They have four children : Paul , Alexandre , Nicolas , and Charles - Édouard .

##title
Cambodia–Vietnam Friendship Monument
##doc
0 The Cambodia – Vietnam Friendship Monument in Phnom Penh , capital of Cambodia , is a large concrete monument commemorating the former alliance between Vietnam and Cambodia .
1 It was built in the late 1970s by the communist regime that took power after the Cambodian - Vietnamese War , which overthrew the Khmer Rouge regime .
2 The monument is located at the Botum Park near the centre of Phnom Penh not far from the Royal Palace .
3 It features heroic statues of Vietnamese and Cambodian soldiers in the " Socialist realist " style developed in the Soviet Union in the 1930s , together with images of a woman and baby representing Cambodian civilians .
4 The monument is in a popular park in the middle of the city .
5 The monument has occasionally become a political focal point .
6 On August 30 , 1998 , during post - electoral protests , several people climbed onto the monument with hammers , poured gasoline on it and set it on fire .
7 This damage was repaired two months later by the authorities .
8 On July 29 , 2007 , a bomb exploded at the base of the monument , causing little damage .

##title
The Sacramento Bee
##doc
0 The Sacramento Bee is a daily newspaper published in Sacramento , California , in the United States .
1 Since its founding in 1857 , The Bee has become the largest newspaper in Sacramento , the fifth largest newspaper in California , and the 27th largest paper in the U.S.
2 It is distributed in the upper Sacramento Valley , with a total circulation area that spans about : south to Stockton , California , north to the Oregon border , east to Reno , Nevada , and west to the San Francisco Bay Area .
3 The Bee is the flagship of the nationwide McClatchy Company .
4 Its " Scoopy Bee " mascot , created by Walt Disney in 1943 , has been used by all three Bee newspapers ( Sacramento , Modesto , and Fresno ) .

##title
ROKETSAN
##doc
0 Roketsan is a major Turkish weapons manufacturer and defense contractor based in the central Anatolian province of Ankara .
1 Incorporated in 1988 by Turkey 's Defense Industry Executive Committee ( SSİK ) in order to establish the nation 's industrial base on rocket technology , the company has quickly risen to become one of Turkey 's top 500 industrial establishments .
2 Roketsan 's current share holders include TSKGV(Turkish Armed Forces Foundation ) ( 55.5 % ) , Aselsan ( 15 % ) , MKEK ( 15 % ) , Vakıflar Bankası ( 10 % ) , Havelsan ( 4.5 % ) .
3 Roketsan is best known for its vast range of unguided rockets as well as laser and infrared guided missiles such as Cirit and UMTAS .
4 The company also produces subsystems for Stinger and Rapier missiles and provides technology and engineering solutions for other integrated civilian and military platforms .
5 In 2013 Turkey approved the construction by Roketsan of its first satellite launching center , initially for low earth orbit satellites .
6 Roketsan is the only Turkish company to have obtained CMMI/ DEV 3 ( Capability Maturity Model Integration – for Development ) approval for all its design and development processes .

##title
Soccer Academy
##doc
0 The Soccer Academy is a children ’s television show produced by Capistrano Films .
1 The show is shown in over 23 countries around the world , including the United States , Africa , and the Middle East .
2 Soccer Academy is a children ’s television show based upon the skills needed by children to participate in soccer .
3 The demonstration of soccer skills during the program are performed by professional soccer players participating from the country in which the show is taking place in .
4 Along with the soccer skills , there is also a mix or culture , religion , as well as interaction with the local people from whichever country the television show is featuring for that specific episode .
5 " The Soccer Academy " qualifies as children - friendly programming from an instructional and educational perspective , and has been issued the IE certificate by the United States for the shows educational value to children .
6 The parent company , Capistrano Films , has offices located in both Los Angeles , California and Detroit , Michigan .

##title
Song of Freedom
##doc
0 Song of Freedom is a 1936 British film directed by J.
1 Elder Wills and starring Paul Robeson .
2 One of two elements pivotal to the plot is an opera composer named Gabriel Donizetti , presumably suggested by the historical opera composer Gaetano Donizetti .
3 The other is a medallion that serves to identify Robeson 's character as a descendant of an African monarch .
4 Song of Freedom may best represent the opportunity Robeson was looking for to " give a true picture of many aspects of the life of the coloured man in the West .
5 Hitherto on the screen , he has been characterized or presented only as a comedy character .
6 This film shows him as a real man . "
7 Robeson was also given final cut approval on the film , an unprecedented option at the time for an actor of any race .
8 As in Sanders of the River , the film called for documentary scenes of West African traditional dances and ceremonies , but this time Robeson obtained a contract giving him final cut , so that the film ’s message would not be changed behind the doors of the editing room .
9 Robeson plays Zinga , a black dockworker in England with a great baritone singing voice .
10 He is discovered by an opera impresario , and is catapulted into great fame as an international opera star .
11 Yet he feels alienated from his African past , and out of place in England .
12 By chance , he is informed that an ancestral medallion that he wears is proof of his lineage to African kings , and he leaves fame and fortune to take his rightful place of royalty .
13 Reunited with his people , he plans to improve their lives by combining the best of western technology with the best of traditional African ways .
14 Although the film was not a box office success in the US , it was notably chosen in 1950 to open the convention of Ghana 's Convention People 's Party .
15 The ceremonies were presided over by the future first prime minister of independent Ghana , Kwame Nkrumah , Robeson 's friend from his London years .

##title
ELAM (Latin American School of Medicine) Cuba
##doc
0 Escuela Latinoamericana de Medicina ( ELAM ) , formerly Escuela Latinoamericana de Ciencias Médicas ( in Spanish ; in English : Latin American School of Medicine ( LASM ) , formerly Latin American School of Medical Sciences ) , is a major international medical school in Cuba and a prominent part of the Cuban healthcare system .
1 Established in 1999 and operated by the Cuban government , ELAM has been described as possibly being the largest medical school in the world by enrollment with approximately 19,550 students from 110 countries reported as enrolled in 2013 .
2 All those enrolled are international students from outside Cuba and mainly come from Latin America and the Caribbean as well as Africa and Asia .
3 The school accepts students from the United States — 91 were reportedly enrolled as of January 2007 .
4 Tuition , accommodation and board are free , and a small stipend is provided for students .
5 An ELAM sister school operated by the Venezuela government and sited in Guri , Bolívar , Venezuela was scheduled to open in October 2006 .
6 However , it was only half built as of November 2008 .
7 The school is named Escuela Latinoamericana de Medicina A.P.
8 Réverénd after French physician Alejandro Próspero Réverénd .

##title
Ramey Idriss
##doc
0 Ramey Idriss ( 11 September 1911 – 5 February 1971 ) was an American songwriter , author , composer and musician , educated at Los Angeles Community College .
1 His birth name was Ramez Idriss but he was also known as Ramey .
2 Idriss was a musician in dance orchestras on radio and recordings and in films , and also wrote television scripts and special material for the Ritz Brothers , Eddie Cantor , Jimmy Durante and Marion Hutton .
3 Joining ASCAP in 1947 , his most popular song composition was the Oscar - nominated " The Woody Woodpecker Song " , as featured in the film Wet Blanket Policy in 1948 .
4 Other compositions included " Worry Worry Worry " , " The Old Chaperone " , " Take a Letter Miss Smith " , " I 'll Wait " , " Leave It to Joan " and " Something Old Something New . "
5 George Tibbles who co - wrote the Woody Woodpecker Song with him remained friends for the next 23 years until Idriss ' death .
6 Tibbles was a Producer and eventual Head Writer of the classic television series My Three Sons in the 1960s and gave Idriss music composing and script writing assignments on the show .

##title
Mess of Blues (Jeff Healey album)
##doc
0 Mess of Blues is an album by Jeff Healey .
1 It was released in 2008 less than two weeks after his death and just three weeks shy of his 42nd birthday .
2 Four of the album 's tracks were recorded live in front of audiences , two of the live tracks at the Islington Academy in London , and the other two live tracks at Jeff Healey 's Roadhouse in Toronto .
3 The other six tracks were recorded at Studio 92 in Canada by Norm Barker and Richard Uglow .
4 The whole album features the band which normally accompanied Jeff at his club , Jeff Healey 's Roadhouse .
5 The song " Mess of Blues " , which appears on the album was written by Doc Pomus and Mort Shuman and was originally recorded by Elvis Presley .

##title
Ross Alger
##doc
0 Ross Patterson Alger ( August 20 , 1920 – January 16 , 1992 ) was a politician in the Canadian province of Alberta , who served as mayor of Calgary from 1977 to 1980 .
1 Born in Prelate , Saskatchewan , he moved to Alberta with his family in 1930s .
2 He received a bachelor of commerce degree from the University of Alberta in 1942 .
3 He served with the Royal Canadian Air Force during World War II .
4 After the war , he received an MBA from the University of Toronto .
5 He settled in Calgary and started a career in accounting .
6 In 1958 , he was a public school board trustee , and later became the chairman .
7 From 1971 to 1974 , he was an alderman on Calgary City Council .
8 In 1974 , he ran for mayor losing to Rod Sykes .
9 He was elected mayor in 1977 and served one term until 1980 .
10 During Alger 's term , notable accomplishments include the construction of the Ctrain ’s first leg , the bid for the XV Olympic Winter Games , and planning for the Olympic coliseum .
11 His brother was Harry Alger .
12 Alger died of cancer in 1992 , which had first been diagnosed in 1985 .

##title
Willi Schneider (skeleton racer)
##doc
0 Wilfried " Willi " Schneider ( born 13 March 1963 in Mediaș , Transylvania ) is a German skeleton racer who competed from 1992 to 2002 .
1 He won two medals in the men 's skeleton event at the FIBT World Championships with a gold in 1998 and a bronze in 1999 .
2 Schneider also finish ninth in the men 's skeleton event at the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City .
3 He won the men 's overall Skeleton World Cup title in 1997 - 8 .
4 After retiring from competition Schneider became a coach , leading the Canadian skeleton team to three medals at the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin ( a gold for Duff Gibson , a silver for Jeff Pain and a bronze for Melissa Hollingsworth ) , and coaching Jon Montgomery to victory in the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver , British Columbia , Canada .
5 In July 2012 Schneider agreed a two - year contract to coach the Russian skeleton team .
